 the workshop is filled with amazing creations worth thousands of hours of loving care into the game.',''),(170,'Cities: Skylines has completely changed the way I play city simulators, and I absolutely love it. The ability to be more laid-back, or switch to extremely difficult settings, is really nice for when I want to be more creative or want to be more realistic. This game helped support my decision to get a degree in Urban and Regional Planning, and found that so much of the actual real-life mechanics play well in the game, too.If you loved SimCity 4, you\'ll probably like this game - but it\'s not the same kind of management style where you are almost micromanaging the city, and the lack of a regional structure is disappointing.The graphics are aging and they were more cartoonish in the beginning. I think as time went on, DLCs came out, mods came out, and they found that people were taking this game more seriously than the original designers intended. It has charm though.',''),(171,'Best...Purchase...Ever',''),(172,'I\'ve not played Cities Skylines for a bit and I\'ve just re-installed it for a quick blast.  I can\'t start a new game without buying DLC.  Instant uninstall.  This used to be a great game; why did Colossal Order feel the need to do this?  Definitely not buying the sequel.  Done with this.',''),(173,'Best City Builder of all time, currently still better than Cities Skylines 2',''),(174,'i love building for 3 hours with infinite money then watching as the whole infrastructure system collapses once i unpause',''),(175,'I\'ll let people know right off the bat that Cities is nearly as good as Simcity 4, and is certainly a good spiritual successor to the Simcity franchise, though it does have its share of issues- which I\'ll get into briefly.  It features a very intricate web of systems that all hinge on a certain kind of delicate balance that can absolutely go wrong in a few minutes or a few hours depending on what you\'re doing or what you\'re plopping down on the map, but its certainly an enjoyable experience.. mostly.  That is until you encounter traffic.  Traffic, whether in a videogame simulation, or in actual reality, is awful.  I hate traffic, I hate driving around poorly designed cities myself, or wondering why certain highways or exits are laid out the way they are or why a bus stop is on one street over another or why the speed limit can change three or four times on the same stretch of road when it only runs through one neighborhood.  Well I can assure that Cities - Skylines has your deepest darkest anguish in mind, because you will not only be planning roads and highways yourself, but you\'ll be able to watch your infrastructure crumble at the tiniest mistakes as well!  Laying down roads in this game is deceptive.  It basically progression checks you early on when you\'re first building your city, so you only have access to whatever your population is, which means you can\'t really perceive yet how much of a nightmare everything is going to be and the game does a very poor job of visually telling you, yes- even with topographical information filters that you can access through the interface- what is currently or about to go horribly wrong with your own layout.  Really you won\'t know its a complete wash until systems start to break down.  I\'ll admit, I don\'t want to build an entire map of roundabouts just to manage traffic, and I never got the hang of the highway systems because it felt weird bulldozing my entire downtown area just because the influx of traffic getting in or out of the city had increased.  Like where do these roads NEED to go?  It never really explains what a good design is because you\'re quickly putting out fires with stop-gap solutions like bus stops or subways.Personally I never really liked the way plumbing and electricity work either, with very finicky power lines or having to account for noise, or pollution until you reach cleaner energy sources to build way later on.  These are all totally locked out and you still have to worry about city policies, fire departments, police departments, hospitals, education, and then even college campuses.  Don\'t even get me started on parks & recreation or tourism, because those are all concepts introduced when you\'re still trying to get the hang of building up your city without setting everything on fire.  The whole game feels like dominoes are about to fall, but you\'re always holding the last one up, slowly preventing the eventual collapse of absolutely everything you\'ve done or accomplished.  ..and I hate that.Its just not as rewarding or as fun as something a bit less realistic like the older Simcity games.  Even Simcity 4 was more visually rewarding when you opened up the tax mini-menu to spike the industrial sectors to 20% taxes in order to move in nothing but clean tech industry moguls and buildings instead.  The systems in Cities are just a little more complex, certainly not impossible to understand, but they take so much time and experimentation to get things just right.  It also doesn\'t help that sometimes icons float above buildings and I check tab after tab to see what\'s going on or why its not getting what it needs, but it just refuses to make sense as to why it has problems.  Not having access to information as to why a scenario is going wrong is a HUGE pet peeve of mine in any city-building title, so having it in Cities behemoth-like presentation is stupid.  Theirs a ton of DLC for this game that I never bought, I always just had the original, so if a lot of DLC fixes issues I had, that\'s totally fine, but the base game is missing many things.. probably actual fun gameplay the most.  Eventually your city becomes massive and its totally overwhelming.  That\'s about when I tap out and start playing Simcity 3000.',''),(176,'game is mid',''),(177,'I like it when the cities skylining all over the place.',''),(178,'',''),(179,'I hate traffic',''),(180,'h',''),(181,'The game would not la