for hours.  I would highly recommend this to anyone and encourage you not to cheat.',''),(245,'Better than Starfield',''),(246,'The devs have been pouring their hearts into this game for years, and continue to release amazing content and features.With the recent \"The Day Before\" scandal, I was reminded what a rough launch this game had and how dedicated the devs were to making this game meet expectations.',''),(247,'When Starfield came out I was in the mood for a space game, so I purchased No Man\'s Sky and do not regret a second of it.',''),(248,'I will leave the cat here, so that everybody who passes by can pet it and give it a thumbs up and awards　　　 　　／＞　　フ　　　 　　| 　_　 _ l　 　　 　／` ミ＿xノ　　 　 /　　　 　 |　　　 /　 ヽ　　 ﾉ　 　 │　　|　|　|　／￣|　　 |　|　|　| (￣ヽ＿_ヽ_)__)　＼二つ',''),(249,'if you are expecting skyrim in space, this is not your game. There is a questline, but it is basically a tutorial of how to play different aspects of the game. This is an open world sandbox game and in that category it is excellent. At times, it feels a bit like im playing minecraft (mining, building), at other times it feels a bit like im playing WoW (scan 8 plants from this planet, deliver this item to that planet). But I like those games, so this one is good for me. I enjoy the game.',''),(250,'Whilst the games basic selling point of the endless galaxy has a good number of hours to explore, the universe eventually felt empty. The economy was very basic and reacted little to my actions and not to all game world events (as there are no real game world events) -- e.g. attack of pirates of XX system means that YY product is in short supply -- such a thing does not exist. The prices of products today seemed to be exactly the price tomorrow. The NPCs said more or less the same thing over and over, the sentinels (the main \'enemy\' you encounter) were just dumb.  Even the scripted main story was low on memorable pieces, I just couldn\'t bring myself to care about any of the characters since they had no semblance of \'life\', just standing around in the same spot forever. Every space station is an exact copy of the one before, with different skinned NPCs standing in the same spots. The game universe is practically endless, but you could see it all in a few hours if you set your mind to it.',''),(251,'If you love collecting rocks and scanning things, this is the game for you. I bought this recently on sale, many years after initial release, so I imagine the game has improved quite a lot since then. But I can only recommend this game as a mostly single-player experience. Multiplayer seems like mostly an afterthought, with large amounts of de-syncing. It is not a good feeling when you search for a resolution for a specific bug and the community replies to just turn off all multiplayer functionality. Additionally, ship combat and flight controls feel weak but I guess this is okay for the target audience; if you\'re use to flying your ship like a mad-man in Elite Dangerous, you\'ll be disappointed. I would even say that the flight controls in Freelancer (2003) feel more responsive. Base building is kinda lame when it comes to terraforming, you\'ll see all the terrain regenerate and clip into your structures but some of the community insists that this is okay and \"working as designed\". So as I\'ve seen other suggest, build upwards to overcome this. Finally, getting the frigate so early feels like it defeats the purpose of a planet-side base. When I can just build a max level refinery on my frigate, why bother going through the phases at the base, plus having to power them. The games strengths lie in its exploration and rock collection.',''),(252,'I just really like exploring',''),(253,'I play this game with my son and my grandson!  Anybody can play.  Anybody can learn...soooo much fun!',''),(254,'I find it hard to keep playing past a certain point (main quest) as I don\'t see a reason.  I need a reason to build a base or upgrade all my equipment and vehicles.  I understand