ll and needed to find games that I could walk around in for a long time, and I had read that VR was a possibility in NMS. The very first time I got into the game in VR, it completely changed my opinion of the game. I\'ve played over 100 hours in VR and I crave it all the time. The game seems so much more impressive in VR. The way the controls work is great. As a VR title this is definitely the most extensive game on the market.',''),(259,'I LIKE SPACE!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! I LIKE GAME!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! ME PLAY GAME!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! ME LOSE LIFE!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! WIFE GET MAD!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! WIFE PLAY GAME!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! WIFE LIKE GAME TOO!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!! WIFE LOSE LIFE!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!',''),(260,'A game that did not start out particularly great, but has since come around to being one of the most excellent open-world games I\'ve played. YMMV but I\'ve enjoyed this quite a bit starting on PS4, moving to Xbox, and finally PC',''),(261,'Really fun exploration game if you don\'t mind some resource gathering. I started playing this in 2016 and still fire it up every now and again.',''),(262,'SEX WITH ALIEN YES',''),(263,'Amazing game, Never ending fun',''),(264,'Don\'t play this game. It\'s actually a time machine in disguise that keeps putting you forward to two in the morning with no idea what just happened.Fun though.',''),(265,'Staring at maps for this long is mental illness.',''),(266,'my wife makes me choose between this game and her. i think looking at my hours played, we can all assume what I choose out of preference.',''),(267,'TL;DR - Amazing game, basically a more complex Civilization in space, but a bit too complex and overwhelming unless you invest a lot of time.I really like this game and recommend it, but it\'s at the limit of complexity for what I can handle in a game and I\'ve had to put it down because there are too many unexplained mechanics. This game is kind of Civilization in space, but with way more complexity than Civilization. Most people will go the conquest route in their first playthrough, but there are ample options for winning through any combination of diplomacy, economics/trade, science dev, etc. Also, it was clearly made by developers who love sci fi, so there are lots of easter eggs and concepts from many sci fi books, TV shows, etc.Don\'t be intimidated by the DLC and in fact I recommend NOT getting them until you start playing the game to get an idea of what elements you enjoy. The base game is good and complete and the DLC just add more options and complexity. As I mentioned, the game is complex enough as is and has plenty of options, so the DLC is really a way to keep the game fresh for existing players rather than a way to unlock needed features. Also, I recommend watching any of a number of HowToPlay YouTube tutorials (MaxTheCatfish has a good series) about Stellaris before playing to understand how things work, because most of the mechanics are not explained in game. This game is a major time sink, so it\'s probably worth watching a couple of hours of beginner\'s guides and tutorials before playing to save yourself even more time wasted with mistakes in game.',''),(268,'This game isn\'t complete without the DLC and it really makes sure you know it. NPC factions will have access to tech you can\'t have without DLC, every update that adds DLC drastically changes something about the base game to make it incomplete without the DLC that was added. Empire sprawl used to be as simple as \"Build more administrative buildings, have more capacity.\" They updated that to be more complicated and hard to manage, without the DLC at least. Same with vassals, when Overlord came out they completely redid the vassal system, and obtaining and integrating vassals became much harder and convoluted in the base game.      I quit playing after Overlord released, and I\'m only posting this review because I looked back at the store page to see if getting the DLC on sale would be a good idea. The ultimate bundle at 50% off right now is nearly 10x as much as the game is on sale. They want you to buy the game cheap, get hooked on what\'s basically the demo, then buy 200$ of DLC to get the complete experience. Not worth your time or money unless you have 30$ to fork over every month (or you can magically get access to the DLC...), because the base game only gets worse with every DLC release.',''),(269,'You can design your own alien species, and do with  it anything you can dream of.I choose to play the base Humans and remind the Xenos they aren\'t made in God\'s image.',''),(270,'After nearly 2,000 hours of game time since May 9th 2016 I think it is finally time to leave a review. TL;DR - Over priced, out-dated engine with severe issues in performance, poor update and DLC policy/management, not a great looking future after 2023.This is a game that, when compared to it\'s original 1.0 release is now unrecognisable throughout the vast majority if not all of it\'s mechanics and features. While I of course appreciate that updates and DLCs will inevitably change core parts of the game, much of the change has been through updates that accompany the DLCs (meaning the update costs you nothing, purchasing the DLC merely unlocks certain features for the player to directly use that are now in the game thanks to said updates) essentially meaning that regardless of buying the latest DLC/expansion you are going to be locked into the new features, for better or worse.Now, let us discuss these updates and DLCs and the ever worsening QA that comes with them; not only will you have to re-learn major parts of the game\'s mechanics time and time again nullifying everything you\'ve learnt over the many hours you\'ve spent in game already, you\'ll quickly find many of the new features won\'t work, nor will they for quite some time meaning that you\'ll have to re-learn the new mechanics again as they don\'t operate the same way when fixed as they did when broken. This is an issue that is increasingly frustrating as the price of these DLCs only keeps going up with the quality and content going down.Moving onto costs; well, it is a Paradox game so there\'s no surprise when it comes to the grand total. If you want the full experience it will set you back just shy of £300 when not on sale. As far as I am concerned this is not worth it, especially after the past year of updates and releases which have, in my opinion, degraded what was once arguably the best modern sci-fi 4X game available. If you really want to give it a try, I would highly recommend waiting for a free weekend that comes about every now and then or a minimum of a 65-70% discount.',''),(271,'Used to be a really fun game but the paragons DLC kinda just started a downward trend of bad decision after bad decision, the latest DLC astral planes is basically a tiny storypack for $20 which is way too much for what its worth',''),(272,'Why does the DLC which barely adds any content cost hundreds of dollars. This is a joke.',''),(273,'Between this game and Europa Universalis 4 I will never buy a Paradox game again. Currently the ultimate bundle which includes all DLC is over $200. I have been playing Paradox games since the original Hearts of Iron but no more. The game on it\'s own is a decent 4x strategy game but I can not support the scummy practices of Paradox. The varying travel methods per civilization is one of the main reasons I bought this game. They were removed for \"balance\" reasons and added back in later as paid DLC. Also the game gets pretty boring for me after the exploration phase.',''),(274,'Unfortunately with how many hours into this game I just can\'t justify buying this game.Stellaris used to be great, really did but as they continue to change things and make it ever complicated. meanwhile they have completely given up on trying to improve performance, if you\'re gonna play the game unfortunately you have to play small or tiny galaxy, don\'t even bother with large or extra large galaxy.  the game continues to lag end game, they have tried everything to fix the end game lag, at the end of the day it just simply isn\'t fixable so you have to ask yourself \"is it really worth playing if its just gonna lag at the end and make it unplayable?\" oh you wanna play with friends? again don\'t bother, stellaris is notorious for \"Desyncs\" basically all players become desynced and the game is no longer playable, you can try googling, restarting, you could have the fastest best computer, all of your friends could have the fastest best computer, it happens anyways. which its kind of funny cause at one point they did fix it, but then it came back and since then again they gave up on trying to fix it. but aside from the fact their game is unplayable it doesn\'t stop them from continuing to release DLC\'s. which I understand that a company has got to make money, but come on... honestly at this point its time for stellaris to die. hopefully stellaris 2 will be remade on a better engine, better performance, better everything. Look up stellaris Nexus, its literally a 5 player game cause at the end of the day thats all they can realistically do without impacting performance. I love paradox I do and when this game first came out it was great, fun, i was excited, they actually made something, but since update after update after update the performance of the game has only gotten worse the bugs have stacked up and they no longer address the issues.',''),(275,'This has got to be the worst tutorial system I\'ve ever seen... No idea what I\'m supposed to be doing and zero guidance',''),(276,'This is a really great game. There should not be 15 something DLC\'s. Most all of the DLC\'s are the same thing: content that was clearly considered good and interesting and was earmarked to be repackaged and sold separately after tinkering and refining it at a later date. There is no reason to release a game at this price point then release enough DLC that it 