o stress just relaxing in my world!',''),(588,'Good for autism',''),(589,'Chill leisurely move at your own pace game, no rush to meet goals or objectives. The math turns my brain into scrambled eggs because math hard. Great time killer. :)',''),(590,'6/10. I would leave a positive review if it wasn\'t such a popular overwhelmingly up-voted game, however, I think these factors will cause many to buy this and regret it.I really want to like this game. It has beautiful scenery, and delivers exactly what it promises; a satisfactory - factory building game. If you enjoy building factories and redoing them over and over again, this is the game for you.My lack of enjoyment comes from the shear amount of time it takes to rebuild each factory after you learn just a bit more, or unlock alternate recipes for a component/material etc. It also seems a little insane that each new tier of factory/item to be produced takes seemingly 2x-4x the previous tier of item/building to produce in any reasonable amount of time. For example, a tier 5 building might take 100 factories of your base tier to achieve an equivalent production value/rate. Add in a map that has way too much terrain variance and obstacles, and a pretty un-intuitive conveyor system (if you want it to be organized at all) and it is just frustrating.This game is definitely a challenge and I can see why many like it, but I do not. If you are on the fence, I highly recommend buying on sale. It\'s likely you will find quite a bit of enjoyment from the game, but you will probably end up burnt out and frustrated after 60 hours (probably 10 of which was just left in background out of annoyance) like me.',''),(591,'Cutting trees and burning shrubbery, enslaving dogs for your own ends, Coal-Power, Turbo-Fuel Powerplants, Nuclear Reactors and waste and no Greta around the corner to point fingers. Satisfactory is all about maximizing efficiency and exploitation, while totally neglecting things like economic footprint or whatever bad things that might happen when you take a epic sh*t on a alien world. Imagine all that raw power, with impressive Unreal Engine 5 graphics and audio that sticks. Absolutely dazzling - 9/10 (b/c multiplayer syncing is kinda messy :/)',''),(592,'If I\'d never played Factorio, Astroneer, Terratech, Scrap Engineers or Empyrion I\'d probably think this was amazing.  But those games exist and I can\'t pretend they don\'t.  There\'s serious technical achievement here (seriously, how does this not bring my PC to a crawl? must be some incredible coding going on in the background!), but the game just feels absolutely dead compared to Factorio.   Really needs more of an MSQ / endgame / threat to give me a reason to push the sand around the sandbox.  Dammit, I wanted to like this so bad but it just doesn\'t work for me.',''),(593,'This game is incredibly fun and addictive. My partner and I have logged well over a hundred hours each playing multiplayer together on a dedicated server since we started a couple of weeks ago. Unfortunately, every time we make it to the midgame, we start encountering gamebreaking bugs, and I cannot CURRENTLY recommend this game in early access Update 8 in multiplayer. I expect in future updates when the bugs are addressed that I will update this review to state that it\'s become my favorite game of all time.As it currently stands, Satisfactory is unplayable for us. It started with an invisible conveyor belt that could not be interacted with or removed, but had collision. It escalated to frequent single-user crashes when using hypertubes for travel. It began affecting vehicles, with frequent single-user crashes while driving. We\'ve now encountered \"the last straw\". I just spent all evening building a factory I was intensely proud of, only to have a splitter go invisible with collision. It acted like a barrier, stopping all products from being conveyed beyond it, and it could not be removed. Worse, nothing it touched could be removed to work around