RODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION PRODUCTION also god gam',''),(598,'When I\'m dead, I won\'t miss leaving Epic behind. Competition can be good, but no one does a better job than steam. Epic needs to stay in the oven for another decade.If you prefer steam then you are going to LOVE when Satisfactory doesn\'t let you play as your character because there is an issue with Epic. All your end-game materials lost until who knows when.You can\'t say you respect your playerbase but also utilize Epic. They are mutually exclusive.',''),(599,'Honestly one of the most relaxing yet complicated games there could ever be. Bored of other games? Try just chilling and build a factory with some friends, build goofy structures, let things clip boundless amount of times. Force your friends to be unable to play (low hardware issues) because you simply went with an idea that has turned into almost a multi-hundred hour project. Getting lost building a factory or simply exploring the different areas to find new resources to gather; foreshadows the bigger looming factory soon to be built in the wonderous terrain. This game has been on my daily playing for almost 6 months straight now. I simply cannot get enough. CONS:  Get ready to lose hundreds of hours if you love logistics and building massive works of artYou do need a substantial pc to run this game into the end game stages.PROS: YOUR FRIENDS WHO DON\'T JOIN SAY YOU YERN FOR THE FACTORIESThere is unofficial mod support and dedicated server support.',''),(600,'If you ever wanted a million things to do and no one to tell you that building a 3 story nuclear powered space hotel for lizard doggos is not helping you make quota this is the game for you',''),(601,'I used to say this was the most Satisfactory game to play, but it\'s become a buggy nightmare to such an extent that it is completely unplayable. Used to be fun, now all hypertubes kill you, or crash the server, if you get hit into a stun you fall through the map, and buildings like to unbuild themselves between sessions. What had been a fun game has been changed into something that is not.',''),(602,'Spaghetti Belts!!',''),(603,'I keeps Crashing',''),(604,'I love how I go into my world for a quick session and log off after 8 hours xD',''),(605,'30 years of getting enough iron mines to support your build queue, 70 years of building nothing but railways and powerstations. 0 years of interesting choices to be made.',''),(606,'Having recently finished a campaign I thought it was time to give a brief review. In summary I have found the experience enjoyable with quite a few exciting moments along the way. There are quite a few negative reviews for this game. As someone who\'s only ever played post 1.5, and as someone who never played the predecessor, I don\'t really share the complaints. The game works fine, the war system does what I want it to (I actually found it rather cool and well-suited to the game), and I had a fun time playing. At the end of the day, the game is a pretty solid financial / geopolitical similator set in the Victorian era and I can only recommend it if those topics are of any interest at all. As a side note, I believe this is the first time ever I have finished a full campaign in a Paradox game. Thumbs up from me!',''),(607,'I cannot in good faith recommend this game to anyone but the most diehard grand strategy fans.In it\'s current state Victoria 3 is an alpha game priced at 50 euro strewn with bugs and obviously missing features which Paradox will sell as exorbitantly priced \"DLC\"s years after the game\'s release. For example foreign investment mechanics are totally absent: according to Paradox these will be added later alongside an expansion - which is strange because you can download totally free user made mods that add foreign investment to the game right now. Go to the Steam Workshop, search it up, hit subscribe, and you\'re good. If some random guy can add foreign investment to the game as a little hobby project then how come a professional team of veteran video game developers can\'t? The answer is that they can. They just aren\'t allowed to by their corporate overlords.That\'s all too often the modus operandi of this company. Release a half finished, broken mess of a game, then slowly fix it while demanding hundreds of euros for \"expansions\" to turn it into what it should\'ve been at launch.With that said you might wonder why I have so many hours in this game if I don\'t recommend it. That\'s because the game\'s foundation is solid, and as it\'s essentially based around watching numbers go up It\'s  entertaining.  It\'s  addicting.  It\'s  unique.  That\'s why you can play it without being bored. It is not, however,  good.  Diplomatic plays is a fine concept, but why are they so limited and restrictive? Why can\'t we interact with our puppet states? Why aren\'t power blocs or crises a thing? The production (of goods) and building system is solid, but why can\'t we do foreign investment? Why can\'t factory owners control their factories\' production methods? Why can\'t we stockpile resources (for example to prepare for wartime)? War is a critical component of any grand strategy game and is present in a somewhat useable form, but why is there no evolution of how war plays out (pitched battles evolving into trench warfare, for example)? Why can\'t you field more than two ship types in a navy at the same time? Why has the issue of frontlines splitting and being left undefended (which can easily cost you months of ingame progress) still not fixed? Why are battles just aggregate numbers fighting aggregate numbers without any nuance? Why is the system so arcane and opaque? And why is the UI so lackluster, confusing, and ugly despite Paradox having a decade+ of experience designing them? Why are internal politics so bland and gamey? I could go on and on and on but you get the point. The foundation is solid but there\'s little more than a wooden shack built ontop of it.And oh my God the performance is atrocious.  Even on a powerful machine (beyond the game\'s recommended specs) the game slows to a snail\'s pace past 1900 (one-third of the game\'s timeframe!). Past 1920 it\'s essentially unplayable.As a silver lining I will say that the game has improved significantly since its launch, especially regarding the warfare system and non-player economics. And don\'t get me wrong: I don\'t want this game to fail. I don\'t want this company to fail. I really, really, really want this game to be good. Because there is so much potential here. But it isn\'t good. It\'s far from good. It\'s a buggy, unfinished, flavorless, directionless mess of a game that future promises and duct tape fixes cannot excuse.Don\'t buy this game. If you want to play Victoria 3 go sail the high seas and come back in a couple of years. Let\'s hope that by that time the game will be what it should\'ve been a year ago.',''),(608,'This game scratches every gaming itch I have. I had been watching it since the messy release and waiting for an opportunity to arrive where it was in a state where I felt I would enjoy the hell out of it. I\'ve always enjoyed pretty much all of the Paradox suite of games, but I\'d say this one has very quickly become my favorite. I love the simulation this game delivers, and the alt-history silliness that can happen. I\'ve made an ultra-capitalistic Presidential Republic Spain, a militarist Sokoto Caliphate, and most recently I had a blast with Japan achieving the Meiji Restoration achievement.Normally, I hate randomly generated systems in games with almost no exceptions, however, V3 has somehow achieved a way to make it feel fair. The events that are purely bad don\'t linger for too long, or they are there to present a reasonable challenge. The difficulty varies all over, and I wholeheartedly appreciate it. The challenging starts that I\'ve tried genuinely feel fun, for example: Egypt is a race against time to build up military to defend against an eventual Ottoman attack, and I\'m not good enough yet to figure out how to do it without ruining my run. I actually enjoy playing all the way through to the end when in EU4 I\'ve only ever done that once. The soundtrack is absolutely without a doubt my favorite soundtrack in all of the Paradox suite of games. I have had a lot of fun so far, and I think that especially if the development keeps going in the direction it has been I will continue to have more fun. I definitely feel good recommending this game.',''),(609,'You shouldn\'t market a game by fixing it through DLC. Paradox has done this time and time again and it needs to stop. Release a game that\'s fleshed out for once Paradox. Worry about DLC later.',''),(610,'I have tried my best to like this game, but it\'s just a disaster. The new update made it better, but that is because the bar was so low to begin with. It feels like every nation plays the exact same, it\'s a boring mess of trying to micro-manage in many small menus. I guess it\'s a good economy simulator, but this is not the legendary grand strategy game we were promised. While the idea of having general\'s lead a war sounds cool, it DOES NOT WORK. Sure the new update somewhat fixed the naval invasion wack-a-mole, but the frontlines system is still terrible and feels more RNG dependant than EU4. Chances are they will \"fix it\" through slowly implementing hundreds of dollars of DLC.',''),(611,'The game is not finished, do not buy it.Plenty of bugs, lackluster warfare and diplomacy, very little flavor given to the diverse world.Give it another year or two.',''),(612,'I thought that I would give this game a try, mostly because I absolutely loved Victoria 2 and wanted to check out this game. Generally I\'ve enjoyed most paradox strategy games but this one was a disappointment. I almost immediately realised that this wasn\'t worth my timeThe biggest issue for me is that the UI is horrible, confusing and just too much. If you just want to look at some number or take some action you have to click through a bunch of menus, some of which you need to scroll to reach what you need. It\'s more like a menu simulator rather than a game. This game will destroy your mouse wheelThe only good parts about this game, is the mechanics that were ported over from Victoria 2 and which may have been expanded a little on. There is potential there but is unfortunately hampered by the messy UIVictoria 3 should\'ve been what Hearts of Iron 4 was for Hearts of Iron 3 but in my opinion, Victoria 3 doesn\'t even beat Victoria 2. Aside from graphics which really is a moo-point for the player baseThey really need to work A LOT on UI changes in order for this to be a enjoyable game',''),(613,'I love paradox games, but this one is absolute garbage. The diplomacy system is completely opaque and unusable. Only a handful of nations are even playable.  Almost the entire game is eventless and is mostly just watching blue bars go up. On top of that the game runs incredibly slowly making the complete static nature of the game unbearable. I literally AFK most of the game and nothing happens. No wars declared on me, no diplomatic actions for or against me for well over 50 years of gameplay in multiple runs. The map is entirely static unless the player does something. Maybe Germany will unite or the US will fight Mexico, but that\'s about it. The nations have no flavor or personality except a few hardcoded events. There is no uniquness and each run is basically the exact same. I just can not fathom how the same company that made EU4 can churn out this garbage.',''),(614,'I ended up going back to Victoria 2',''),(615,'This is my first Victoria series game. There\'s a steep learning curve, but once you figure it out it\'s a fun economic, diplomatic, and military simulator. It provides an intellectually stimulating platform for reshaping historical events, making it an engaging  experience. Events do tend to repeat themselves at times, but nothing annoying like other games. 10/10',''),(616,'玩了一天，怀疑人生，为什么要把大好时光放在这么一坨半成品里？？？CK、HOI甚至是烂尾了的IR也比这个好玩多了。',''),(617,'Untill they fix the horrible AI and diplomatic stuff i can\'t recommend the game.Sure patch 1.5 with Tropps and military update is nice.But when bugs like alliances and good friendship is suddenly overturned because of a small war in Arabia. Breaks up Alliances and other stuff out of nowhere with no explanation.Well if u want a headache and want to save/load rinse repeat go ahead buy the game.I for one will be putting the game on the shelf for now.',''),(618,'doesn\'t work on OS X 10.14',''),(619,'TLDR: We\'ve waited this game to release for years, sadly it didn\'t meet expectations at release. But have no doubt it will get better in time.Steep learning curve as with all paradox games, but feel like this is super watered down version compared to the other games. Most of the mechanics don\'t make sense and feel like your actions are going around in circles which could\'ve all been abstracted away or automated. Unnecessary RNG in some mechanics (eg. Enacting new laws).  Give it some time, perhaps a couple years for them to fix and enhance this badboy.',''),(620,'Bought this a year after realese and yet it feels a lot like a beta. Three play throughs in