 You can \'slow down\' but its really not enough for proper planning, especially when you can potentially buy up the whole map, but you can\'t ever pause anything to get a full scope of what you are doing? This game leaves me wanting terribly. The game is cute and i like how it looks but play Frostpunk or Going Medieval or something if you don\'t want to deal with awkward and unexpected \'Defeats,\' confusing vague instructions, and horribly disorganized menus.',''),(1035,'Can\'t play the game anymore today because uplay somehow ♥♥♥♥♥♥ up.',''),(1036,'WARNING! After all this years and updates, this software is still broken. If you are unable to remove the mountain in the campaign to get to the iron, you have to restart the game and pray.Apart from this, the game seems to be great...',''),(1037,'requires the launcher to start, the launcher often won\'t workthe game is probably not bad, but it\'s very hard to give objective review when I\'m angry',''),(1038,'100%ing this game does in fact attract more women 11/10',''),(1039,'i\'ve played for 251 hours that\'s enough evidence',''),(1040,'5/10 - I wish they saved similar gamedesign to original instead of making open-world with countless fillers and mediocre levels',''),(1041,'I don\'t like sand',''),(1042,'I love Lego games.I love Star warsI don\'t think this game manages to live up at least to 70% of either of those two.\"Lego game shouldn\'t be third/first person shooter\" is a clown responseThis game breaks the simplicity of lego games of the past\'s format with a new, format shattering well... format.The idea of the lego games (in my mind) being simplified versions of the story made sense. Legos are not very realistic are they? But with this new format, they\'ve tried to mix their simplistic style with the complexity of star wars as much as they physically could and have managed to create a game that doesn\'t know how to feel like a game.It really does feel like this game had an identity crisis:On one hand - its trying to be star wars battlefrontOn another - Its trying to be Force unleashedand another? - Jedi Fallen orderBut the thing it SHOULD feel like, isnt present. It doesn\'t feel like - Lego Starwars.-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------What about the DLC? you might say...Its not worth it.Just check the entire list if you want your own opinion.76 British pounds for a bunch of characters that are not functionally different?No...All i see is corporate greed piggybacking on every Star Wars Sub-IP (such as Andor, rebels, book of boba fett ETC) and turning them into characters for almost a literal quick buck.I was unfortunate enough to pre-order this game because i trusted TT Games as i\'ve played their games since i was a small boi of only 10 years old. God how godamn wrong i was.For my admiration and pride i showed to this franchise, what did i get for Pre-ordering?A yellow Obi-wan-kenobi.  Thats it.♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ disgraceful',''),(1043,'Worst LEGO Experience....       It just feels like they added so many unnecessary things that completely take away from what made the original games great. Why is there barely any building? What happened to those fantastic original levels? Why would they switch to overhead perspective? Why does mumble mode suck? Free Roam is absolutely attrocious! Almost no puzzle solving, big empty areas with nothing to do',''),(1044,'I will say right off the bat, this is not a difficult game. This is not hard or meant to be too challenging. If you are looking for something with more difficulty, the older LEGO games will be for you.However, that being said.. this is the largest LEGO Star Wars game to date! The sheer amount of characters, missions and content to interact with, do and collect is staggering. Compared to previous games which had individual selections with their own missions, condensing each trilogy down to a series of 6-8 missions for each movie. This game has every single Star Wars movie/trilogy so far, and even characters from things like TV series\' or extra content if you go for the character DLC. (Yes, even the ♥♥♥♥♥♥ Disney sequels.)There are over 200 characters to collect in the base game, many missions to do, and places to explore. Every planet in the game is a large free-roam map with multiple places to go, things to explore and people to talk to. They even have player and class upgrades and various boosts to buy with things you find! That being said, if you aren\'t too keen on doing side missions and the story content is what you\'re after, this game probably has the shortest story segments of any previous LEGO Star Wars game. Previously each trilogy had many individual missions based off of each movie, here, each \"era\"/movie of Star Wars has only 5 individual missions for each. All with varying lengths in what you are actually supposed to do. For example, The Phantom Menace, Attack Of The Clones and Revenge of the Sith all together are only 15 missions long. If you are looking for a LEGO game with lengthy story content similar to the Complete Saga, and want to spend a good long while on lengthy missions enjoying the variety, this game may not be for you. The missions aren\'t exactly long compared to The Complete Saga, but they aren\'t so short they\'re breezed through in a few minutes either, there\'s just less of them.However, if you want a LOT of stuff to do in a LEGO game, and the story bits don\'t concern you much, like Freeplay, then you will likely really love this. There are so many characters, new classes, different abilities, and new \"perks\" with different types of characters that.. it\'s honestly staggering. Not only that but the open world areas have so many hidden areas, collectibles and easter eggs that it\'s honestly great to roam around in! Hell, they even made characters never before seen playable as playable characters in this, such as pod racers like Sebulba, characters have multiple outfits like Jar Jar\'s senator outfit, and everyone has all updated appearances compared to the older models used in Classic LEGO! Not to mention the voice acting.TLDR: If your here for the story and mission/level design, you may want to skip this one as it has less individual missions and less mission length then the past LEGO Star Wars games. But if you want a game with a massive sandbox to play as whomever you want from a massive cast of characters, you\'ll like this! The sheer amount of characters they\'ve shoved into this game is.. staggering.',''),(1045,'Great sequel to the original saga',''),(1046,'digital crack',''),(1047,'I bought this game with the excitement from the nostalgia of old lego games like: lord of the rings, harry-potter, pirates of the Caribbean, lego marvel super heros, batman and many more. But this game was just outright disappointing. I don\'t know if it\'s because I\'m older or if the game is to blame, but i didn\'t get the same joy i remember getting back then. The game itself has changed a lot from the old lego game recipe. skill trees have been added and the combat slightly more complicated than the old lego beat-em up formula.',''),(1048,'Ambitious but annoying. I had to force myself through the game a lot. That’s because up to 90% of it is just mindless filler. I remember being genuinely amazed by the open world concept back when playing Lego Marvel Avengers for the first time. Had I known that it would eventually devolve into something like this, I certainly would have been more skeptical. Let’s start with the first few things that bothered me. The Hud is very crammed with unnecessary displays. And those that are necessary don’t need to be this big. Some could thankfully be turned off. In addition to this, the camera, unlike previous Lego games, is too zoomed in on the character, amplifying your lack of vision. Then we have a similar issue with markers. Whether it’s collectibles or enemies in spaceship battles, the hud is just clustered to ♥♥♥♥ with these markers. I can hardly find anything when looking for one specific objective. But it doesn’t stop there, these spaceship battles are a massive pain in the ass. Partially due to the controls simply refusing to operate when moving too much into a certain direction, but mostly because they are too frequent and time-consuming. Every ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ delivery mission will have you sit through 3 separate loading screens accompanied by a battle after each. A competent developer would have stuck all the battles into the same area.And speaking of loading screens, that’s what you will be seeing the most throughout the game. Why? Because 90% of it is filler content. Whether it’s collectibles or quests in the open world, that’s where you will be spending the majority of the game. We are talking about 24 planets, each with upwards of 30 collectibles and various quests. The worst part is that a lot of these quests will send you on a journey throughout the galaxy. This is one of the worst cases of fetch quests syndrome I’ve ever seen. Imagine sitting through 5 or more loading screen for each quest. But that’s not all, because the developers decided to be very generous with the world size. There is a ton of walking in this game. If you want to torture yourself with this garbage game, go to Hoth and do the Wampa quest to unlock the character, he is the fastest to my knowledge.Then we have the absolute biggest pisstake of this entire game. It’s the character selection. Unlike previous games, there isn’t a button that will automatically swap to the next characters in your roster. Every time you want to change your character, you will be forced to open your roster manually and select the character your want. And because the buttons for browsing through your roster can’t be edited, you will always be forced to take your right hand off the mouse to hit your arrow keys for that. But it gets worse. Because in this ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ game, your roster doesn’t give you all the characters you need. You will have to open the character menu, which is the most convoluted pile of ♥♥♥♥ I have ever experienced in any game, select the character, close the menu completely, open your roster again, then pick the character you just put into your roster. I really want to know what kind of mindless baboon came up with such a nonsensical system.The only positive thing I can say for this game is how short the levels are. Unfortunately they managed to ruin those too. They introduced a new form of lightsaber combat which stretches every boss fight unnecessarily long. Remember how boss fights took a mere minute to finish in the original Lego Star Wars? Well, prepare for 5-10 minutes of fighting, running around, doing a bunch of ♥♥♥♥, just to finish each level that has a boss fight. Lego games never needed a complex combat system, it’s just too much for what these games are trying to be. Button mashing and quick time events? ♥♥♥♥ right off. I just want to finish the fight already. And to add insult to injury, they decided to add challenges for every mission which are mandatory for 100% completion. Thanks for making every level even more convoluted. Because now I have to look up a guide to make absolutely sure to accomplish this very precise task.I think I’m done with Lego games as a whole if this is the route they want to take. It took me 67 hours to finish this awfully coded mess. I didn’t even mention a few other things. Like how you can sometimes softlock a level because the scripted lightsaber combat won’t happen, the amount of unnecessary character categories, the lack of abilities that were present in previous games like grabbing enemies with force lightning and hovering generous distances as certain characters, how your second computer player is literally braindead most of the times and can’t do basic tasks that were no problem in previous installments, unskippable cutscenes, and many more that I couldn’t be bothered to memorize. All you need to know is this, there are 1200 collectibles, most of which are acquired through patted-out filler content. 90% of my time was spent fast traveling from planet to planet, just to gather collectibles or finish quests. Only positive thing I can say in this regard is how the developers didn’t account for players using the force on their partner to easily cheese certain collectibles. Thanks for that. I would also like to thank both J.J. Abrams and Rian Johnson for ruining a multibillion-dollar franchise. Congratulations!',''),(1049,'dull as dishwater to play',''),(1050,'is not 2 player',''),(1051,'very w rizz lego game',''),(1052,'It\'s an incredible game! =)',''),(1053,'By far the best Lego game. Everything is better in this one, camera controls, split screen coop, the ui, how you choose different characters, the upgrade system is great so you can choose things like \"magnetic\" so the coins come to you and so on.It\'s really hard playing Lego games older than this because they\'re so bad comparatively.',''),(1054,'mhm starwars good',''),(1055,'Good graphics but...The coop game feels lagging, slow and is so zoomed in that you cannot see anything. Poor humor and nothing to assemble feels off for a lego game. I much prefered the older title.',''),(1056,'👍',''),(1057,'good game',''),(1058,'This game would be widely revered and adored if they had just not marketed themselves as Left 4 Dead 3. They wanted it to be Left 4 Dead 3, we wanted it to be Left 4 Dead 3, it was NOT Left 4 Dead 3, and we were left with a sour taste in our mouths. They marketed their game as the next gen Left 4 Dead, and that brought an ocean of ire upon it that just wouldn\'t be there if they had said \'hey, we\'re a roguelite zombie shooter\'. The game dug its own grave the moment it stepped on holy ground.',''),(1059,'I went in expecting a dumpster fire of a game because of the reviews, but I\'m pleasantly surprised. This game is a lot of fun, I\'ve only played solo so far and can say I\'m happy with my purchase. I got it on sale for 85% off, I would definite