further support.Can I get a hell yeah, brother',''),(1070,'The game is good but i should have refunded it the devs lefts no playersonly bot gameplayso don\'t buywasted money on it because it was left 4 dead creators',''),(1071,'Originally a good game, had a lot of fun in the beginning. Card system was neat, the combat wasn\'t horrible, characters were pretty mid with no charm to them but serviceable. However, just like the faith I had in Evolved (yeah I know) it was quickly thrown away and since then the game has since been abandoned by turtle rock. I feel like they never really give their games time. So I guess I won\'t be giving turtle rock anymore of my time either.Good game that mightve been better had they tried, ruined by a disappointing dev team, unfortunate.',''),(1072,'I actually like this game. The shooting is good, the characters are cool, the perks and all that are awesome.. HOWEVER. This game is confusing as HELL. There are so many different things that could be EASILY simplified, like they were in L4D. I KNOW, this game isn\'t supposed to be L4D3, but it was still made as a successor (Which, honestly, it still fails at being). L4D had such simplicity, that a new player could learn very easily. This game, however, is not that. It\'s complex and confusing for seemingly no reason. My biggest problem is the \"Act\" select. It\'s not like in L4D where you just pick a map, pick a difficulty, and play. This time, you need to \"Create a New Run\", then something happens I dunno It\'s CONFUSING (Genuinely not sure if you can pick different maps/campaigns), pick a difficulty, pick a character, choose some cards, then some other things pop up or something, and THEN you can play. Then you realize that you already played through the map it selected, then you leave andd... Well, it\'s stupid. It REALLY should be how it was in L4D. It was simple and strait-forward. Despite the confusing and complex nature of this game, I would give it a 8.5/10. (SIDE-NOTE: I would REALLY recommend getting this game when it\'s on sale, instead of buying it normally. I got the Ultimate edition which is almost $100 for LESS than the price of the normal game, which is $50. I don\'t remember what sale that was... Probably Christmas. So get it when there\'s one soon! ..If you want to, that is.)',''),(1073,'15$ for Ultimate is totally worth itand its really fun with friends 9/10',''),(1074,'I\'m a L4D veteran and B4B gets my seal of approval. Very satisfying guns for tearing apart hordes of zombies. Love the card deck system. B4B has weapon attachments, and you can set the difficulty of the game to make teamwork a must.',''),(1075,'One of the Best Co-op with Friend Zombie killing experience.',''),(1076,'Don\'t pay the full price under get it on steam sale or something and get version that has all dlcs  , game works fine graphics are good but is abandoned by devs themselves, online is almost dead if u have 1 to 3 other friends who have fun playing together get this game you wont regret it . apart from this the weapon attachment system is is bad, all attachment are random eg: u get shotgun with 8x scope and cant change it, the game will mostly give you  weapons with 20  round clip or something like that u cant change it(its annoying), theres m4 or ak in shop with bigger mag but it also has 8x scope, also weapons feel underpowered specially mg which u get with random 4x scope and does half dmg, some weapons could use rework, eg: minigun which looks like they just copy pasted from LFD2 and still managed to make it worse.',''),(1077,'Just buy left 4 dead. That game is way cheaper and way better.',''),(1078,'There\'s two directions I can take this review. One is \"I recommend, but ...\" and the other is \"I don\'t recommend, however ...\", and they\'re both probably going to say the same things. Strap in, and grab a cup of hot chocolate, daddy\'s gonna tell stories again:If I compare my experience playing the first game on release to this one on release, this one is much, much better. But how?The original Cities: Skylines was a relief from the crushed dreams of SimCity fans. It came in as the rightful conqueror of the city building genre, and built a huge community of gamers, designers and modders that have influenced the growth of the game since. It refined the SimCity style beyond expectations, it broke the gridded city building style, it introduced gamers to urban design and planning ideas that they have never thought of before, and a whole sub-genre of urbanist YouTubers rose up from this. However, when you compare the two vanilla games, without the mods and DLC and hundred of YouTube content creators, the first game is great, but a bit empty. It didn\'t start with a day-night cycle, that was added in After Dark. It didn\'t start with many of the best transit options, they came in later DLCs. Inland water treatment plants didn\'t exist until 2020 with Sunset Harbor.Cities: Skylines 2 starts with everything that the base game should have. It doesn\'t only have a day-night cycle, it has seasons. It doesn\'t just have different zoning densities, it has mixed use zones. You don\'t just place down industry building and print money, the game has a diversified economy, hearkening back to SimCity2000 when you could individually manage tax rates for different industries, but here you can do that to the entire economy. You can encourage and develop an economy based on retail and services, or primary industries, or manufacturing of any kind. You don\'t just have buses, trains and planes, you have the option to use taxis, buses, trains, trams, subway metros, planes and boats to transport your people and cargo outside cars and trucks. To build the city you don\'t just lay down roads, you can plan curves and bends and intersections using the various feedback that it gives you, create clean interchanges and intersections, and use a variety of tools to limit turns and eliminate traffic conflicts. You can even obverse traffic accidents affect your roads and disasters affect the city, pollution affecting the environment and a myriad other things that you didn\'t even think of when the original was released in 2015.Compared to that, yeah, no questions.So why is everyone saying \"Yes, but ...\"?I won\'t repeat it in detail, you\'ve already read the other reviews. Basically, expectations for the game\'s performance and delivery were misaligned between the developers, the publishers and the consumers. Performance issues were a huge problem right off the bat because most people do not have systems that meet the requirements of the game, but the developers have been tasked with making the game suitable for console. Misaligned expectations. The game\'s economic system was too opaque to clearly understand what was going on, to the point that unsubstantiated rumours began spreading that the economy was fake (it\'s not). Feedback to the user was not adequate to completely understand what was going on, and many players assumed things were bugs when they were not. Misaligned expectations.However, the performance issues and opaque UI feedback aside, none of this was helped by the myriad of bugs that have since seen six major patches to clean up, with more work to come out after the Christmas holidays.Finally, to nail the point home about misaligned expectations: content. I came in to the original game in March 2015, right on release. I was with it the whole way through. I was there when the beacons were lit and Gondor called for aid. I didn\'t even bother using mods until 2019, because that\'s when they were interesting and mature enough to really make a difference in the game. By the time the Great Plague of 2020 hit, the original was primed to receive huge interest in the game. Content on the workshop exploded. YouTubers exploded. Everything exploded. It was wild! So when, in early 2023, the new game was announced, a host of gamers came in with huge content expectations and none of the context. YouTubers speculated on the most insane speculations, people were having meltdowns about the new engine staying on Unity instead of hopping over to Unreal Engine. Wild.And so on release, despite having literally been released with more tools and content than city builders have ever had, with all of the good ideas from everywhere in the broader community being incorporated into the base game, the chief criticism was a lack of content. The game felt empty. Grey (UK)! Gray (US)! Graey (WTF)! Critiques went from blasting CS1 for being too cartoony to blasting CS2 for being too realistic with its browns and concretes. At this point, I stopped listening to shameless and pointless, often contradictory criticism and looked for genuine concerns.These are easy to list:- the game is still in need of more performance fixes- the game\'s UI needs more obvious indicators of what\'s going on with underlying systems- the game is a resource H-O-G- tools still feel a bit unrefined- there are missing options that would make things so much nicer (props, prop tools, decorative tools, etc)- no mods at the moment, we want mods- no editors, no map editor, no asset editor, none of that yet- console version still needs to be released- the bug issues have delayed the Ultimate Edition\'s Q4 and Q1 DLC releases- there are still some major bugs that require further investigationTo be frank, though, my stance is straightforward: bugs can be fixed, and these issues will be ironed out over time. The devs have repeatedly shown that they intend to see this through.So yes, \"I recommend, but ...\", be mindful of the things that are still to be fixed, and you may enjoy the game. \"I don\'t recommend, however ...\", set your expectations appropriately and you will realise this game has enormous potential to be the definitive game of the city simulation genre. The first game rightfully conquered the crown. This one will keep it, even it has to fight for it.',''),(1079,'It\'s not ready yet. Let it cook.',''),(1080,'The potential is there but this game is in beta at best. I put hundreds of hours into the original CS and this game is awful in comparison. I didn\'t pay to test the game for you.',''),(1081,'The novelty of the experience has dissipated, and the enjoyment in engaging with this game has waned. I have acquired a comprehensive understanding of the simulation, if one could generously term it as such. Frankly, this game appears to be a substantial misrepresentation, even in light of recent updates. Upon reviewing the weekly developer videos, one is left to ponder whether they were addressing an entirely different game. It strains credulity that any of the developers have successfully managed a city exceeding 100k in population. Below, I enumerate a series of grievances:Cargo possesses the ability to teleport indiscriminately from one location to another, obviating the necessity for any form of vehicular transport.Absence of toggleable zoning on roads, a manifestation I classify as a bug.The Statistics Panel/Menu displays only half of the chart.Canines are inexplicably abandoned when a simulated entity utilizes public transportation to a destination beyond the city limits.Frequent crashes to the desktop occurring approximately every three hours.Influxes of taxis originating from external locales, converging on an arbitrary point, idling, and subsequently departing the city via ostensibly the most inconvenient route, characterized by its protracted duration or sluggish pace.Occasional inexplicable surges in the \"waiting on a hearse\" phenomenon without corresponding spikes in statistical data.Inoperative post and mail sorting systems.Hospitals and clinics perennially devoid of medical supplies, resulting in diminished efficiency.Inexplicable preference for exporting over support for local businesses.Persistent pollution of water bodies, unaffected by the passage of a decade despite strong water flow.Shifts in wind direction, notably the Barrier island experiencing inland winds, leading to the dispersal of pollution over the city.Discordance between Chirps (in-game messages) and actual occurrences within the city.The need to mute the radio after 25 minutes due to its repetitive nature, devoid of relevance to the city\'s development.Paradoxically, the game operates at its maximum efficiency on the 1x speed setting, while higher settings result in slowdowns rather than acceleration (i.e., 0.5 or 0.2).The inability to sustain a 15-minute simulation run before encountering graphic glitches, specifically LOD (Level of Detail) flickering.A discordant and unappealing city soundscape, rendering the developer\'s claims about audio in the trailer incongruous.Public transport lines sporadically reverting to the default color.The flatten terrain tool fails to render the land truly flat, leaving undulating hills and bumps in its wake.An anomalous phenomenon of \"building on water\" in the absence of proximate water sources.Issues abound in both vehicular traffic and pedestrian behavior, surpassing the deficiencies observed in the first iteration of the game.Vehicles mysteriously despawn while moving at full speed.Ongoing utilization of a removed pedestrian crossing by simulated individuals.Peculiar stop-start behavior in the traffic AI\'s interaction with roundabouts at full speed.Last-minute lane changes by the traffic AI, involving abrupt stops and 90-degree turns.Proliferation of illegal U-turns throughout the city, inducing frustration.',''),(1082,'Check what the CEO of CO just posted:Thanks for all the feedback. When it comes to the gameplay and simulation we set goals for the game and we have reached those goals.Surely there are issues that we\'re looking into and fixing bugs, but the overall gameplay experience is what we aimed for. Cities: Skylines II is the better game compared to the first one. If you dislike the simulation, this game just might not be for you. If there is a bug that ruins it for you there\'s a good chance it\'s fixed sometime in the future. Games are a subjective experience and it is impossible to please everyone. There\'s a bugfixing patch on its way soon however, so hopefully we\'ll be able to resolve at least some of the issues that may be a deal breaker for some. We thank you for your patience!For clarity the above is for the simulation and gameplay. The performance is not where we want it to be and we are hard at work to improve it. This is also the reason the consoles were delayed. The modding support is an important part of a Colossal Order game, so it will also be rolling out as soon as possible.We are disappointed we couldn\'t make these aspects of the game ready for you on time, but we refuse to give up. The missing features and platforms will be available in the upcoming months.I\'ll TLDR and simplify it: \'If you don\'t like that it\'s not a real simulation, go **** yourself.\'I applaud the audacity. “Games are a subjective experience”. Y’all can say that when you all deliver the game you advertised. I can’t believe CO wants to die on this hill but with that attitude, no wonder it’s flopping.Luckily I had like €50 worth of CSGO skins so I barely paid anything for this pile of trash.Please don\'t buy this for now. Review was posted 30-11-2023.',''),(1083,'im too lazy firing my wood stove so i got this to heat the room with 900 Watts',''),(1084,'+ Better graphics- Lack of modding support- Traffic AI still bad- Perforamance- Fun disasters etc.Half baked game....',''),(1085,'They should have waited until the game was actually ready to release which it is not.Big L for Paradox.Don\'t waste your money.',''),(1086,'1:50 PM: Crash1:55 PM: Blue Screen2:05 PM: Blue Screen another one2:20 PM: Blue Screen scores again2:30 PM: Crash (90+3)with my ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ RTX 4090 and i9 13900K on low settings. only had BSOD with this game. thanks for this unique experience',''),(1087,'In <3 yrs this will be a classic which will go for a decade. Admittedly bare-bones now but really enjoying it even so',''),(1088,'build penis in city',''),(1089,'After spending more than 1000 hours with Cities: Skylines and enjoying it thoroughly, Cities: Skylines II has been a huge letdown.The amount of (sometimes game breaking) bugs and missing (but promised) functionality is a huge slap in the face. I regret having pre-purchased this just as much as the fact that it took me more than two hours to figure this out, and now Steam won\'t let me refund it. Lesson learned: Deliver first, get paid after.',''),(1090,'screw paradox im tired of this model of release half baked game fluff up numbers before the end of the year by holding a half baked contest that was a giveaway more then anything rude discord staff no sense of accountability and you know that this is going to have 27 dlcs priced between 15-30 bucks a piece its a buisness model that is getting really old and i and many others are getting tired of it if you want to play a city builder get the first one while its on sale its a solid game and worth it if you get some dlc with it which will still come out cheaper then just this base game.its just not good they have been around long enough to do much better then this',''),(1091,'Under baked, little content, many bugs. Not worth it currently.',''),(1092,'I have over 1k hours on CS1, and I have never been more excited for a game to come out since. So it pains me to say, the sequel is total unplayable garbage. Here\'s a few reasons this game sucks so much:1. The simulation (kinda important) won\'t create demand for anything but low-density housing. You have to find ways to trick it into getting a real city.2. Bugs everywhere. One tax bug bankrupted me before giving me millions, totally randomly. Had to turn the tax rate to 0% to stabilize it after exploiting it to generate some money. Might as well just play with unlimited money since the economy is completely broken.3. Game decides what streets are connected and you can\'t change it. Have a roundabout leading into another road? Well too bad, you can\'t rename it without renaming both roads because the game gods decided it\'s just one continuous segment.4. Performance issues, but this is a known issue. It actually ran ok on my system (got to ~50k pop).5. Graphics are oddly gray all the time.6. Glaring lack of basic features: no university campus, no complex parks, no commercial or office specializations, no dirt roads, only one type of pedestrian path, no quays/canals/any water landscaping, and so much more.Basically, this is an unfinished, buggy demo - and even if they fixed the obvious issues it\'s still worse than the original game. Shame on them for selling it at full price. Unfortunately, I\'ll never be able to trust CO again - they disappointed and failed.',''),(1093,'As much fun as I have playing this game the lack of optimization this game has cannot be overlooked. I just lost 4 hours of progress because the game crashed. The frame rate drops a considerable amount every time you manipulate the camera in anyway. The game looks good but feels rushed and incomplete. I feel like now I have to save every 10 minuets to ensure I do not lose any progress. Wish I did that earlier because I now have to rebuild my entire city expansion from housing, resources, even to highway infrastructure. In the future when there has been several updates to deal with these issues I would recommend the game, as for now I can\'t. Buyer beware and now onto taking a long break to deal with the frustration of losing all of my progress.',''),(1094,'barely bearable to play',''),(1095,'Wait until the game is corrected. Once it gets all of the bugs out, it will be a great game.',''),(1096,'All in all, this game is a severe downgrade from the original both in terms of philosophy and in terms of performance. Cities Skylines 1 fans will be disappointed. Some concepts were simplified (almost childish) and some made really complex for no reason.Set a calendar reminder 1 year from now to come back and maybe buy the game. It might be stable by then.Alright, here are the bullet points detailing the issues I came across a bit more.Reasons not to buy (game philosophy):- Portions of the simulation are... simulated... (that was the whole selling point of CS!)Really hope that this is another \"bug\" that will be hotfixed and not core to the game design. It has Sim City Societies vibes right now.Confirmed by the CEO of the company that this is intended: \"If you dislike the simulation, this game just might not be for you.\"- Progression goes through \"XP\" (build a tonne of buildings with 0 pop and progress...)Feels very childish. You don\'t feel that sense of accomplishment for the city improving.- The Tech Tree does not provide you with any meaningful choices that impact your gameplay Feels very out of place in the way that it was implemented. A Tech Tree implies branches and picking a few to get different outcomes. Here, you just mash XP and then unlock everything really quickly.- Building upgrades levels are not reflected visually enough.You really don\'t get that sense that things are improving except that buildings are getting taller.- Wealth = Education level. This completely removes depth to gameplay. People\'s lives don\'t matter anymore, only if they get through certain levels of school.While I understand that we could make that assumption, are we cutting more corners here?- The RCI indicators purely indicate the demand of cims for a category even if this desire would mess up your city.While I like the idea and it sort of helps you, I had to spend quite some time searching through forums for answers on how to achieve demand for certain categories. It feels broken.- Import/Export of services lacks balance and control (happens magically, you can\'t really decide anything) Garbage just magically goes away! Exporting electricity does not recoup the cost of maintenance, making exporting electricity unnecessary. Reasons not to buy (related to \"Early Access\" state of the game):- The game is still being heavily hotfixed- Releasing hotfixes for core game mechanics that end up messing up your save gameI opened a save after a few days and I suddenly had way more income than before which reduced the overall feeling of difficulty of the game now that it was basically just sandbox mode.- The unofficial mod store users received a warning that saved games may just completely break since breaking changes will be made to how some data is handled in saved games!lol- Building upgrades are not balancedYou either have houses bumping up really fast or extremely slowly.- There is no official mod supportNo-brainer on why this is bad... A lot of bugs that the game has could\'ve been fixed by the community already.Reasons not to buy (graphics & performance):- The game is prone to crashing (make sure to enable auto-save as it is disabled by default)- Setting game settings sometimes does not save those settings (double-check that auto-save is enabled...)- (RTX 4070) the graphics end up being super ugly in order for FPS to be above 20- (RTX 4070) the framerate is way too low for the game to be enjoyable - Graphical glitches all over the place (day/night, trees blinking, buildings disappearing, etc...)- No matter how you change the graphic settings (Upscaling, Anti Aliasing, etc...), it doesn\'t feel like those really make things look better (Ugly A or Ugly B)',''),(1097,'The game\'s not ready--they\'re working on it. I wouldn\'t buy it right now...just wait to see if they fix a lot of the bugs before or shorty after the console release. If they fix it up, I\'ll happily change this review for a game I was looking forward to for years.But hey, maybe this simulation just isn\'t for me--at least that\'s what Mariina Hallikainen, CEO and co-founder of the Finnish game development studio Colossal Order has told us all.',''),(1098,'As of the Science Update, I am happy to report that I am finally enjoying this game. The framerates have vastly improved (though I havent had a chance to build anything larger than a mun rocket) and the wobbley rockets are a thing of the past. The science mode finally gives me a sense of progression in the game and the way that they blended the career mode \"quests\" with the science mode works really well in my opinion. It does a good job of guiding new players in what to do next. If you were holding off on buying this game, I actually recommend it now. Sure, it still feels like an early access game, but now the difference is there is actually a game to play instead of a vessel builder. Well done devs, and keep up the hard work. You are showing your community that this game isn\'t a greedy cash grab and that you can deliver on roadmap objectives.',''),(1099,'The game has redeemed itself with the For Science! update. Not only was most of the missing content from KSP1 filled in with the update, but our confidence in Private Division has been restored. As most of the launch issues are gone, and we finally have science, I can finally recommend this game to those who loved KSP1.',''),(1100,'as of the science update it seems this game has finally got on track. this was the feature i was waiting for and it seems like a steady foundation for progression in game. performance has improved since the original launch for me ( rtx 3090, i5 13600k)fingers crossed for more updates as substantial as this that are less than 9 months apart. not out of the woods yet but heading in the right direction',''),(1101,'just play ksp1 until this is actually a finished game',''),(1102,'Well they did make a lot of improvements in the science release, but i think the significantly better reviews mostly come from just folks having reduced their expectations down to rock bottom. And this cleared that hurdle.I just played about 8 hours of the game starting a new science campaign, and the campaign missions are bland but reasonably well thought out. It gives the game some structure.But jeez, none of that can keep your attention away from the just miserable amount of bugs and problems the game still has. I dont know how they keep releasing this game with just unsolveable issues everywhere you go.my favorite bug is the time advance slider. Its just so random. because it has some sort of built in delay switching between options, but you can click it a lot faster than that delay, you are just constantly in 4x speed but actually paused. Or at 1x speed but you cant use your engines because it thinks you are 2x speed still. Its not a game breaking problem, but for old kerbal veterans its just maddening because you do it ALL THE TIME. can you setup manuever nodes while paused? NOPE. gotta do it at 1x speed. But if you are in 1x speed and the game thinks you are in 2x speed, you cant interact with the node. WTF its just stupid.Want to set a target of minimus to do your alignment burn, but you have a sattelite in low earth orbit around minimus? good luck! you cant click on minimus without clicking on the satellite. Oh i will just zoom in then, nope now the satellite is like a giant pixellated icon blocking minimus entirely.I try not to judge it down just because they chose to do something differently than ksp1, but damn, try to check how much fuel you have in a random tank in your setup. You can do it, but its 3 clicks and then if you try and transfer its bugged and it keeps replicating your tank. Why on earth cant you just right click on a tank to see how much fuel is in there?they added a bunch of fancy tick marks to the map view when trying to intercept a planet, but they took away the ONE THING I NEED! the periapsis for the planet approach! its so much easier to intercept when you can minimize that periapsis value. It just makes me feel like these people have never played the original game. The ticks are nicer than the original ksp1 single tick mark i guess, but thats just to get you in the ballpark, you need that periapsis to actually intercept well.they \"fixed\" the janky rockets problem of the original, mostly by just making most of the joints rigid. Thats really how ksp1 ended up fixing it long ago. It was a little more complicated than that but fundamentally thats how it went. The one positive thing i will say, it does look like they are really trying to make it better. I had assumed when it came out that it was just a money grab. This release shows promise. Maybe with another year or two we will actually get there.',''),(1103,'I did purchase this right out of the gate and.. well.. I played for about an hour and hung it up. A lot of things that were mandatory for you to even get to orbit were broken.  I did not even have the trajectory line to maneuver off of... or see if I was going to miss the planet. I just started playing it again just over a week ago. It is fun now.... It does have a long way to go to get to the hype.. but it is early access (looking at the GIANT tag just below where I am typing for reference). The Devs seem to really be working on the feed back provided. Seeing how the game has been refined in the few months it has been in early access is great. Should YOU get it... depends.If you are willing to have an incomplete game from people that continuously worked on the previous iteration for like... a decade that will likely NEVER be a perfect game as they seem to be reaching for the stars (literally) with this game and be okay with that as it will be great fun trying to make theoretical interstellar travel as realistic as possible.. Then this is the game for you. Get it. Play it. Give feed back.. wait.. update.. play it....... If you want a perfect game. Do not get it.If you do not want to deal with the feed back portion and you just want to wait until full release to complain that the game is not the way you want it to be.. then just wait. If you can do better. Download Unreal 5 and get to work.. it is free.',''),(1104,'listen man, i bought this fella on launch and it was not worth it. now it got a bit better because of mods but.. buy this game when autostrut update comes ok?',''),(1105,'I have several hundred hours of flight time with KSP1, and am reviewing this game with several hours of pre-science update, and a few hours post.  I\'ll break this down into two reviews, and will update if I run into anything that changes my mind: Newbies: If you are interested in rockets and think Kerbal might be for you, then I can confidently say that KSP 2 is a good place to start.  The game runs really well, and the foundations of the systems are solid.  You are buying into early access, so there is some jank, but the game will also grow with your capabilities.  I started KSP 1 incredibly early in it\'s beta (pre steam) and envy new players ability to watch a game develop along with their understanding and skills in the game.   The game looks great, and there is so much information provided for the player that there is always an answer for your problem.  If you are at all curious I would say go for it, as long as you are okay with playing early access.  I would not have said that about this game a month ago, but it\'s now at the stage where I can say it has a strong enough foundation to be genuinely fun.  Why play Kerbal?  You will pretty much get an education in the fundamentals of orbital mechanics, while remaining accessible, and fun.  I have several hundred hours in KSP 1 and can honestly say I have learned more from that game than any college course I\'ve taken.  If you have kids who you want to teach about science and the process of discovery I can also recommend this as a teaching tool that is fun, and honestly pretty hilarious for kids.  I play with my 6 year old and my two 3 year olds, and they LOVE this game.  They prefer KSP2 to KSP1, I think because of the visuals, and sound.  Veterans: The game has stabilized immensely and will now be my primary place for playing the game.  It is still early in development, and they have a ways to go before they are at parity with KSP1 but a couple of my biggest gripes with the old engine have been addressed and I cannot go back.  Stability in and out of warp, spinning ships not turning into garbage, the amount of information provided up from by the UI.  I also think the game looks and sounds way better as well.  I totally get why people would be uncomfortable dropping money on KSP2 if they have a fully modded and stable KSP1, and those people should probably wait.  But I find this a better playing game, and the way the engine handles warp, and extreme physics much more bearable, and can\'t go back. If your biggest issue with the game at release was frame rate, buddy I\'ve got some great news for you.  Game runs like butter (mostly) now. Great job Intercept!',''),(1106,'Pros - The game has a lot more character than 1- The tutorials the game offers are \"cute\". - The foundation and underlying physics systems of the game seems to be better than KSP 1 in every way.- It\'s pretty- Runs well on medium-high settings (Nvidia Recommended Settings) on my GTX 3060TI. It is ram hungry though, so having at least 16 is a must, 32 if you can swing it.- PROCEDURAL PARTS!- Exploration is good. Incomplete, but very promising. Cons - There are still some annoying bugs. Only major ones I ran into was the orbit lines going away, Turns out it\'s because the game thinks the ship is on the ground, so recovering the ship and launching again fixed it. The other being parts randomly not being in the same place when reverting or loading a save.- The Maneuver planner needs an overhaul. It\'s a big step back from KSP 1. The planner UI, where you can see the after state of your obit needs to come back. I dislike dragging on the node.- SAS is very twitchy with planes. I can fly them no problem with it off, but as soon as I turn it on, the plane starting \"bouncing\" in the air and is very twitchy. Mixed - It\'s pretty obvious there are a lot of \"holes\" in the content when you\'re playing it. On the other hand, it\'s fairly close to KSP 1, just in a different direction. So it\'s obvious you\'re playing a game with lots of stuff in the works, but it also feels like a game with stuff in the works because there is a lot of obviously missing content.- There are fewer parts. Personally I think this is fine. It makes the game easier to get into and I\'m not overwhelmed with choice. The procedural parts do help fill some of the gaps.- The new UI looks nice, but is less informative and intuitive than the old one. There are a lot of good COL features though. I think this is something that can be improved by just having the devs give some HS kids $50 and some pizza to let them watch them play the game for a day. Wish List - More Procedural parts! I think having procedural tanks should be a minimum. Then instead of unlocking \"bigger\" tanks, you unlock tanks made of different materials that are suited for different applications, like in RP-1.- I want there to be an option (another mode) like Exploration, but with a more realistic progression. Starting with crewed space flights feels a bit weird to this day. I would love to start with sounding rockets, then sats, before sending fruit flies and dogs into orbit before moving onto crewed space flights. Then lock tech behind contracts that are linked to the progression. Maybe the first crewed flights are x-planes to make planes matter more.- A built in simulator for builds. The cheat menu is nice and all, but I think it would be great to be able to run a simulation from the VAB.- Give me a way to actually pilot recoverable stages or do air launches. There is a mod for KSP 1 called FMRS that will drop a save for you when your craft splits into more than one controllable piece. You can fly one of them, then \"time travel\" back to separation and fly the other. It stitches the saves back together for you after. Some sort of \"time travel\" feature could probably be done much better by the devs, and I would love it, particularly because I love doing air launched rocket planes.- Give me better waypoints. They don\'t seem to exist in the game right now. I want it to work like the waypoint manager mod for ksp 1, where you can set waypoints on anything in the game. I can\'t even set a waypoint for the KSC right now to find my way home after flying a plane without opening the map. This is desperately needed.- Improve the UI, particularly the manuver node editor.- MORE SCIENCE! There needs to be more science experiments in the game. In particular I would love to see some experiments that need to be left running for extended periods. Days, months or even years and give you a steady flow of science while they are running.There are some other things on my \"wishlist\", but they were already announced, so I left them out. Verdict, is it worth getting now? The verdict is, I\'m enjoying myself with this game. It offers a bit more character than the first one and while it\'s not quite matching 1 in many areas, it also offers a slightly different experience. If it\'s on sale, it could be worth picking up if you know you will get it anyways. With the planed updates, it should give you a somewhat steady flow of \"new things\" to keep you coming back over the next couple of years.',''),(1107,'As of right now, this game has become fun. It will be even better with the next updates, but right now it\'s almost at feature parity with KSP1 in a less crowded, easier to learn, cleaner package that makes we want to discover all the planets again. So much has been done in terms of quality of life compared to KSP1 that I cant see myself going back to it again, like being able to set delta-v calculations of each stage to any altitude or space individually or free camera movement in the map view. The tech tree is great and makes sense too. Exploration mode is also a clear upgrade from both Science and Career mode in KSP1, the missions are much more like milestones and less \"do x thing at y altitude on z planet\".',''),(1108,'the bugs that stopped me playing previously have mostly been fixed. yes there are still bugs to be fixed, but its MUCH better, and actually playable, thoroughly enjoy this game now',''),(1109,'this game has huge potential, and with a passionate fanbase, and many brilliant people from the ksp1 modding days on the dev team (namely blackrack for atmospherics including scatterer and volumetric clouds, and Anth for bug reporting and QA) i\'d say this game will reach its potential. and with the For Science! update coming on dec 19th bringing science, reentry vfx, and heating systems, as well as a whole slew of other features and an as of yet MASSIVE list of bug fixes, the For Science! update will be the one to save this game',''),(1110,'after the sceince update this game is SO MUCH BETTERGRAPHICS ARE A 10/10GAMEPLAY IS A 9/10 point removed because we still are missing some stuff from ksp1 but its mostly here nowthe game still has some bugs but its now playable and the bugs dont effect gameplay all to muchi think its safe to say  ksp2 pulled a nomans skybtw im getting 30-50 fps on a nvidia gtx 1660 super with mostly high graphics settings so the game is more optiomized now good job intercept and private division',''),(1111,'It is now a game you can enjoy',''),(1112,'hmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmm interstellar',''),(1113,'THEY DID IT ITS GOOD NOW',''),(1114,'Very playable and fun now after the \"for science!\" Update. Missing lots of quality of life features still but its finally good enough for early access.',''),(1115,'It is insane that this game will sit with the Multiplayer tag for years....with absolutely no multiplayer.',''),(1116,'For Science completely changed the game as I knew it would.  I purchased the game day 1 to make sure to get my money in the pot so the devs could see some fruit from their time and I am glad to report I made the right choice.  The game is only 40% done and you have to know that coming in.  With 60% of the game still in development I can definately say its worth the money and will only get better over time.  Stunning graphics, streamline gameplay, and everything that made KSP1 great only refined.  Yes there will still be some issues by my God hike up your pants and make the buy you\'ll be glad you did if your not a whiny brat.Absolutely my favorite game over all other 2023 games I\'ve purchased *BG3 / Robocop / Starfield / Cities Skylines 2/ SOTF included* and its only going to get better.',''),(1117,'Better now with For Science, still isn\'t there yet though.',''),(1118,'One of the best I\'ve played in a while. When I play survival games, I usually get bored and quit after a while. But this game is different. I played it  w/ friends nonstop until I finish the game 100% (there is an achievement for that). But anyway, the dev team did a great job. Play this, it feels like we are living in a Pixar movie! 🩷',''),(1119,'Absolutely amazing game! From the moment you spawn you constantly have something to do and have some sense of progression. Whether it\'s with quests, building or your own gear.I would definitely recommend playing it with a friend (or multiple friends). This makes it even better. Just have a chat, lay back and build some stuff or do some quests together to progress further into the game. The multiple layers of the garden makes it feel like you constantly reach completely new areas with new stuff to do.The combat in the beginning felt a bit off putting and boring, but later on I realised it was actually pretty engaging and fun. Because of the strength of the bugs, different playstyles and weaknesses.Overall I would definitely recommend this game! Probably in my top 5 (online co-op) games of all time.',''),(1120,'A really fun game to play with friends and pretend that life doesnt suck',''),(1121,'Absolutely magical.Captivating design and game world. Would lose track of time running around the back yard searching and further extending my comfort zone.Highly recommend!',''),(1122,'You ever go in an ant hole thinking you\'re safe because there\'s no possible way anything bigger can fit through said hole just for a giant wolf spider to jump into your screen fueling your arachnophobia to a point where you can\'t even think or speak? ...Do you want to?Based on a true story',''),(1123,'Great game and super fun with friends!',''),(1124,'good game. im enjoying it. lots more stuff to do. so, there is a fair bit of content.',''),(1125,'You can kill cute bugs like ladybugs or bees with a two-handed mace made from soldier ant mandibles, and you can wear the hides of cute grubs after brutally beating them to death. it\'s a cool game that doesn\'t hesitate to show the absolute brutality, savagery, and uncalled ferocity of the humanity.',''),(1126,'I\'m still grounded, someone free me.',''),(1127,'when you see the spiders\' eyes turn red it means they fell in love with you, embrace them',''),(1128,'Is this game frustrating sometimes? Yes. Is the game grindy? YesBut is it damn good? Yes!For a game that has some pretty annoying moments, I never seem to not be having fun! Its just always fun to walk around the place, gathering materials to upgrade and to just explore the world. I\'ve not seen the entire map yet, and I doubt I will. But this game is a genuine blast for anyone looking for something to play with friends!',''),(1129,'an amazing and fun game unless you are scared of spiders',''),(1130,'This game provides a whole new perspective to what it\'s like being under 6 ft.Now I am able to empathize more with short people - thanks devs!',''),(1131,'best survival game i ever played, so good weapon and armor tier system, good enemy designs',''),(1132,'I can\'t get enough of Grounded.I have played on and off since early access in 2020 on console from xbox gamepass and have played every major update since. I finished the game at the 1.0 release and haven\'t touched the game since until about 2 weeks ago after I got a PC.After playing the game on PC, I can say that Grounded is one of my top 10 favourite games of all time.Combat, Weapons and Armour:The combat system, with perfect blocking, is a fantastic way to reward players for learning attack patterns and timing parry\'s allowing good players to take on the toughest Insects with ease, creating that fun skill ceiling that makes you want to improve to become a Grounded combat master. Different insects have different weaknesses and resistances making the choice of weapon matter. Not only do each weapon type deal different types of damage, but there is also elemental damage as well adding another layer of choice and skill to killing insects. The armour and weapons get stronger the further you progress and all have unique mechanics to give them all a fresh feel and to keep the game play from feeling repetitive. And the layer of combat don\'t stop there, because there are buffs and debuffs that happen depending on the bug you are facing, so don\'t forget to eat a meal and drink a smoothie as these are ways to get extra buffs to help take down enemies easier. So weather you prefer shooting you\'re enemy with a bow made from wasps, or want the clobber them with a club made from ants, or maybe you want to slice them in two with a battleaxe made from candy, Grounded has got something for you.Mutations:Mutations are a game mechanic that work amazing with the core game adding extra abilities to the player for as long as the player chooses. you unlock different mutations throughout the game by doing different challenges around the yard. Want to run faster, mutation for that, want more hauling strength (carry more stuff), mutation for that, want to minions to fight for you, mutation for that. Mutations are a fantastic and integral addition to the game.Story:I will keep the story section spoiler free. The story progresses at a good pace with different data pieces to help piece together the story. I love how it gives the choice to the player on what to do, but guides them so you don\'t end up never progressing. As you play though the game, different areas of the map have locations you will visit and you get rewarded by unlocking items that will help you take on tougher insects. They really tried to make the story interesting with the players who want more from the story being able to search around for extra pieces of data, whereas if you just want to get through the main story stuff and speed through the progression, you can do that too. It doesn\'t hold your hand and baby you through the game, but doesn\'t require a wiki or youtube video to know what to do next. It\'s hard to talk about the story without spoiling it, so you will have to find out yourself if you play this game.Exploration:finding things to discover is easy because of how much the map is packed full of things to find, with raw science, milk molars, sca.b\'s, new resources, and much more which can give you upgrades, weapons, armour or other goodies. Landmarks can be found around the map and give you a reward for finding them which is a fun way to motivate people to explore the backyard. But if you weren\'t convinced to explore the backyard, you can find a plethora of different insects. From spiders, to beetles, to ants. Some insects fly, some crawl, and some swim. Some friendly, some neutral and some angry. The variety in insects makes the game so easy to sink hours into, learning and mastering the all the insects.Building:The building is easy to understand and has plenty of different things you can build, allowing for creativity. you could build whatever you want really. I\'m currently building a basketball stadium because basketball is a playable sport (to a certain extent) in Grounded. Build yourself a base anywhere you like, just be careful because you may annoy the local insects. Building is what can make a play through of the game a long a fun process, giving you a reason to keep playing after you beat the game to 100%. But if gathering resources doesn\'t tickle your fancy, Grounded has a creative mode allowing you to build whatever you want right away.Bosses:I don\'t want to spoil any bosses because the feeling of walking into a fight not knowing whats coming is a thrilling experience you will get only once. The bosses are all unique, with some being optional and some tied to the story. After facing all of them I can safely say that fighting these bosses with not disappoint. Fighting these bosses give unique and powerful drops making it feel worth fighting the optional bosses. I was not disappointing when facing these almighty foes.Extra challenge:Last little thing to talk about is those who want a challenge. Although there is a hard difficulty (Whoa!), I like a real challenge. At the end of the game you receive a report card, it basically shows stats like \"insects killed\" and \"Deaths\". You also get a grade based on how much of the game you completed (including the optional stuff). So for those who are completionists like me, Grounded has a completionist challenge with a steam achievement tied to it.Grounded will forever be a game I will look back on be glad I got to play it. I highly recommend you play this game.9.5/10Thanks for reading this if you did.',''),(1133,'Good game perfect with more then 1 player and very fun 10/10',''),(1134,'How short \"people\" go about their daily lives. (cant relate i am 6\'1 and very cool :))',''),(1135,'You know, when you see Obsidian Entertainment, the game is going to be good, no doubt. It\'s a survival crafting game with \"Honey, I shrunk the kids\" wacky science stuff. It\'s an awesome game if you want a good crafting survival with a nice story about a goofy scientist inventing a shunking device and an evil corporation doing evil things with it. And you get into this little mess. Like survival crafting? No brainer - go get it.Also, my arachnophobia wanted to add to this review a few words: AAAAAA! IT\'S A GIANT SPIDER! NOOO! DAMN! NOOO! GET IT OFF! GET IT OFF! AAAAAAAA! GOD NO PLEASE NOOOO! AAAAAAAAAA! THEY ARE EVERYWHERE! AAAAAAAAAAHHHHH! RUUUUUUN! RUUUUUUU