g them is to trust a \"guardian\" character that you picked at the start of character creation, and only shows up in weird moments as a deus ex machina? And how does that play into the game? The scenario is a mess. It throws the player from wall to wall, and leaves you wondering \"what? why?\" in a bad way.Secondly, I think, DnD 5th edition is a shadow of its glorious 2, and 3.5 days. The ruleset is a mess unto its own, the barbarian being as sophisticated as a wizard in the name of \"balancing\" and equal power to players. With a party of 4 you end up spending \"considerable time\" trying to figure the optimal setup, character feats, sub character classes, various miscellaneous magics, calculate meticulously number of rages, attacks, damages, bah. I am not a munchkin, but the amount of work you need to do is \"boring\" just to swing an axe.Stealth in the game is dodgy at best. I have played games with better stealth implementation some from Larian itself. The new skill and ability check methods are going to make you \"SAVE-LOAD\" cheat quite a bit. They tried to mitigate that with \"inspirations\" but that wears out quickly. You end initiating dialogue with the wrong character, you pick an item with the wrong character, you walk around with the wrong character....load, load, load...There is also no indication of \"what was missed\" It may be a crucial button, or something trivial. Story should tell that. At least if something important is missed, induct suspense.And back to the story again, in a good game you should rarely if at all go to wikis to \"solve it\". With BG3 and its obscure methods you spend equal time reading wikis and guides as you do playing the game. There is no hand holding of course, but also, I mean, that\'s the point of skill checks right? You have to \"nudge\" the player.Also... critical hits and misses... a disaster in both cases. Bland, boring, tasteless. Not even a flavor text.The inventory is where you will spend most of your game time. Man