er is that there\'s always something to do for solo and cooperative play. The game is a definite buy for gamers who enjoy playing with others to accomplish challenging feats.',''),(1314,'Even better than the base game',''),(1315,'10/10',''),(1316,'GOOOD GAME',''),(1317,'AAA game. Bethesda & Blizzard can\'t make games like this anymore, but Rockfish can.',''),(1318,'It becomes repetitive too fast, main arch/quest losses focus. At times if you dare to transition into a new area as soon as you are able you can get sort of stuck in a heavily unbalance situation that forces you into a lot of grinding that is just not fun.  And going back to the previous area is not always a viable option since the game lvls up everything there too and the quest/missions options left in those areas are repetitive.  Is like hitting walls along the way that wont let you move forward in a meaningful way...just annoying af.  Also, I did not expect space flight dynamics like in star citizen or elite, but what we got is a mix of atmo/space that leaves very little evasive maneuvering options.   Finally, the game only has a few ship frames available for your lvl at any given time, and some look too generic. I did like the premise of the game, graphics, and voice acting.',''),(1319,'If you liked Freelancer from now defunct Digital Anvil from 1996 and wished it had updated graphics, mechanics, upgrade elements, and story...well here you go! I played the ♥♥♥♥ out of Freelancer the early 2000\'s and this is so far the only game I\'ve come across I can really call a spiritual successor. I previously played this on Game Pass for PC and opted to buy it when it went on sale.You have several different ship types to choose from as you play the game, and there are several different areas of space to travel around and explore. The combat is satisfying and while I wish the game had fully animated cutscenes, I\'m okay with the artistic choice they made. Especially since the game is fun to play. My only criticism of the game, is the puzzles can be a bit frustrating sometimes and required me to use Google or YouTube more than once to look for guides with the solution as it\'s not always obvious even after flying around for several minutes looking for clues. That aside, I\'d give this game a solid 9 out of 10.',''),(1320,'Arcade-y, Open-world, space shooter.It doesn\'t try to be anything other than this, and it does it well, and with polish. Very fun if this is what you\'re looking for. I\'m probably about 10+ hours in and I\'ve barely touched the length of this game (The other 12 hours were from early access,) it\'s big. This is quality.The only issues I\'ve had have been with the input binding menu. It\'s very much set up to use controllers, and trying to bind my HOTAS setup has a few hiccups, but it definitely works. Specifically two things: Scrolling the menu is a little glitchy, and it thinks one of my joystick hats is analog so it won\'t let me bind specific things to it. That\'s it... the only thing bad I can say about it.',''),(1321,'I would absolutely recommend the original EVERSPACE, one of the greatest space games ever made.Unfortunately I can\'t do the same for the sequel, which is very, very disappointing. I wish this wasn\'t the case.In short the sequel is like a box of chocolates, but it\'s 80% plastic and 20% chocolate. It feels like a grind with no payoff.In the original game everything was balanced and everything had a purpose, the story was great, the characters were great, you knew where you were going and it was a challenge to get there. While the sequel doesn\'t know what it wants to be. It\'s more \"open world\" but the gameplay is not complex enough for flying around in empty space to be interesting. Proof that more isn\'t always better.It\'s not the first game to fall for the open world \"throw every idea into a mixer\" trap and it probably won\'t be the last. Developers need to learn from history or be doomed to repeat it.',''),(1322,'I\'m using a H.O.T.A.S setup and this game will challenge you to refine your joystick/thruster skill set and build up on it.',''),(1323,'finished main story on hard before realizing i could toggle inertia dampening.......................comfy game :)',''),(1324,'If you like puzzle games and searching around for things this is for you. If you tend to \"cheat\" through 3 pages this is for you. If you feel all that time of looking around to find the things is a cheap way of creating in game time then it is not for you.',''),(1325,'Fun space combat, excellent environmental design with a serviceable plot. Puzzles can be annoying and time consuming especially when they hide that last button where its not obviously visible, and the difficulty curve flips from being hard early game to easy as your ship becomes more powerful. Still a worthy spiritual successor to the venerable Freelancer.',''),(1326,'It\'s not quite what I expected after playing Everspace 1, but I was pleasantly surprised. There is a well developed plot, it\'s no longer a roguelite like Everspace 1, it is an RPG with a strong story and lots of dynamic and relevant decisions impacting the game. Have to save that pilot but accidentally shoot them instead? There will be consequences for that accident which impact the quest/game, but never prevent you from progressing. This is a big plus for immersion and realism in my books. There is a relatively realistic economy, prices vary by regional demand, and by buying low in one region you can sell for a higher price in another region and generate income just by shipping cargo back and forth. This may not be for everyone but there is a certain sense of accomplishment that comes from learning and leveraging the various regional demands to your financial advantage, this game definitely provides that. It is not necessary to do this as part of the progression of the game / story as far as I can tell, it\'s just an added bonus for those who want to rake in the credits.Flying feels great. It\'s similar to No Mans Sky if you\'ve played that. The controls are a bit tedious (as with most flight simulator games) but once you\'re acclimated to them they are very fine-tuned and there are some interesting options available to you in the settings, like disabling inertia dampeners to give a more realistic space-physics experience. With dampeners on, your spacecraft will be more manageable, though still with some carry-over movement which lends the flying aspects of the game some great depth and realistic feel. I think of this game as a hidden gem in the space/flight genre, if you are debating giving it a try I would urge you to take the leap. This is a fantastic game for the price and one that I will probably start replaying as soon as I finish it.',''),(1327,'Better than the first in pretty much every way.  Just the space \"pew pew\" fix I needed this year.',''),(1328,'This is truly a masterpiece in the space fighter pilot genre. The story keeps things on track, plenty of side activities and quests.  The world is open and fairly large for being hand crafted The Graphics and attention to detail is generally amazing. I have only seen the game improve as the early access continues. The quality of game play is top notch, controls are very responsive while the ships fly smooth and feel great to fly. This game is great with controller or KB&Mouse. If they can continue to expand on the game\'s replayability factor then EverSpace 2 could stand as one of the best in space combat.',''),(1329,'There is a lot to like in Everspace 2.If you are unfamiliar with the title, in short, the game is a single player story driven space looter-shooter.It is a beautiful game, well designed and very visually appealing, and while the story isn\'t going to win an Oscar the story is still well paced and decently written. The game loop is pretty strait forward: Explore, Fight, Upgrade, Repeat. With that said if you are a fan of extremely deep and complex space games like Elite Dangerous or Eve Online to name a few this game is going feel much more shallow in what it has to offer, but personally I feel like that is a good thing. I wish the game supported Co-op and there was a little more variance in the loot, but this is being a little knit picky.Also, the Developers are awesome, Rockfish Games is a small company based out of Germany and they are very passionate about their game and it shows in there many steamed Q&A\'s.',''),(1330,'Compared to the first one, this one is a lot better',''),(1331,'*Most important thing is the game is designed with consistent play in mind, you can play it for the story but all the upgrade systems and contracts/side missions make it hard to get a banger ship without spending time just cruising around and doing side hustle. This can be a bad or a good thing but this is not an 10 hours story game*Successor to Freelancer to anyone who\'s old enough to get the reference yet it lacks the weight behind the story and immersion. Instead, however, there are a lot more fun encounters and puzzles you can solve that turn the game into a \'5 min rollercoaster\' chain. It\'s fun to zone out and just vibe.Something I don\'t like is a POI travel system where instead of jump gates (though they\'re still here) you go to a different \'map\' and fly to next point and then you arrive and enter a new scene. It saves on resource and game scope, I get it, but I wish there was a bit of seemless-ness to the look as you have it in elite dangerous or no mans sky. Occasional asteroid belts or random anomalies would be so sick in a space game. But each instance looks great and well done despite the immersion break.',''),(1332,'This is what GoF2 was meant to become.',''),(1333,'Bit of scavenging, bit of dog fights, bit of flying, bit of leveling your ship. Great mixture. Haven\'t had this much fun in space since freelancer. I am in love.',''),(1334,'extremely fun space shooter with great controls, flight mode and nice graphicsthe variation in ships as well as the upgrading and component system lets you customize your ship to your playstyle, depending on if you like to hang back and kite, get right into close range brawls, have your own drone army or dodge in and out of range with a fast fighterit reminds me a lot of the classics like Freelancer and Privateer in a very good way!the story is decent, voice acting is also very solid (and often very funny)',''),(1335,'I would give this a low replayability rating but it kept my attention for a good amount of time. The story is relatively forgettable but the gameplay was good.',''),(1336,'Same looter shooter formula minus exciting loot.  The part that broke my will to continue is that every area has environment \"puzzles\".  These puzzle had me flying around non stop picking things up and dropping them off at other points, often \"rewarding\" me with a menial upgrade and a component for ship upgrades.  I wanted to skip every one of these long drawn up boring events but instead decided to skip the rest of the game completely.  On the plus side the games does allow you to skip cut screens and mute voices, a fitting combo for the \"story\" presentation.',''),(1337,'Total War: Warhammer 3 - An Actual ReviewIt\'s quite difficult finding an actual review on TW:Warhammer 3 as the Steam page is taken up by CA\'s exploitative DLC policies, their dumb forum comments and the White Knights trying to defend everything. I\'ll get to all that stuff in a while. But how\'s the actual game?Game PlayJust in case someone doesn\'t know, here\'s the quick and dirty about the TW series. It\'s a turn based 4X game on the strategic map and a expansive RTS on the tactical battles. It\'s geared more towards combat (eXterminate) than the other 3Xs (eXplore, eXpand, eXploit) with those engaging RTS fights. If you really are new to the series this game has a pretty thorough tutorial as well. Bonus points for that.As someone who owns all 3 TW: Warhammer games, I\'m actually at a bit of a loss to find the differences between War 2 and 3. There are different factions available in Warhammer 3 and some quality of life improvements, a few new interesting mechanics and expanded settlement battles. The settlement battles were divisive on launch but I personally I think they\'re decent if a bit confusing. The improvements are minor but they do add up.The combat maps are decidedly better, with a few more obstacles, hills and the like to use to your advantage. The maps have come a long way since the wide-open Warhammer 1 maps. Graphics have been improved over the life of the series and the game is really a joy to look at. Of course, there are the new factions. I\'ve been playing Grand Cathay for the last 30 hours and they \"feel right\" to me. I like generally playing the good factions and tend to turtle a bit. Having a faction with some decent troops behind a huge wall is kind of up my alley. But I\'m looking forward to playing some of the other factions as well. That\'s the thing about this series, especially if you have the prior games and DLCs. As long as you don\'t get bored of the game play, there\'s always someone new to play.The main draw of either is in owning the previous entries. War 2 has the Mortal Empires mode, which combines the factions and maps of Warhammer 1 and Warhammer 2 (if you own both games on the same platform). Warhammer 3 has the Immortal Empires game mode, which has the combined maps and factions of all three games. It\'s massive, with about 180+ factions playing at the start. But if you don\'t own the prior games, you\'re going to be very, very frustrated when you open the game and find there are around 25 different factions to play and you have access to maybe 6 or 7 of them. More on the DLC later.The world-building/city-management hasn\'t changed much. You still build from a relatively small pool of buildings (level 5 for a capital, 3 for a settlement), grow your city to build better troops. Depending on your difficulty level you may find yourself swimming in money which means it\'s time to build more armies and fight some more.I\'ve already mentioned the RTS battles. They\'re really good here. The Warhammer universe, with its magic and very diverse unit types, really suits this engine. In some prior TW games the combat felt \"samey\" very quickly as you fought essentially the same units with different skins over and over again, Not so here. Each race feels very different and I find myself trying to understand my opponents more in this game. What do they have? Magic? Flying Units? Poison? Mega artillery? How do I overcome that? Of course, there\'s always the auto-resolve for when you get tired of combat.Bugs, DLC, Creative ASSembly and Community UproarIt wouldn\'t be a fair review if I didn\'t mention why this game has Mixed ratings. (1) By all accounts it released in a pretty bad state - buggy, slow, etc. I didn\'t get into this until the 4.1 patch and in 30 hours I\'ve hit only 1 bug that caused me to have to drop to the desktop. There may be some other bugs and issues with factions but I\'m not in the weeds enough to know what those are. There are still some lengthy loading times for combat maps (30 seconds to 1 minute) as well. So while it was buggy, it\'s not really that way any longer. Still, you only have one chance to make a first impression and War 3\'s wasn\'t great for many folks.(2) The DLC policies are exploitative. First of all, if you don\'t own TW:War 1 and 2, you\'re going to HATE loading this game up because most of the Immortal Empires races will be locked. If you\'re still enjoying Warhammer 2 and you are looking to expand your experience, you would do well to purchase the first game right now instead of the third. It\'s cheaper, has just as much new content, and will enable you to play Mortal Empires which is an incredible campaign. You\'ll get to explore The Old World from Warhammer 1, which then borders the location of Warhammer 3. So you\'ll be able to orient yourself better if you go on to complete the trilogy at some point on the future. (3) Then there are the DLC prices. $25 for the Chaos Dwarves? That\'s insane. They raised the prices of their DLC and now are offering less content for each. Yes, the DLC is optional but it\'s still just...wrong, especially for loyal fans who own the first 2 games and much of that DLC. Shame.(4) Then there\'s Creative (Ass)embly\'s attitude towards their community.  There\'s really no excuse for their widespread forum bans or telling people the right to leave a negative comment on the forums is a \"privilege\". They\'ve also gone to war with some of their best YouTube channels like Legend of TW. Frankly,  CA needs a rectal-cranial extraction. The community has every right to be upset and CA needs to do better.ConclusionWhen it comes right down to it, I\'m enjoying the game. The game play, races, Immortal Empires campaign....it\'s a pretty great experience. So yeah, I\'m going to recommend it with the caveats I mentioned above. (1) If you have 1 & 2 and enjoy the game play then 3 is pretty much a must-buy. (2) If you don\'t have 1 & 2 and want to try one of these titles with a good tutorial, this is also a great choice so long as you understand the DLC spam. (3) But if you have that FOMO and you\'re going to get upset about not having access to 80% of the races in Immortal Empires, stay clear. Go buy #2, get some of the DLC on sale and play that one instead. You\'re getting pretty much the same experience for less money. Then if you want to expand, buy the 1st game for more races. Only then should you dive into #3.',''),(1338,'\"The right to a positive review is a privilege.—it is not an entitlement you earn by making a game\"',''),(1339,'I just realized I fell into a similar trap when making fun of the Sims 4 pricing policy. The only difference is that you can declare war on your annoying neighbors in this one.',''),(1340,'\"The right to discuss is a privilege—it is not an entitlement you earn by playing the game\" - CA',''),(1341,'The right to a positive review is a privilege',''),(1342,'Solid dev/art teams are being let down by marketing/growth teams.',''),(1343,'CA has become greedy and lazy. \"The right to discuss is a privilege—it is not an entitlement you earn by playing the game\" is terrible.',''),(1344,'I want so badly to be able to recommend this game, but I simply cannot. Whoever is directing this latest trend with the Total War franchise is milking the good reputation of the series for profit and eroding any good will their audience might have left over from the initial joy of seeing a game made with so much effort put into it. Leaving negative reviews is not enough if they are laughing all the way to the bank.One must simply stop buying products that are not worth the money. Go outside, watch a film or play an old Total War game instead. I won\'t be buying the latest DLCs until CA is done milking this property and Valve starts flogging them for 80% off, and I suggest you do the same.',''),(1345,'Uninstalled. I will not support developers or publishers that treat their fans the way Creative Assembly does with Sega and Feral Interactive supporting it.All three have lost my business.',''),(1346,'Bought the game only to find that like 60% of factions are dlc blocked, I immediately refunded.',''),(1347,'I\'ve thrown a lot of money at the TW series and had fun for many, many years.From the early Rome to the madness that is Warhammer trilogy.Recent company policies, questionable PR moves, drop in product quality and pure greed remind us just how quickly can things go south.Vote with your wallet.F**k CA',''),(1348,'\"The right to discuss is a privilege—it is not an entitlement you earn by playing the game\" - CA',''),(1349,'I cannot recommend this game, not because the game is overly bad, but because the company that makes has grown outright hostile towards their player base. It has been an increasing trend over several years and has come to the point whe