led with bug after bug and crash after crash.. bye bugthesda :) paid all the money i did on this trash like a fool.. don\'t be like me, just don\'t buy or pay for the game and you\'re good. it should be free. feels like it\'s still in beta and i mean beta not public test servers',''),(1374,'this game is like an abusive relation ship i hate everything about it and i want to kill my self every time i boot it up but i just keep saying it\'s just a little quirky',''),(1375,'we\'re living in microtransaction hell!!!!prepare to pay a monthly subscription if you want to play the game that you already paid for',''),(1376,'I stopped playing this game due to FOMO on season/battle passes. Games like this should follow Halo Infinite, or Dead By Daylight where you can go back to every season willingly.',''),(1377,'Why the ♥♥♥♥ is it so complicated to cancel my Fallout 1st subscription?',''),(1378,'TLDR: The game is still buggy and glitchy, barely worth getting at a discount, only get if its free or on a major discount.So after five years i finally decided to take a crack at fallout 76. I got it during the last black friday/cybe monday sale for 8 bucks or so. And after looking into other peoples reviews i kept hearing the same thing, \"the community is the best part\" and i 100% agree. The community is very kind to new comers, it isnt toxic, it isnt filled with griefers. Just nice people wanting to share the loot and help ease you into the game. But after that the game falls apart.As of right now over 5 years since launch the game is still glitchy and buggy. Although im sure its better since release it isnt at a acceptable state, especially for a company the size of Bethesda. For me personally at around 65 hours or so ive encountered tons of issues such as:Not launching or being able to sign in nearly every time the first timeMajor to minor visual bugs, such as \"ghosting\" where ill see the outlines of trees or building clippingHaving my character get stuck in the gun aiming animation, unable to heal, use vats, bring up the pipboy, or reloadClipping and falling through the world occasionally when using the cannibal perkGetting stuck in doors or other movable objects in the worldAnd encountering an insanely broke main story quest where im forced to fast travel away and back over and over and over again to try and fix broke npc path finding. So youd think after 5 YEARS they would have fixed these things right? Major issues that heavily impact players during the most basic day to day issues or even a major quest in the main story. Cyberpunk fixed itself, no mans sky fixed itself but not fallout 76. Other then glitches and bugs, the game is basic MMO stuff. Grinding materials, overly long quests sending you back and forth a hundred times, Basic ten minutes enemy waves as events, cosmetic grind etc. If your into that stuff youll more then likley have a good time but im finally hitting the wall and finally getting fed up with the game.I think if the best thing people can say about a game is that \"Its fun with Friends!\" or \" The game has a great community!\" then you as a company have failed. ANY game is fun with friends no matter how boring or bugged or simple it is. Having your community have to help and pander to newbies to keep them coming back isnt a good thing, but bethesda doesnt care. If they did they wouldnt have left the game in the state that it is right now. They wouldnt be going to reviews telling people they are wrong and showing how insecure they are about the garbage they put out. They would have made it up to their fans not gave them the middle finger and refused to give refunds, or leak personal information, or give a few bucks worth of in game currency to collector editon buyers, or put out such a ♥♥♥♥ game for a cash grab. DO NOT BUY FOR FULL PRICE, go to a discount website like G 2 A or wait for a sale.',''),(1379,'This game is still broken, can\'t even keep a resolution change without you having to create a custom .ini file and after \"fixing\" the resolution issue the game just refuses to load beyond the login creen and freezes, was excited to play this since it\'s basically fallout online but damn.',''),(1380,'Another game ruined by multiplayer. All we wanted was team co-op and you chained us down with lag instead.',''),(1381,'I know I will get hate for this review, but this is what i have to say about F76.I get it this is an \"MMO\" even though it feels more like just multiplayer anyway, what is great that you are able to SELL your stuff to other players who visit your set up shop, however while you are allowed to sell whatever you gather, but your space is so limited that practically I am always struggling with it. Okay so there is partial \"solution\" for it. Why partial? Because you get unlimited space for JUNK items only and that costs money. Are you kidding me? Why would i waste my money for partial solution when this should be in game by default without costing money. And top of that developers do not want to expand default inventory/stash space which at the moment is 1,200 KG, seems a lot? Not really, it will be filled within couple hours because Junk takes most of space and if you want to save weapons it will be full sooner. You would think that entering Power Armour could ease your inventory struggle? Nah, for some stupid reason whatever you are wearing (modified gear that expands your inventory) before entering power armour, your character\'s inventory has about 250 space for example and after entering power armour then you will lose all those buffs. Really? Like your character is undressing everything before using power armour? That was not a thing even in Fallout 4. So wearing power armour reduces your inventory even more, because P.A disables modified armour buffs. Either I walk around and get into combat with just my modified regular gear that gives additional inventory space and die within 3 seconds or i enter power armour and lose all additional space and walk around slow as molasses and survive for 10 seconds.I like to gather and collect stuff across the game even weapons which i would like to sell to other players but this mechanic is Just plain horrible.Microtransactions, really? You already sell game for 40 euros by default and you keep adding new cosmetic $hite to the game for what reason? Only thing you can interact from cosmetics you sell in game shop are chairs and couches the rest is garbo.Either double the size of stash or make special subscription for unlimited junk only that sells for 2.99 a month and we have a deal.I stopped playing F76 around March, 2023 and now only recently re-downloaded it at the end of November, 2023 and I can\'t just can\'t play it this way. I lose interest as soon as i load in into server.Inventory management is killing me.',''),(1382,'If I could pick a \'so-so\' option I would.Unlike a lot of people I came into 76 looking for a buddy-multiplayer experience, rather than either a solo experience or an MMO experience. Like most things you do with your friends, it was pretty fun for a while. The setting is interesting enough and there are a handful of standout areas and quests that were genuinely interesting and surprising. The progression system is interesting enough to hold interest and the capture-point minigame is neat. However, at the bottom of 76 there is something oddly hollow that I would argue is actually present in Bethesda\'s solo Fallout games (3 and 4 respectively) but is cranked up to 11. First a comment on the multiplayer experience: the game is oddly hostile to premade groups. The gameplay loop assumes you go back to base regularly which, with three or four regulars, is tedious. Also some dungeons and quest givers simply don\'t let you have everyone in the zone at the same time, so you have to break up the group to each do something solo before meeting back up again. This is part of the compromise with having choices in the game or with having content that is meant to appeal to soloplay but completely takes you out of a fun romp with your friends so three people can each have identical, separate experiences for some reason. Okay so onto the hollowness. Bethesda open world games thrive by giving you the impression that there is something new to find just over the next horizon. 76 is certainly big enough to accomplish this, and for the first 20-50 levels or so it does this fine, and frankly, the first 20-50 levels is enough content for some people and if it is, this game is fine. However, after that point, you start to see through the game systems. What\'s on the next horizon is another near identical boss fight, a group event that requires almost no input from you, another achievement based task that might net you a new hat or something; in other words, you learn there is nothing new to discover, just more tasks you\'ve already done before or environments you\'ve already seen. Combined with the fact that, by it\'s nature, the game requires you to consistently revisit old areas or do some things repeatedly, and the illusion that there\'s a world with things to do and discover peels away, revealing the MMO side of the game.The MMO side of the game is... fine, if a bit easy. It\'s similar to most other late-stage mmos where you grind the same tasks repeatedly for marginal gains. If you\'re hoping the endgame is PvP, you\'ll be disappointed. This game isn\'t awful, it\'s fine, and it\'s really where Bethesda\'s Fallouts were heading all along.',''),(1383,'Boring unskippable dialogs and having no relatable questline from begining, make this game too boring to bother.',''),(1384,'They sell bundles and individual items on the store that you will suddenly lose access to and no signs of a patch to fix the issue, no refunds for the effectively stolen money, etc. Still riddled to death with bugs',''),(1385,'100% recommend this game to ppl who loved game design of modern tomb raider trilogy..This game is Wiedzmin3 and Tomb raider mashed together in a mixer with a lot of downgrades in gameplay no smooth movement and aim feels like sponge instead of normal mouse.(if you play this game you know what i mean).The story is decent in the main parts.. sometimes animations are out of sync with sound, sometimes sound doesnt even load.. But this issue is mainly in side missions and random quests. In main missions it happens rarely.The world and npcs feels as flat as airport runway because you can bump into them, slice them and they wont even notice your presence.. some does with one sentence ussualy containing one word .. they wont even move or anything when they get to contact with you.. basicaly like a randomly moving pillars.This is amplified when you get to market in Meridan which sounds like there is a lot of npcs yelling at each other or doing some trades but in fact there are only few npcs there hardly any moving mouth like talking.. A lot of the positives goes into technical side of the game.. Like how well devs managed to hide all loading screens.. Sometimes even too well that if you manage to go into certain location without poping the loading animation the game either gets corrupted or start to slowly load all the assets soo it will drasticaly decrease your fps.. Both happened to me several times during exploration.On negative side of things: Hidden damage scaling with your character level.. I saw this when i slowly progressed trough game. On start i was trying to do stealth kills because they were highly efficient but on lvl 55 I found myself just oneshotting most of the low health robots like scrappers,watchers etc. with my spear(without dlc you cant have modifications on it soo i didn\'t put it on until i started playing dlc)Also what trows me off a lot was many instances of console movement where i couldn\'t shoot until i stand still or vice versa.. Happened in some \'\'Dungeons\'\' also you can\'t do more than 2 things at the same time.. Like you can\'t run, drink potions and have focus activated.Mounts in this game are basicaly obsolete thing you shouldn\'t use unless you want to make your life miserable. They can\'t jump unless the game decide its good time to jump, they can\'t jump down from things because it\'s too steep for them even if its just 20cm fall and unless you go by predeterminated road your mount will run slower than it should.Same thingy goes for parkour/swimming in this game.. You can do cool stuff with parkour or just swim really fast but only if you go where the devs want you to go. Otherwise Aloy refuse to get up from water even tho she is basicaly swimming in a 20cm pot. same goes to parkour.. she can jump from wall to wall even 4meters away but when it comes to basic stones you are lucky to not die and you need to spam spacebar to even make her jump somewhere.. Also if you go too high in mountain which you technicaly can the game will automaticaly kill you and respawn you on last saved spot.But hey it still have a decent story soo try this game when it gets discounted.',''),(1386,'Highly recommend this one. I grabbed it for $12 on a sale and it was so worth it. The stories are great. The atmosphere and immersion factor is great. The visuals are great. The NPC animations while they are speaking to you - are not great - at all. I turned the music down to 60% but maybe that\'s just my speakers. NPC\'s will sometimes talk over each other and cause you to miss some dialog. Or you\'ll be in a town talking to someone and a music band will appear beside you and start playing. Subtitles help with that.Zero Dawn is a unique experience, but I think it is similar in some ways to Assassin\'s Creed Odyssey (without oceans and boats). If you liked Odyssey but felt it was too big, then you will appreciate Zero Dawn which is still rather large and diverse but doesn\'t feel overwhelming.Non-Spoiler Warning: You\'ll get a Power Cell at the beginning of the game and you\'re told to find more. Most of them are locked to story progression and you will not be able to find them all until almost the end of the game.This game runs very well on the old LED Steam Deck docked to a 1080p TV using an xbox wireless controller, with most of the settings on High.',''),(1387,'I liked it.This game kinda splits itself into two uneven parts for me. The lesser part is the ubisoft-ish open world with dosens of funpoints (tm) and the writing that is waaay too young-adult-novel for it\'s own good. It\'s all perfectly functional - this is one of the better ubisoft-ish open worlds out there. It\'s just a tad uninspired. The better part is the apocalypse event in this post-apocalypse game. There are big parts about what lead up to this world, and I was 100% into it. It was just deliciously bleak and hopeless and brutal and I loved it beginnig to end. Kinda wished the present parts were more about that and less about the Mary-sue adventures with her harem of hunky boys.Oh well.',''),(1388,'Beautiful game!',''),(1389,'Great game, but the port does have it\'s flawsI\'m one of the nerds that wasted a lot of time playing (and getting a platinum trophy) on the PS4 version of this game, and absolutely loving the game. By far one of the best RPG titles out there! There are definite cons and pros like any game, but the cons are more about the core of what makes RPG games the way they are, and why i play very few of them.Pros:-Very captivating story which does a pretty solid job fleshing out and keeps interesting throughout the game.-Combat is pretty well balanced though your addiction to dodging will be the key to surviving at least 75% of battles.-Aesthetically, a masterpiece of a game, though it being the first huge title for a company like Guerrilla since the Killzone series (which I never was as invested in and never were as big as the Horizon series has been.) and the first in the series it definitely feels a bit lackluster/disjointed in the talking sections as the characters sometimes have unnatural movement (NPC classic moments) or the lip movement doesn\'t match the tone/volume of some of the lines they say. Not uncommon for the first in a series to have those issues. Those things aside the beauty of the game is incredible and it feels huge and exciting once you get going (mostly after you leave the Embrace).-Big array of weapons, equipment, outfits, machines ect. It left me feeling like there was always something to do and much to explore. At times it was overwhelming, but as you get more familiar and understand the curve of the difficulty as you play on everything tends to work out as what you primarily will fight with and wear during certain encounters.-Much to do and explore and it kept me coming back as most side quests were usually beneficial and relatively unique, but no game is immune from repetition ESPECIALLY in an RPG title lol.Cons: (there maybe some spoilers but i\'ll try and keep it as ambiguous as i can and censor most spoilers)-The endless running. it makes sense with such an open environment that you need to flesh out as much as possible and being a true RPG the game is going to be just massive, but if you\'re ok with sometimes just running 3 miles because you don\'t have any fast travel packs and you somehow missed that pack of striders running amok. It sometimes feels like a drag, but it\'s part of the game play.-This being a port it will have it\'s glitches from time to time, and i had a game breaking glitch initially where if i looted something too quickly it would either freeze momentarily or drop down to so slow for 20-30 seconds that it was less than a frame every 3 seconds. Then it would freeze to the point that it permanently ran at like 1/10th FPS which also slowed my PC to that speed until i restarted my whole laptop. I found a fix which resulted in me going to the properties tab in the game and turning off full screen optimizations which has fixed the issue, buuuut it was an issue i was having. Also some textures take a crap in certain cut-scenes which is jarring, and sometimes funny at times.-Slow progression at times. Just RPG stuff I\'m not always a fan of, but I will say some of the upgrades are worth the work to acquire.There\'s more i could elaborate on, but those are some of my pros and cons I have about this game. The cons are more about the issues of the port as those issues were never something i experienced with the PS4 version of the game.Should you buy this game at full price: I initially did for the PS4 and didn\'t regret it, but as for this version I\'d say wait for a sale as I did. There\'s just enough issues that SHOULDN\'T be issues, and mostly with it being a port it takes away from the high price take of $50 still. This being said a friend of mine hasn\'t had a single game breaking issue so your experience may vary from mine.Do with this info what you will. Have a nice day!',''),(1390,'Great story, questionable mechanics and stealth',''),(1391,'Wanted to enjoy this game but couldn\'t. Generic and boring. I\'m not one of those weirdos that hated this game because the player character is too masculine or something though- let me make that clear. I dislike this purely on a gameplay level. Aloy does not need to look different or whatever',''),(1392,'Horizon Zero Dawn builds a world where smooth-brained tribal cultists worship fallout bunkers and try to convince big jaw children that they\'re not real people.The old world plot line affords you the distinct pleasure of Lance Reddick patronizing you while you spelunk for orphan clues. As you progress, you discover elon musk takes credit for things he doesn\'t do and isn\'t actually that cool of a guy. This is overall quite engaging but the plot holes are closer to plot craters - cough - bow and arrow kills megamind machines - cough.Many new world quests, i.e. things that don\'t pertain to old world tech, are as developed as the cultists frontal lobes. At one point, you have to prevent 2 bombs from going off so you push one out a window which explodes and ignites the second one - this is considered a bomb squad success.I think the devs found this out themselves as the spartan tundra hellscape dlc is damn near better than the base game. That said, no matter what portion you play, you will still be fighting the highly precise aim system that controls like a hummingbird after a bump of coke.Oh yeah, and the facial animations are better than Starfield. Bethesda can suck me and Obsidian made the good ♥♥♥♥.',''),(1393,'Absolutely loved the game!It\'s got everything I could want in a game. The development of the story was fabulous, Massive creatures with destroyable tech, a rich environment, amazing detail.. and the characters! I fell in love with Aloy nearly immediately. Such a great game, I can\'t sing its praises enough.',''),(1394,'If you can push through the robotic facial animations and embarrassing dialogue, you\'ll find a solid open-world game with cool robo-dinosaur fights. Not much more to say.',''),(1395,'There you go PlayStation, TAKE ALL MY MONEY JUST BRING RAGNAROK-GOD OF WAR FOR PC AS WELL',''),(1396,'Title: A Promising Blend with Minor HiccupsRating: ★★★★☆I recently played this game on my Steam Deck, and I must say, the visuals on the smaller screen are impressive. The fusion of Assassin\'s Creed Odyssey and Fallout styles creates a unique atmosphere that keeps you engaged.While the FPS drops occasionally occurred, they weren\'t game-breaking and didn\'t overshadow the overall experience. The intriguing storyline, complete with unexpected plot twists, kept me hooked from start to finish.However, the game\'s attempt at promoting inclusivity felt forced, with a noticeable imbalance in character portrayal. It\'s disappointing to see most white males depicted as villains, alcoholics, or ex-war criminals. On the flip side, the positive portrayals of characters often come with unnecessary details like being gay or vegan, raising questions about the relevance of such specifics in the game.Despite these concerns, the game manages to deliver an enjoyable experience, blending elements from popular franchises. With some adjustments to its approach on inclusivity, it has the potential to be an even more captivating adventure.',''),(1397,'I vividly recall watching Horizon\'s debut through a streamer\'s eyes, initially drawn in by its stellar graphics and compelling storyline. The game\'s standout feature, combat against machines, adds an exhilarating twist to an already engaging experience.The mechanics are a standout highlight, particularly the ability to scan enemies for weak spots and tailor arrow types accordingly. The variety—regular, tear, shock, frost, fire arrows—enhances strategic depth, making encounters truly immersive.Visually, Horizon hits a perfect score. The synchronization between mouth movements and voice acting is impeccable, complementing the stunning graphics that beautifully craft its art style.One facet of the storyline that left a lasting impression was Aloy\'s journey from societal rejection to becoming a beacon of hope. Her evolution from an outcast to a revered figure, saving countless lives from the looming machine threat, is a captivating narrative turn.Environments remain consistently refreshing, devoid of repetition. Each area brings new experiences, save for the familiar herbs, maintaining a diverse and captivating world.Immersed in the game\'s audio with headphones on, I found it both captivating and functional, aiding in tracking enemy movements and adding depth to encounters with satisfying combat sounds.The ability to override and stylishly dismantle machines stands as a unique and thrilling feature, further elevating the gameplay experience.While encountering a few minor bugs—like arrows passing through enemies and herbs stuck in rocks—these were hardly detracting factors from an otherwise flawless adventure.With the inclusion of a New Game+ feature, Horizon offers the opportunity to increase the challenge while retaining progress. This feature, combined with varied dialog options and reduced fast travel, adds substantial replay value.In summary, Horizon deserves a perfect score of 10/10. It comes highly recommended. Its immersive world and gameplay beckon players to experience it repeatedly. Embrace the title of Nora and delve into this remarkable journey—it\'s an experience you truly deserve.',''),(1398,'ALOOOOYYYYYYYY',''),(1399,'hot redhead',''),(1400,'I just have a lot of fun running around and killing machines.  Wasn\'t a huge fan of the prologue, just baby Aloy wasn\'t as much fun to play, but once I could get out and non-linear, it was so much more fun.Not the best game I\'ve ever played, but I enjoy it quite a bit, and am having fun exploring all the places that are available.',''),(1401,'Good port of a good game',''),(1402,'I\'ve got to say amazing !I used to finish it once in my PC before i bought it on steam.. and i read every single note and voices of the game ..and dude.. it\'s a huge idea of how the worlds goes inside another world that horizon made.you see all the robots and still have all the traditional folk human beings!graphic is awesome for a 2017 game.equipment and all the staffs u can do is nice though.well done SONY!Rate: 8.7/10',''),(1403,'Absolutely adore this game and Aloy. Worth it even when it is not on sale, and especially when on sale. Story was interesting and the graphics were absolutely stunning. Fighting mechanics were sophisticated yet quite easy to learn and master. You can take fighting the robots from silent strikes in stealth or just cause ultimate havoc. Absolutely love this game, so easy to get lost in the game. I\'ve been waiting for wild west release on pc in early 2024 and I will 100% continue to wait.',''),(1404,'I\'ve played half an hour and the visuals and feel of the game are absolutely stunning. I\'m constantly questioning how my computer can run this beautiful game and i FEEL that its going to be fantastic.It has the same feeling as when i played uncharted 4 for the first time as a teenager, how do people create games with this atmosphere i will always be in awe, what a talent. I will update when i\'ve played more but i get goosebumps playing this already...Amazing work, for $20? Buy it.',''),(1405,'Short review Like its predecessors, Crusader Kings III is built on a principle accessible to all: at the heart of a kingdom, the player\'s objective is to make their dynasty thrive, generation after generation, making it more illustrious and powerful. The disappearance of the dynasty in total obscurity means the end of the game. On paper, as you may have understood, the idea is quite simple to grasp. The issue, however, is that the franchise has never been a symbol of aesthetics and accessibility. The content is so colossal that it has left many in the dust, much like knights departing on a crusade and being defeated in the midst of a desert. Not to mention the interface, as austere as possible, which has driven away even the most determined players. Tackling this third installment, game designer Henrik Fåhraeus and his team knew they had to provide more significant contextual assistance and clearer guides. In this regard, Crusader Kings III takes a softer approach than its predecessor by offering a real tutorial this time, allowing even novices to grasp the basics and fully dive into managing their lineage.Crusader Kings III, a colossal medieval sandbox, has no equivalent. With incredible depth, the new gem from the Swedish developers at Paradox takes strategy and RPG to new heights. Aside from occasionally wayward artificial intelligence and a DLC policy that won\'t please everyone, this installment benefits from a remarkable interface, staggering content, and a much more pleasing visual approach than in the past. Each playthrough is a discovery, leading to decisions that are sometimes unexpected. For the first time, the series features a tutorial and numerous contextual guides, opening it up to a much broader audience. Without denying its origins, Crusader Kings III elevates the franchise to new heights and deserves my applause. Truly remarkable. Long review The tutorial is set in 1066, in the southern part of beautiful and sweet Ireland. Murchad of Brain, Duke of Munster, aspires to restore the reputation of a kingdom in decline. Between love affairs, family matters, diplomatic relations, treaties, betrayals, and plots, the burden of a throne never seemed so heavy. To establish and make his lineage prosper, the player must learn to weigh each decision, and that\'s precisely what the tutorial, with its explanatory guides, aims to convey. Crusader Kings III highlights an immense number of parameters that can be divided into several major segments. First, there is family management, taking into account love stories, marriages (arranged or not), the education of children, and the missions assigned to each of your relatives. Then, there is the diplomatic part and the relationships maintained with your people, allies, vassals, and neighboring or distant kingdoms. Added to this is the notion of fortification (buildings, men-at-arms, including the arrival of knights) and the formation of armies, essential for the conquest of territories. It is also impossible not to mention the significantly enhanced RPG aspect (thanks to a system of personality traits and a clever skill tree system inherited from the Way of Life expansion of Crusader Kings II) or the religion mechanic, derived from the Holy Fury add-on, which makes its return in an improved version. Each character has their own personality, opinions, and it is essential to surround yourself with loyal followers and advisors working towards the same goals. Finally, one must face a succession of random events (disease, etc.). It quickly becomes apparent that the longevity of the dynasty, which involves agonizing decisions, goes hand in hand with daily difficulties. Failing to keep an eye on power and its surroundings is a sure way to be annihilated. And this leads to difficult choices, such as getting rid of an intrusive advisor or even one of your children spreading false rumors and tarnishing your reputation. Thanks to tutorial, you can glimpse the richness of the game, but they are only a timid preview of what truly awaits you.Crusader Kings III offers a playing field that stretches from Europe to Africa and all the way to Asia. After selecting the desired era (9th or 11th century), all that remains is to choose the character to embody. Depending on the title of the said character (count, duke, king, emperor...), the beginnings will be more or less challenging. Paradox Interactive\'s creation is undeniably time-consuming and demands hours of governance to grasp all the ins and outs of a playthrough. Every event, whether familial or diplomatic, will have an impact on the ruler\'s stress gauge. Physical and personality traits must be considered to avoid situations that affect the ruler\'s mental state. For example, if the ruler is shy, it is preferable to avoid large crowds. Each playthrough is a discovery, and you must adapt to each of the individuals taking the throne (and those surrounding it). Some will be better at combat, others will be more strategic, while some will delegate excessively. What is exceptional is managing a playthrough for several hours only to find yourself in a ludicrous situation due to a misjudgment (an imprisonment, an assassination, a plot, a wounded soldier holding a grudge, a vassal you\'ve sent away...). In this title, nothing is predetermined; the foundations are there, but no one can anticipate the events to come. And that is undoubtedly the great strength of Crusader Kings III, even if, through experimentation, you will eventually discern certain AI routines.No more endless menus and the slightly cluttered appearance of the second game of the series! In contrast to its predecessor, Crusader Kings III aims to be much more pleasant, modern, and streamlined. The visual leap is considerable, thanks to a superb map, a completely revamped interface, and a myriad of contextual frames that seamlessly fit into the game\'s new approach. It\'s not uncommon to be confronted by an event that imposes a crucial choice, and there\'s no longer the feeling of being drowned in a cascade of menus with imperfect ergonomics. Crusader Kings III has been polished, refined, and meticulously thought out in every detail. The developers have managed to preserve the richness of the series while \'compacting\' everything into menus of great clarity. While some shortcuts would be welcome, it\'s evident that one no longer gets lost, and all information is accessible thanks to cleverly placed icons. In terms of interface, Paradox Interactive\'s title is simply a case study, and one can easily imagine the time it took for those involved to achieve this result. The introduction of 3D portraits is a welcome addition, with decent modeling and graphical details that will satisfy fans of the franchise. The musical aspect is also a success with good themes.Crusader Kings II held its throne for eight years. During these eight years, Paradox developers literally inundated the community with multiple DLCs, each addressing a specific theme (management of a different religions, map expansion, incarnation of a historical character, etc.). There is, therefore, a strong likelihood, especially after experiencing Crusader Kings III, that the same will be true for this installment. This DLC policy is sometimes felt during gameplay, as if certain elements were less integrated than others. While the novelties are numerous, it is nevertheless noticeable that certain aspects of the title are less developed than before (or downright absent). For example, the battles could have been more spectacular. I also think about the management of epidemics (Syphilis, Black Death...). It is evident that the game will gain content with expansions coming in the coming months and years. The studio, through Henrik Fåhraeus, has clarified that the add-ons will be less numerous than before and will be denser. For now, fans of wargames with a touch of RPG can rest assured: there is plenty to do with this splendid episode!',''),(1406,'☑ be a peasant☑ try to sleep with the king☑ get rejected by the king☑ start a peasant uprising☑ overthrow the king☑ become the new king☑ try to sleep with the peasants☑ get rejected☑ get overrthrown by a peasant uprising☑ repeat10/10',''),(1407,'Remember kids, in any other context, incest is wrong.',''),(1408,'I\'ve wasted so many hours of my life on this game',''),(1409,'The Vikings really fell off hard after they started introducing dwarfism into their genepool.',''),(1410,'Sims for menNever discuss anything you do on this game to outsiders without context.',''),(1411,'Please Paradox for the love of God do something about the stress system it\'s way to penalizing for such minor things not to mention some interactions that just don\'t make sense. Like with paranoid if you murder someone you gain monstrous amounts of stress even though you\'re literally getting rid of an enemy. It\'s terrible and needs to be majorly reworked. Trying to mold the players actions around the traits of the characters they play as makes sense but the stress system is much to infuriating, you shouldn\'t go insane because you gave a peasant money and your greedy it\'s way to extreme.',''),(1412,'той притулок які самотні макіавелістські жінки знаходять в \"сімсах\" самотні макіавелістські чоловіки знаходять в іграх від парадоксів',''),(1413,'don\'t play it is sucks',''),(1414,'Have you ever wanted to be the King of a long forgotten Kingdom? When you assume control of the throne, your brother starts causing trouble, so you plot to have him murdered and then seduce his wife. When she rejects you, she\'s sent to the dungeons where she spends the rest of her short life. Then you conquer your neighbors and tax them into oblivion. All while spreading the joys of your faith to your new subjects. You send the Pope a letter of appreciation, but he calls you a heretic and decries your wicked ways. No worries, because there\'s a beautiful new courtier that you have your eyes on. God can wait...glory is now.Seriously, this game is everything you could ever want in an RTS. Be good or evil, live, love (or just seduce). It\'s not about the kingdom...it\'s about your dynasty, which gives you almost unlimited power to bend the world to your will. I can\'t recommend this game enough (with or without DLC). It\'s a fantastic kingdom simulator. It has a relatively high learning curve, but if you\'re familiar with any other Paradox products, it shouldn\'t be too hard to pick up.',''),(1415,'This is great game if you\'re the type of player who likes to set their own goals and make their own fun. It\'s really not hard to cheese the game and just \"win\" but if you\'re playing this game to \"win,\" you\'re doing it wrong. Favorite example: - Playing Vikings- Pillage and conquer- Be Danelaw- Life is good- Only son gets craven trait- Son inherits, uncles not happy with craven viking- Son tries to reform culture to rid vikings of warlike ways and be more like those nice Dutch- Son is overthrown and quickly surrenders (see: craven)- Son lives happily in Netherlands- Give up Norse ways and become Dutch- Build thriving economic powerhouse- Uncle Ragnar raids Son\'s lands- Son uses mountains of gold to buy mercenaries and captures Uncle Ragnar- Good bye, Uncle Ragnar.- Life is good.',''),(1416,'So many ways to play this game, it\'s really absorbing. Played it quite a long time and keep coming back to it every 5-6 months',''),(1417,'If you\'re hooked up to the radio signal and are radio-steered, then this game might pass, but for those who aren\'t high on the radio, this game doesn\'t live up to its expectations. The economy remains simple as in the previous CK games and all the inner workings of a realm doesn\'t exist. For example, alliances are not forged out of strategic need so much as it is about marrying off some of your relatives. To beat a stronger nation, there\'s no tactic to employ other than paying for mercenaries to add up to your army. Sieges are too cheap, the attacker only has to bid his time, the defenders have no say. For example, there\'s no sally option and the attacker doesn\'t run out of provisions.As for the rest, it\'s familiar with other Paradox games. Smaller countries don\'t have a mechanism of their own to withstand larger countries which makes them unplayable and the DLCs that are released don\'t add much value to the game. You should release a DLC when the game is good enough.',''),(1418,'good incest game',''),(1419,'Discount costs more than chapter bundle which is even not lasting till the end of the year.',''),(1420,'One of the most entertaining strategy games I have ever played. I listed my overall impressions below, but if you enjoy this genre and are on the fence, I would say just buy it. You will not be disappointed!Pros:- The RPG elements make each play-through unique, the \"choose your own adventure\" for each character you play as in your dynasty challenges you to adapt your play style within the game.- If you enjoy history, looking into some of the noble houses (at least when you start the play through), cultures, and religions is neat. You could learn a lot new things. Cons:- Some of the DLC offered for this game should be free updates in my opinion as they don\'t really elevate the game play (ie. offer wardrobe pieces or additional situations you can click through). However, Tour and Tournaments and Royal Court are absolutely worth getting, with drastic game play changes that improve the base game.- In-game tutorials are helpful but even with that, the learning curve can feel pretty steep and overwhelming. There are many ways and mechanics in place to learn that you can use to accomplish your goals.',''),(1421,'This game is like real life to me. You can live your fantasies of ruling an empire, you can get rejected by a woman, you can be have the lowest iq level in the world, its way too realistic. One time my son killed his wife because she cheated on him with me and shortly after that I died, then my son who was me now also died and since he had no children because he killed his wife, my entire game ended.',''),(1422,'i married my sister, who was married to my father, who was actually her uncle and grandfather, who in turn produced some children that look like martin shkrelii am really good at this whole hapsburg thing i guess10/10',''),(1423,'Read it and weep Saladin!',''),(1424,'it good',''),(1425,'Glad they finally decided to make some kind of private servers. I can now enjoy the game again instead of being spawn sunk. Now they need to make it so you can make a bigger private server with more ships. Kinda like closed crew servers on gtaV. I really don\'t care if \"it\'s a pirate game get over it\" yeah well that\'s gonna lose you a lot of players especially with griefers and spawn sinkers not being punished for it. Who wants to play a game where you spawn in and get sunk before you even set sail? Or immediately followed, it\'s not our job to make sure we don\'t have those things happen, it\'s on the devs who years ago made an April fools joke out of it, they let the game get purely focused on PVP instead of it actually being a pirate game...',''),(1426,'This game is totally amazing. I bought a desktop computer in February of 2023 to play this game, and I was disappointed the first time I played it. I redownloaded it in November 2023 and did a few things differently:1. I played with more than one person.2. I did more than just quests -- like grind forts.3. I made it far enough to purchase my own ship.4. I got hooked on hourglass.Like most games, this game has a steep learning curve. Once you make a few friends and learn a few things from YouTube (and change your keybinds) then this game starts to come alive in a way that really no other game has before. I am not sure if it\'s partially because I am ex-Navy, or if it is something else about it, but I love this game. It will be my main grind for a while and I am always looking for people to play with.My discord is wagen3886. You should add me and tell me you want to play some Sea of Thieves. I am cool with you being completely new, but would appreciate being told that is the case. If you like high stakes games with intense communication and cooperation, then you will love Sea of Thieves. It\'s included on Game Pass, but it\'s well worth the money.',''),(1427,'A while ago I gave a now deleted negative review for this game and for where the game was at, I think it was well-deserved. Requiring PVP in a game with so much rich PVE content was almost worse for me than just releasing a completely awful game. The wasted potential for a PVE mode or a split progression system was incredibly frustrating and ultimately led to me abandoning the game. There are plenty of games with PVE modes and PVP modes that work, do well and please both sides, but they devs continued to try and force PVP only down our throats. This was a few years ago and at the time, the devs said they weren\'t looking at a PVE mode and that it was against the spirit of the game.Fast forward to this week and Safer Seas, their version of a PVE mode was added to the game. I\'m so glad the devs learned from their mistakes, because this game is incredible now that the PVP mode is disabled. Safer Seas certainly isn\'t perfect. It needs more features, like higher progression levels for factions, etc. I just want to experience all the content the game has to offer without the toxic PVP aspect. I don\'t even really care about the 30% rewards, the fact that I can\'t fully level up the factions or participate in events that don\'t require PVP is more of a bummer for me. There are also features like captaincy that were taken out of safer seas that have no business being taken out. But the fact that the devs listened to the playerbase at all and added a PVE mode is such a positive sign to me that I actually have hope for this game to get even better, which I couldn\'t say a few years ago. So here\'s to hoping that the devs continue to learn, grow and provide a fantastic experience for those who want PVE, PVP or both!',''),(1428,'Sea of Thieves is a game that could be for everyone. Instead, it’s so obsessed with catering to hardcore PvPers that it forgets to make the game fun for anyone else. Even though PvE content is a massive portion of the game, the devs will actively punish anyone who tries to engage with it, leaving them to lose hours of work to a rival crew or to miss out on the vast majority of rewards and content.Good news! After waiting the better part of a decade, players can choose to sail the seas alone without the aforementioned threat of losing work. It’s called Safer Seas, and it’s definitely a step in the right direction.Bad news! All rewards you get from this mode are 30% of what they are on PvP servers, making an already grindy game even grindier. Most of the best money making methods are also locked, so really it’s more like 15-20% of what you would get otherwise.(Yeah, we know rewards are cosmetic, but unlocking these rewards is still what keeps many of us playing. When a PKer can make more progress in one hour than you can in five, it leaves a sour taste.)There’s also a level cap in Safer Seas, and most of the really interesting features are removed - even those like captaincy which have nothing to do with combat. If you’re a solo player like me, the main game is even worse. You have basically no chance of winning a fight with a group unless you sink hundreds of hours into learning the game’s mechanics. I know, I know, “find a group, it’ll make the game easier” - but what if I don’t want to play in a group? What if I want to go through at my own pace? If Rare cater for hardcore PKers, they should at least throw a bone to people like me. I don’t have the time or inclination to “get good”, and if there was a viable PvE mode, I’d probably sink hundreds of hours into it. Rare could triple the rewards for Safer Seas, and it’d still be behind the main mode in terms of earning potential. Only this time, there’d be a lot more people playing it. A vocal minority of the fanbase champion the PvP-anywhere gameplay, which is fine. Unlike Rare, I’m not here to tell you how to have fun. But any glance at a Safer Seas discussion will show there are a ton of people who play the game to chill out, complete quests and battle skeletons. It’s immensely frustrating to see Rare throw away such a golden opportunity to appeal to a wider audience. Hell, the whole reason I bought the game was because of the upcoming PvE mode. In conclusion, play this game if you’re interested in the group PvP. If you’re interested in anything else the game has to offer, from adventure to questing to fighting krakens, then you should wait for things to change. If they ever do.',''),(1429,'In a world of games competing with one another to offer the most user friendly and accessible features and gameplay Rare has decided \"NO!\".Got a couple of kids you want to be a pirate with and enjoy a fun family adventure? Called horrific names and spawn camped by other players.Want to play a LITERAL DISNEY themed story based on a popular Disney film franchise? Called horrific names and spawn camped by other players.Want to enjoy a relaxing night after work with your spouse fishing in a virtual world that has rewards just for fishing in said virtual world? Called horrific names and spawn camped by other players.Then, wait... 5 years later... PVE servers? A private server you can do all the above without other players calling you horrific names and spawn camping you?Lmao, sure. Except this time it\'s the dev\'s killing all your fun. Rewards are cut to an abysmal 30%. Half the features are missing, including features DESIGNED for PVE experiences, and then you\'re told \"This game is not for you, go play something else\" because I want to enjoy this amazing world you created? I jump onto the forums to see what people are saying and it\'s 100 different usernames pleading for rare to knock it off and 3 usernames defending the obviously INSANE decision to require PVP in order to play the full game, and not nicely either, actually by... calling you names and trolling your posts.Toxic community. Toxic ideology that purposely excludes people, and only for the reason that 3 out of every 100 people keep pointing back to Rare\'s \"Original plan for the game\" as reason to not make changes to be more inclusive to non-sweatlord gamers. What a joke. Give me full game and I give you wallet. Easy.10/10 game otherwise. Give the PVP folks a big bonus for being big **** sweaty GaMErZ and let us 30yo chill folks enjoy the full game with our friends and family the way we want. Why limit it? It makes NO SENSE! I\'m ready to buy my kids all the dogs and cats and birds and Banjo Kazooie ship cosmetics... but for 30% rewards and 30% features? LOL get real.',''),(1430,'Trapped a pig, befriended it, and then cooked it',''),(1431,'If you plan on Playing Coop or The new PVE aspect of the game get it on sale because alot of the content worth doing has been stripped from it.The community and developers get TILTED ANGRY, when anyone tries to Associate with anything PVE related in this game. people are literally just trying to buy it and play it.currently when you make a new character it informs you playing safer seas will lock you out of most of the content worth doing including ship ownership, cosmetics, and alot of the factions.and you will be throttled to a 30% mate inducing a massive grind of bare content.I suggested on the official Forums when you make a new character you should have the OPTION to choose if your progress carrys over into PVP and if you dont you should get full access to the content on safer seas, IMMEDIATELY locked and dismissed by the moderators.th