 and the world around you feels vibrant and alive.The story of Arthur Morgan, a member of the Van der Linde gang, is a triumph of storytelling in the video game medium. It\'s a deep and emotionally resonant narrative that explores themes of loyalty, redemption, and the moral gray areas of a fading Wild West. The characters are richly developed, each with their own motivations, and their interactions with Arthur are layered and meaningful. The moral choices you make have genuine consequences, and the weight of those choices can be felt throughout the game.Gameplay in RDR2 is a seamless blend of action, exploration, and survival. Gunfights are intense and satisfying, with a variety of weapons and a dead-eye targeting system that makes you feel like a gunslinging outlaw. But it\'s not all about violence; hunting, fishing, and exploration provide a welcome change of pace. The attention to detail in mechanics, like maintaining your horse and managing your health, adds an extra layer of immersion.The world of Red Dead Redemption 2 is also teeming with activities and side quests. Whether you\'re robbing trains, solving mysteries, or helping strangers, there\'s always something to do. The game\'s open-ended approach to exploration lets you carve your own path through the world, ensuring that no two players will have the same experience.The visuals and audio in RDR2 are nothing short of exceptional. The level of realism in the character animations, the environmental effects, and the stunning sound design immerses you in this world like few other games can. The musical score is hauntingly beautiful, and the voice acting is top-notch, bringing the characters to life in a way that is truly captivating.In terms of longevity, Red Dead Redemption 2 offers an enormous amount of content, keeping players engaged for hundreds of hours. The multiplayer component, Red Dead Online, allows you to continue your adventures with friends, forming posses, going on heists, or just exploring the vast world together.To sum it up, Red Dead Redemption 2 is a masterpiece of the highest order. It\'s a testament to what video games can achieve in terms of storytelling, world-building, and immersion. It\'s an experience that will linger in your memory long after you\'ve put down the controller. Whether you\'re a fan of the Wild West or not, this game is a must-play and a shining example of the art of gaming.',''),(1457,'The store page is not clear enough on how mandatory the social club and online portion is. On console, this is optional.\"This game\'s first-time setup requires an internet connection.\"It also requires an internet connection after first-time setup, forever. Even if you\'re just playing story mode. Workarounds online don\'t seem to work, and when I try to launch the game offline, it doesn\'t work. I bought this in part to play on Steam Deck, so mandatory internet connection is a dealbreaker for me.',''),(1458,'If only once a year were made a game like this',''),(1459,'LITERALLY THE BEST GAME I HAVE EVER PLAYED',''),(1460,'Great game, of that i am sure. Buuuuuut, a game i have not played in decade(s), RDD was amazing and if i remember had no tutorial either but i need a little time to get to know the controls to feel more immersed in this triple A title. That on top of a better video card...',''),(1461,'It\'s an absolute masterpiece. Phenomenal story, compelling characters, top notch voice acting. But it is best enjoyed when you fully immerse yourself in the world and appreciate the little details.',''),(1462,'“We Can\'t Change What\'s Done, We Can Only Move On”Now that I finished this game, after I put it off for a long time, I regretted that I didn’t do it earlier. Now there’s nothing left to do but remember these emotions that this game gave me a sea of ​​emotions of joy for those characters who, as if they shouldn’t caused such a strong reaction because they are “not alive”, but in fact you begin to empathize with them as if they are not just characters in the game, but something more for you, as if they have a place in your heart and in your soul, some of them you hate as if they were your personal enemies. This game is one of those that can touch you to the core , leave warm memories and a sediment in your soul. I won\'t be too verbose and say that in recent years I haven\'t played anything more beautiful and emotional. All those who have not started yet, I can say one thing, you are missing out on a lot, friends, be sure to do it, don’t make the same mistake as me by postponing it for later. I want to say a huge thank you to all the developers and a deep bow to you for this piece of art.I don’t regret the time spent on this, thanks to everyone.',''),(1463,'Having played games from 3 different eras, I think it\'s fair to say that this is the best game I\'ve ever played. While every game has its flaws, this one feels the closest to perfection, atleast subjectively speaking. Everthing from the gameplay, the storyline, graphics, ambience, soundtrack, characters are well done and calling it a masterpiece is the least I could say. In terms of details Red Dead Redemption 2 never fails to impress, as it offers a rich immersive world that\'s meant to be explored, aside from the main storyline itself. Rockstar Games really set a new standard in terms of open world games, with its intricate and mesmerizing world, thriving wilderness waiting to be tamed, different towns with each one having their own personality, so many NPCs with unique dialogues, side quests, random encounters, hunting, fishing, crafting, treasures, unique weapons/items and other secrets to be found.All these activities will often set you off a different path, making it easy to lose yourself and forget that this is a Western game after all.The storyline, while not perfect, is second only perhaps to character development. Despite having a slow start, the theme of the Wild West and the Outlaws\' last days manages to keep you intrigued. That and Arthur Morgan\'s part in the story makes up for a brilliant partnership that truly puts Red Dead Redemption 2 in a different league.Having said that, I recommend that you play this game atleast once. Certainly worth the full price aswell. Enjoy the ride!',''),(1464,'I love my horsey and my horsey love me',''),(1465,'Better cultivation game than Tale of Immortal. English fan translation.Highly recommend',''),(1466,'PRETTY DOOD',''),(1467,'Imagine Mario maker but the creator of a level has not to finish the level himself before uploading it, what could go wrong eh?',''),(1468,'It\'s a well made asymmetric FPS and base builder that can dance the line between tense dungeon crawling and frantic movement shooter chaos. The game is split between building your own outposts and raiding outposts made by others. Both are appealing for different reasons and can be rewarding but it is not mandatory to do both if you find yourself gravitating towards one over the other.RaidingRaiding sees you entering another player\'s outpost and trying to steal a key resource (referred to in-game as GenMat) while avoiding all of the traps and guards the opposing player has set up to kill you. Everything in this game operates on a one-hit-kill basis so raiding is based predominantly on quick reactions and carefully taking stock of your surroundings. Something that should be said is that while I quite enjoy the raiding, Meet Your Maker is not the game for you if you get easily frustrated when having to repeat a challenging level over and over. Many of the outposts available to raid are brutally difficult and you will be reminded constantly that the builder\'s goal is the kill you as many times as possible. If you find that kind of challenge rewarding, you\'ll have a very satisfying experience with this game. There\'s an undeniable joy to finally finishing a difficult outpost that\'s had you tensely moving around every corner desperately on edge because you\'ve made it further than you ever had before and don\'t want to lose your progress.The gameplay options available to you as a raider are simple yet efficient. You can only carry two weapons and a couple special items. These can range from guns to swords to grenades to shields. This is in addition to passive buffs you can apply to your character via either your suit abilities or single use enhancements. The game\'s received a few updates by this point and the options for equipment loadout now offer a decent variety of playstyles. The systems aren\'t overly complicated but that\'s because most outposts are designed to be completed in only a few minutes (provided that you don\'t die. In practice some of the harder outposts can taken considerably longer to finish as you go through multiple attempts)Something that is remarkably strong is the movement system for the raider. You can use a grappling hook (seemingly a necessity in all sci-fi FPS games now) and can move around an environment very fast, zipping around enemies and traps dodging dozens of projectiles as you try to clear a room. My one major criticism of the raiding experience is that while this type of movement is possible, it is only viable in specific circumstances. In most outposts, it\'s much more reliable to take it slow and only put yourself in least amount of danger at a time, which feels like a waste of the movement mechanics. Rushing in, especially when you don\'t know the trap layout will certainly get you killed. BuildingThe other half of the game is building outposts for other players to raid. While the raiding can be equal parts tense and chaotic, the building is obviously much more relaxed and almost meditative. The layout of each outpost is based on a 3D grid of blocks, looking very much like a high-res version of minecraft but also including 45 degree slopes. You can place blocks or create entire walls/floors at a time. Traps and guards can also be easily dotted around your environment. Everything has to be placed manually though. There is no way to copy entire sections and paste them or rotate them elsewhere. This can make certain features like repeated decorations or trap layouts a bit tedious, but the tradeoff is that that building system is very approachable. There\'s a very low learning curve to the technical side of building, although the more creative side both in terms of visuals as well as good trap placement and level design will take quite a bit of practice to become really proficient with.There are several limitations to the building system. The main one is that there needs to be a clear path from the entrance of the level to the GenMat for the raider to collect. This path needs to be navigable by the Harvester Unit (HRV) which cannot jump or climb walls. This means that the path must be continuous. This can feel a bit limiting, but it\'s vital for ensuring that the raider has some idea of where to go. If you could put the entrance to the GenMat down a hole or tucked away in a wall somewhere, the raiding experience would be defined more by boredom from trying to find out where he/she is supposed to go rather than by the challenge of contending with your traps. Another limitation is that the plot of land you can build on is auto-populated by immovable bedrock which shows up in random patterns for every outpost you create. Once the bedrock is generated it is impossible to remove it and you must build around it. I understand that this was done to force builders to use different layouts for each outpost they make, but sometimes the amount of bedrock generated can get frankly obnoxious.Something else I want to highlight though is the possibility for artistic expression. Having to build exclusively with cubes and 45 degree slopes may sound limiting, but Meet Your Maker provides a lot of cosmetic options for customizing your outpost. These are all entirely optional, but there\'s a lot of flexibility for some visually impressive maps as demonstrated by the community. Not every outpost you run into will have that kind of love put into it, but some of the ones that do really shine.ProgressionUp until very recently, this was something the game really struggled with. It\'s improved significantly with recent updates, but it\'s still in my opinion the game\'s weakest part. This mostly stems from how there isn\'t much to spend the different types of currency on. You\'ll find that unless you are building and activating/reactivating outposts a lot, you\'ll quickly find yourself with a buildup of currency. Something you can spend the money on are boosts that result in you getting slightly more money for a short duration (only an hour or so depending on your level) which seems baffling and like the kind of thing that would be done in a free-2-play game... except Meet Your Maker isn\'t free-2-playRecently though, there\'s been a collection of cosmetics you can unlock by raiding a lot. These help provide some more incentive to raid more outposts (which in turn gives the builders more rewards, as they earn progress for kills and accolades given to their outposts) but it doesn\'t solve the aforementioned currency issue. The cosmetics themselves are pretty good. Given the game\'s very serious tone they can\'t go into wild territory for suit/weapon skins like a more cartoony game could, but it\'s still a welcome addition.ConclusionMeet Your Maker is a game that tries and mostly succeeds at balancing both fast paced and tense first person combat with more relaxing and user friendly base building. The raiding can lend to frustration sometimes and the building takes a while to develop as a skill, but both offer a satisfying gameplay loop, even if the meta-game progression still needs to be ironed out a bit as the development progresses.',''),(1469,'i hadnt played it in a while. decided to check out the new sector 2. new layout was incredibly confusing for me, idk why i had to start at .5 star when i was comfortably playing at 3+ star before. crashed on my third run, had to restart my pc cause its horribly optimised',''),(1470,'Do you enjoy dungeon crawling in games like Skyrim? Have you ever thought to yourself \"If I owned this area, I would put traps there and there and have guards posted there\"? Then boy do I have a game for you.',''),(1471,'The game has an interesting core concept which it executes quite well. There are some rough corners on the technical side, but it mostly runs great nowadays and I still come across unique and fun build ideas after over a hundred hours.Coop can make some levels too easy but its great fun nonetheless. Don\'t expect much interaction with other players though. There is no real community or even a chat function in the game to tell someone why you liked or disliked their level. I can understand not wanting to moderate the \"productive criticism\" for harder levels though.',''),(1472,'Game is great but the dlc system is broken. You can unlock the dlc content by spending quite a large amount of in game currency. But if you do, then later buy the dlc, you aren\'t refunded. And since the dlc packs have multiple items you may unlock half of it, then end up wasting your money. It\'s a small thing and I\'ll easily change my review if it was fixed.',''),(1473,'This game is hard to love. And yet I do.',''),(1474,'Slay the spire ESQUE but with so many fun layers to explore and a party system that is fun. I absolutely love the art style and combat flow. I am very excited for this full release.',''),(1475,'great with friends',''),(1476,'Great strategy, good deckbuilding, lots of replay value',''),(1477,'actually a really fuggin goated game. sometimes when they update and add new things they need hella balancing but they are really good about doing it!',''),(1478,'fun positional card game',''),(1479,'Long story short, the game has poorly designed mechanics that the devs haven\'t touched since early access release (about 10 months from this post). Add to that basic functions like hotkeys aren\'t implemented (yet?).I have no faith in the devs. It took a while for them to even implement mediocre controls companions in singleplayer. Originally they seemed to think people would be fine only being able to see 2 out of 5 or more cards in a companions hand. It was really dumb from the start and should never of been considered from the start. Thats the kind of crap you get from this.',''),(1480,'Malware detect after opened game and core isolation got disabled. Don\'t trust this game',''),(1481,'I see this is one of those games the community is trying to rally against even without playing it or looking into it in any depth, and so I\'ll spend some of my life writing my first steam review.I like hard games, I like Asian aesthetic and historical culture [as well as folklore], and I like uniqueness.  This game checks all those boxes well, and I\'ve seen the game grow in playability since it\'s early seasons; In fact, I don\'t think they even called them seasons at first.  It\'s not perfect, and my biggest gripe at first was that it was a game with an upfront cost as well as many micro-transaction options.  The game is now free to play, however, and you unlock legendary skins/items every now and again from just playing, as well as offering ways to unlock playable characters of your choice with in-game currency.When mentioning this game in conversation, I\'ve been met with disinterest because of it\'s lack of popularity as well as some off-hand racism.  I encourage all that are looking for a challenging and fun game to give it a try despite these stigmas.  I\'m very glad I tried it out that first time.Since this is an honest review, I\'ll mention cons as well.  I feel there\'s just a bit too much going on in the main menus as far as events, currencies, packages, skins, doo-dads, links, texts, ect.  I DO enjoy it to some extent, as it\'s a fun tribute to the Chinese culture to have festivals and events and cool little gifts; However, it\'s just a bit excessive of this function, to the point where I don\'t know what some things are because I simply want to get into a battle most of the time and not try to track down what kind of coins I just acquired randomly and what shop I can use them in.Gameplay-wise, I have a great time.  There are some very good players in this game, and it\'s very important to try to pick apart what exactly they\'re doing better than you and try to use those skills for yourself; Which is akin to martial arts, and I think that\'s cool.  A high-skill ceiling for sure, BUT those that are scared of this shouldn\'t fear TOO much.  There is a bot mode with 3 difficulties that you can play solo or with your friends so that there is no chance of being whipped up and down by the \'Lord of the Lobby\', as I\'ve affectionately named the player you can see in the lobby before you spawn in that has a mastery rank that you can\'t even understand.  Piggy-backing off that point, when you play PVP, there will be bots in the mix, and you will feel great for defeating many of them; But when you meet the \'Lord of the Lobby\' in that same game, your fate will likely be sealed before you realize it is he/she.  It makes you pay more attention, if anything; BUT the skill jump can be a bit of a shock when it happens.Might I add, you can accomplish the in game quests/achievements in the bot modes.Overall, this is one of my favorite games to play lately.  I\'m a bit of a casual gamer, as you can see I don\'t have thousands of hours in this game, only a hundred or so; But I still find it challenging and fun.  For fans of the Dynasty Warriors series, it will feel homey but also much more polished and fluid.  If I may interject with a comparison here, there are many, many Dynasty Warriors games, and they\'ve gathered quite a following over the years.  However, they have been much of the same game with improvements here and there on graphics, features, and playability.  This is a fresh take on a very similar concept of gameplay, polishing it up and also incorporating pvp and online co-op.  Dynasty Warriors holds a place in my heart from years and years ago, and I think looking at the two side by side grows my love of Naraka to and even higher state.I won\'t give a number rating for this game or any other game, that\'s not my style.  Just know I like this game a lot and I think more people should give it a try.  Thank you for reading my review, and may your journeys be full of wonder.',''),(1482,'This game feels nice but the countless times I get ganked by Chinese players into lagging hell really suck the life out of wanting to keep playing. Literally I have no issue until you use cheap methods to exploit the severs to your advantage. The devs will not do anything because honestly majority of the players are from china and they cant lose the player count. Just please for the love of god if someones ping is trash take them to their servers and stop ruining what is honestly a nice change to the BR genre.',''),(1483,'This game is so dead that it puts u against top 10 or top20 players that dont have life and dont go outside and the cheaters are full,how can i have 50 hours and be put against players that played in j cup dude,like im getting matched with players that play like pros in tournaments,dont reccomend for new players and lag is so bad',''),(1484,'Great game. Game play is fun and challenging. I am constantly learning new things about the game so my interest is always peaked. Always adding new and good content. My only negative opinion about the game is loot boxes but I have never been a fan of the loot box system in games and believe the products being offered should just be purchasable without random chance. Although the loot boxes are only cosmetic so they have no barring on game play and it would seem that the money they make they actually reinvest into the game to constantly bring the player base new and interesting content. Most games will just make variant game modes that don\'t play much different from their