ey but a game made for all ages, and a game made out of love and passion. I\'m so ashamed of myself for sleeping on this for so long. I bought it back when it came out and just never got around to playing it until now. Ironically enough, I kind of put it off a bit thinking it would be “yet another Pokémon clone.”I\'ll be transparent and say I haven\'t finished the game, but I\'m on track to doing so. It runs well enough on Steam Deck and utilizes the Godot game engine. My playtime has been split between playing on my laptop and playing on my Steam Deck. I leave it set to 50 Hz on Steam Deck, and leave all other battery settings at their default values. Turn off half rate shading if you\'re using DeckyRecorder. HRS seems to cause some sort of flickering in footage. May cause epileptic episodes if you open footage without realizing you\'ve left HRS on. Steam Deck does get frame drops, and they are noticeable, but due to the nature of the gameplay, they are not game-breaking. I did get some crashes, and I think my issue was limiting the wattage to 13 instead of leaving the limiter off. I have been unable to recreate the crashes after setting wattage back to default. I don’t have an OLED model Steam Deck to compare, but the fans ramp up quite a bit on the old 512 GB LCD model Steam Deck.Cassette Beasts is 100% what I would call a wholesome and cozy game. It\'s got some creepiness and some cuteness. It’s got a good amount of diversity. It’s got some heartfelt moments, and some good potential for character development. There’s been some really clever moments that made me go “Huh. That’s interesting,” as well. I think I still have quite a bit left to do, and I\'ve been stumped a couple of times. The game could do with some more hints or giving more guidance on what you\'re supposed to do next at certain points. It just kind of started to slow down at one point, and I ended up wandering around until I stumbled into what I was supposed to do. This actually happened a couple of times during my play sessions.There’s some really good music in certain locations and boss battles of this game as well. I was in a cafe at one point and was suddenly hit with some music that took me aback for a moment. I wasn’t expecting that kind of vibe from this game going into it. As a music lover, I can’t help but love the record-themed stages. The first boss encounter had a really good song, as well. Not quite the kind of music I was expecting from this game, but definitely not disappointing by any stretch. I find the fusion and cassette/recording mechanics to be really interesting. They’re a good twist on the monster collector formula. Type matches and mismatches, abilities, buffs, and debuffs all feel really good to me. They’re fun to play around with, and they make sense in this game’s world. I really like the way the leveling system is implemented as well. I never felt like I was hindered by the beasts I wanted to use. Your beasts level up, evolve, and all that good stuff. However, your player character also levels up. That’s the interesting part. There’s a lot to play around with here, and a lot of interesting twists on the monster collecting genre. It’s really not “just another Pokémon clone.”To just describe it as “Pokémon but better” or something along those lines is to do Cassette Beasts dirty. It’s so much more than that. It’s a love letter to what made those classic Pokémon and Zelda games great. It wears its inspiration on its sleeve, and it does it in the best way possible.Pick this one up. Buy it on sale if you want, but I think it’s worth the full asking price.',''),(1759,'I\'ve had a lot of luck when trying out new genres the past couple of years.  Cassette Beasts was no exception.  This game constitutes my first JRPG and first Creature Capture game (nope, I\'ve never played a Pokémon game). I must admit this game has been a ton of fun. The music is quite catchy and the main song is very peaceful. It has an \"I ❤️ the 80s\" retro theme with its pixelated graphics, limited voice acting and character wardrobe. None of which took away from the gaming experience in 2023. The gameplay is enjoyable with plenty to do on a large map... you can even play with a friend!  Most of the tasks are fairly straight forward, but if you want to 💯 the achievements you will have to grind to find at least one of every bootleg type, obtain a copy of every beast and obtain additional info on every beast (there are a lot of beasts, evolutions and fusions). You can adjust the difficulty to your preferences, but I found the default to be very enjoyable.The price is extraordinarily reasonable. At $19.99 you can feel good picking up this game at full price... on any sort of discount, it\'s a steal. In fact, the devs could have fairly priced it at $24.99- $29.99, but I do appreciate the lower price point. I haven\'t said anything about the story or gameplay. Both are interesting and engaging. Most of you are better gamers than I, so suffice it to say,  \"you won\'t have much trouble naturally figuring out some of the less obvious elements as you progress through the game.\" ... battle strategy, chemistry, how/ where to find bootleg beasts, etc... and for the things that weren\'t intuitive to me (like how the heck do you beat a ghost!? And where on New Wirrell is that gold coin??), steam guides and youtube videos have been a big help.This one\'s a 10/10 for me. It\'s not a perfect game by any means, but the devs have given it a ton of love and it has been a real treat to play. I strongly recommend you give it a try.',''),(1760,'it\'s good and i do recommend it, but there\'s definitely a few problems. first, the good everyone mentions is rly good. the music is shockingly good, the monster designs are great, the characters are a little 1.5 dimensional but are still very enjoyable with overall pleasant art. when the game opens up, the world feels really fun to collect stuff in. the story is alright, it has some very charming subplots and the ending is good, but everything working up to the payoff is pretty shallow. the main problem with the game, for me, was that it is too open ended. i feel like i stumbled upon almost everything i was supposed to do, which i think to some players that\'s great, but i didn\'t feel like i discovered anything, i just wondered over to the next open-world-collectible/miniboss. the world is very diorama-esc, which makes it feel very... game-y. again, this likely really appeals to some players, but it made it hard for me to feel emotionally invested in almost anything in the game, and it seems like the game wanted me to be invested. i never felt a narrative arc, no sense of escalation or pressure, just wandering around finding stuff until the game says i found enough stuff to unlock the final last stuff to beat the game. the villain is present here and there but in the most indirect ways, almost every goal of the game is just to gather more resources, do little platforming puzzles (that were fun enough, if a little stale towards the end), or go fight X thing. because it can be done so open ended-ly, they all have to just be kinda hanging out in plain sight, and i started to get serious open-world-game-fatigue.this is not helped by the fact that the game tries to guide you via the level curve of certain areas, but by the midway point you can go most places as it is very open ended, which creates the problem that pokemon gold/silver had: the beginning is strangely hard as it tries to bottleneck you into the areas where you first level up, and then the mid to late game is suddenly incredibly easy once you start to outpace the remaining sections in levels. the post game it gets a little bit harder again, but strategy in the game is WAY more free-from than pokemon, which at first is really fun as you get to handcraft kinda broken strategies by holding onto all moves (stickers) and applying them to the appropriate CBs, with some pretty absurd (and not the best balanced) passives. However, this gets old when you realize the opponents do not have the same access to strategy, or else they too could create CBs that have like a 20% chance to instantly nuke your first starting CBs and maybe even you or your partner. so by the time you get to the end game, you will likely know a few nigh unbeatable strats if your CBs are in a remotely similar level range as your opponent.overall, i\'m critiquing the game a lot despite the fact that it is really pleasant to play, just because some of the core design detracts so much from what is good about the game for certain players. it\'s good to set your expectations accordingly. i honestly still recommend it to pretty much anyone: the music, the visuals, the area design, the side quests, collecting monsters, building your character, all of that stuff is incredibly fun. the game manages to be very funny as well. but if you aren\'t a huge open world fan, keep that in mind.',''),(1761,'it just drips charm. every sprite and detail has surprising amounts of thought put in. the type system is clever and pretty intuitive. i hope they get online features now or in a future installment. i see this franchise growing a very loyal fan base if they continue to treat their projects with respect',''),(1762,'I am shocked. I really like Pokemon but this game is Pokemon but with a better story, better quality of life, tons of npc\'s with a personality, an empty map to explore, some awsome mysteries, so many quests, amazing artstyle, 100+ achievements to gather and of course an absoloutely perfect soundtrack. It is insane that I have heard so little about this game.Please, spend a bit of money to have this beautiful game.',''),(1763,'I’m completely blown away by the quality and the amount of content in this game. There’s so much to do, the pacing is fantastic, and the difficulty is just right. The soundtrack is so good I get excited every time the vocals came on, had to sing along every time. 10/10 game.',''),(1764,'Wunderbar! A surprising little game. The story is deceptively interesting;The battle mechanics deeper than they initially appear;And that soundtrack!Worth picking up to play; especially for those looking for something to scratch that pokemon itch.',''),(1765,'The best monster capturing game I have ever played. Took about 24 hours for me to reach the ending (the review will say 14.9 hours but I played the game mostly offline on the steam deck). Highly recommend',''),(1766,'How modern pokemon games should be, definitely would buy again!',''),(1767,'The more I\'ve played it the more I\'ve loved it. It feels like finding Pokemon for the first time all over again. Super cool world. Fun characters. Great combat. SUPERB MUSIC. Jesus christ this soundtrack. Buy it. Play it. Get it. The music is so good',''),(1768,'++TLDR: This is a fantastic monster taming game with fun exploration, an interesting story, and great combat mechanics.  However, there are areas for improvement with art, odd filler content, and some combat mechanics.PROS:+The game is open world, though some of this doesn\'t open up until you learn certain abilities.  This makes exploration quite interesting throughout the game.  And, by the end of the game, since the abilities that enhance your exploration allow things like double-jumping and gliding, moving around is an enjoyable breeze.+The game introduces mechanics to replace weakness and resistance, which is a breath of fresh air.  Rather, type-advantages cause temporary buffs and debuffs, which, when explained by the in-game tutorials are both hilarious and logical at the same time.+Combat is made more interesting by introducing a point system that allows different moves based on the available points.  Higher hitting attacks cost more points to use, so players need to ramp up and balance their turns instead of spamming heavy hitting attacks every turn.+The game introduces relationship strength to encourage players to pick combat partners and explore their storylines more extensively.  By the end of the game, I had unlocked several interesting combat partners to fight with.  SPOILER: Exploring multiple relationships and growing the partners and their beasts actually matters for the final boss fight.+Puzzles exist in this game and sometimes offer a challenge.  This was greatly missed from games like Pokemon that oddly have removed those in the last several generations.+The story is quite interesting and has multiple, interesting twists.CONS:-Combat can be slow because of the points system the game introduces.  This means that some fights against lower level monsters can drag on and cost HPs desired for a boss fight.  By the end of the game, I was largely trying to avoid fights.-Some of the anime art for the characters seemed very amateur.  I would hope that if there\'s a sequel, more money is put into hiring a better artist that could channel a similar, but more professional vibe for the game.-While exploring, the perspectives sometimes change.  This is interesting when that reveals new, hidden, areas, but often just became frustrating having to change controls or watch the camera shift often just because I\'m near the border of an area where the perspective shifts back and forth.-Some of the characters had random interactions to reveal they were gay.  Though, there really was no plot enhancement or story that this added and this never came up for more than 10-15 seconds.  Rather, this seems shoehorned into the game for no apparent reason other than \"inclusivity.\"  I\'d rather this be more fleshed-out if it\'s going to be in the game.  In this case, I just groaned.',''),(1769,'8 hours in and I can say I\'m really enjoying the game, I love that you can merge the monsters and everything, it\'s a very cool rpg!',''),(1770,'One of my fav game in years. Pros: - Cute pixel art graphics.- Open world works great. The game can get easy as you become stronger than certain areas, but I did not care: I had creatures to evolve and the fights can be quick enough that It was not a problem. - Exploration is fun. There are secrets to discover and map abilities to unlock. - The story is also interesting and delves into some interesting existentialist questions. - Great variety of creatures to evolve and develop. - Creatures can be modified considerably. Lots of fun combos to try and put together- So many types vs types effects. Looks overwhelming, but I learned them fairly quickly and they add a lot to the fights and strategies- Not too long. I finished the game in 35 hours. I wanted more when I was done, which is rare for me. I usually rush to finish a game in order to start a new one. (There are so many interesting games to play)Cons:- hardcore gamers will find the game too easy.',''),(1771,'Absolutely loved it.It was a bit hard to understand at the start, but once you get the mechanics you really start to get in the groove. The songs are bangers too.',''),(1772,'A fantastic take on the \"monster collector\" rpg subgenre (of course mostly known because of Pokemon).  Gameplay and combat is solid and interesting, especially with all the different ways elements interact beyond \"x is weak/resistant to y\".  The story is interesting, the music is INCREDIBLE, and the game is all around a joy to play.  Definitely worth your time, especially if you\'ve become disillusioned with certain...other franchises as of late.',''),(1773,'Absolutely flawless made game with turn based action & brand new way of playing a Creature Collector with honestly really fun combat & story-rich along with a genuinely beautiful map, absolutely love this game :D',''),(1774,'Better Pokemon. Amazing soundtrack. Story seems deeper than just \"collect all monsters\" & \"beat all trainers\". It is visible that a lot of heart and passion went into this!',''),(1775,'game of the year frfr',''),(1776,'Cassette Beasts is the newcomer in the recent slew of monster-taming games, a genre that has mostly been content to follow the ropes and tropes set by a particular market leader. But I’m happy to report Cassette Beasts carves a new path through subverting expectations and refining the genre in ways you might not even realise you want.Let’s start with the main event – the combat. Cassette Beasts’ combat is focused on ‘energy,’ a resource that needs strategic management and preservation. Every turn you’ll gain a fixed amount of energy and any decent move has an associated energy cost. Between those powerful attacks your turns will be spent playing defensive options or doing mild chip damage. It’s reminiscent of the sort of resource management you’d find in tabletop games and interesting tradeoffs naturally emerge, even in wild battles that would feel inconsequential in other RPGs.These interesting play mechanics are all enhanced by Cassette Beasts solely featuring Double Battles and dedicating a significant proportion of its moves to enhancing or protecting your team mate. The combat possibilities are dizzying and the best indicator of those possibilities is in Cassette Beast’s equivalent of ‘Gyms,’ which are not based on monster types but each instead showcases an entirely unique battle strategy. It’s great stuff.I also never stuck to a single strategy thanks to team experimentation being made trivial. Experience persists across all your monsters and attacks can be outright transferred between them (so long as the receiving monster’s movepool accepts it). Once any final evolution was reached I swapped them out, meaning I was able to progress both the bestiary and storyline without falling behind the level curve, creating a rewarding sense of progression.Said story is well-planned - a somewhat sombre reflection on nostalgic escapism and those themes will resonate with the target audience. The execution is serviceable, is filled with late 90\'s charm, and the boss battles along the way are a stylish highlight. However, I do think more sidekick-focused quests would have helped flesh out the characterisation, as the game lacks that immersive ‘ensemble goes questing’ feeling you might desire in your RPGs. I think some of that comes down to a lack of “quality time” you get to spend with the cast, so keep those expectations in check.On the topic of characters I’d say ‘creature designs’ are typically the weakest point of other monster-taming games, but Cassette Beasts bucks the trend by drawing from a range of inspirations while weaving a consistent design language throughout. The spectrum goes from ‘adorable’ to ‘edgelord’ while always maintaining a unique ‘Cassette Beast’ feel. Shoutouts to ‘Djinn Entonic’, ‘Brushroom’ and ‘Elfless’ (my beloved).My only major gripe here is navigating the overworld, there’s significant traversal stutter when moving at pace and the visuals are just about adequate (in comparison to the excellent monster sprites). It also takes a while to unlock your full navigation moveset and the interim does feel like something is ‘missing’ which makes for a bad first impression. Keep at it though, once you unlock the Bulletino Dash everything will start to click.So, to summarise, Cassette Beasts may be the monster-taming newcomer but imo it’s the most interesting of the lot. Serious effort has gone into identifying and challenging genre staples and using them as opportunities to innovate. I’ve kept details about a lot of that polish vague because the best bit of Cassette Beasts is in the surprises and delights you’ll discover along the journey. To any fans of turn-based battles seeking interesting yet accessible gameplay then Cassette Beasts is the one to grab. Highly recommended!',''),(1777,'the only game ive been able to get a shiny in :,)',''),(1778,'Pros:- Good music- Not bad idea in general.Cons:- The game contains denuvo malware.- The EULA is absolutely unreasonable, they can do whatever they want with your personal data and are not responsible for anything. And you\'re going to read the EULA after you have the game purchased, not before. Scam tactics.- A lot of unfinished and/or unbalanced mechanics.- AI is amazingly dumb.The most frustrating mechanic is happiness. If a character has no favorite labor activity, she/he will be constantly unhappy, will experience meltdowns, that makes characters like Maki not just useless but dangerous. And this is not a fault of Maki, but a bad balance of the game.',''),(1779,'Denying survivors ability to repair existing gear and instead requiring to build all gear from scrap is tedious and puts a huge drag on gameplay.  When I\'ve got six survivors and they require 16 hr work days making new clothes and new guns because no one can stitch a sock or clean a gun, I have to accept they\'re just doomed.',''),(1780,'The game is amazing. Many different biomes, scenarios, random generated maps. Tons of resources to harvest, hundred of buildings and items to craft.Combat can be disabled for a meditative experience, or it can be set as difficult as to trasform the game in a tactical tower defence, and everything in between.The AI is good enough to require almost no micromanagement, graphics are beatiful and performance really good and stable.The game is beeing developed further after release, with new biomes and scenarios added regularly, and on top of that there are hundred of mods in the workshop, including complete overhauls.I wouldn\'t say this 3D Rimworld since the social interactions are way more basic, but if you like the genre you can\'t let this one slip off.',''),(1781,'This game was at the top of my wishlist forever. Finally pulled the trigger and, my god, I wish I had left it there. This game is boring. it is beyond boring if there is a word for that. Every level of this game is just a slow chore. And I play Anno in normal speed. I like slow builders. This one goes no where and take forever to get there. Even the RTS combat lacks all forms of excitement. The NPCs just stand in place, shooting/swinging on their turn like its 1998. And why is this a space game? Last map I played looked like Utah. No space suits. No zero G. Nothing Space unless you count the skin swapped, very earth like, creatures. I don\'t. There is no game design beyond what has been stolen from other, more competent, developers. Bugs will attack your base like clockwork, their numbers inching up each time. Each area is dominated by a resource while lacking the others. This means your building will all be the same. You start with 4 people that burden the load and as your camp grows, well you better hope they don\'t die cause you may very well never see another person. Wooohoo....fun? A city builder that just makes you spread your labor paper thin. No, fun it is not. TL:DR It\'s just boring. I played on 3X speed the whole time and that wasn\'t enough for an exciting pace. As I progressed I never felt accomplished, nor the desire to continue.',''),(1782,'Really fun even if all your survivors want to kill each other by day 4',''),(1783,'Stranded: Alien Dawn introduction starts you out with a cool spaceship crash to begin your adventure. This is a survival / crafting / combat challenge to test your ability to get a rescue ship to your base. You\'ll have a lot to deal with priorities, qualifications, construction, combat, and weather situations. Game saves are critical just in case you have a major decision planned. New recruits are available but crew size is limited to six. The crew all have attitudes, traits, and skills to deal with & understand.I couldn\'t enjoy the game until I traded all my refund time for tutorial hours. Learning the game is deep so don\'t get stressed burning thru your refund window. The game was purchased with the robot dlc on sale but I\'m not ready for that right now since I have so many other map and seed selections available.I have not escaped the planet... after all this time I have not come up with success. I had the orbital transmit radio but couldn\'t find or craft the rest of the pieces to make it functional... so back to the drawing board.Update 12/21/2023  Well folks I did it! The last survivor departed my outstanding base in the rescue pod and I took Annabelle my Level 9 K-9 with me. If you discover my base enjoy yourself and please mow the lawn.',''),(1784,'I really want to like this game since I enjoy rimworld and going medieval but I just don\'t. The pacing feels really weird to me like i\'ll go from dying from the cold while huddled by a fire then the next day i\'m already nearing endgame items.',''),(1785,'Not what I expected. I bought it on a whim during a Steam sale fairly cheap. On the first night I stayed up late, then I called in sick the next day, then the weekend came and went, I haven\'t spoken to my family in days, I smell funny and now my wife is leaving me. I helped her pack.  This game is that good.',''),(1786,'I have really enjoyed this but after a while it does get repetitive within a game. I like the alien survival aspects, different lands, moons, and scenarios to play as well.',''),(1787,'I find this game to be a perfect balance of strategy and chill base building.  You can make the game difficult and a fight for survival or just go and enjoy a game that is a wonderful combination of Rimworld and The Sims.',''),(1788,'A great colony sim and base building game, with mechanics in place to slowly ratchet up difficulty against you so that you have to stay on your toes. And slowly is right - unless you really dawdle, you should be able to stay well ahead of the curve in normal difficulty ranges. I like the additional requirements of having to observe and understand local resources before you can use them - although I don\'t love that random seeds will also sometimes shut you out of certain resources. By the same token, access to new crewmembers, which is vital to thriving in this game, is very RNG dependent - some seeds will have folks walking into your camp, and some won\'t have you run across a savable survivor for years.All in all, though, a solid, enjoyable game with a good production loop. Recent updates have added quality of life concerns, easing development building and helping with late game gathering and production. Well worth your time.',''),(1789,'My recommendation is that if you have never played RimWorld, try that first.  Overall it\'s a better version of this game.  If you have played Rimworld but it was too complicated to enjoy, S:AD may be a better fit for you and you should give it a try (or if you can\'t get into the simple graphics and think the 3D will help).  But if you are a Rimworld expert S:AD will probably be a disappointment for you due to lack of depth in the management tools and how unbalanced a lot of things are.Tl;dr - Stranded Alien Dawn is good but definitely lacks polish considering it is a copy of Rimworld.  Many shortcomings feel like a combination of the devs being lazy and not actually playing their own game to experience how frustrating some mechanics are firsthand, which is sad.  Hopefully it gets some balance changes in the future, but the fact it hasn\'t yet this long after launch makes me doubt that will happen.The game is basically a simplified version of Rimworld with 3D graphics.  Almost all the mechanics are identical but the management systems aren\'t as fleshed out.  For example, clothing wears out the same as in Rimworld, but you need to manually tell colonists when you want them to change gear instead of being able to set a threshold where they automatically switch out what they are wearing when it gets too worn out.  And then you need to manually mark worn out gear to get scrapped instead of having anything below a certain HP automatically get scrapped.Same thing with the storage system.  Containers have a \"Store here first\" option you can check to prioritize where items get put first but if you want something stored in multiple places (ex. food in the fridge, but then also wanting a container near barrels to make loading them quicker) you are out of luck.  You also have to choose between allowing any item on the approved list take up the entire container or limit each approved item to only 1 stack.  So if you have only two items you want to store but want to ensure there is always space for some of both you\'re forced into leaving the container half empty.  Meanwhile Rimworld lets you set storage priority order and set specific limits on each item in storage.  Hell, you can customize each crafting job to specify which stockpile to get inputs from and where to store the item when it\'s finished!  In this you have 0 control over any of that.Another example is the taming menu, which does show growth and fattening %, training level, etc, but for some reason isn\'t filterable/sortable and doesn\'t show which animals are pregnant.  And selecting an animal from the taming list doesn\'t actually select them either, just centers the camera (which has a menu over it) on the animal.  So if it\'s in a crowd you end up needing to click through them individually anyway.Crafting times are very long and doesn\'t seem to be impacted by colonist level much either.   It\'s impossible to find info on how each level affects crafting speed but I think someone at level 10 crafts something 2.5-3x faster than someone at level 0.  So assuming that is true, a crossbow would take 10 hours to craft at level 0 and 3.33 hours at level 10.  To craft a full set of clothes for a colonist it takes 60 hours (at level 0) of crafting time: shirt-12, pants - 12, vest - 18, boots - 12, helmet - 6.  So even at level 10 it will take at least 20 hours.  And then you can only use 50% of the clothes health before colonists complain they are worn out and need to be replaced.',''),(1790,'very nice detailed survival base builder',''),(1791,'Solid game. Imagine the setup of Rimworld with the cosmetics of The Sims and you will know what you\'re getting into.',''),(1792,'Seemed a little unbalanced. I really like the idea, but my biggest issue is there\'s a lack of ability to really micromanage people. You can have a few crafting tables setup for different topics, but your priority system doesn\'t allow you to really assign people to crafting tables and such. The ever increasing enemy waves is irritating as well. I just want to build out my initial base without too much hostility, then hostility can come. A lot of the item crating just takes too bloody long.',''),(1793,'The game that made me forget my suffering and pain.',''),(1794,'Masterpiece survival village builder. 10/10',''),(1795,'I have some hard frustrations with this game that seem very easy to solve, but I\'m done with it. I\'ve spent enough time trying to have the fun everyone seems to have with this game.',''),(1796,'It\'s like playing the sims and starship troopers at the same time. It\'s crazy good.',''),(1797,'Great game, it\'s very addicting. You think you will just play for a couple hours and then its 5am and yur wondering why yur so tired.',''),(1798,'10/10 a good few tips for any noobs. Eat freshly severed limbs in front of the dying original owner to assert dominance over the cannibals and make them fear you more.there is a completely free pistol in the orange lifeboat with no risks thanks to the cannibals not knowing how to swim.opening every boarded cave entrance early on increases loot quality around the world.killing cannibal children and mothers causes the population to decline and them to not attack you out of fear. the moment you spawn in, any cannibal you see, you kill on sight to prevent them from warning the others thus leaving you with a greater period of total peace.destroying cannibal camps further reduces the cannibal spawns making the area much more peaceful.when starting out any cannibal group you see acting weary and not immediately attacking can be pacified via acting aggressive and killing their members thus making them fear and not attack you for the length of the game.red mushrooms both damage you and provide a 5% movement speed bonusif you jump off a cliff and hold control you dont take any fall damage no matter the height',''),(1799,'i can throw rocks at my friends',''),(1800,'For every like this review gets, I will consume 1 spoonful of mayonnaise',''),(1801,'After 455 hours...It\'s the almost perfect gave for builders...Honestly, you can run through the main story in about four hours. After that, all there is to do is base building. Once or twice a day between four and eight enemy NPC\'s will come to attack your base. Its usually the cannibals in the afternoon around 14:00 and two or three times a season at night around 23:00 the mutants come out. There\'s no hunting, in fact, there\'s barely any wildlife. No quests or side objectives, there is actually no reason to explore almost 80% of the map as all of the story objectives are on one side or 15 -20% of the map. They did spread the inventory items around the map a little better than they were for early release, but once you have them there is no reason to be on that side of the world unless you just want to be.I wound up making a save where I flew around the map spawning thousands of extra enemies just to make it interesting for a fresh play through.I do think this would be a great game for groups to play together, especially if one person is acting like a DM. Using the DEV Commands to summon enemies and adding or removing things. But for solo play... if your not into building then probably don\'t waste your money.',''),(1802,'Love it! One of the best survival horror games :) Devs are amazing, constant updates and great content. Keep up the great work! :)',''),(1803,'Greg is delicious and sustains me, my friend, my mute log collector and my three legged wife every winter night.',''),(1804,'Sorry in advance, this review is going to be similar to this game: not very good.I was a big fan of the first The Forest game, and this game expands on that.  The inventory system is just as annoying, but at least it\'s expanded.  Most mechanics are also similar to the first game and they kept the immersive nature of performing an action, regardless of how little sense it makes.The island is beautiful and much larger than the first game.  The map is actual GPS so much easier to see where your character is.  The inhabitants on the island are new and interesting and difficult.  There are multiple types of mutants and cannibals and they act different from each other.  Some of the events while adventuring through the game definitely gave me pause and I admired them.However, the game just wasn\'t fun.Exploration of the island was dull.  It\'s massive and empty.  There aren\'t really many things to find.  And those things that you do find hardly further the plot.And there\'s not much plot.  The ending felt like it was part of a fever dream that I couldn\'t remember how I got there.  Too many of the clues were throw-away emails that weren\'t important.The combat was annoying.  It\'s difficult to find bullets and the melee combat mechanics aren\'t great.Building was pointless since there\'s no reason to keep a place to sleep.  You can complete the game easily without a base.  If you do choose to build, raids on your base show that defenses are largely ignored by enemies.  And the damage that some enemies did to some build pieces was far too high.There was no point to cooking.  Or really eating anything better than basic items.There were too many items that weren\'t required to progress the story.  We could have skipped half the game and accidentally beat it.There were too many bugs.  This is a more minor issue since at the time of this review the game is in early access.  But my group and I nearly all got stuck in walls or had some other game-breaking bug that required using commands to restore the ability to play.I expected a lot more from this game.  But after beating it, the only feeling I have is that the developers were more interested in mechanics than what makes a game fun.',''),(1805,'Game is very good :), just waiting for them to add the big bonfire',''),(1806,'Played this game from very early on and they\'ve added so much to it since then. It\'s a lot of fun and has high replay value for me. I still get creeped out sometimes and I know what\'s around the corner in most cases. Highly recommended.',''),(1807,'My gambling addict friend said if I post a review on Sons Of The Forest and it gets 50 likes and 15 Awards that he will buy me a case of beer. So im just gonna leave this here.',''),(1808,'Pros:Excellent base-building mechanics.Intelligent AI behavior.Well-balanced weaponry.Cons:Insufficient content in the later stages of the game.Persistent bugs.Scarcity of ammunition across the map.The game loses momentum after the first winter, offering limited activities beyond expanding your base and sporadically defending against cannibal raids, which occur roughly every three days.Additionally, the absence of AR-style weaponry is puzzling, considering the player\'s role as a PMC. Given the scenario of being deployed by a well-equipped private military company, the lack of modern firearms seems weird.In summary, the game delivers an enjoyable experience up to the point of achieving self-sufficiency. Beyond that, the excitement fades due to a lack of compelling content.',''),(1809,'Pretend your an ewok and this game gets better',''),(1810,'Very good',''),(1811,'cute game makes my pc crash',''),(1812,'RUN FOREST RUN',''),(1813,'...............,´¯­­`,.........,´¯`,....­­/....../¯/.../..../..../../.../..../­­..,-----,../../.../....//­­´...........`../../.../..../­­......../´¯\\....\\(\'.(\'..(\'....(\'....­­...|.....\'._.\'.\\.................­­...`\\.../´...)...\\...............­­......V...../.....\\.............­­............/.......`•............­­.......•´..........|.........­­........|........▓▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▓........▓▒▒▒▒▒▒▒▓',''),(1814,'Man cut down trees.Man build house. Man happy',''),(1815,'They need to release a OST for this already',''),(1816,'Live Laugh Love Kelvin',''),(1817,'Velmy topra hra',''),(1818,'We need crime