tes, then they can revive you anyway regardless of their class. Also since any class can use any type of weapon, it makes the class type even more moot. Sure each class specializes in a certain weapon type and they gain certain benefits from it, but it\'s really not that big of a hindrance to use a different weapon.I can\'t really explain it, but between the poor map design, the game\'s fast paced focus (faster than what a good Battlefield game feels like), and the fading of classes, it just feels like a watered down shooter that looks like a Battlefield game, but lost touch with what a Battlefield game is suppose to be. All I want is more Bad Company.Actually, all I want is a 2142 remake.Also, ♥♥♥♥ you EA for locking a third of your content behind the elite edition.Is it worth $10.00? For some mindless fun, sure. It beats getting an aneurysm from sweating in Warzone. Is it ever worth handing over your money to EA? Absolutely the ♥♥♥♥ not.',''),(2140,'My friend was 10 feet in front of me picking me up in his jeep when 10 tons of pain rained down upon him from a fighter plane above and blew his carcass about a mile away right off a cliff in front of me.What was left of the car ran me over while I was trying to process all of this.Then I got home and played Battlefield 2042.',''),(2141,'Better than Baldur\'s Gate 3, BEST GAME OF ALL TIME!!!!!!!!!!',''),(2142,'game sux',''),(2143,'still need improvements but its fun and i am having fun',''),(2144,'my friend said that is this post gets 20 likes he will give me some skittles couch change and some kraft cheese so ima leave this here ok bye.',''),(2145,'here i will leave the cat, friends who pass by can pet it and give it a thumbs up　　　 　　／＞　　フ　　　 　　| 　_　 _ l　 　　 　／` ミ＿xノ　　 　 /　　　 　 |　　　 /　 ヽ　　 ﾉ　 　 │　　|　|　|　／￣|　　 |　|　|　| (￣ヽ＿_ヽ_)__)　＼二つ',''),(2146,'After the big updates and patches, definitely - yes, I recommend it.',''),(2147,'I found a bear in a jail and recruited it. 10/10',''),(2148,'Last ten years, ı slowly came to realize that I didn’t get any joy by playing games. Then I installed Wartales….',''),(2149,'Purchased it when it was early access and it got me hooked up. Took a pause till the game was fully finished.. and gave it another go. A lot of added content and variety, good lore, lots of small details that make the game more immersive. It\'s one of those games.. that makes you forget about dinner and keep you hooked for hours.',''),(2150,'Wartales is a great mercenary simulator type game where you manage your future war-band across the land in search of renown, fame, or conquest. You start off with four members with various different types of backgrounds and then proceed to increase your party with varying types of roles, skills, and abilities as you progress. There are various types of professions which help with the creation of weapons, armors, food production, things for your party and camp, etc. These are done by small mini games that give the game a good variety in their creation. Timing can help to produce even better quality gear. You pick up quests along with random contracts given out at taverns in different towns. Managing your inventory, goods, and items are all part of the game play which feels really good. There are also a variety of different menus and skill trees to be advanced which feel really good. Each character has progression trees, the war-band themselves have trees based on how you play along with professions. This system feels very rewarding.Where the game shines is the combat. This is handled in turn based combat with movement and skills that are factored in how you maneuver your troops and execute their attacks. At the beginning of the combat you have the ability to position your war-band unless your group is surprised. From there the turns go by initiative until resolved. The animations are great and the kill cam that triggers on a great last kill always feels satisfying. I find the combat to be my favorite part of the game.I don\'t really have much in the way of negatives aside from the leveling of the professions and the level of each member of your party can get a bit slow and grindy as you get higher levels giving the feeling of a very slow progression. Aside from that, this is an absolute gem of a game worth every penny. I eagerly look forward to any further DLCs or expansions that may be in Wartales future. Highly recommended.',''),(2151,'I bought the base game last year after reading a book about a man who begins the story by jumping off a cliff into the sea in attempted suicide, to running his own ship and small army by the end. Along the way he acquires fame, learns to fight, and forge, makes friends, and enemies, and fights his way into some big paydays-though he spends essentially all of it keeping his crew fed, and housed; a never ending cycle of getting a big score, and then spending the resources in order to reach the next big score. I thought this game seemed like the ideal way to live out that lifestyle: A turn-based, survival, open world, management, rpg featuring aspects of economy, thievery, camp life, bounty hunting, prisoner taking, animal befriending, choice making, and bad-guy stabbing. Perfection. Only thing it was missing was the boatsWell now, a year later, they added the first large DLC, and lo and behold, there\'s boats. Life finds a way',''),(2152,'One of the most powerful attention catcher for the past year. Once your are in - you will lose the track of time for sure, coz of all micromanagement you have to focus on in every damn second. Also I have to praise the devs and for splendid integration of many game mechanics and techniques. My hat\'s off.',''),(2153,'I almost never post reviews, but I wanted to like this game enough that I\'m going to. Can\'t recommend this game at the time of this review. Things wrong with it:1) Pathing. You want your group to cross a mountain ridge? Need to do it manually. If the option for smart pathing exists then it\'s not enabled out of the box. Which is ♥♥♥♥. You say I\'m being too harsh? No. Because this problem exists not only for global pathing but local pathing too. Why do I get stuck on terrain when the destination is literally a few meters away from me? You also can\'t just travel across a town even when there\'s a road going right through it. That means if you want to catch a merchant caravan before it disappears in town, you need to path around the town. I can not think of any sane reason for this design and attribute it to the laziness of the devs.2) Oh you say it\'s fine, manual is good, it\'s old-school, it\'s more authentic, unlike that hand-holding BS in modern games... I don\'t buy that but if that\'s the argument then at least allow fast forwarding. I\'m not even asking for unfair travel speeds where you can always run away from danger or something. Just let me get to the destination faster. Of the hours I played the game, most of it was spent walking back and forth. If you like a walking simulator, buy this now and never look back.3) Combat isn\'t well thought out. Difficulty should come from tactical elements and not things you cannot do anything about. Some civilian will light your well-armoured military unit on fire who takes 15% max hp damage every time he ends turn and the only way to put it out is from movement abilities that most of your guys probably won\'t have. Is that fun? No. Oh by the way, did I mention the core mechanism in the game for melee units is you \"engage\" an enemy by attacking them in melee range, thereby locking you in combat? And to debuff them you can \"surround\" them by having multiple melee units adjacent to them. But that means civilians are very high threat because they can light all surrounding units on fire. Yea, no.4) Resources. Iron ore node respawn is 15 in-game days or something ridiculous like that. ♥♥♥♥ that. Not many merchants will sell it either.5) Choices for relationship issue resolution make no sense. What\'s the point if the relationship will deteriorate regardless unless you sack one of the units? This makes the game \"hard\" sure, but not in a fun way. For context, I took a gamble with my archer and she hit a teammate. Next rest, the teammate wanted her gone. Best option was to ask the teammate to drink it away but it required a beer, which I can\'t find anywhere but many wines are readily found.6) The scaling that everyone complains about is there and yes it\'s bad. The enemy group sizes grow as you recruit more people, but the drops don\'t seem to scale. I killed a whole group of 9 guards and walked away with a spiked club, and 100 suspicion level which costs 200 gold to clear. Ok so crime doesn\'t pay, got it. But I fought a similarly sized group of bandits and also came away with scraps. So the game disincentivizes fights. Why even play then?These are the main issues and I\'m only a few hours in. Save your money and buy only on sale for $10 or something. At the current price I can\'t recommend it.',''),(2154,'- Great combat, that rewards tactical positioning and aggressiveness- Morale meter that allows you to end combat early when you obviously have won (e.g. only 2 enemies left compared to your full party). Real time-saver- Classes and their specializations feel distinct. Some are more obviously powerful than others, but all have their role to fulfill.- Nice overarching main mission for each province- Arena is fun and rewarding- Most non-combat skills (e.g. blacksmith, cooking, etc) are meaningful- Upgrade-able legendary weapons are sweet- Using pitons (deployable ropes + spike) to help traverse between different levels on the overland map is pretty cool. You can use it to get to secret areas, shorten travel time and avoid combat. Thankfully, enemies dont seem to know how to use them- No endgame crisesCompared to similar games:Less RNG and more forgiving than Battle Brothers.Combat reminds me of Expeditions series, in a good way.Overall, great game',''),(2155,'My 2023 Game of the year.290 hours in and I\'m pretty much finished.There is just a heck of a lot to this game (without too much grind in any particular area).Heaps of content and mini-games or non-core gameplay aspects (fishing, mining, arenas, tombs, base building, Rugby etc).You would be hard pressed to complete the game and under 100 hours, and you would miss a lot of content in doing so.The Belerion expansion adds about another 60 hours or so.Overland travel is fine.Combat is turn-based.RPG elements are relatively minimal with a little bit of character progression and occupation levelling.Plenty of mods available (nexus) if you would like to tweak the core gameplay.I hate long rambling reviews.',''),(2156,'Overall Impression (tl;dr) - Wartales is a turn-based strategic RPG with solid story, engaging encounters requiring brains and making tactical decisions - as well as a co-op mode working reasonably well. The game is largely polished. I have encountered few frustrating bugs, but I believe they have been fixed by the active Dev team. Overall, it is great worth for money and lets you have epic-scale arguments with your pals on who goes first during the fight.Final rating - ★★★★★  Follow Vaporlair for more reliable recommendations! Experience (gameplay/lore) -You lead a band of mercenaries - starting with four members of the group and a pony. With all of them being equipped in low quality weaponry and armours - and with rather serious chances of dying during first encounters - you struggle up, completing missions, leveling up, getting better gear and gathering resources off the map to grow your camp. There currently are 10 professions your novice mercenaries might choose from - with levels ranging from novice to master. These are going to be majorly useful on your way, allowing you to craft superior gear, medicine, torches and otherwise - gain knowledge points necessary to advance and upgrade your mercenary team. Lore is pleasantly designed: giving you unobvious choices to make, taking you through lands experiencing refugee influx, pestilence - and so on, so on. It\'s not that easy to take a side and you\'re likely rethink some decisions.Audiovisuals (graphics/audio) -Wartales is pretty. It\'s how you\'d like your Mount & Blade 2 to be, in fact. You\'ll find yourself, I\'m sure, rather happy with how locations are designed. Interiors of places - towns, shops, points of interest - are pleasantly arranged and furnished, great outdoors are full of trees, shaped coastlines, terrain of different height and bodies of water. Companions do have few customisation options, all the clothing changes are reflected as well.The music is fine. It\'s not very memorable; the award here should go to sound effects - noises, groans, moans, weapon effects hearable during attacks - that\'s really well-designed and makes you in awe of all the combos, critical strikes and choice of weaponry!Optimisation (mechanics/bugs) -Wartales is well-optimised. Actually, I am surprised with how small in size this game is and how fast it works even on mid-tier PCs. Loading screens before combats are short, you can load your game really swiftly. Combat restarts can be done without disconnections on co-op and are also rather quick.I\'ve had some issues with troops passing through places they shouldn\'t, disconnecting my group on co-op and forcing us to reload; I\'ve had bugs disallowing my folks to pick up the loot and customise their characters in initial menu. Fortunately, they were single occurrences and some of them, allegedly, have been fixed - hence, I don\'t have much to complain about.TAGS:#rpg #strategy #coop',''),(2157,'This is an odd one... The game has solid foundation but i feel that its ultimately held back due to questionable design choices.I was writing a proper review in the reasons why but i noticed i ended up writing an article pointing the flaws in game design.So the TLDR: You are punished by doing well. You are punished by leveling up too fast because your equipment doesnt have time to catch up to your levels.(You end up being lvl 8 with half your team using stuff for level 3-4 or worse if your team is big)Somehow they managed to punish efficiently grinding in a VERY grindy game. They punish you for taking people with perks that earn extra exp because they will get ahead of the team and make the enemies higher level while your team didnt catch up to the levels. ALSO the enemies will drop items that have higher level requirement that your team cannot use. ALSO you will have less time fighting enemies in a certain level meaning you have less loot, meaning you will have less options to equip your team with. ALSO the enemy teams gets bigger as your team gets more people... but the loot doesnt increase. So the bigger your team less rewarding is the fights.Like i said there is very odd gamedesign decisions in a pretty solid game, at first its not a big issue but after some time in the play-through the issues gets more and more glaring. I restarted my runs multiple times trying to understand what was going on and messing with game settings but sadly its simply design flaws holding this game back.Theres \"solutions\" for these flaws, you game the system. EG: You leave your high level characters in a town and leave with a smaller team of lower level characters. So the enemy groups get smaller and lower level, allowing for easier fights and more chance to get loot of your proper level.I mean... at this point you are taking the flaw in the design and taking advantage of it to make the flaw less relevant.And the devs? WELL.... This game is on gamepass. The version of PC on gamepass is ERASING SAVES for sometime now.The devs announced a DLC. That shows how much the devs care about the player experience.',''),(2158,'I can\'t recommend this game. There will be some spoilers in this review.I like games where you are controlling tiny guys on the screen and part of this game has that. It wasn\'t particularly compelling, but good enough. I also like turn based combat- again this game wasn\'t particularly compelling but good enough. There is some resource management- your soldiers can be miners, scholars, tinkers, etc. and there is some mini-game like features associated with crafting... that isn\'t particularly compelling but good enough. Just about the whole game is good enough but nothing special.Then, for some reason, when you get to the fifth zone this very, very low magic world introduces zombies.It calls them plague victims, but they\'re really zombies. I could deal with that, but it also introduces new game play features which amounts to being good at running away. There are encounters where your job is to run away because the zomb... plague victims will spawn endlessly. If your guys, which you\'ve spent hours developing as tough, stout fighters aren\'t fast enough they will die. I couldn\'t stand it.I\'m sure some people will like this game, it\'s gotten very good reviews. If not for the run away encounters it\'s very likely I would\'ve finished this game because it was a competent game that was good enough, but mainly because I don\'t have anything else to play. I\'m not going to ask for a refund or anything. Up until Luden I was happy to keep playing. As I said there\'s plenty of OK gaming here but, at least for me, there\'s not enough to justify having endure encounter styles that I absolutely loathe.',''),(2159,'Awesome, strategic and addictive game.Started first playthrough  on adaptive extreme difficulty. Lost party, started again, finished the game.Endgame is just missing. So, i guess there was no point to make the game \"eternal\". I guess your party can fight with time, getting older, suffering from old wounds, etc, having risk of dying before Path goals are achieved. But it\'s just stays as is with no further plot/quests to deal with except regular head-hunting. This game is very similar to \"Sid Meyer\'s Pirates!\" so the similar solution looks logical.Anyway, it was awesome 200 hours. And for me, it is definitely game of the year.',''),(2160,'Saw Splattercat play this on his channel, it debated for weeks if i was going to spend money on this game. I\'m glad i did! there is so much to uncover. when you think youv\'e seen it all, you head to a new region and there\'s more to find! it has some kinks with pathfinding but its really not that bad. tombs are great fun! i hate turn based combat but the devs found a way to make it not painful and even fun, almost like a puzzle: \"move this guy here, set up the next round like so, have this guy cause bleeding so the next guy can crit, open the round with my AOE monster of a tank\". I struggle with wanting to be a criminal thief murderer versus the savior of the land. woe is me!',''),(2161,'\"Wartale\" excels in gameplay diversity, offering a refreshing detour from the typical \'chosen one\' narrative. It compels players to grind, strategize, and evolve from pretty much nothing. Its varied mini-games in relation to skills and careers add layers of depth, making each step of the journey feel earned. The game masterfully balances challenge with progression, delivering an experience both rigorous and rewarding. I really don\'t know why it took me as long as it did to buy it. Fans of management, turn-based strategy, and \'Witcher\'-like fantasy settings will enjoy this.',''),(2162,'I actually used to really like this game. I was in fact fairly close to the end of it when they announced the new dlc so I decided to wait until it came out to buy it and play through the rest of the game.     Unfortunately a balance patch that released with said dlc killed the game for me. What was a quick and brutal tactical game has just turned into a tedious slog to play, with every fight taking twice as long as it should. I ended up just dreading each fight because I knew it was going to take too long and I would be struggling with the games completely arbitrary starting positions in every combat. Goes to show how little changes can massively impact the experiences of the people actually engaging with the mechanics. What may have been an improvement for some was an unexpected and unwelcome change for me. So the game was more than the sum of it\'s parts before it start to break down, early on it\'s quite good when money is tight and you actually have to be a little careful but quickly the numbers of units on both sides balloons to be unwieldy and to bog the game down. Quite literally in combats case because it seems like half of you units always start in the mud and the rest are on the other side of the map.      The management system is interesting, you camp set up is important as your characters will develop relationships with other characters based on proximity in camp and their activities in combat and will also play a big part in your ability to keep prisoners from running away. You research and unlock new items and upgrades for your camp and different terrains provide different activities for your mercenaries to perform overnight to gather resources and raise their skills. Sadly I found most of the management side of the game to be over and done with about half way through my play time with every item unlocked and upgraded and food and money easy to obtain.The combat is the bulk of the game and each of your mercenaries has skills based on their weapon and class, with the selection ranging from great, to pretty niche, to just bad with there being times when levelling where I was faced with the choice between three skills or upgrades that would never get used. Visually while the dark fantasy aesthetic looks nice there is little variation in armour so your mercenaries tend to all look the same, compounded by the lack of interesting choice between weapon skills and class meaning that most of your mercs of the same class will be filling the same role and using the same equipment. I found myself having certain characters using inferior helmets just to be able to tell them apart. The basics of combat is that each mercenary has their move of their basic attack and pretty much everything else will cost you action points to use which come from a pool that the entire group draws from consisting of two types, permanent points which are gained by sleeping and regenerate each day and temporary points which you gain in combat through various actions based on your class skill tree like engaging enemies in melee combat or killing enemies. The order of combat is initiative based and being hit is costly because each damaged piece of armour or wound will need to be healed so you are very much encouraged to pin down or kill every enemy before they can do anything to you and when it works it\'s gloriously fun and brutal. But the  problem is that there are a few factors that really drag the experience down. The first is the way that positioning is done at the start of combat, with a number of slots that your mercs and ponies to fill just arbitrarily scattered around the place so you most likely will end up having to split your forces because you didn\'t have enough slots to actually set them up the way you wanted. The then there is the mud, which is an obstacle on almost every battle field and for some reason half the starting positions are in the mud. So you end up on the other side of the battle field and moving slowly from the mud. Up until recently I could mitigate this problem turning what is a major frustration into an minor annoyance but this has been changed requiring more units. The main problem being that the combat really starts to be a slog when you have more units. i find what was fast paced brutal fun becomes slow and tedious and that fails to match the pacing of the rest of the game, travel is only slow at the start very quickly becoming fast paced, management is really quick, arenas are quick, exploration is quick and my favourite aspect of the game. The other big issue that mars combat is that fact that the maps are not interesting in the slightest and you will see the same ones a lot, with most consisting of some mud scattered about. The set piece fights are so much better than most of the rest with interesting mechanics and situations, except for any of the ones where you have to run away from something which then comes back to dealing with the movement problems of other combats.   The exploration deserves a special mention because it\'s the aspect of the game that really shines. On the over world map you can set up new paths using pitons and ropes and the actual act of moving about the map is mostly well done though it does suffer from some pathing problems. The exploration of the tombs is a great little dungeon crawl with some easy puzzles and fighting monsters in the dark shakes up the combat and each one was a nice side diversion that ties really well into the research system.     Overall the pacing of turn based combat is a difficult thing to pull off and can often be quite subjective but in this case the tactics are not in-depth enough for me to want to spend that much time in each individual fight considering I am going to be fighting hundreds of times. Before the pace was pretty good for me when using a particular set up but now  to get the same pace in combat I need more units which means more food and more gold which slows down the pace of the other aspects of the game. It\'s a balancing act between all of them that doesn\'t work for me anymore.',''),(2163,'An impressive and ambitious game that expertly blends strategic RPG elements with turn-based tactics. What really impressed me was the game\'s tactical depth and the importance of positioning in battles. The fights are challenging, and every decision matters, which really makes you think.I particularly liked the camp management system, as it provides plenty of opportunities for character development and exploration. The game\'s world is rich and detailed, with each region having its own challenges and stories, adding depth to the experience.However, the pace of the game can sometimes feel slow, especially due to the extensive walking and long battles. This can occasionally make the game feel a bit monotonous, although this is somewhat alleviated by the later introduction of fast travel options.',''),(2164,'Fantastic mercenary management game which successfully blends together a few genres. Has improved quite a bit since early access and I would say deserving of the overwhelmingly positive reviews. It\'s mostly a mix of the following:> Turn based combat which rewards build choice, strategic positioning and use of all mechanics> Light RPG mechanics (levelling & dialogue options)> Camp and mercenary management (you can even capture prisoners/animals in battle)> Exploring regions with their own locations to find, sidequests and main region quest> Trading runs> Earning knowledge XP for knowledge points and spending them on new items/perks/unlockables> Minigames which are actually enjoyable> Gritty low fantasy setting (no spells, fantasy creatures)Similar games: Battle Brothers (feels more tabletop, highly addictive!), Mount & Blade (for the world exploration), Jagged Alliance 2 (haven\'t played 3), Wasteland 2/3 (not mercs, but some overlap).',''),(2165,'A Compelling Blend of Strategy and StorytellingWartales, the debut title from Shiro Games, successfully marries strategic depth with immersive storytelling, resulting in a captivating and engaging gaming experience. Set in a medieval-inspired open world, Wartales beckons players into a world of mercenaries, exploration, and dynamic, turn-based combat.Strategic Brilliance:At the heart of Wartales lies its strategic brilliance. The game introduces a unique blend of turn-based combat and real-time exploration, challenging players to navigate their mercenary band through a perilous world. Tactical decision-making is paramount, as players must balance resource management, character progression, and party composition to overcome diverse challenges.Mercenary Management:The game\'s mercenary management system adds a layer of complexity and depth. Assemble a diverse band of characters, each with their own strengths, weaknesses, and personalities. The decisions made in recruiting, training, and equipping mercenaries directly impact their performance on the battlefield, creating a sense of attachment and investment in the narrative.Open-World Exploration:Wartales offers a rich and expansive open world ripe for exploration. The handcrafted landscapes are visually stunning, providing a picturesque backdrop for the unfolding adventure. The non-linear narrative encourages players to delve into side quests, discover hidden secrets, and engage with a world teeming with lore and possibilities.Compelling Narrative:The game weaves a compelling narrative as players guide their mercenary band through a world rife with political intrigue, moral dilemmas, and unexpected alliances. The choices made resonate throughout the storyline, shaping the fate of both the characters and the world they inhabit. The narrative depth adds an emotional dimension, elevating Wartales beyond its strategic core.Artistic Excellence:Wartales excels in artistic design, embracing a charming and stylized aesthetic that complements the medieval theme. The character designs, environments, and animations contribute to the overall immersion, creating a world that feels both lived-in and fantastical.Technical Polish:In terms of technical performance, Wartales showcases a commendable level of polish. The game runs smoothly, and the user interface is intuitive, ensuring that players can focus on the strategic nuances rather than wrestling with cumbersome controls or technical issues.Multiplayer Dynamics:Wartales includes a multiplayer component that allows players to join forces or engage in competitive gameplay. The cooperative mode enhances the strategic depth by encouraging collaboration, while the competitive mode pits players against each other in intense battles of wits and tactics.Conclusion:Wartales is a triumph for Shiro Games, demonstrating their prowess in crafting a game that seamlessly blends strategic gameplay with a rich narrative tapestry. Its engaging mechanics, captivating story, and artistic charm make it a standout title in the strategy genre. Whether you\'re a fan of tactical RPGs or narrative-driven adventures, Wartales offers a compelling and rewarding experience that leaves a lasting impression.',''),(2166,'Génial! Enfin un vrais rpg tactique. Ils ont tout compris !Il y a même des armures de plate qui ressemble enfin aux vrais de l\'époque médiévale. Si si c\'est possible!',''),(2167,'Sequel to my favorite Digimon game Digimon World 1 on PS1. If you\'ve played it and want to experience it again and some more, get this game.',''),(2168,'Gameplay is time-consuming for the grinding and taking care of Digimon, but the graphics and batlle dynamics seem smooth. Leveling up is cyclical by design, so you just need to get the hang of it.Looking forward to leveling up and learning more within the game.',''),(2169,'Digimon World: Next Order captures the tamagotchi niche very well, although it will be more enjoyable for everyone than the average tamagotchi, it doesn\'t change that this is a niche game.Depending on what you want in your monster taming games, this can be more or less enjoyable than Digimon Story games, while also being more or less enjoyable than Digimon Survive depending on your appreciation for that game\'s niche.- This is basically a straight improvement from Digimon World 1.- Digimon World 2 to 4 have mixed to poor reception, which means DW:NO should stack up quite well by default.The flow of the game is really nice, building city and slowly methodologically training Digimon means that you get into this Stardew/Animal crossing type of daily rhythm which makes it comfortable, relaxed and easy to get in a flow while the game provides significant battle challenges when you are ready. It takes a while to get used to the balance o