he free Car Packs. I willingly I spent the extra dollars because I am a enjoyer of cars. Then here comes Playground Games and Xbox Game Studio releasing car packs that Ignores the car pass I paid for. This is scummy practice that they are starting to employ and we as a community need to let that be known, stop it, or else we will get taken advantage of.',''),(2225,'AI difficulties don\'t adhere to the same physics and car characteristics as you. Also, I love that you start in 8th in every starting grid. The higher difficulties are definitely beatable, but what\'s the point of beating something that is effectively \"cheating.\"',''),(2226,'DON\'T BUY AS A STEAM DECK USER!The game runs horribly, even at the absolute lowest settings possible at the lowest resolution possible with fsr set to performance. the stutters are so bad that it genuinely feels awful to play.',''),(2227,'I am now a racist',''),(2228,'It\'s okay.It\'s the same gameplay as FH4 so it will feel very familiar but just in a bland and boring location.Yes, the graphics are a bit better but that doesn\'t make it a better game and even with older graphics the UK setting looks better.The seasons doesn\'t make any real difference to the look of the world or the gameplay. In fact I barely notice the difference. The music is real downgrade from FH4 but that\'s subjective of course.They left a lot of my favourite cars from FH4 out; maybe they\'ll be added later.On the plus side, newer cars, better graphics, better sound and more ways to upgrade your cars.Not saying avoid, it\'s a good game in isolation but I feel a downgrade from the previous instalment.In summary: FH4>FH5',''),(2229,'I really like this game, especially the car trading and tuning',''),(2230,'The Tim Burton fishing sim we all been waiting for.  Great atmosphere and scenery for this dark and twisted fishing game with a twist!  Mechanics and layout are simple. Doesn\'t take long for you to get sucked into the mystery of the waters and whats really down that rabbit hole.',''),(2231,'Me in-game: Oh no, it\'s night. I need to go to bed.Me IRL: Losing sleep over the game.',''),(2232,'I can see why it\'s good. I didn\'t return this because I think it\'s bad, but rather because I have problems with motion sickness in games and this one made me feel a bit ill. The game itself seems good :)',''),(2233,'I can\'t help but feel a little betrayed by DREDGE. It promises a delicious and intriguing adventure, proves to you that it indeed can fulfill this promise - and then it just kinds of... trails off into mediocrity.Okay, mediocrity is a bit of a strong word. The game still manages to be very engaging, and the way it channels the spirit of Lovecraft\'s... uh... craft - a nice surprise, considering how often \"Lovecraftian\" is just a shorthand for tentacled cosmic horrors. But that only strengthens the burning question I\'m left with after beating it: what if?Sunrise over Innsmouth the MarrowsSee, DREDGE has a very strong start. Something\'s not right. You know something is going to happen. Fishing? Sure, let\'s fish, sell the fish, get better gear. Don\'t pay attention to the black ooze coming from the package you\'re asked to deliver. And make sure to come back before sundown.Point is: the mood is there. On top of it, you\'re given a nice gameplay loop with an extensive upgrade tree. Oh yeah. This is going to be a great ride. Eventually, you begin the main quest in the earnest, and things really get moving.A leak in the hullBut then you slowly start noticing the flaws. The pacing is not quite right, for example. When upgrading my boat, I often felt constrained in this... artificial way. Almost like I\'m just supposed to do things in a specific way. This one\'s a bit hard to explain, and maybe it\'s a me problem; who knows. Another artificial feeling comes when you realise how the game world is structured. It feels less like a living, breathing world, and more like, well, a set of video game levels. Everything is too deliberate; too functional. You might say that it\'s a good thing, keeps things lean. I say it\'s a tradeoff - one I personally didn\'t like too much.Light up the nightAnd the final complaint is that once you begin the main quest, the dread just stops. Yes, there is the general feeling of \'what the hell am I even working towards\' which keeps going until the very end, but that\'s about it. The areas start feeling sterile. The threats - all manageable with ease. Even the night stops being an issue after a while.Also, the general design of the areas other than the central one is just... not very eldritch, if that makes any sense? There\'s nothing ominous about them. Yes, there are major, location-specific threats, but they\'re rather obvious and have some pretty fool-proof ways of neutralising. Maybe it\'s my fault for comparing this game in my mind to Sunless Sea (can you blame me?), where literally every place filled you with a dread of different flavour (even if the gameplay itself was nowhere near as fun as here).Rise from the depthsYeah, the game is fun, in spite of all these flaws. Fishing might be a collection of minigames, but they\'re varied and short. The inventory management is a pleasure throughout the entire game. And even though I said that the threats are all trivial to manage, it still remains a thrill to do so - mainly because your boat is very susceptible to damage, and every hit can ruin your haul.And the main mystery, hoo boy. You\'re being fed pieces of the truth as you go, and let me tell you: I\'ve seen a lot of mysteries. I hate the extent of my plot prediction abilities. And here? I managed to piece one thing together, but the final twist caught me off guard like a champ. And it\'s excellently foreshadowed. Throw me backI guess I just wanted... more. More mystery. More exploring. More upgrades. It\'s a great game, all things considered; and the combination of fishing and Lovecraft seems like such a natural concept. And yes, in spite of everything I wrote, I recommend this game wholeheartedly - even if, or perhaps especially if you\'re not very good with horror.And for those who don\'t generally play indie titles - thanks for reading. DREDGE is a good game, but trust me, if you decide to, uh, dredge the depths of the Ocean of Steam, there are so many amazing experiences out there to find. For sure, play this one; just perhaps consider throwing your fishing line into the unknown sometime. You\'ll be very surprised by what you\'ll find.Curator page',''),(2234,'DREDGE is a neatly packaged game.Its scope is strongly defined, its aesthetic is consistent, and its gameplay is well-realised.You find yourself in Little Marrow after crashing your ship into the rocks that flank the town, indebted - both metaphorically and financially - to the townsfolk who rescued you. What follows is a dozen hours of fishing mini-games, inventory management, and exploration, guided by the game\'s story - an understated, mysterious, lovecraftian tale of tragedy, which is intriguing if a little conventional.The gameplay is enjoyable enough but doesn\'t take long to become a repetitive task, though checking off the list of sea-dwellers in the encyclopedia is satisfying. Each creature has one or more aberrational variants - a manifestation of the eldritch forces that loom over the world - and further variety is added through the different biomes, requirements for catching specific fish, and how well you are able to maintain your sanity in the wake of witnessing otherworldly abominations.Creaking pontoons, clacking winches, and swelling waves help deliver the atmosphere of the game effortlessly, along with the often serene and occasionally unsettling score. Depictions of strange fish reveal the unspeakable terrors from the deep: voids where eyes should be, blistered and bubbling scales, and grotesque many-mouthed beasts.On a technical level the game performs wonderfully. It\'s evident that the resources required aren\'t anything remarkable but it\'s still nice to see such a smooth experience. I played on Steam Deck mostly, with a little time spent on PC, and never ran into any issues. Despite Steam telling me otherwise, the game worked perfectly with a DualSense controller and displayed the correct button prompts.Though the majority of your time is spent engaging with \'cosy\' gameplay mechanics, they coalesce effortlessly with the horror aspects to deliver a rewarding experience that makes DREDGE a game well worth playing.',''),(2235,'The fishing mechanic, which the entire game seems to be based around, doesn\'t land with me. It feels like an overpriced mobile game.',''),(2236,'This game is somewhat difficult to recommend simply because I\'m not sure what it offers. At it\'s core it\'s got a nice idea, playing as a fisherman in a lovecraft story. However the characters are very thin and the story is somewhat minimal, so you aren\'t going to get any deep conversations or meaningful themes.Perhaps gameplay? It\'s a good game to play in the background, but for a creeping dread horror game that\'s not a strong endorsement. I thought it was going to be scary in a \"Is that just a trick of the light, or did that shadow just move?\" kind of way. As your paranoia meter goes up, more spooky things start happening to you, but this already shows a fundamental misunderstanding, Now there\'s a clear line between I am in danger and I am not in danger. Spoiler: If your paranoia meter isn\'t flashing red, you\'re not in danger. Any potential danger outside of this is very easy to spot.\"But it\'s an adventure game\" There\'s 5 locations in the base game each with a minor gimmick and a few fetch quests.I don\'t understand why this game is overwhelmingly positive. It\'s alright, it\'s not a bad game. On a sale I\'d even recommend it, but as it stands the game is just kind of mediocre. The game has a lot of potential but squanders it with a lack of character, intellectual meat, or quest variety.Additional Note for the Devs: If you\'re going to add an enemy that resembles another boat, have there be other ships that we can mistake it for. As it stands, I can see it from distance and cleanly avoid it.',''),(2237,'Why are DLC achievements stopping me from getting 100%. Bad game design, sorry can\'t recommend.',''),(2238,'I wish there were a \"aight\" review option because this game does atmosphere really well, but I feel like it doesn\'t do characters or events much justice. Level design was mostly innocent, but also felt goofy at times just from the nature of the way I explore games.I\'d say, if you want to play a fishing game with great lovecraft atmosphere, then this would be a huge recommend, but I was here for some lovecraftian horror and storytelling that I feel fell short.I would have really liked some characters to have more dialogue after their pursuits/quests are complete. It really feels like someone asks something of you, you do it and then nothing happens. I don\'t think this is excused by the whole \"Horrors beyond comprehension\" trope either as EARLY QUEST SPOILERS:  literally nothing happens when the fish market is given an aberration to eat. He just closes for a couple days and then pretends it didn\'t happen. Similar with the dock worker. Dude apparently just placed an order for a horror beyond his reading level and then stands there for the rest of the game as a pale zombie. Maybe the game just isn\'t exactly for me as I believe the appeal of being a fisherman is meant to be as present a selling point as the eldritch horror. It would hurt the fishing catalogers to suddenly and without waning have important NPCs lose their minds from staring at a rock too long,  but I still feel that a lot of the horror could be expanded on conceptually and fleshed out like the end of the main story pursuit is which was really cool!The ice DLC is good except for the weird entrance to the iceberg. which felt... idk too artificial?The key DLC is garbage though. I don\'t have a problem with supporting devs for making a sick game, but the workshop that the key unlocks is visible for 98% of the game and nothing tells the player that they need a DLC they don\'t have in order to open it. I don\'t think I should have the option to inspect the workshop if I don\'t own the DLC personally.',''),(2239,'Bought it for the overwhelmingly postivie reviews, and I really don\'t see it. Every area is barebones, generally with a single NPC to talk to (not including the same shopkeeper in every area), who needs a specific fish for some reason and then you get a small powerup like fast travel or fishing really fast for a bit. They should remove the lovecraftian tag because there\'s pretty much no horror in the game at all. The scariest thing that can happen is a large snake thing chasing you. None of the NPCs seem to care, and the spooky lovecrafting powers are just  random game tools like fast travel or a speed boost. It\'s very hard for anyone to take it as a mysterious otherworldly power when it\'s just the equivalent of stepping on the accelerator.Most NPCs have no interaction after the first time you talk to them. There\'s a point in the game where you have to help an NPC called The builder make a house and then take them there. At which point you never say anything new. Most NPCs are in the first 2 areas after which you\'ll won\'t even find more than 1 per zone.Every quest is a fetch quest and all of them are convuluted reasons for which someone wants a particular fish. Even then, it can be nonsensical. There\'s a quest to give a certain fish to a robed cult members and the reward is a boost to your engine. This feels more like a mobile game that people can play on the side while doing something else.',''),(2240,'We do a little summoning.',''),(2241,'When I sat down to play DREDGE, I was expecting a lax, calming game about sailing the seas and harvesting some fish. Sure, the \"Lovecraftian\" tag tipped me off a little, but I was sure that my innate fear of the ocean would keep me plenty entertained.What I was NOT expecting was to walk away with DREDGE as one of my favourite games of the year in a year that has been jam-packed with amazing releases.Seriously, this game does everything you\'d want a game of this genre to do. It delivers on the fishing, it delivers on the world, the characters, the immersion and... well, that tag isn\'t there for no reason. In fact, it was so good that I was immediately compelled to go for 100% right after seeing the credits.As for gameplay, it goes for a bizarre blend of a fishing minigame that you might find in a game like Stardew Valley or Animal Crossing, but it manages to sprinkle in one of the most ingenious elements from a game like Don\'t Starve: the Sanity (panic) meter. Trust me, you\'ll get used to frantically glaring at the surface of the water while that chromatic aberration kicks in.The upgrade system helps you feel like you\'re truly progressing, and something that I cannot commend the game enough for is the freedom of choice. Do you want to brave the waters on the first night, slowly dredging while something larger-than-life waits beneath? Go ahead. Want to take your time, upgrading your ship as much as you can before entering a single major area? You can do that, too.I CANNOT recommend this game enough if you\'re into this sort of \"subtle horror\" experience. If you\'re like me and are helplessly scared of any body of water that\'s more than two-feet deep, then all the better.Definitely one of the standouts of the year, and one that I\'ll look back on fondly.',''),(2242,'Crab pots. Pet dog. Good game.',''),(2243,'Game was fun but expected more from the main story for the amount this game costs. Game has a great start but grinding for all the upgrades to the ship felt useless at the end as well.',''),(2244,'I LOVE FISHING!!!!!',''),(2245,'all my homies HATE cocoon',''),(2246,'My biggest complaint is the pricing - I would absolutely recommend this game, but I would also suggest you pick it up in a 50% sale or so...Other than fish, the world felt a little empty, but what was there, I really enjoyed. The atmosphere is great, especially the way madness creeps up on you when staying awake for too long.Mechanics and gameplay loop are pretty decent too, but it\'s still a fishing game of course - So gameplay is not particularly dense and the game feels a little short at 10-15 hours, considering the pricepoint. I just wish there was more exploration and story. DLC: If it\'s your first playthrough, it\'s a nice addition. If you\'re considering returning purely for the DLC, I\'d say: Don\'t bother.',''),(2247,'i always say morning instead of good morning because if it was a good morning id be fishing',''),(2248,'Some are red, and some are blue.Some are old and some are new.Some are sad, and some are glad,And some are very, v̸̪͉́͠e̸̤̋r̵͔͉̍y̸͇͙̚ ̵̢̖̏ḇ̷͍̕a̶̦͇͐̈́d̵̳̬̊',''),(2249,'It is a relaxing game with a nice atmosphere. Very enjoyable but it does get repetitive after a while because all you are doing are fetch quests and the same fishing mini game.',''),(2250,'The game feels unfinished, as it is seriously lacking things that give others it is genre staying power.  Their does not seem to be any RNG for a Random Map, you only have a select few maps simply based on difficulty.You always start with Goblin units, with no real explanation of why you start with Goblins, other than they being the basic starter units.The same script plays out time and time again.Their is no Player Character unit, unlike other Spell Force games, that can level up and own the battlefield as a powerful Mage. Player character exists only in the Narrative. No early obvious way of increasing Army size.Maybe I need to play longer to see some of this, but can\'t really recommend this game.Edit: Played a bit more. And basically agree with my earlier review.The game really needs a few more RNG features for world generation.  Always start out with the same army of goblins and then whatever familar based on my Crafting Choices. Always get the same Apprentice multiple turns in, always have the exact same fights to reclaim the reserarch. The map might change if I pick a different map out of the choices of 5, but beyond that way to much is static.The AI is also just wierd. They move on the map, and claim sources that you have already claimed. Even while some of them say they are willing to give you a chance. Then they get angry that your inside their border. I get that they are not suppose to be treating you as an equal. But the AI interactions, seem incredibly limit, and one sided. You can initate doing favours for them. You can give them all-fire sources out of a desire to appears them. I get your suppose to be insignificate, but some of them do have small amount of quests, and are willing to ask you to do things, but that only seems to slightly delays the inevitable fact that you have to go to war with them. As their are far more ways to lower your Rep including the static message that lowers it by a set amount of a number of turns.  Even though some of them say they are willing to wait and see...',''),(2251,'I pissed off a necromancer guy and he sent a titan to kick my ass. I did not survive. The titan army killed 4 of my armies then roflestomped my flying tower. I\'m not going to say that it was unfair. The game warned me about it but I did not change my army comp. I had access to medusa unit with stun and light damage and i could make golems. I was also playing an artificer and could have made a bunch of anti undead runes but oh well. T_T After you lose like that it really makes you wanna give it another shot.   This game have a lot of very cool mechanics. Crafting is VERY good. Unit customization is the best I\'ve seen.  You can get a unit that can enslave other mobs. You can make armies on the fly with summons. You can terraform the map or give your armies ability to fly. There are RPG quests, artifacts, runes that give you new abilities. The game pace is a bit slow but building your armies feels rewarding. You can move your mage tower! In fact you should do that often. The other mages get more and more upset with you since you keep messing around with glowy magic holes and it\'s all fun and games untill titan shows up. You can find more magic book pages and research some neat spells.I like it. The concept is unusual but it works. Might take you a couple of starts to figure out how to play though.',''),(2252,'This is not a bad game, not really. But most things are so lazily done that I just cannot recommend it.Take the quests, for instance. The game is centered around them, but the developer originally didnt provide any way to track them. Now, eight months after release, they released a patch with \"quest overview\" that only shows you a location, but doesnt tell you what you are supposed to do there. Would it be so hard to include the original dialogue or a one-sentence summary of the quest? Seriously, this half-baked nothing took eight months?The UI is another sore point, many things could be communicated much better. The battles are OK, but again, many things could have been clearer, including where your units can and cannot move.I loved the third Spellforce installment and played through all the DLCs, but this is just disappointing.',''),(2253,'This game was definitely not ready to be released. These developers are beyond lazy and released a game with where the primary focus is relying on completing quests (outside of defeating the other mages). In their infinite wisdom they chose to not create a quest tracker, so your basically running around the map and generating quests and it doesn\'t tell you how to complete them and sometimes doesn\'t even show you where to go to complete the quest.',''),(2254,'Great game, pity it has no voice overs, but therefore the price is much lower than your typical game. Love the Spellforce lore',''),(2255,'This game is truly awesome. To me, it\'s like Heroes of Might and Magic IV brought to a new height, in the sense that you get to plan and customize your troops much more, and there is a significant sense of progressions for your force. With crafting, spells on units, leveling units, ... it feels like an awesome combination to me. To me it\'s the best game among the dozens of games I find and play in 2023. Maybe a reason that the review isn\'t overwhelmingly positive is that the combat system is kind of deep, creating some barrier for players to enjoy it. And yeah, that can be an issue or a superb advantage, depending on what we look for.',''),(2256,'I was really conflicted about whether to recommend this game, but in the end it\'s a no.  It\'s very beautiful but the game balance is frustrating.  At a basic level the problem is that hidden information makes it difficult to complete a level until you take several tries at it, but when you DO finally do so it\'s fairly straightforward to get all the animals, all the bonus achievements, etc.  For example, in the first biome, you only find out you\'ll have to pick up all your equipment by riverboat once you\'ve completed basically everything else- and the best time to build new riverbeds is in the first stage of terraforming.  This feels really unfair, like fake difficulty.  It some ways it\'s just a matter of framing- the surprise in the 4th environment felt perfectly fair (it tells you there\'s seismic instability but doesn\'t tell you the consequences until you inevitably trigger it).  But framing matters, or we\'d just be playing a puzzle game with colored blocks.  If it was easier to barely scrape by on your 1st or 2nd try, but could take a dozen or more tries and very careful planning to create all the micro-biomes needed to 100%, then I could recommend this game without reservation.  As it is there\'s too much frustration up front, and too little replay value afterwards.',''),(2257,'This was a fun little teraforming game. I enjoyed the environmental renewal concept, it mixed well with bringing back ecology into a ruined planet. I do wish the game was longer (it only took me a few hours to complete) but it was a well thought out and complete game. My main complaint about the gameplay was being unable to move things after placing them, occasionally I would place something without thinking and would have to start the whole level over. It was kind of annoying.Final comment: I agree with previous posts $25 is too much for such a short game. Wait for it to go on sale.',''),(2258,'I recommend this game, with a specific reservation. I\'ve read some of the negative reviews, and I agree with their sentiment but not their reasoning. I have no idea how I heard about this game, but I was more excited about Terra Nil than even some of the big games this year. A little puzzle builder, with a unique premise and really good presentation. It just scratched a little niche itch for me, and I was eager to give it a try.I opened it up on launch day, and dove in. The art and sound design were great, and the difficulty was surprisingly challenging for such a chill game. You have to learn how to set yourself up, and each biome has a really unique set of challenges. And then once I beat the game, watched the credits roll and sat back... I returned to the same earth I started on, and it just didn\'t feel satisfying. Did I want to play longer? Maybe, but it\'s not like Journey was a rip off given the ratio of playtime to dollars spent. Going to a movie can cost the same and lasts much shorter. This is the sentiment I saw in reviews - people finishing the game and wanting something... more.In reflection, I think the issue is that this game promises a chance to save the environment. But you get to the end, and close the game and real life floods back in and it\'s just... not any better, really. Earth is fundamentally the same, and my hard work didn\'t make a dent. I recommend you play this game. Enjoy your time with it. Things can get better for a little while, even if only virtually. Just know that once you\'re done, you\'ll have to come home and the world isn\'t saved.',''),(2259,'Great concept, but far too short. It has the scope of a demo.',''),(2260,'The visuals are very pretty and I enjoyed the combination of building and puzzling aspects. I liked the concept of building up healthy nature from a wasteland and then leaving no trace after completion. For me it was a very chill building game with some light puzzle elements.That said, at least on medium difficulty, the actual puzzle was often not particularly challenging and even once I \"got\" it it still took a fair bit of time to go through the motions of actually completing the levels. I didn\'t mind so much because of the beautfil visuals. Speaking of levels: As of the time of this review this game has eight levels in four different worlds, each with slightly different mechanics. Considering the price this feels very light on content.I bought this game on sale and enjoyed my time with it. I don\'t think I\'d recommend it at full price. I also encountered a bug where the game automatically selected a vertical resolution and didn\'t display the in-game handbook. So that was confusing at first, but adjusting the resolution also fixed the issue of the invisible handbook.',''),(2261,'This game had so much potential. It\'s very pretty and the optimization puzzle is engaging, as the demo indicated it would be... but there are only 8 puzzles in the game total, and 4 of them are essentially reworks for the first 4.',''),(2262,'The game has very little content. The atmosphere is pleasant, but I don\'t think it\'s worth such a price for so little.',''),(2263,'As other have said, it falls short of being excellent; the mechanics are good, not excellent. There is NO story. There is no plot, or motive other than depolluting the landscape. There isn\'t an explanation on why some things happen the way they do.I found the lack of meaning to really detract from the main idea - why was the world ruined? Who are you even, and why are you teraforming the world back? How do the animals just return from the branches and trees? So basically finishing each map and ultimately the game without the story feels like... just completing a game. I lacks the sense of awe that should come with a world blooming back - or a sense of tragedy and loss from the ruined landscapes and ghost towns. It is unfortunate what potential was lost ultimately.',''),(2264,'I actually really like the idea of this game, and most of the gameplay. It\'s just the \"pack up and get off the map\" phase that\'s extremely frustrating. First you have to place the recycling units within range of the buildings, and then you have to place the beacons on waterways to summon your drone (which is a little boat that always get stuck and your only hope of un-stucking it is to exit and then re-enter the game) to collect the recycling units (which might be out of range of the drones in which case you need to build a turbine in order to build an excavator in order to build a canal which might also need to have water pumped to it in which case you need to build a pump too. And then all these have to be recycled). I\'m glad the game factors in cleaning up your stuff but the terrible gameplay mechanics of this phase just make it infuriating and un-necessarily time consuming. Maybe the ship could just, y\'know, collect all the recycling silos you\'ve built as it flies out?',''),(2265,'it\'s really cute and fun. i wish there were more continents to clean up, though. according to the progress, i\'m already halfway through, but i doubt there are any more at this point^^ still a good game.',''),(2266,'Tried the demo and had hoped for something more advanced in the full release. I think the City Builder tag is incorrect, the game isn\'t complex enough to really feel very satisfying and just feels like you\'re supposed to min-max tiles and nothing else. Great concept, heavily flawed execution.',''),(2267,'It\'s like a puzzle game, relaxing and with very nice soundtrack. The negative aspect is that\'s very short so I only recommend it with a discount of at least 50%.It doesn\'t worth the normal price. I will not pay more that 10€ for it.',''),(2268,'This a weak game. I would expect a game like this in the 2000\'s but not in 2023. First of all, it\'s a puzzle game, and a bad puzzle game. The game only has 4 levels, that are repeated 2 times (with a few tweaks), so you could say it has 8 levels, and no story...  I just didn\'t refund it because it\'s playable, and you\'re kind of saving the environment I guess. Clearly not worth 20€. I gave up at level 7, i\'m uninstalling it to be for ever lost in my Steam library.',''),(2269,'On Mac OS (ARM) the game is crashing quite often (game not responding anymore, waited several times a few minutes in the hope it get responsive again, but had to force quit it). Due to the crashes had to replay big parts several times which made me lost any motivation. Even for the time the game worked, it didn\'t captivate me as i felt very restricted based on goals and sequential gameplay.',''),(2270,'Beautiful game, 8 hours for 100% completion means you won\'t need to stick around for hours if you don\'t want to.I can see myself launching the game every now and then to do a relaxing map when stressed out.Performance issues are still somewhat present on max zoom during some busier scenes. Can\'t wait for more maps or custom content support.',''),(2271,'A fantastic strategic solar punk adventure. It\'s a short but lush/saturated experience. You are tasked with terra-forming a trashed and abandoned planet, restoring the flora and fauna before packing everything up and leaving again. Hopefully this helps turn a few more people into environmentalists. 5/5',''),(2272,'Fun game and beautiful aesthetic, very nice to relax and watch nature flourish. That said, I completed the game 100% (4 maps with two sets of challenges each) in 7 hours, so don\'t expect a long game.',''),(2273,'Terra Nil falls just short of greatnessI waited for the full game for a while ever since playing a really old demo. But there are way too many annoyances to let this game feel great. It IS a beautiful game, with a beautiful message and all that good stuff. But for the sake of brevity I will only point out the shortcomings.Too long/Didn\'t readImmersion-breaking bugs, lack of clear information on goals and counter-intuitive area progression took away that feeling of satisfaction when playing this game. It could have been great, but felt unpolished and unfinished.BugsWhile at first the game is spotless, the mechanics added in later levels, such as letting you move your buildings, will often break.In my playthrough, I could not get grass to grow in a square that was previously occupied by a building I moved before. It even allowed me to try and move that \"building ghost\" a second time, even though that building was not even visible anymore, only to have the mover drone stuck in place, forever trying to place something that didn\'t exist anymore, locking down resources.Marked areas, such as animal scanned zones and powered tiles will often linger around after you have deselected them, leaving a blank area highlighted for no reason.UIThe presented information is frequently unclear.Let\'s say you want to scan and find an animal. This one having two requirements. The animal location hint says it is in an area with ocean. So you scan somewhere with ocean tiles and possibly some other tiles to try and find both hints. You might get an yellow level Ocean tile hint, which means you got that right but not entirely, and no other hint, remaining a red question mark.Well, turns out you should have had a 4-tile wide ocean where you scanned. Did you not leave any area like that on your map? Well, you\'re out of luck. Scan as you will, the game won\'t stop you or give you any idea of what\'s missing. And for the second requirement? Oh this species is only around below a certain temperature threshold, and you since you\'re in phase 3, you probably increased the temperature above that a while ago, so in the next run it is. AND you have to figure that out yourself.I know this is meant to encourage playing again, but when you have done well enough so far with the puzzles as to have spare resources, but still be unable to get 100% completion on the first try simple due to lack of previous knowledge is just not fun.',''),(2274,'It\'s a cute little game.Although shorter than I had expected for the price. As there are only 4 levels (with I guess 4 bonus levels) in which you go through in less than an hour each.It\'s kinda strange, it was a good experience, but it leaves me a bit on the side with the thought of wanting more...Personally I already would recommend it for the concept alone, but the experience feels a little shallow to justify the price.If part of it is a donation for helping the planet, I wouldn\'t have mind. But just for the game itself...I think it\'s better to pick it up on a sale.',''),(2275,'Fun little game - very satisfying at first but starts to feel like a chore after while. Regardless, it is one of the few games that has gripped my attention and got part of me wanting to complete every level to 100%. In 8.6 hours I completed all 4 areas once, went back and did 3 of them a second time to introduce all the animals and complete all the climate goals (I completed the 4th fully first time so that I didn\'t have to go back and re-do it!), and I still have the option to go back and complete the alternate versions of the 4 areas to hit 100%. After that, if I\'m still itching for more, I can replay the game as much as I want thanks to its procedurally generated maps.',''),(2276,'Please bring Ragnarok to PC',''),(2277,'Atreus: What are we hunting?Kratos: You are hunting deer.Atreus: Which way?Kratos: In the direction of deer. 10/10',''),(2278,'ruined my marriage 10/10',''),(2279,'Steam Deck review! I gave this game a shot after missing out on all previous games before it, because PlayStation exclusivity. I will say as someone come from zero prior experience, the game does a fine job of introducing relevant backstory elements in a way that isn\'t confusing, but may leave you wondering whats going on.Did I mention steam deck? Yes I did! This game works fairly well after scaling back a few settings. I think the steam deck has trouble with atmospheric stuff like clouds. When you bring those down and increase the quality of everything else, it runs really well. My only issue with it is that when it does crash you have to hard reboot the deck to get out of the crash.Would recommend to anyone that wants a glimpse into the God of War storyline that hasn\'t experienced it before.',''),(2280,'This game is so good and im so glad i can play it without a playstation',''),(2281,'Do you have erectile dysfunction problems? This game is the cureDo you have vaginal dryness problems? This game is the cure10/10 Recommended by your doctor.',''),(2282,'Play it...',''),(2283,'In theory this is a very flawed game. Atreus\'s character is annoying and doesn\'t make a lot of sense. Quite a few bosses are recycled. The platforming is completely fake so that people who are even worse at video games than me can still beat it, and the camera can sometimes get you into trouble. But ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, the presentation, the weighty, crunch combat, the environments, the graphics, the music the characters, it all just comes together into something so epic you probably won\'t care about all the stuff wrong with it. Games do not need to be perfect to be great and this game is proof.',''),(2284,'memory leak causes regular crashes on steam deck. adjusting settings will buy you time but it will always lock up eventually. Somehow marked as verified despite a little research showing this to be a well documented issue.',''),(2285,'Not my first god of war..Even better than dmc.Waiting for the next.',''),(2286,'Ragnarok sony?',''),(2287,'BOI!',''),(2288,'boy.',''),(2289,'can\'t believe i\'m only now playing this... 10/10',''),(2290,'The story of the game is very good and the gameplay is also very good.',''),(2291,'Before playing it, I thought it was a game just trying to make money from its name.I was so wrong, and I\'m glad I was wrong.',''),(2292,'Now I can truly be the best father to my future son - having gone through this dad simulator.This is a gaming triumph, flawlessly uniting gripping narrative, breathtaking visuals, and intense combat. Kratos and Atreus\' journey through Norse mythology is an unforgettable experience, setting a new standard in gaming excellence.God of War (2018) - 10/10Bring me God of War: Ragnarök!\"If you take a man who is willing to do anything for his son, and you take away his son, there is no limit to what that man will do to get revenge.\"',''),(2293,'kratos is better a father than mine. best childhood yearning simulator 10/10',''),(2294,'Kratos says \"BOY\" 119 times in the main story.  10/10',''),(2295,'Great i loved the old parts and this one also just the story maybe can be longer i mean just 16h main story what ever nice gameBRING RAGNARÖK ON PC pls.',''),(2296,'Came for the promise of fulfilling my dreams of becoming Dracula/Alucard.Stayed for the addicting loop of Vampire Factorio Minecraft.Abandon all hope ye who venture here...',''),(2297,'This is a wonderful vampire fantasy adventure and base building and crafting game. There is an impressive game map, oodles of enemies and items, and lots of fun thematic elements. The music is pretty nice too. The overall soundboard is great, and there are fun voice lines for all the enemies. The game world feels alive in a way, and it\'s pretty immersive for a top-down game. The graphics and visuals are a somewhat unique cartoonish style that I find both lighthearted and grim at the same time. There is a day-night cycle, critical to a vampire\'s concerns for obvious reasons, in which you find yourself managing activities based on time. The base building is fun and role immersive, meaning you can make your castle spooky and strange, utilitarian, silly, or whatever suits you. For PvP, it\'s obviously more about defensive and offensive strategy. As a small disclaimer, I enjoy this game casually, having spun up my own PvE server. I\'ve not taken part in PvP. I hear it gets pretty intense, I just frankly don\'t enjoy PvP in this sort of game. I\'ve never played on public servers!PvE is often challenging, especially all the mini-bosses you must defeat to earn various powers and crafting recipes. Combat in general is fun because it does require some effort, with each enemy type and each boss having their own mechanics to learn and play around. There are many different weapons and spells, each with their own unique abilities, flavor, and preferred enemy effectiveness. I find I have one main setup that I usually enjoy, switching to different weapons or even changing spells on occasion if a particular enemy is difficult or calls for a wildly different strategy.There are a huge number of recipes and crafted items. As you go along, you unlock more. These items range from base parts, crafting stations, storage boxes, weapons, armor, potions, and the list goes on. All of the things are interesting and unique, and you find yourself excited to craft the next new thing.I really enjoy all the transforming abilities. It\'s pretty fun being able to turn into a bat, bear, wolf, toad, rat, or even don a \'human disguise\' for trading coin for goods with the locals. The various forms unlock the ability to traverse the landscape in new ways, or even aid in combat. I also enjoy the horse riding method of getting around the map, especially once you can \'dominate\' a horse to make it into your own special spooky vampire horse hoopty.There\'s also an interesting facet of play involving the magical capture of NPC\'s. They can be taken as servants and sent on supply missions or even used to defend your base from PvP attacks. You can also capture and keep various NPCs you find in game, imprisoning them. You must feed them and balance their health and misery gauges to keep them alive. You do this because they can supply your character with blood of various types depending on whom you\'ve imprisoned,  each NPC type is also blood type and will have a random quality percentage. These can weakened in combat and then fed upon in the field, killing them, to receive temporary relevant bonuses to your character. However, capturing them means you can choose to have an ongoing supply of a desirable bonus. While adventuring, simply identify an NPC with a blood type conferring the desired bonuses that is of high quality. You weaken them, then \"dominate\" them magically to lead them to your prison. It\'s a pretty interesting system in my opinion.You will eventually have legendary items and armors which confer various bonuses, as well as modifier items to \'tweak\' spells in various ways. Through these, you can create custom \"builds\" to play in a way that suits you. There are so many that I couldn\'t begin to guess how many possibilities there are. I love that level of deep customization in any game, though at first it\'s a bit overwhelming perhaps. I started just using whatever I found until I got a few items which seemed to play well together or combo in fun ways.As far as end game, well that remains to be seen for me. I\'ve got 139 hours in at the time of this review. I\'ve build a few different bases across two character runs. I\'m currently only about 3/4 of the way through the bosses I think. I do believe there are some extra hard challenge bosses at the end. I think the only real end-game beyond that is just playing around with base building, perfecting character builds, collecting the cosmetic helmets, or perhaps moving onto trying PvP- but from what I understand that really requires a team of friends to accomplish successfully and have fun doing so. There probably are solo/no-teaming servers for PvP, but as I mentioned I\'m not personally interested in PvP in this sort of game.There are a couple cosmetic dlc\'s you can purchase. These in no way at all enhance character power or ability, nor are they required in the least to play and enjoy every item and area of the game. This is a huge plus to me, as so many other games have gone a bad direction with dlc\'s.Negatives?Well, it can be a bit boorish alone if you aren\'t into this sort of base-building/crafting/harvesting sort of game. Best to play with a few friends, as is often the case for many games. Controls are a bit hard to master at first, with mouse cursor position dictating attack direction independent of WASD, all while using right mouse button to rotate the camera around. And it can be a bit hard for some- I wouldn\'t let the cartoonish graphics fool you, this game can be brutal. Steering the horse was a pain at first too, but eventually you\'ll get the hang of it. (not sure if there\'s controller support or not, I use keyboard/mouse) And lastly, I feel that while the character creation options are mostly sufficient, the armor \'looks\' cannot be changed. This bothers me. You can customize the character, and collect dozens of different capes and hats, but you cannot currently change your armor appearance or color. The armor just is what it is. Not that it looks bad, but I really feel they missed the bar by not creating a customization option for the armor colors. It\'s not a deal breaker, but it does bug me. A role-playing game of any sort in 2023 should have all kinds of character customization! Maybe they\'ll add that in the future? Let\'s hope.I hope you enjoyed my review! It\'s not very in depth, but I feel you can watch gameplay on youtube to get a better sense of the visuals, combat, and crafting. I do highly recommend this game overall, and especially so if you enjoyed Valheim, 7-days, Ark, or other base builders.Cheers,Luckymod13',''),(2298,'1/16 S