s here.',''),(2300,'W game, too slept on',''),(2301,'Great game, but no controller support is a shame from the Devs. Hopefully in the future...',''),(2302,'playable halo 3 rat 10/10',''),(2303,'I honestly really wanted to give this game a positive review but there are many issues that must be fixed before I even recommend this to someone.  Pros--Amazing base building-Combat against regular enemies is very enjoyable-Co-op outside boss arenas is super fun -Vampire theme done right-Resource gathering isn\'t an awful grind-Map is a great size with done of variety with enemies and locations-Many things that it does different that worksCons:-Locking stronger armor/weapons behind bosses is the absolute dumbest thing I could think of and I feel like this is one of the main reasons that the game has a lower than average player count. Let me explain for those of you that are actually planning on getting the game. You cannot upgrade your character with better gear until you kill certain bosses. So if you are stuck on a boss the only thing you can grind for is stuff to repair your armor/weapons. You will not be able to make anything better. For anyone defending this system you are actively the reason why this game will perish. This is something I hope won\'t happen but I am being realistic.-Boss fights are the most unfun I have ever had in a game, you are always struggling with bosses since upgrades are locked behind their deaths. They are even worse in co-op since the boss scales with how many players are with you and normally this would be fine if it was an even scale like many souls games for example. But its almost like the devs didn\'t even try their own game and sometimes you can tell where the skimmed through without making sure this would work with the community.-IF YOU ARE SOLO there is a good chance you will not enjoy the game. And again this does go back to the bosses especially once you reach level 60 (spider queen). I recommend any of you to watch this boss fight on youtube and tell me if this actually looks enjoyable. Also there are a few wandering bosses that despawn if you do not kill them fast enough. SIDE NOTE: I know this looks like I am raging at only the boss fights but trust me the boss fights are literally the main part of the game. You literally cannot progress any other way.This is pretty much it  when it comes to this review and although there is more good than bad. The bad weighs a ton that actually affect the rest of the game. I will allow comment if anyone has questions.',''),(2304,'good practice before summer vacation. how to avoiding the sun and why to stay indoors :D',''),(2305,'Never Stop Rising',''),(2306,'Best game in a long time! New survival mechanics and sooooooo many bosses to fight, you\'ll be playing for weeks on end!',''),(2307,'Game is ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, they have no protections against griefing and doxxing so goodluck when a player doxxes you takes over your castle, all your progress is lost and time spent wasted, stay away.',''),(2308,'- Solid combat and core mechanics.- Well-designed boss fight and skill system.- Well-balanced weapon and tier system.- Castle building is user-friendly and you don\'t need a lot of time for a beautiful castle and so can focus more on fighting.- Deep and wide server setting options for different kind of players.- Well-rounded crafting system with many things to aid you in battle progressively.For survival game, it\'s a 9/10',''),(2309,'excellent game',''),(2310,'Best game!',''),(2311,'its good for playing wif yo fwendlol i just wanted to put that it is a good game',''),(2312,'Stake to heart 10/10',''),(2313,'It\'s fun',''),(2314,'[PVE, private server viewpoint] My new favorite survival game and I am obsessed! Just the general concept of being a vampire/the bad guy instead of the typical human hero, and avoiding so many things that are out to get you like humans, creatures, sunlight, garlic, etc is really fun, especially with friends. The progression is the best I\'ve seen in a survival game. The bosses are very fun but also difficult which helps make progression feel so rewarding. I love how every boss is different and all badass. Makes you feel badass for finally defeating them and taking their powers. The building mechanics are also super satisfying, I spend most of my time building unique vampire castles on different lands. There are some nitpicks about building though, but it\'s still only an early access game so I think it\'s fine for now. But overall for an early access game this is extremely polished. Can\'t wait for the full release next year!',''),(2315,'Wonderful game. Beware! it is too addictive!',''),(2316,'all right then. keep your Bloodborne Sony.',''),(2317,'Amazing and wonderful game Hard but if you give yourself time to practice perfect guard you will not have any problem progressing the game.',''),(2318,'A Souls-Like worthy of the name.',''),(2319,'My favorite thing about Lies of P is it\'s potential for player expression. You\'re allowed to beat the game (mostly) however you want. You can \'Perfect Guard\' every encounter, dodge every enemy attack, or do a mixture of both whenever you see fit. Typically, there are better approaches to every fight, but the game will meet you on your own terms and give you the freedom to choose how you tackle it. You\'re allowed to build any weapon you want by combining different blades with different handles or use any special boss weapon from the various fights throughout the game. If you want to stick a giant wrench to the end of a dagger handle, you can. If you want to put a greatsword blade on a rapier hilt, you can. This simple tweak to a standard weapon selection system adds so much variety between every playthrough and every person\'s experience with the game.You\'ll encounter several boss fights over your 30-hour playthrough of the game. Most of them are good, if not great, while a few of them not so much. Bosses are incredibly aggressive, but readable and reactable, say for a few \'Fury Attacks\' which require memorization in timing as opposed to testing of reactions. I was actually surprised to see how many fantastic fights this game offers. There are several bosses I would understand seeing at the top of someone\'s favorite Lies of P boss list. The game is also a lot harder than I was expecting with several bosses taking over an hour, sometimes up to 3, to beat. Another thing to note is the game\'s story. I won\'t be giving any summary here, but I\'m surprised at how invested I actually was in the characters and story surrounding them. It\'s a refreshing change to see a game in this genre with such a defined and explicit narrative. There were more than a few characters I grew to genuinely really like and feel for. Complementing the story is the great soundtrack through the game. This includes boss themes, as well as the vinyls you can obtain and play in the Hotel hub area. The songs used give the desolate and depressing world so much more life and context. The world of Lies of P is beautiful and feels lived-in and overrun by the puppets and corrupted roaming about. It could have done better with more impurities in the objects around the levels and architecture, but that\'s more of a nitpick than anything.The game isn\'t perfect, however. It falters towards the end and stumbles in it\'s final act. After Laxasia , you feel like you\'re closing in on the finale, but then it sort of just continues for a bit too long before the actual end of the game. The reason I take issue with this area is because up until this point the game has done an incredible job at making every location feel fresh with new or remixed enemy types, level design, and area visuals. But this final stretch feels like a retread of the last few areas without enough of a difference to warrant being included. You could argue that this serves as a sort of down-time before the final fight, but the enemies here are just as aggressive as usual and you\'ll probably end up running past all of them at this point.All in all, Lies of P is one of the biggest sleeper hits in recent memory and surpassed the expectations I had for it by a  long shot. It\'s one of the best \'Soulslike\' games I\'ve had the privilege of playing, and I\'m incredibly excited to see the upcoming DLC and whatever next game comes from this series.',''),(2320,'femboy',''),(2321,'We have bloodborne on pc (lies)',''),(2322,'This game should be the standard for storytelling and world building for souls-like.',''),(2323,'Lies of P, as you might have known already, is a lovechild of Sekiro and Bloodborne, and although Lies of P didn’t really do anything out of the ordinary or made any breakthrough in anything, the game is still very fun and fantastic and is probably the best souls-like I ever played that is not from Fromsoft, judging after finishing my first playthrough which took me about 30 hours. Totally worth to play and can really scratch your Sekiro itch if you are a huge fan of Sekiro like me. The game is at worst mediocre but at its best, really is a fantastic polished game that you can just tell got a lot of love from its developer. Really looking forward to what Neowiz and Round 8 can cook up next time.9/10',''),(2324,'Voted GOTY',''),(2325,'Lies of P is not \"just another soulslike\" - it is an outstanding entry to the genre. Fantastic art direction, incredibly satisfying combat, deep customization options, and interesting spin on the story of Pinocchio. I\'m on NG+4 and attempting deathless runs - I am completely enamored with Lies of P, it\'s my personal GOTY, and I really don\'t see myself getting tired of playing it. Neowiz hit it out of the park on their first try, and I\'m very excited to see what\'s in the future for this series, with DLC or Sequels.',''),(2326,'It is an incredible story-rich game with an awesome soundtrack and outstanding visuals throughout the playthrough. There is quite an adventure with emotional and unexpected endings. This awesome story is worth playing, even several times',''),(2327,'As an amateur player of Souls-like games, I find \"Lies of P\" to be a story-rich and authentic game, definitely catchy with a combat system forgiving for beginners. Those who rush through Sekiro like the wind and enjoy perfecting parries against enemy attacks will find themselves quite comfortable in this game. Same for those who prefer dodging or attacking from a distance with a big sword - you folks can too defeat bosses and progress through the storyline. My point is that this game is a good fit for both types of players and is highly recommended for those who enjoy interesting story plots.\"Lies of P\" is among the top three best games of my 2023, and trust me, it will be a valuable addition to your Steam library.',''),(2328,'Amazing game! Just finished my 1st playthrough and really enjoyed it. Has it\'s difficulty spikes but not super difficult. Lots of customisation with the weapons allowed for so many different builds, it was a nice touch rather than having just standard weapons and what you see is what you get. Combat was very solid, Cross between Bloodborne and Sekiro with parrying attacks the main goal rather than trying to dodge everything. Bosses were solid, Some felt fairly straightforward but others you really needed a strat rather than going all in aggressive. Overall it was an 8.5/10 for me. 1 of the best Souls like out there (besides the Souls series) and the closest thing we have to Bloodborne for PC.',''),(2329,'IMPORTANT  - you can easily lock yourself from some achievements AND you at least need to do 2 playthroughs to get them all: - The Story of a Stranger Girl + Golden Melody  - FIRST read Alidoro\'s Cryptic Vessel Decryption and only after that go talk to Eugene. Otherwise you bind yourself to another playthrough. - Veteran Explorer  - to get reward from Mechanical Cryptic Vessel you must buy Frozen Feast special weapon with Reborn Champion\'s Ergo. Imma great Bloodborne fan and I\'m waiting for PC port like I\'m waiting for my boyfriend coming back from army.On a serious note - I didn\'t get much BB vibes from this game. Nevertheless it is very fun game. Side note - I got easily bored with dark souls and elden ring, since gameplay-wise they are very simple (don\'t mix simple-complex with easy-hard). You can only master dodge-roll and that\'s all you will ever need. Autotarget magic is boring, parry is optional and those games aren\'t MADE to be parried.- However Lies Of P is made to be parried- You must master parry like in Sekiro, however parry in Lies of P doesn\'t feel like a dance to me- Lies of P is made with love and care for the player, not only for the game itself- You get so many Quality Of Life small features, that From Soft didn\'t came up to- Game can be hard sometimes, but to me it was always FAIR during all my 50+ hours NG+3 playthrough- It has predictable LENGTH from one bonefire to another and has rhytm which helps you to predict what\'s next - Parrying with Dragon Sword is one of the most satisfying and fun mechanics I\'ve ever learned',''),(2330,'good',''),(2331,'Good souls like. Very linear level design.',''),(2332,'game of year',''),(2333,'so nice',''),(2334,'Excellent combat, excellent boss fights, decent level design.',''),(2335,'The city of Krat is designed in a cheerful, interesting and historical way, and the problems between the sections between people and puppets have made the City of Krat an inextricable street. The happy of brain, character designs and the feeling of hitting are presented to us perfectly. This successful production has become a style of play that will completely appeal to you. In this case, South Korea has done a great job.PINOCCHIO THEME, CITY, BOSSES AND ATMOSPHERE COMPLETELY REMINDER OF A LARGE-SCALE DARK GAME THEME. WHY WAS THIS GAME NOT IN THE FIRST PLACE IN GAME AWARDS?',''),(2336,'Definitely worth it, especially with the 33% off sale, but full price too. Very great game, had me hook for the first moment I started.Graphics are amazingGuns feel impactfulLevel design has me I awe every time I stop to smell the rosesGameplay is super fun and seems like it\'ll take me a while to master it, which i love! Buy it, try it, don\'t like it? Returnal XD',''),(2337,'The game is fun, but there seems to be a memory leak or something of the sort. After about an hour of gameplay, you need to reboot the game otherwise you get performance issues. Until they come out with a patch, I recommend getting it on PS5.',''),(2338,'Id love to play it, truly. Two Fatal errors one hour in and the boards are full of people telling me it doesnt get any better and a patch isnt coming. like, ok :/ Guess I\'ll refund? Shame, it really had me by the neck in the first hour, too.',''),(2339,'I saw everything that was being said about the memory leaks and I decided to ignore them because I saw ONE redditor say that it wasn\'t as widespread as people make it out to be so I listened to him and thought to myself:\"theres no way that with my completely new setup and 16 gb of VRAM that would be an issue for me\"What the hell was I thinking.On my second day of playing i got the memory leak within 30 minutes of opening the game. My frames cut down from 200 fps to 100 within the course of seconds. My VRAM usage went from 4 to six to 12 every time I blinked my eyes.I\'m genuinely torn that this happened because I actually REALLY like the combat, even after requesting and getting my refund I find myself wanting to get the game again but the memory leak issue is too much to ignore and unfortunately the devs have appeared to abandoned updating it.',''),(2340,'Game runs pretty baldy on my pc. Couldn\'t finish it.',''),(2341,'Its challenging in the beginning but just stick with it & you\'ll start enjoying it, its really addictive, the combat is amazing too.',''),(2342,'yes!though i did get extremely inconsistent performance... game runs 100fps, then sometimes theres one enemy on screen that tanks fps to below 20 fps, also a TON of frametime stutters.i did enjoy, and do recommend - but be wary (and DEVS -> do better!)',''),(2343,'Came for the action stayed for the story. Thought this was just going to be another mindless bullet hell roguelike but the story and voice acting was surprisingly well done. The sound design and visual also makes for an amazing atmosphere. The game is difficult but very rewarding. Well worth the money. 10/10.',''),(2344,'I guess as an old gamer I just don\'t find it fun to play 30min only to have my entire progress reset.I don\'t have time for THIS much grind.*** UpdateChanging review... Judged too hastily...',''),(2345,'Pew Pew',''),(2346,'This game is very difficult but fun. When you get a build going and feel like you cant be stopped that is when the game will throw a curve ball',''),(2347,'i absolutely love this game, dont get me wrong. but DAMN there are a lot of bugs with co-op. just encountered one where my partners camera was in the wrong place, making it impossible to see his character or play, so we had to suspend and quit then all his progress was lost. I think the game itself is really fun and fantastic, there are just sooo many game breaking bugs',''),(2348,'Honestly the game is far too unforgiving. I love almost everything about it, the weapons are fun, the world is great, the story is interesting so far...but when you finally get your build working, and have some great synergistic parasites, a high level weapon that you love, then you walk in to a boss room for your first time fighting something deliberately designed to be difficult only to be killed and sent back to the start of the game with basically nothing it\'s too disheartening.I get that it\'s a roguelike and that\'s part and parcel, but where this falls in comparison to others is that the time sink for each run is massive. Roguelikes actually want you to complete them as the real fun in them lies in completing them multiple ways, and changing your decisions to get more interesting results...but this is narrative game about a woman trapped in an endless cycle of torment and they want you to feel that. When the game pulls away from bullet hell and puts me in a house scared ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ at every sound and movement, I\'m on the edge of my seat.Then I pick up some item and it puts my max HP at 50% then it puts me in a room with 8 octopus dogs flanking me from every direction and 6 jellyfish trying to ram in to me whilst a teleporting tree-man attaches me on the ground, and 4 turrets are blasting me from range and a big green pulse is healing everyone faster than I can damage them, then flashes \"LOCKDOWN IN PLACE\"...and I\'m just like, where do I even start with this? And that\'s not to mention that I\'ve already finished this level and I\'m just trying to get back to the other areas to progress further.If this game was a soulslike where I could take time getting the items I want and min-maxing my build, I\'d happily bash my head against this wall over and over, but as it stands right now I\'m not having any fun.',''),(2349,'This is a rogue like 3rd person shooter game.You are an astronaut who crash landed on an alien planet following a strange signal. There you discover signs of alien civilisations and get attacked by hostile creatures. The story is told mostly through audio logs you can collect. Funny thing is every time you die in the game you start from scratch and the world changes. You only get to keep a very few permanent upgrades when you start over.I must admit that the game is brutally challenging. I am yet to complete the first boss and I have already restarted over ten times already.Pros: Story, Graphics, Audio, game play, replay ability.Cons: Could have been better optimised. It runs fine on my PC, but still it stutters every time during the PlayStation logo cut scene every time I start the game. PC configuration: 1) NVIDIA RTX 3060 Ti 8 GB2) AMD Ryzen 5 5600X3) 32 GB of RAM4) 2 X 512 GB SSD and 2 TB HDD5) Resolution: 1920 X 10806) Windows 11 ProFPS Result at epic settings: 87 FPS (average with RT turned off)',''),(2350,'unpolished, inconsistent, shallow',''),(2351,'I can highly recommend this game. It\'s cute if nothing else. You need a little skill to play it, which is good for my 83yr old brain, but it has all the attributes one looks for in a city adventure type building game.The buildings are well presented, farming is how it should be, the figures are unusual but fit in nicely with the background theme.Go on have your self a happy holiday and buy this game for a nice relaxing game.',''),(2352,'Delightful graphics, audio and a compelling game-play loop make this a colony builder to keep an eye on. In it\'s current state, however, I wouldn\'t recommend a purchase. All the content the game has to offer can be seen in a very short time and there isn\'t much in the way of replay-ability.',''),(2353,'The game has a lot of potential but BEWARE: at this point in time you can experience all the content in a very short time and there\'s little to no replayability. My suggestion would be to wait a few months (maybe even a year) until its more fleshed out. Buy only if you\'re really interested and want to support development.',''),(2354,'This game is great but definitely early access. There\'s quite a bit of work to do to finish this game, but it\'s a fun city builder. Hopefully my review gives the devs some feedback and lets you know what state it is in right now before purchasing.At this point in time these things are unfinished and give unsatisfying limits on parts of the game: - Only 2 tiers of upgrades/citizens, which maxed out in 8 or so hours. When I compare to a game like Timberborn which has seemingly endless things to unlock after 10s and 10s of hours, this feels like the most unfinished part. The game could benefit from better pacing and more unlocks. - Courting only goes so far.. unclear end goal - No war.. why did I train so many soldiers? - Not enough quests.. Not always something to do - Hardly anything for the hero to do - Trading doesn\'t refresh and so you can only do so much with your excess resources - Needs better population management. When you have hundreds of Fablings you need a way to fix everyone\'s workplaces easily that they\'re all close to home. You have to click through every workplace to do this as of now.Also this game needs some attention to detail on preventing user errors: - right clicking moves the map but also cancels anything your building. annoying mistake forcing you to do WASD when building- clicking \"Court\" (the largest button!) can immediately cancel a different courtship- Adjusting the area of townhouses resets the configuration you may have builtAll this said, this is a very fun game. It\'s not a bad thing that I\'m begging for more. Hope they keep at it!',''),(2355,'Fun and chilled game, cant wait to see the full release.',''),(2356,'Decent little town builder and fun/quirky folklore related events, very chill game!',''),(2357,'Works with a more casual approach to banished-like games, requiring less, albeit, satisfying amout of planning and thinking, and a beautiful art style.Buy it if you want to have a relaxing time building a city, in a game that has similar mechanics to more hardcore instances of the genre.',''),(2358,'A lighthearted, cheerful fantasy city builder with lots of folktale cuteness layered on top of it. For an early access this has a lot of potential in it and sits on a really solid foundation. What it lacks in content at the moment it more than makes up for in charm. All told I have had a lot of fun poking at this title, and look forward to what the developers have planned. Now on to the pro/cons, with the disclaimer that this is based upon an unfinished product:Pros:- well put together- decent UI- somewhat modular building system- runs decently on older machines, even at ultra-quality settings- very few bugs.- active developer and community with a clear passion for their projectCons:- very short \'completion time\' on individual builds- uneven balancing on technology unlocks- early access, and thus, not feature completeI will be honest, I do feel like I had to reach a bit with the cons portion of this review. Generally speaking, most city builders suffer from the same general problem of \'sameyness\', so getting to a \'complete\' state ends up happening rather quickly in this genre, I can\'t honestly fault the developers for that. The bit about uneven tech unlocks comes from, in my mind, certain technologies that are in the game, either fully implemented, or currently being worked on, should realistically come out ahead of or at the same time, as others. But that is simply my bias rearing its ugly head. Then of course, there is the early access tag, which, may be a turn off for some people. With all that said, the developers are very active, friendly, and excited to interact with their players, which says a lot about the future for this game. I will continue to poke at this thing myself at least, and look positively the potential this title has.',''),(2359,'Only a few hours on the game so far an I\'m already loving it!It\'s a simple little city builder but it has it\'s own unique charms with its fairy tale, and romance aspects, I look forward to seeing this game grow over time,',''),(2360,'coziest game ever ^^',''),(2361,'nominated for the sit back and relax category, for just reason.i sit back in my chair to play this game, cant do that with much else in the library.full credit to the devs on this keep up the good work, cant wait to see more',''),(2362,'At this stage, the game still has incredibly slow progression, particularly due to how few and far in-between new citizens show up in your town. On top of that, one citizen is \"lost\" for any new house that has to be occupied. The relationship missions are a bit boring for now as well. The use of the hero is underutilized at the moment.This leads to lots of waiting around for no reason and becomes a bit of a slow slog. I think this game has potential and has a charming feel to it, but it has quite a bit to bake out still.',''),(2363,'DO NOT BUY FOR VR!!!Way too many bugs and inconsistencies make it completely unplayable let alone unenjoyable. It\'s a fantastic game, don\'t get me wrong, I\'m just telling you not to buy it for the sole purposeof playing it hands-on in VR because it will NOT be as you would hope it would be.',''),(2364,'Sure, this was phased out over years with questionable business models, company structure changes and online connectivity. But now, HITMAN World of Assassination is great value for money, even more so on sale. A huge bundle of high-end HITMAN content: great graphics and feel, countless possibilities through varied levels, challenges and gamemodes. Fun for dozens of hours, with replayability up to many hundreds of hours. Even \"imperfections\" add to greatness, like \"exploits\" the AI and physics allow. The developers understand what makes HITMAN awesome and continuously support it. Stealthy assassination, mass murder, stylish suits, wacky outfits, scoping out, planning or speedrunning. Great design allows for it all. Once you\'re done, I recommend looking up videos of clowns clearing levels in mere seconds or something like \"Bird%\" to contrast your hours of hard work. Simply marvelous.',''),(2365,'I actually enjoy the VR mode of this game but you have to be facing in one direction the whole time.   The VR is broken for Quest Pro and Quest 3 though as is corroborated by that folks on Reddit have the same issue.  The render isn\'t matching the lenses of eitehr appropriately for some reason or another which makes part of the image blurry.  This is not a problem on Quest 2 or Reverb G2.  So this game needs an update in relation to Quest Pro and Quest 3 lenses.  Please. Thank.',''),(2366,'If you like the Hitman franchise or if this is your first foray into the game, Hitman 3 (aka Hitman World of Assassination) is the best entry point into the series.Freelancer is the best mode for both new players and veterans alike, but new players may want to try playing through the story to get used to the maps... or not.SPECIAL NOTE: The New York Bank map and the Maldives Island Resort map are both available in Freelancer WITHOUT any additional purchases. They are only inaccessible to Story mode without the Deluxe Pack Bundle purchase.Also note: Sniper mode unlocks NOTHING for any mode EXCEPT for Sniper mode, so if you really enjoy Sniper mode, then maybe extra maps for that mode might feel useful to you, but otherwise maybe not.You do not \"need\" anything other than the base game to enjoy the content, but the \"Deluxe Pack Bundle\" is probably the only real \"worthwhile\" expansion content to get. Mostly for the two extra maps that are quite enjoyable, but also there are a few Escalations that are quite fun and some specific suits and cosmetics that are some of the \"better\" options for the game.I would NOT recommend any other DLC content unless you REALLY want the cosmetics that those DLCs provide, because that is ALL they provide. Sure, a couple have some new Escalations, but really with all the various Escalations in the base game alone, and possibly the additional Escalations of the Deluxe Pack Bundle, you really don\'t need any more Escalations.',''),(2367,'most of the content is locked behind a pay wall..greedy company. as much as i love hitman, ♥♥♥♥ this company for wanting to charge to play merged content when you already own the 3 games AND then continue to charge for quests...who tf does that?',''),(2368,'I am deeply torn. I love this game. I love this franchise. I am also SO VERY TIRED of buying the same content over and over. I bought the 1 levels when 2 made me and chalked it up to a technical naivete that wouldn\'t be repeated. By all indications, the transfer to 3 exemplified those learnings right up until you tried it. So much progress ignored. DLC content I had paid for that I would have to buy again. I\'ve held off playing for a very long time because I just couldn\'t swallow how having feel like a sucker as I repurchased the same content, yet again, like a sucker. So here is my compromise. I am paying for the same content yet again. I\'m playing it. I\'m enjoying it. But I\'m discouraging anyone else from entering in this toxic relationship.',''),(2369,'🤡🤡🤡 i bought H1, H2 and H3.. but wheres my \"free\" H2 expansions on H3? 🤡🤡🤡',''),(2370,'I\'m downvoting because the last couple missions of Hitman 2 are kept behind a \"deluxe\" edition that necessitates another purchase, which was not conveyed well enough when buying this. Actually disgusting to be doing that in my opinion. It\'s fun and all but make sure you get this on sale if you really want it, DO NOT give these chumps what they\'re asking for. It\'s simply not worth it otherwise.',''),(2371,'Love the HITMAN series, only thing I don\'t like is that it is always online for a single player game and you can\'t transfer your progress from the EGS version to the Steam version. I\'ve written more about it on nuclearmonster.com',''),(2372,'im a psycho',''),(2373,'Always online is really bad. I randomly get kicked out of games for seemingly no reason despite it being a single player game, and if your connection drops when you save a game it seems to outright corrupt saves for some reason. Game itself is good though, I just wish a fully single player game didn\'t have major problems forcing itself to be \'always online\' for some reason.',''),(2374,'I am the spy',''),(2375,'Shady business. Fun game. Not worth the price or morals.',''),(2376,'♥♥♥♥ you IOI. Don\'t force me to buy stuff again I already own. What the ♥♥♥♥ is this ♥♥♥♥. Do NOT buy for full price, get it discounted in a key store or something but don\'t support this ♥♥♥♥.Otherwise the game is great, but forcing people to buy DLC again is just straight up scummy as ♥♥♥♥.',''),(2377,'Rating: 9/10The first aspect that immediately captivates players is the stunning visual design. Each location is a masterpiece, from the opulence of Dubai\'s skyscraper to the atmospheric gloom of Dartmoor\'s Thornbridge Manor. The attention to detail is unparalleled, immersing players in a world that feels alive and reactive to their every move. The graphics are not just a backdrop but a crucial element that enhances the overall gameplay experience.The narrative in Hitman 3 is a pleasant surprise, adding depth to the franchise known for its focus on gameplay. The story takes unexpected twists and turns, keeping players engaged throughout Agent 47\'s globe-trotting journey. It\'s a fitting conclusion to the trilogy, tying up loose ends and offering closure to those invested in the narrative.Technical performance is commendable, with smooth controls and minimal bugs or glitches. The game runs seamlessly, allowing players to focus on the strategic intricacies of their missions without distraction.',''),(2378,'I recently embarked on a thrilling journey as Agent 47 in the game Hitman 3, and let me tell you, it\'s not just a game—it\'s a high-stakes fashion show! Move over, runway models, there\'s a bold, bald, and impeccably dressed assassin in town.From the runways of Paris to the sunny streets of Dubai, Agent 47 struts his stuff in the most dapper disguises you can imagine. Forget about high-end fashion magazines—this game is the ultimate style guide for anyone looking to make a killer impression (literally).The level of attention to detail is mind-blowing. Who knew that sneaking around could be so chic? The seamless transition between blending in and unleashing chaos is smoother than Agent 47\'s perfectly shaved head. And don\'t even get me started on the iconic briefcase—move over, Hermes Birkin, there\'s a new must-have accessory in town!The in-game locations are not just stunning; they\'re practically interactive catwalks. Whether I\'m pushing someone off a balcony or sipping a martini by the bar, I feel like I\'m walking the red carpet of espionage. And the NPCs? They have no idea they\'re in the presence of a fashion-forward legend.The storyline is engaging, the missions are challenging, and the humor is as sharp as Agent 47\'s razor-edged tie clip. Who knew that eliminating targets could be this much fun? It\'s like a deadly game of hide-and-seek, but with more flair and fewer hiding spots.In conclusion, Hitman 3 isn\'t just a game; it\'s a masterpiece of stealth, strategy, and style. Move over, James Bond; there\'s a new secret agent in town, and he\'s dressed to kill (literally). Bravo, IO Interactive, for creating a game that proves fashion and assassination go hand in perfectly-gloved hand! 👔🕶️💼 #FashionablyDeadly ⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️⭐️',''),(2379,'Hitman is the only game where sneaking around in a clown costume isn\'t just acceptable, it\'s encouraged. From assassinating targets with exploding rubber ducks to blending in as a fashion-forward gardener, this game turns murder into a laugh riot. It\'s like a twisted version of \'Where\'s Waldo?\' – only Waldo is armed, and you\'re trying to avoid eye contact. Who knew contract killing could be this entertaining and strangely hilarious?',''),(2380,'I hit on men',''),(2381,'The game is so silly throw a coin and the most powerful men and women in the world will go pick it up and seal their fate.',''),(2382,'I am 32 years old.My ex-wife and I have a daughter together, and we adopted our son together. Both are now 4 years old.When we were going through our separation, I felt lost and unhappy. I was self-destructive. One day, I was so angry with everything spiraling out of control that I punched a concrete wall in a moment of overwhelming emotion. This resulted in breaking my fifth metacarpal in my right hand—the hand I worked with, played games with, and used to carry my children to bed—the hand I desperately needed to ensure I could continue providing.Upon learning the severity of the self-inflicted damage, I became almost suicidal. Keep in mind that just a few months before this, I was the happiest man, with no history of depression or anxiety. I had never experienced anger outbursts, nor was I the type to break down and cry, but I was in a tough situation that truly prevented me from seeing the light on the other side.With nothing better to do, I looked for a game I could play WITH ONE HAND while recovering. Somehow, I stumbled upon this game and read some of the comments. I decided it was worth a try... I must admit I didn\'t beat the game, nor did I play as much as some of you. In fact, I may have played this game for only a day or two. That being said, after doing so, I had a new joy and hope for life. I managed to leave behind the pain and suffering that had been thrust upon me. I could experience the joy and happiness of other people. I relaxed for 5 ♥♥♥♥ minutes listening to this music, long enough to realize that I would be okay.After realizing this, I turned off the game and went back to work. My hand hurt a lot, but I was motivated. I stopped feeling so sorry for myself and became the father I needed to be at that moment, not the weak boy I was behaving like.Today, I am close friends with the mother of my children. We don\'t fight, argue, or say hurtful things to each other. We are parents and friends.Now I have 3 children. My third child is, wait, ALSO 4 YEARS OLD. The woman I am with was going through a very similar situation at the time of my separation, and we just unexpectedly stumbled into each other\'s lives. We have been dating for a year and are very happy together.Moral of the story: you never know what life has in store for you, and if I had given up when all odds were against me, I wouldn\'t be where I am today. This silly little game helped me realize that.Thank you.',''),(2383,'Honestly? One of the best strategy games I\'ve ever played.In short: if Civilization games partnered with Heroes of Might and Magic (rest in peace), this would be their child. And, oh god, isn\'t it such a beatiful thing?I\'ve always had a soft spot for strategy games. I grew up with RTS mostly, but I\'m no stranger to Turn-Based 4X or Tactics (my favorite genre). It all started with HoMM3 and onward with Civilization 3 and many others from then on...To be frank, I didn\'t really know much about this franchise... I\'ve owned AoW3 and didn\'t play it much, as I thought it was an ugly game for its generation. Moreover, 4X games tend to be somewhat exhausting as matches can last for days and some have annoying little micromanagement quirks. This is not the case in Age of Wonders 4.To elaborate, this is a game that rewards your creativity and doesn\'t require much knowledge or the previously mentioned genres. It is a very solid entry into 4X and turn based strategy. A lot of it\'s inner workings are rather simple: you have a throne city, which you must expand by capturing provinces (in game tiles) and a ruler, who acts like a hero/general unit that you can level up through combat agaisnt other factions or neutral armies. On top of that, as your turns pass by, you research magic by choosing tomes, each containing a few reseach projects that last a few turns each to complete. Here is where the beauty of this game shines through.As stated before, this is a game that rewards your creativity a lot:You may play with any of the default rulers and their races or create your own.In the tomes system, you can make an absurd number of combinations: Want some evil elf barbarians? Game got you. Ruled by a dragon overlord? Got\'cha. Eventually transform your people into draconic hybrids? Hell yeah, brutha :vAs you progress through the story or random matches, be them online or single player, you unlock cosmetics and traits to further increase your options when creating races and rulers.Several events in the game in which you are presented choices which will impact the way your game develops, or even the race you created, by obtaining permanent traits through the outcomes of such events.Lords you have won games with in realms can be ascended, which allows you to have them in your games as recruitable heroes or even allies rulers, maybe you\'ll see some of your creations as oponents or free cities you can annex or vassalize.Every race is different from one another: different units, aesthetic and the way they usually play, their advantages and disadvantages. Some rewarding an evil playthrough or good one. Because, yes, there is an alignment meter which will come into play for your available decisions in random events.Every tome you choose will have an assortment of enchantments to augment your racial units (poison arrows, frost weapons, anyone?), spells to use either in combat or the world map or even more units (!!) which can determine your strategies not only in battle, but as you reach out for victory. The list would go on and this would turn into a major wall of text. Do yourself favor and play this game when you are able.It is simple to learn but by no means less fun because of that, plus an active modding community adding even more options? Yes, please.',''),(2384,'Create your own faction up to the smallest details, and crush your enemies in a turn-based 4X fantasy world that you can fully customize. Play the good guys or conquer the world. Explore, experiment, defy the usual tropes and try new perspectives. There’s plenty of room for roleplaying if you are inclined to do so. You’re in for a great experience.On the board, Age of Wonders 4 behaves like a regular 4X game, complete with the expected elements (medieval setting, no firearms or futuristic technologies, use of magic, diverse sentient races) along with your personal preferences. Turn-based battles allow for another level of depth, and using spells and enchantments against your enemies is very fun.The star of the show is customization. You can either go wild with creativity or stick to convention. Want to play Tolkien’s standard-issue elves against a rising evil power? You can. But you can also play undead feudal toads, honorable faith-bound orcs, angelic moles, scholarly crocodiles or vicious, barbaric halflings. The fact that you can personalize your faction leader gives you even more fantastic options. A draconic overlord leading a troop of enslaved dwarves? A minute wizard rat as the monarch of a human kingdom? Yes, you can.Age of Wonders 4 follows the current trend of “multiverses” that so commonly these days explains the infinite possibilities of characters in different situations. You play as a god or “godir”—one of many—that visits one of the countless realms (game worlds) to fight other godirs for dominance. A game within a game, if your godir dies she returns to the afterlife hub to try again, and the same will happen to your opponents. Or you can play as a commoner in one of such realms, fighting to win the right to ascend to your very own pantheon of divinities. You can create as many as you want, and play with them however you like. The only real way to kill a godir is by deleting him from your game options.The models are gorgeous, colorful and varied, and there are lots of them. Mythical creatures, extraplanar beings, animals and people are all depicted in detail and variety. The animations are excellent, despite some clipping with capes and beards—something quite common in games of all flavors. The graphical style is fine, even if not too original, but the interface feels a little bit dated and derivative.There’s a wonderful feature that I’ve noticed after a long time playing, that is seldom mentioned elsewhere. Depending on your chosen race and traits, you will be able to construct certain buildings that make for a unique scenario experience. My shadow dwarves were able to build experimentation chambers and underground laboratories, but those were not available to the rest of my factions.The concept of magic is associated to tomes, which contain spells that share a common topic. While there are some more advanced and powerful than others, you will never be restricted to a specific magical school. There’s something for everyone, and you can alter your strategies on the spot. You’ll find spells that can summon mythical creatures and monsters, buff your allies, enchant your weapons, and even alter the climate and turn the landscape into a barren wasteland, a frozen desert or a lush forest.There is a moral system in place, but I found it somewhat rudimentary or too simplistic, that tends to polarize factions and influence certain situations. An artificial “karma” of sorts will mean that if you behave in a wrongful way, you could even get worse results in dilemmas and choice events. I personally disliked this, since it takes away some of the fun of being evil.The music is fine; sometimes overly dramatic and with little thematic variation. I found it repetitive after a while, especially in the faction creation screen. If you’re like me and most of the usual gamers of the genre, you’ll spend a lot of time here. There is little voice acting—mostly in terms of flavor text—but it’s solid.Mechanics-wise, Age of Wonders 4 is best played with mouse and keyboard. Misclicks are sadly common thanks to a cluttered interface, army models and banners in the world map. Sometimes the use of right and left clicks was unclear to me, but this is mitigated with on-screen help. I did not encounter a single error, crash or bug in over 80 hours of playtime.The triumph of Age of Wonders 4 is its enormous flexibility, which derives in the huge number of possibilities for you to shape your gameplay to your liking. If you have played other fantasy games before, you’ll soon appreciate this. Those titles will eventually appear too rigid and limited, but we must remember that with many available options comes generalization and a lack of focus.I’ve heard some comments on the apparent blandness of the game, but you can’t be universal and highly customizable without being abstract and generalist. That’s the price to be paid for personalization, and it’s perfectly fine.I bought the premium edition with a small pre-order discount. So far, the experience has been satisfactory, and the game content is plenty and adequate. The DLC so far has been nice and adds meaningful elements to an already interesting gameplay, like the ability to play as a dragon lord, and an additional race and culture.If the idea of having a powerful playground full of alternatives to create your dream realm of fantasy tropes appeals to you, you’ll love this game.Wonderfully recommended.',''),(2385,'Overall a quite enjoyable game. If you liked Age of Wonders: planetfall you\'ll like this one as well. The game looks really nice, I really like the artstyle the animations the whole thing. The DLC faction and dragon lords are amazing (granted they are DLC but still at least they deliver). Also the whole system with the race alterations that visually show up on all your units is really nice.Buuuuut there are a few things that are really irksome.Main thing is the AI. Its dumb as a bag of rocks. The enemy cheats (spawning units from thin air completing construction quicker that sort of thing) which i think is fine because otherwise it would be way too easy. Where it becomes annoying as all hell is when you get the bright idea that you don\'t want to murder everyone. Now in that case the AI is really nice and rewards you with blocking you in with outposts, taking all of the free city vassals and just generally being really annoying.And diplomacy is a joke you can sell territory to AI but you can never buy it (which would really easily solve the blocking in problem)The other thing is the story. In previous titles in a campaign there was some persistent characters that you got to level up gather some good artefacts and so forth. Here there is not even a campaign. You have story realms that are technically campaign missions but for example if you want to play the whole thing with one leader you are starting lvl 1 on every map. And the storyline is kinda all over the place as well. Fair enough this last one is pretty subjective but i still want to point it out. But hey maybe you\'ll like it.So yeah if you want a good turn based strategy game then its a good buy. If you liked Age of wonders: planetfall i can whole heartedly recommend it.If you want to play something akin to Age of Wonders 1 or 3 then only go for it if you are willing to put up with the above mentioned things.',''),(2386,'The strength of this game is how customizable it is. You can define your nation and leader with a ton of different choices. There are lots of options for generating random maps and scenarios. Once the game starts, you can customize your heroes, cities, and research. There are so many spells to learn, items to collect, and units to build. I don\'t know if I\'ve played a game of this sort with more options.People say the AI isn\'t very good. I\'m not sure if that\'s true. It feels competent to me, but I\'m not a very skilled player. I treat the game more like an RPG, and I try to make decisions that are interesting rather than optimized.I used to auto-resolve all the battles, but then I stopped because the detailed battle system really is half the game.',''),(2387,'I\'ve grown up with the Age of Wonders series, and I believe that Age of Wonders 4 is not only the best of the series, it\'s a powerhouse of a 4X game with a deep magic and race system that evolves through playtime. Note that my review is entirely from a single player perspective.There\'s a lot to talk about here, but the key points (from me) are:- Extreme Customisation: Each race can intermix with a variety of civilisation types, which can also match across a variety of magic types. Entire maps (worlds) are randomly-generated with player input. - Robust Magic System: If you like to get all in-depth with your magic types, you\'ll have fun here. Explore the ends of power in several unique schools of magic. Spells are used at a World, Army, and Combat level. - Good UI: With so much information available at any given time, AoW4 does a good job making everything easily accessible. I believe good UI is important for long-term engagement, and Age of Wonders 4 makes the game easily accessible to those familiar with 4X games at a surface level, but it\'s also structured to feel familiar to experienced players. - Steam Workshop Integration: While I\'m generally not in to modding my games at all, the Workshop here does offer many tweaks to affect the game.  In my case, I use a mod that provides some better unit scaling for combat and I still get Steam achievements.The AI and difficulty can be disastrous, however. AI and the interplay between NPC entities and the player are downright bad at times. Additionally, vassals cannot be trusted for help without explicitly directing it, which felt odd. On a global scale, it\'s very difficult to \'make friends\' with the AI, as it feels very easily for everything to degrade into squabble and battle. For example, my lawfully-good humans won by conquest (naturally), vs my full-evil frostlings winning by diplomatic victory (difficultly). It\'s kind of a case where modern AI thinking just devolves in to \"combat\" so I hope this can improve.Some players like how races transform as they gain power, some players do not like this.  What you need to know is this: you can have a race of cat people who can evolve in to beings that are not cats, thereby making them less \'cat people\' and more \'new people\'. Like, a cat person who is also made of tree. Or fire.  Or frost.  It\'s going to happen, so - be warned, I guess.It\'s not perfect, but Age of Wonders 4 is a great, modern fantasy civilisation strategy game with a focus on all the good stuff like Heroes and Hero types, races and abilities, underground worlds, independent city states, battles of good / evil, allegiances born and failed; there\'s just a lot to take in.  It\'s most definitely in the conversation for Game of the Year, but in a year with so many great titles, AoW4 is an underdog.Get it in a bundle with DLC if you think you\'ll probably be interested, otherwise just wait for a deep discount and grab it then.  In either case, you won\'t be disappointed. Recommended.',''),(2388,'It\'s a good game that gets me hooked. I like the age the game is based in plus the city building and war. The game has an immersive experience. The game has a couple issues though. My two biggest issues with the game are the extremely long turn time and daily crashes. The turn time can take minutes which really starts to take a toll on you as you progress. The daily crashes are annoying because I\'ll have to redo my current turn and then I\'ll have to wait for the extremely long turn time again.Again, I really like the game and play it all the time. There are definitely a couple areas of improvement.',''),(2389,'If you enjoy Civ, then you\'ll enjoy this. It\'s like Civ but with a fantasy world theme.',''),(2390,'It\'s alright, but it just doesn\'t reach the peak that Age of Wonders 3 or Planetfall did for me. 3 had stronger unit designs, and racial features were more fun and distinct. The random world gen for 3 wasn\'t great, but the handcrafted maps were very strong.Planetfall\'s upgrades made low tier units more relevant, the larger provinces felt better, and cities having inbuilt garrisons was a welcome feature.Both had better combat maps, and both had a decently long campaign, whereas 4\'s maps all feel too flat and the campaign is much too short. Computer turns also take an incredibly long time.4 isn\'t terrible, but I have a hard time recommending it over one of the prior entries.',''),(2391,'Great fun, easy to get into, despite initially being overwhelmed by options! Tooltips are very well made and crystal clear you pick it up in no time at all. Endless customisation options that allow for very different experiences each playthrough. Dragon DLC is really worth it and a lot of fun. Excellent game!',''),(2392,'I made a race of order following rat-people led by a hairy and stubby dragon I named the giant rat that makes all of the rules 10/10.',''),(2393,'I was expecting a fun and complete game, it seems like the base game is missing key 4X features that look to come from the DLC and I do not like to purchase games that do not have good stand alone gameplay prior to DLC expansions.',''),(2394,'Best Age of Wonders game yet.  I\'m terrible at it, but I\'m still really enjoying it.',''),(2395,'If you\'ve played any of the previous games in the Age of Wonders franchise, you know you\'re getting into and AoW4 takes the core experience you know and love to the next level.If you\'re new to Age of Wonders, don\'t worry too much - Unless you are desperate to learn how The Second Age (AoW2 & Shadow Magic) plays out, The Fourth Age does a good job of welcoming newcomers into the fold whilst giving returning players something to look forward to.To recap the Third Age, you had campaigns with a strong narrative focus to them.  Some of them were relatively easy to get into, but there were instances that felt like you were playing a Square Enix game where the difficulty spikes all of a sudden.  The learning campaign didn\'t waste time knocking you around like that.  If you were one of the players walked passed the campaigns and played Random Map or jump into multiplayer, can\'t say I blame you because did exactly that.  AoW: Planetfall\'s campaigns objective focused whilst taking on the openness of a random map, AoW4 continues this open campaign style - I can understand why Triumph might\'ve gone that route, but I to SOME degree I can appreciate the sentiments regarding the lack of a story focused campaign.  Whilst the story heavy stuff is great for getting a feel for all the world building that goes into these games, the open nature of the game does allow newcomers the opportunity to learn at their own pace without having to jump through any potentially brutal scripted hurdles.  Given that AoW4 builds upon the insane level of customisation from AoW3, this game offers the level of DIY world building one would expect from Dungeons & Dragons.So what is Age of Wonders?It\'s a Roleplaying Grand Strategy franchise - You manage your empire and statecraft affairs 4X overworld map, whilst battles are fought as classic turn-based RPG encounters...  Unless you prefer to \"Roll\" your battles via the ol\' Auto-Resolve.Whilst Planetfall was the exception being a 1980\'s inspired space opera, Age of Wonders is typically a high fantasy themed franchise.  The basic rules of a game come down to this:  Your chosen/created \"Hero\" (statesman) and your Throne City (starting city/capital) are your \"King Pieces\".  Slay a player\'s avatar and sack their Throne City before their hero can respawn, they\'ve suffered a Military Defeat.  Otherwise, you have an assortment of goals similar to Sid Meier\'s Civilization.Age of Wonders 4 builds upon Planetfall\'s annexation system, where you are able to expand from an existing population centre by placing an exploitation (improvement) on an available territory connected to your given city\'s border.  This particular system really fleshed out the city building aspect of AoW compared to AoW3.  Near as what I can tell, unless there\'s a mod or I missed the flavour text in one of the realm creation options - There\'s no Nomadic start, something I miss from AoW3.  For most people, AoW4\'s world building comes from creating your hero and empire.  Sure, you\'re going to have your \"Min-Maxxers\".  But, your average roleplayer is going to be taking their time considering the options best suited for the character their looking to play.  Expect to be spending a good chunk of time in the creation suites if you are a roleplayer, because you\'re going to be setting up realms too.  It\'s a good thing you have a nice assortment of pre-constructed realms and characters, because some times you might want to get a feel for what you can create for your next session or just roleplay with what the developers took the time to craft.Soundtrack for Age of Wonders has had some memorable pieces by Michiel van den Bos, Age of Wonders 3 being the recent of them.  Age of Wonders 4 like Planetfall takes on more \"Soundscape\" oriented musical soundtrack - If you were more partial to AoW3, this soundtrack isn\'t going keep you captivated.  Chances are, you will let play out once or twice before firing up something like Spotify.Is Age of Wonders worth it?Not ONLY would I recommend it for lovers of both high fantasy RPGs and 4X strategy, if you can afford to...  Go Premium!',''),(2396,'Its a 4x game where the only thing to do fight. I normally don\'t like the focus on fighting. But this game makes you feel very powerful as you progress through tech. Also you can be a despicable necromancy civ. I\'m a sucker for necromancy.',''),(2397,'if you love might and magic 3 buy this game',''),(2398,'Brilliant game, what Master of Magic should have been I guess.',''),(2399,'I really love this game. I\'ve played strategy games that are based around magical worlds or middle ages. This game reminds me a little of Stellaris, huge difference, but you can customize any faction and have a different game each time. I played a game with 7 random factions, and happened to have 3 of them that had the same last names. My quest was to destroy all 3 of them. They were evil brothers lol. I never seen that in the 40 or so game i\'ve played, but each one is different.They games are very long. I haven\'t been able to try this with friends, but I think it would be so much fun with friends.I\'ve played Stronghold games, Warhammer games, Age of Empires games, Stellaris... and I think this might be my favorite game now.',''),(2400,'My opinion of Age of Wonders 4 is in comparison to Age of Wonders Planetfall, and it is worth noting that there are many ways in which AoW 4 practically styles on Planetfall in regards to improvements to gameplay. I simply couldn\'t list all of those improvements without them being the main body of this review, but in general many of the annoyances and roadblocks one might experience in a match of Planetfall are mitigated or outright gone in AoW 4.However, despite all of AoW 4\'s functional improvements over Planetfall, the game is completely lacking in terms of story and personality. When playing Planetfall, every world played on had a sense of character, every character and faction had motivations, goals, and ideological divides both internally and externally. As a point of example, I generally have a sort of \"peace and harmony\" strategy when making choices in video game campaigns, but I made several choices in Planetfall scenarios against that mentality on the basis that the characters in those scenarios wouldn\'t make those decisions. Put simply, the conflicts and characters within Planetfall are well written.Meanwhile, despite having 3 games of lore to draw from (4 if you count the experience from Planetfall), I only understood what was going on in AoW 4 in the vaguest of ways AFTER beating all of the campaigns. On top of that, some of the conflicts in the scenarios are flat out cop-outs. Without spoiling, the entire conflict that the story builds up to is rendered retroactively pointless and nonsensical, and two of the scenarios cop-out the interpersonal conflict part of the story by making the bad guy corrupted by magic evilness.All of that would be annoying and frustrating on its own, but what really irritates me is custom/random scenario tools for after you\'re done with the main story. Things as basic as a lighting change for the world (which the story scenarios have!) are not available, while the features that are there to be customized are heavily stripped down. I can\'t think of a succinct way of describing how pitiful and lacking the custom world options are beyond saying that you need look no farther than Planetfall to see it done right.Which brings me to my conclusion: as much as AoW 4 improves on Planetfall in many ways, if this game looks interesting to you, play Planetfall instead.PS. The AI tries to build cities as close as it can to strategic resources directly around your capital, to a degree that is both blatant and insane. If you don\'t believe me, this is a steam discussion on the issue, and you can find many more through people noting it through a simple google search: https://steamcommunity.com/app/1669000/discussions/0/5294588689491084454/ . To say that this is infuriating and ridiculous is an understatement; it has made my blood boil throughout much of the early game of nearly every scenario I\'ve played, and single-handedly caused numerous rage-restarts. F*k that.',''),(2401,'A bit simpler than I like as far as combat and city building goes...BUT, I still find it a lot of fun! Nice maps, interesting enough customisation of maps and races, a bit of RPG Hero tailoring....along with the joy of expanding your empire, minor diplomacy, and battling enemies with some neat looking units on the field, Overall worth it. If I can get 80 to 100 hours out of a game (minimum) without becoming bored or completely turned off a game, its worth it for me.',''),(2402,'A 4X game with a good battle system heavily inspired by Heroes of Might and Magic.The selling point here is customization : - You create your leader, a kind of demi-god to lead your race; from a mighty warrior, champion of its people to a slave-merchant warlock able to alter reality to a ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ dragon god anything you think of is possible, your leader doesn\'t need to be from the race you will play.- Then you create the race with its visual being independent of the racial traits you choose, you want some kind of nimble undead dwarves ? suit yourself, the possibilities are nearly infinite.- You then pick a faction from a pool of 6 (7 with DLC) each with its unique buildings, units, passive trait and leaning toward a play style that you can ignore if you want to.- Finally the fun really begins when you select a Tome, Tomes are the tech tree of the game. They give you the ability to buy new units, build strong buildings in your city, cast powerful spells to help you on the map on or battle and even enchant the weapons or even your race itself. There are 6 styles of Tomes each having 5 tiers the first 4 containing 2 tomes. This is how you make your race and your gameplay unique and this is extremely fun even just theorycrafting builds. There are some Story maps you can play at start to get used to the system but you will probably use CUSTOM MAPS where you can chose a lot of settings to alter the experience and even some weird victory conditions allowing for a good hundred of hours of chaotic fun.',''),(2403,'proving to my dad that being a good father is easy',''),(2404,'A daughter raising game that reminds me of princess maker. It is fun if you like this kind of game',''),(2405,'This game actually feels mechanically better and LOOKS better than actual \'Princess Maker\' games. Art is gorgeous, and I REALLY appreciate that the game allows you to pick MULTIPLE endings, and has stat decrease items to achieve even more endings in one save. I loved the story! It was very cute despite some of the flaws I saw in it\'s narrative.So are there any problems? Yes. 1) The English translation is NOT good. Sometimes I can barely understand what was happening. In fact, I didn\'t even know time looping was a thing until someone on a forum mentioned it to me. The English translation doesn\'t read like real people are speaking. As another example; I had difficulty telling whether Kenneth could REALLY not speak well, or if it was just the translation struggling to portray someone socially awkward. The translation NEEDS to be redone at some point, because there exist many english speakers who refuse to buy this game because the translation is so bad. 2) The plot has some holes because the protagonist (your daughter) is only an observing party until the very end of the game. You see, aside from the fathers memories.... the plot goes on without the player almost entirely in the background. And infact, one could argue that the plot is more about the mother, father and three lords... Not the daughter. And this is a problem; because there is a specific plot point concerning her father... where the daughter SHOULD\'VE been actively searching for a cure, but never did. She instead just keeps it a secret, and lets the three lords figure it out themselves while she lived life completely normally. And this caused narrative problems in the story, as certain plot points remain unclear which would\'ve otherwise made sense if the daughter was actually involved in the plot.3) I loved the characters, they just didn\'t have enough involvement in the story for me to feel much attachment. Other than the lords, only Nina is the only other reoccurring character in the plot. Every other character fundamentally doesn\'t matter, as they are not at all involved in the story and their events are completely optional.Characters such as Kenneth, Hackett and Ze had a LOT of potential for additional story points; but that potential is never actually explored or realised in the game.----In summary: LOVE THIS GAME! It\'s an upgrade over the \'Princess Maker series\' despite its flaws. However, I would like to someday see a better english translation, and perhaps some DLC concerning characters like Kenneth, Ze and Hackett. I feel like having them be the individual protagonist of their own mini episode would flesh out and get players more attached to their characters.If this devloper makes any future games, I hope that that they make the daughter more involved in the plot. And I hope for some more fantasy characters(Let us marry a demon lord!) and more fantasy endings. As those are my favourite elements in Gainax\'s princess maker series.',''),(2406,'Don\'t recommend playing this game if your native language is English. I\'m fine with some grammatical mistakes here and there, but the dialog is clunky and sometimes indecipherable. Asking for a refund on this, hopefully one day it gets fixed cause the game looks cute.',''),(2407,'If you are a person who loves Princess Maker or Long Live The Queen: you will absolutely adore this game, and will probably become so entranced you sink hours and hours of your life into this. It is peak Raising Sim. I adored it. Yes, the translation is very choppy - that\'s an unfortunate truth. But I managed to adjust pretty early on. The art style is gorgeous, the CGs are plentiful, and the daughter is loveable. What else can you want?',''),(2408,'The English translation is just awful.',''),(2409,'A great game and a lot fun, very reminiscent of Princess Maker 2 but a more modern take. I played ALOT of Princes Maker 2 and adored it so I was very excited to see a similar game release in modern times. Art is beautiful and the world much more fleshed out then the game it resembles. Also has much more in depth friendship system though I really wish there was more character events then there currently is. This game also has a longer play style then Princess Maker. 1 full playthrough took me about a full day or a estimated 7 hours which is a BIG difference from the quicker playthroughs that Princess Maker generally had. That is if your going for the bigger endings.I must mention the translation for this game is a somewhat bad. Most of the time I can understand whats being said and happening but during the larger story reveal the bad translations made following far harder. I don\'t think its bad enough to drag the game down as I still enjoyed it a lot even with the errors but its something to be aware of. The beginning cutscene particularly is bad but it gets much better throughout the game in my opinion.The story overall is alot of fun, though I feel a weird about the fact that she can end up with the adults or her own professors. But you don\'t have to unless your 100 percenting the game and the gameplay really is fun so I can let it go. Its easy to make sure this doesn\'t happen just be sure your chosen love interest has the most relationship points. Though if the others reach a certain level as well you may get a dejected letter from other characters in the ending, but that\'s easy enough to skip through. Would definitely recommend I\'m already on my third play through and still having a blast. If you enjoy the Princess Maker series this is absolutely worth the price.8/10 slight point loss for the weird dating choices and bad translations',''),(2410,'I love this game because of the story, and how it changes based on your choices. There are so many romanceable characters that it is hard to choose who you want to be with. And the \"true\" ending will simply make you smile.',''),(2411,'I will protect her at all cost',''),(2412,'When I first decided to buy this game, I was a bit hesitant for the translation issue that was noted in some of the previous reviews thinking that it would be bad. Well, after playing for 30+ hours I do say that it could have been better, but honestly the issue wasn\'t bad enough for me to ruin the game and I enjoyed it. It has variety of things to do which are fun and interesting, a whole array of possible career, story, and romance (IT HAS HAREM AND REVERSE HAREM ENDING?! I\'m sold!) endings which is a requirement for a good CYOA/Simulation game, and a decent story plot (a bit of inconsistency at the conclusion but oh well).Do note that while the game is kind in offering wide-range of possibilities, this game is pretty rigid on the requirement of getting it so if you are a game completionist then please beware. Otherwise, this game is a great way to spend your time by nurturing and watching your virtual daughter grow up and handle their future.',''),(2413,'They grow up so fast...',''),(2414,'It is an amazing game that I didn\'t expect to enjoy as much as I did.',''),(2415,'I enjoyed it but it\'s very repetitive at some point. It\'s really cool that they made multiple endings but I don\'t think the game is fun enough to play it once more.',''),(2416,'I absolutely refuse to do the bad parent route.',''),(2417,'I\'ve really enjoyed the raising sim genre since playing Princess Maker 2 back in the heyday of DOS games. I\'ve only found a couple since that really improved upon the genre or added anything noteworthy. The other before Volcano Princess being Long Live the Queen. VP is a breath of fresh air in a rather stagnant genre of niche games. The game play is comfortably familiar while not being afraid to discard a few tired systems and tropes. The art is lovely, the lore extensive and interesting, the story is intriguing, and the potential endings plentiful. I\'m so glad I came across this game and definitely see myself coming back to this fun and cozy title for years to come.',''),(2418,'It is my duty to date all the women (LEBSA MY BELOVED)PS: After like 30 hours, the game has gotten a bit boring. But i enjoyed the artwork and characters a lot, and it was fun to screw around and see what endings i would get.  I also have to warn yall that there may be hints of  grooming and incest  in this game which may be disturbing to some. (I get it! I\'m still shocked!!)',''),(2419,'when you launch, you might experience a lot of lag. Or, in some cases: freezing, which could cause the game to crash.',''),(2420,'Incredible value for money, glad I got it during the latest sale. I thought it was a mere visual novel and kid sim, but it\'s practically a full-fledged RPG too. There\'s so many little things to do.I hope the English translation could be improved upon',''),(2421,'very cute and wholesome game. Enjoyed playing it!',''),(2422,'Protect the child at all costs! I\'ve already put 51 hours into this game and still haven\'t done around half the endings! It\'s definitely worth your money if you like multiple endings and life sims. Addicted and wish there was more.....DLC please????? or Volcano Princess 2? ; ____ ;',''),(2423,'I rarely take the time to review a game, good or bad.  I\'m simply going to say this.  Relic charged full price for an incomplete \"Alpha\" version of the game.  Those of us who paid for it have been doing \"free testing\" for them.  Now, they announce a massive new update that finally \"finishes\" the game.  Yet, the new content is bundled into a new way to extract money out of their loyal fans.  16 bucks for this?  Come on.  It\'s not that I have a problem with the price or what you get it.  It\'s the fact that clearly those in charge are brain dead and completely tone deaf to their player base.  I can easily afford it.  I may end up caving in and paying the 16.  I also may never spend another dollar on a Relic game again.  Shocking.  why don\'t you do the right thing and include the new content for free to those who have already purchased the game as a way to say sorry for the complete and utter trash you that you released to us at full price?',''),(2424,'Play Company of Heroes 2 instead',''),(2425,'Wow... just wow. I normally don\'t leave reviews, regardless of whether I like or dislike a game, but I\'ll make an exception for this. I\'m a big fan of the franchise ever since I first played a demo of the original Company of Heroes at Gamescom. I love RTS games, and this was the wet dream of all players. Of course, it had its limitations, but they were manageable. I convinced all my friends to buy the game so we could play together, and we spent a lot of hours enjoying it.Then Company of Heroes 2 dropped – a new setting, more complex tactics, and, most of all, more different units and compositions to style your game. At launch, it had a lot of problems, so after buying the game, I uninstalled it to play Company of Heroes 1 again. But after a year, the game played like a charm, and although different commanders were locked and easier to obtain through paying with real money, they were also unlockable through in-game currency.Then Company of Heroes 3 was announced, and I was excited! So much that my friends, the same ones I convinced to buy the other two games, created a fake hard case of the game with pictures of me on it. Inside was a Steam gift card with which I pre-ordered the game. When it finally released, I played and played and played it. The gameplay was smooth for me, but the lack of basic things like multiple commanders and a new setting, which were present in the previous entries, disappointed me a little. I had hoped the game would finally visit the Japanese theater and include all previous factions in multiplayer for the ultimate Company of Heroes experience. Instead, we got an unrefined game even after one year of release, and the first big update that should include multiple commander choice/customization is a DLC? It feels like a joke. I don\'t work in the game industry, so I don\'t know if there are hidden reasons behind these paywalls and unfinished games coming out in the last couple of years. Or maybe it\'s because I\'m getting older, and my standards are changing, but this doesn\'t feel like the game studio I convinced many of my friends to buy multiple games from so we could play together.Company of Heroes is one of the games I always have installed on my PC. It\'s my go-to relax game after a hard day. I guess I\'ll have to go back to Company of Heroes 2.It pains me to say, but if you haven\'t bought the game yet, I suggest you\'re better of investing the money to buy Company of Heroes 2 and its DLC. Then you have a more complete game than when you get this one...',''),(2426,'I\'ve been following the CoH3 development and its general release very closely.  I\'ve been an avid CoH player for many years starting with the original game then the sequel.  I\'ve always been fond of the original CoH title since it\'s a rare gem in terms of gameplay and replay ability.  When CoH2 released I was excited for another CoH title and gladly bough the collector’s edition. This was also when THQ went bankrupt, and Relic became part of Sega.  I can only imagine what happened to CoH2 as a result from that change.  The result of CoH2 was quite a departure in the overall gameplay and replay ability that I loved so much from the original game.  The overall quality dropped quite a lot and was far more disappointed than I would have thought and the DLC\'s being released were not the DLC\'s (called expansions in those days…)  from Relic\'s older games that you would never think twice to purchase without question.  CoH2 really set the stage for my expectations of CoH3.  I would not preorder and wait until I felt satisfied that the game was worthwhile to play.CoH3 sounded amazing when it was announced but the development was rushed to release.  Despite delaying the games release to a few months later the initial game release was quite unpolished and unfinished, but I would argue CoH2 even in its end state is far worse to the current state of CoH3.  I wasn\'t part of CoH3 until the recent patch of Steel Shepperd.  I have heard it bought quite the improvement to the game but even before then I didn\'t see it as bad as what CoH2 was mainly due to a pathetic game engine that bugsplatted all the time until it got better with the 64-bit version of CoH2 that got released later in its lifespan.  CoH3 from initial impressions is quite satisfying but I can only imagine the state of the game before German Shepherd.  I got used to how bad CoH2 ran and even on a decent system seemed to perform bad regardless of what hardware you used, but CoH3 doesn’t exhibit those issues.  I find CoH3 a pleasant departure from the performance issues of CoH2.  I’ve been playing only for a few hours, but I find the current state of the game is worth the buy if you get a 20% or more discount.With the Steel Shepperd update came the first DLC (or expansion) as Relic calls it.  Its not an expansion all it provides is two battlegroups you can unlock for free using Merits and then a bunch of cosmetics.  The asking price for this content is very overpriced.  If you have prime gaming, you can get decent skins just from those drops.  The premium edition includes this DLC for free, but I would recommend you avoid the premium edition since its not justified by its price and what it provides players.  Most players who preordered the premium edition has been largely disappointed by what it provides for the money.As much as I wish Relic would remain in its glory days of making some of the best games of all time it simply hasn’t been for quite some time.  Relic refuses to deliver what its player base wants, and it puts anything and everything behind a massive paywall.  I’m honestly not sure if this is a decision by Relic or Sega or both.  I would confidently say that the overall value of DLC’s is quite questionable for what you get, and I can only imagine how the future DLC content will be moving forward.  I would, however, expect overpriced skins or other cosmetics or new battlegroups that for those that rely on them can introduce a pay to win scenario if Relic decides to not offer them to be obtainable in game without spending real money (such as using Merits instead).I would confidently say that CoH3 is a worthwhile title just be sure to be cautious of any DLC’s or Expansions that Relic might announce since it may not be what you may expect.  If you want a copy of CoH3 I would recommend purchasing the base game not the premium since it’s a better overall value in many regards.  I just hope that 10+ months later that Relic continues to support this game and not recreate the overall experience of CoH2 that left me very disappointed with a franchise that many hold dear in their hearts.  I have no issue supporting Relic, but Relic needs to support their fanbase and start going back to their roots for what made them so beloved for so many years.  I always have a glimmer of hope that Relic could do just that since CoH is still a great franchise!Added remarks after playing the game: (I’ll add content/updates here to not diminish my original review)For CoH3 specifically I’ve been playing Skirmishes and have noticed that playing the game the animations and the way the game plays is much improved compared to CoH2 and even CoH1.  The game feels very fluid compared to past CoH titles.  Arguably, CoH1 still has better visuals than CoH2, but I personally think currently CoH3 is better generally speaking.  CoH2 had some janky animations and odd things that would occur that CoH3 doesn’t exhibit such as dead units being able to attack you until they finally died – lol!  I do find that the character models don’t look overly improved from any of the older CoH titles and if you zoom into them, they don’t look much better and even loose a bit of detail and quality.  Perhaps Relic is using older models from the previous titles I’m honestly not sure but its not AAA title graphics but they sill look good none the less.  Keep in mind CoH games are far smaller games to install compared to AAA titles you are looking around 100GB’s per title.  They look fine when the camera is set to the default zoom.  I’ve also seen that CoH 3 has a decent map selection along with 4 factions to boot which past games you had to purchase expansions to get them.  I am also very pleased with the steam workshop coming to CoH3 where it was later integrated in CoH1 and 2 later in their life.  After a quick browse of the Steam Workshop for CoH3 there appears to be quite a wealth of content from maps, tuning packs and much more to choose from and it appears to be growing quite a lot.  I found once Relic stops patching the game the Steam Workshop brings a new life to the game which allows the game to remain engaging.  Overall, I find the factions and general gameplay elements such as the way the factions play along with the general controls to work quite well.  Maybe they are not optimally balanced, but their overall completeness feels quite better than previous titles.  It’s hard to explain but I felt in older games some of the factions clearly lacked in certain areas to a fault.  I feel in CoH3 there is something to work with the faction and its mechanics which is a welcome change.  I feel I can play as any faction and have some method to play the way I want to the way the faction plays.',''),(2427,'Many criticize this game for the lack of content (number of commanders/maps/etc), and it is absolutely deserved. However, what this game lacks in quantity it makes up for in quality. The game play from COH2 has been incredibly polished. Units have unique and interesting abilities, unit path finding is excellent (usually), and the maps the game did release with are excellent. HOWEVER, I hate the breakneck, profits first approach Sega has imposed on Relic. The lack of content is not Relics fault. The developer team is relatively small and the time and resources they had to make this was insufficient. I\'m sure with a couple more expansions this game will be everything the fan base was hoping for. But I believe that fans are justifiably upset with the lack of quality. I want the game to be successful, so I am leaving a thumbs up.',''),(2428,'Starting to look like a Company of Heroes game',''),(2429,'I\'m one of those who played CoH 1 alot back in the day.When CoH 2 came out I got so disapointed. Not that it needed to be pathced up with balance and such. Mayor thing was the amount of commanders. You never got a sence of knowledge what your opponent specced and because of that you couldent counter it any way. Its just mouseclicking chaos in comparison to COH 1.Now, CoH 3 reminds me alot of CoH 1. And thats good. I\'m not much for singelplayer campaigns or vs AI.CoH 3 has fewer commanders again and that give you a better understanding of your enemy. More strategy and thats a +It also has smarter units, they jump over fenced by themselfs intelligently now.Also units has a slightly better hold out value and that let you keep your units alive a bit easier. Its so frustrating when you have 2 front combat and loose a unit where you are not looking. Now you got better time to switch forth and aft.I rate the games for how I experienced them for their current eraCoH1 - 5CoH2 - 2CoH3 - 4If you liked CoH 1 you will like CoH 3 - atleast I do.',''),(2430,'The December 5th update is how the game should have launched, yes Relic have made mistakes with the launch (As always) but the Steel Shepherd patch is a step in the right direction.',''),(2431,'On release it was a buggy mess with potential. One year later an update comes out that makes the game look like it should have on release.However with an overinflated store cost for new battlegroups and a pitiful and greedy merit system, forcing people to pay with cash to get what they want because otherwise it would take almost 2 months of free grinding, hard focusing on the challenges.The only way I can make my review positive after I wasted my good faith on buying this game, is they have to at least add merit rewards to finishing games like in CoH2, start releasing battlegroups and content like you promised and fix those ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ prices in their store. Because let\'s be honest as gamers. We love skins on our stuff. So if the prices were lower they would have probably sold a lot more.',''),(2432,'I don\'t know if I have ever posted a review.  The game in its current state is where it should have been upon release.  Extremely underwhelmed with the new \"DLC\" but happy they finally have the game where it should be.  Next time, just release the game with the \"early access\" flag Relic.  The same thing happened with AOE IV. I will never buy a Relic game on Day 1 ever again if they are given the chance to ever make another game...',''),(2433,'Edit - They have patched the issues with the BGs. Is it perfect; no. But it is now generally balanced and playable.COH3 has the promise of becoming a brilliant RTS.With the release of Hammer and Shield \"expansion\" the game is approaching an almost complete state. The updates to the UI and other graphics are brilliant, new sound design and two very flushed out battle-groups mark the end of the COH2 piecemeal commanders.The engine performance is a marked upgrade and while the graphics are arguably lacking compared to even the original COH, they aren\'t offensive enough to cause any real harm. A four faction release is also a big plus but it may have been better to maaaybbbee have focused on polishing two factions first and release the next two in rapid succession to fulfil the legal promises of an \"expansion\" without resorting to a pitiful, review bombed pair of battle-groups.The game still fails in its narrative. COH1 was the epitome of setting and tone done right. Graphic and sound design all worked towards a gritty and realistic war environment. COH2 was the edgy kid at the back of the class listening to Bring Me The Horizon that no one took seriously. COH3 doesn\'t feel like it knows what to be. It touts being a dark and gritty representation of war but is full of vibrant colours, tanks that look they\'re out of a \"my first army\" toy set and facepaint wearing Cherokee warrior skins. The campaign is poor, with comedic and stiff banter between the generals completing disrupting any sense of immersion, what\'s wrong with a sequential scenario based story campaign? But COH3 has one of those too! i hear you cry. Unfortunately It has the production value of a nativity play and is seriously lacking in comparison to even COH2\'s campaign.Overall I still enjoyed the game, I love the COH series with a passion, but even with my bias approach, the game is currently an utter failure.If you want immersive second world war then go play MoW, Call to Arms or Steel Division. COH3 aims to differentiate itself by being an excellent RTS first, with a poorly fitting WW2 coat. Yet the recent update \"Hammer and Shield\" has demonstrated the developers utter incompetence at balancing this game.Skill issue, I know. But we find ourselves re treading the same pitifully unbalanced path that COH2 followed. The recent update has introduced a meta of sim citying, the same thing that had plagued an earlier build of COH2 and the developers have either not play tested it properly or there\'s a hydraulic leak in the vents at the office because it has become an unplayable bunker building simulator with more artillery call ins than the somme. Remember Achelous River? Imagine being able to recreate that on every map.I had a friend who purchased every cosmetic in the store, who adamantly defended this game during it\'s unfinished initial release and I watched him give up today. If the developers continue to refine this game then it will one day reach the status of its predecessors but thing\'s like this that will whittle the fan base (and thus, the funding) down to an unsustainable level.I\'m going to go play some COH2.',''),(2434,'Coh2 is better',''),(2435,'I. Early Game ReviewBought this game today. Can\'t enter the game at first due to connection issue (you gotta be online to launch the game for the first time), not a big problem. I played the game, the gameplay mechanics are not so different from previous COH entries. Tutorial is good, it explained everything you need to play the game. Gameplay is actually fun, I enjoyed my first 106 minutes of this game.  Haven\'t tried the Campaign yet, but played the multiplayer and it was all good for me.  And with the addition of Tactical Pause feature, the singleplayer felt fun if you want to practice strategy in the field or to explore your playset.  The graphic is really something different and it\'s refreshing to my eyes (somehow). The battlefield felt more alive by removing most of its predecessor\'s gritty and dark atmosphere. Overall, I love it! I bought the COH3 Standard Edition during  discount  (IDR Rp. 428000; aprx. USD $29) and its absolutely worth the money (for me). Thank You to all of you guys! And to the Relic Development team!',''),(2436,'Honestly this game is......Very Disappointing Played COH1 For many many years COH2 was ehh but this definitely is the worst game in the series had so much to work with and the unit variety is pathetic sure the new campaign mode is nice but so much else of this game just feels lazy and they put the bare minimum level of effort and content into the game i preordered the big fancy edition of this game(mistake) and after day 7 i havnt touched it since i really regret my purchase',''),(2437,'I am what you could call a fanboi of the franchise, and this review is solely with regards to the multiplayer experience, since I have not played either of the campaigns or have plans to. I bought the premium digital edition, and I desperately want this game to succeed. But something is rotten in the HQ of Relic. The game, has been a solid and fun game since launch, but with tons of minor mistakes,  a large amount of missing features and content. I was hoping, that this new patch and content release would push the game in the right direction, and I does, to some extent. It\'s good content and a much-needed breath of fresh air. But... and yes there is a huge but. As of launch of patch 1.4 with the “Hammer and Shield” dlc, the game crashes every other game in multiplayer. I have had one crash prior to the release of \"Hammer and Shield\" over the course of 200ish hours. The balance has been effectively ruined by the overall buff of indirect fire, and sector artillery abilities of certain units and battlegroups. The game crashes, and is a bunker indirect-fire no-fun zone. The games strength, cover usage, flanking, light vehicle play, team weapons, cool mechanics etc., is now relegated to getting bombed until the game crashes. There is still a huge lack of multiplayer and skirmish maps, which makes the experience at best repetitive and at worst extremely tiresome. Charging 16.99 € for the “Hammer and Shield” dlc, and calling it an expansion is an insult. Do not buy the game or the \"expansion\". Hold off til the game gets better. Company of Heroes 2 is a great game today, and had a disastrous launch back in 2013. I hope that the devs get to mitigate the large amounts of issues with the game, and that Company of Heroes 3 will be the great game it has potential to become, before SEGA (or relic themselves) destroys the franchise. Ps.  I will update this review down the line, as the game gets patched.',''),(2438,'I\'ve played enough of this game to give something of a review. I loved the earlier company of heroes titles. This one though, it\'s just so much less. You can feel it, Less unit variety, less faction variety, less everything. I\'m comparing this to company of heroes 1 in fact. It\'s quite incredible just how stripped down this game is compared to past entries. No I wouldn\'t recommend it. Get COH2 on sale or perhaps COH1 just to compare. This just isn\'t a full game. Maybe in a years it might be, but it certainly isn\'t now.',''),(2439,'Getting a severely broken game at release and now having solid new content blocked behind a paywall after waiting months. God I hate what the franchise became.',''),(2440,'As much as I recognize the game still needs a fair amount of work, I truly think that this is the perfect blend between CoH 1 and 2.I\'ve been playing the series since 2010, prior to that my rig dind\'t event dreamed of running the first title. CoH 2 I\'ve played on launch and as much as it was cool, it didn\'t felt like CoH 2 and it received a lot of hate of the fanbase, just like CoH 3 now. The game really began to shine after the USF and OKW expansions wth the Brits giving the final thumbs up to the fans before the devs focused only on ballancing the multiplayer experience and adding a few commanders here and there.CoH 3 have a much more fun campaing with a dynamic way to play it, even not being cinematic as the prior titles, its fun and challenging. The Afrikakorps campaing is short but will garantee a couple hours of fun and an interesting and educational story about german and british ocuppation in North Africa.The devs are now working on bringing more content and I truly believe this will be a solid and rich game in the near future. I can\'t recommend paying full price but if you\'re a fan of the series as much as I it is worth giving a chance on the next sale if its at least 30% off.Next year I will update this review to confirm if my faith in Relic was worthy.',''),(2441,'How to make a good game? >Release a game>Release the Sequel>make it slightly bad than it\'s predecessor>Make a tons of cash grab DLC for it>Release an even worse Sequel>Proceed to release it with an even worse DLC',''),(2442,'I got into COH quite late, all things considered. COH1 was my favorite RTS after I delved into it, and while I tried to get into COH2, being years late to the party had me highly confused at pretty much everything that was being thrown my way. So many of the commanders in that game had abilities that others also had, in different slots, so it made a very difficult learning curve that stunted my desire to really learn. Didn\'t help that certain bugs (ie, laggy main menu) hadn\'t been fixed despite the longevity of the game.COH3 on the other hand is the sequel that I wanted. COH3 takes what\'s good from COH1, and grabs what they learned from COH2 to create a really fun experience. While the game isn\'t perfect, it\'s a lot of fun to dive into. My only complaints I can really say compared to COH1 is that the game features an in-game store and cosmetics can make it a bit trickier to tell what unit belongs to what team, however the big icon over each squad makes this mostly a non-issue, and the dynamic campaign is seemingly bugged/rebalanced to remove the ability to turn all overworld battles into various skirmishes (I really did like those), however the multiplayer is where I spend most of my time nowadays. All of the other bugs/issues I\'ve had from the launch of the game have been addressed at this point.The most recent update in December of 2023 was the first content drop we\'ve gotten, and it\'s been pretty fun so far. Not necessarily worth the huge pricetag, but luckily you can grind out the ability to buy them with in-game currency.Lookin\' forward to future updates and new ways to play the game. In the meantime, there\'s still plenty of mods to scratch that alternative gameplay itch when I need it.',''),(2443,'DON\'T BUYThis game keep crashing, the gameplay isn\'t smooth at all. Buy it for the beautiful course tho.Refund it because its unplayable. 2 out of 10',''),(2444,'game loses connection to ea servers constantly, can\'t even complete a round of golf. I\'ve been stuck on the same tournament for 5 different tries now, i get to hole 14-17 and it says lost connection and expects me to restart the whole round over again. its terrible, game doesn\'t play like other golf games. theres no learning the mechanics and expecting shots to perform after doing all you can to setup the shot to be a good one.  game just randomly decides to do something with your ball no matter how you aim or shape a shot.  Makes no sense and is a terrible game. EA servers suck, save your money and buy pga tour 2k.  much more reliable and consistent. terrible game overall. only good thing about it is that it has augusta golf course, but doesn\'t matter because odds are you won\'t finish the round without ea servers crapping out anyways.',''),(2445,'I\'m on my second go-around with PGA Tour Golf and this time I\'m giving it a strong \"recommend.\" Like some of you, I\'ve been playing computer golf since the Links days, then on to Tiger Woods iterations, and lastly the last two 2K games... until now. After 20+ hours I\'m finding this game to be fun, which is a key consideration for me. I\'m retired and play 2-3 \"real rounds\" a week at my local club and I find this game, after all the updates, to be a fair representation of the game. Did I mention it was fun? It wasn\'t always so. I bought the game (the first time) shortly after it came out and it was a hot mess. I got a refund, and stuck with 2K23. Well, here it is, several months (and major updates) later I decided to give it a go (again!) and see how it played. As you can tell by my description, I was favorably impressed, enough it remains happy in my library. It is now my go-to PC golf game. My PC is no beast, by any stretch. Remember, I\'m retired! I\'m running a long in the tooth cpu (i5-7600K - not OC\'d), I did upgrade the GPU a while back to an RTX 3060, 12 GB VRAM. I can now easily play the game on high graphical settings, even with this PC. Despite not having the most robust player customization, I find the career mode itself to be really good. I was crap at first, so I had to go into the Korn Ferry tour. But with upgrading, earned for achievements and performance, I\'m becoming a halfway decent player now. In fact,  I have won a few tournaments.  Bottom line: if you were like me and tried this game at the beginning of its life and decided \"no way!\" I would recommend you try again. Maybe wait for the next sale to pick it up. I think you\'ll be pleasantly surprised. Heartily recommend.',''),(2446,'DO NOT BUY. Game is full of bugs and connectivity issues',''),(2447,'It needs Fixes bigtime, stopped playing it untill EA gets their ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ ♥♥♥♥ together',''),(2448,'When I saw Forspoken had mixed reviews, I figured I could dismiss the negative ones. Part of that was due to an early review of the trailer I read, which complained about the \"Whedonification and Marvelization of video game quipping\".   Between that narrative, and the mixed-race female lead, I figured it was just a few angry keyboard trolls down-rating what was actually going to be an impressive experience, with a cinematic game design philosophy behind it.Holy crap was I wrong. The game has two major problems: repetitiveness and inconsistency.  Let\'s start with the inconsistency. Imagine trying to yawn, and someone pokes their finger in your mouth to interrupt it.  Now, imagine playing a game where every time you have an instinct to explore, you get rewarded with that sensation.  That is the experience you\'ll have in reaction to several of the game\'s acrobatic mechanics.  You can jump up walls - but only some of them and they\'re not clearly marked.  You can grapple-swing like Spider-man, but only really short distances...except when you can swing really long ones.  You can skip through the air across large pillars just like in the trailer - only that experience only takes place in the one area, and the mechanic it\'s built around only functions reliably in this one particular region of the game (seeming as if this region was given extra attention specifically, just so it could be featured in a gameplay trailer). There\'s a move you learn early on where you can jump over enemies then punch the ground to shock them...only the system doesn\'t recognize 70% of the times you\'ve jumped over the enemy.  The game isn\'t broken or buggy mind you - it\'s just inconsistent physics and game mechanic performance.  It\'s essentially like hitting the gas in a car and not knowing how much acceleration to expect.  Basically, one of the games biggest selling points is one of it\'s weakest area of performance.  The game also encourages you to explore, yet - despite all of the acrobatic skill trees you\'re encouraged to develop - scaling the walls and mountains is entirely unpredictable.  Some you can cross, some you can not.  This makes tracking down your in-game chores by traversing large swaths of the game\'s maps - and they do feel like chores - incredibly difficult.  You never know when you can hop a mountain range, and when you\'re expected to hoof it. This leads to extensive 15 - 20 minute detours of areas you\'ve already been in.  It\'s not encouraging exploration, it\'s just artificially inflating gameplay time. That brings up the other problem: this game is seriously repetitive.  The soundtrack is bad enough, with less than 10 arrangements making up 80% of the soundtrack (if that doesn\'t sound bad, just wait till you\'re hearing the \'fight engagement\' theme for the 10,000th time).  What\'s worse though is the thing I was pretty excited about - your character Frey and the wristband Cuff bantering about.  They have about 12 minutes of 20-second conversations that loop ad nauseum throughout the game.  The first time you hear an exchange between the two, you will probably enjoy the writing.  The twentieth time Cuff is asking if everyone left because you annoyed them, you want to find out how such a simple part of the game could get so messed up.    That\'s just the audio though.  The game itself fails hard compared to games like Far Cry, Skyrim, and Mass Effect - TRUE AAA games.  They make repeating missions each feel unique and interesting.  Here, you\'re just doing chores on repeat, just with different skinned monsters to fight (something like 20 creatures, 3 skins each, with 10 attack patterns between them) across the games 8 major environment shifts (across 4 regions).Lastly, I\'d call out the project manager exclusively: They did a terrible job of balancing the game, the mechanics, the consistency of the game-play and difficulty, and even the flow between the \'quest\' mode and what are called \'detours\'.  The detours are meant to add to the story, and are written well enough. At the same time, the pacing is like walking through a gelatin desert. Repetitive & inconsistent, Forspoken is irritatingly addictive.  Despite having likely required the investment of any other AAA game release, no one should purchase Forspoken for more than $25 (US) in order to avoid rewarding poor game design and project management.  Ultimately, Forspoken is the reason why STEAM needs to have a 4-tier rating system rather than two (I\'d give it one thumb up rather than a negative downvote).  I won\'t say don\'t buy it, but DEFINITELY don\'t pay full price.',''),(2449,'Once upon a time, Square Enix crafted worlds that whisked us away from reality. Now, with \"Forspoken,\" they\'ve given us a protagonist who makes us wish we could escape back to our own world.Enter Frey Holland: a New Yorker who stumbles into the magical realm of Athia. But instead of embracing her hero\'s journey, Frey seems more interested in a self-absorbed monologue about her childhood traumas. You\'d think being teleported to a fantasy world would broaden one\'s horizons, but no, Frey is as introspective as a mirror in a dark room.IGN hits the nail on the head, describing the game as a \"generic RPG with bland story and repetitive combat\"​​. They forgot to mention how Frey\'s constant navel-gazing turns every potential epic moment into a therapy session.It\'s like watching a modern-day Narcissus, but instead of a pond, she\'s got an entire magical world at her feet. PCMag points out the game would\'ve been passable a decade ago​​. Perhaps back then, we had lower standards for character development.The world of Athia is visually striking, but it’s wasted on a protagonist more interested in her own inner turmoil than the wonders around her. GamesRadar+ calls it an \"exceptionally middling experience\"​​, and they\'re being generous, especially for a game from Square. It\'s like being on a guided tour of paradise led by someone who can\'t stop talking about their bad day at work.Then there\'s the combat. GameSpot mentions the \"boring combat, poor characterization, and loose movement\"​​. If only Frey showed as much enthusiasm in her battles as she does in her self-pity, we might have had something exciting.In a time where she could\'ve been a beacon of hope or change, Frey chooses instead to wallow in self-reflection. PC Gamer suggests the game could have been excellent if it tried a little harder​​. Sadly, the same could be said about its main character.\"Forspoken\" had the potential to be a magical journey of growth and discovery. Instead, it’s a missed opportunity, bogged down by a protagonist whose self-centeredness is as vast as the world she fails to appreciate. Square Enix, we remember the days when your games inspired awe and wonder. Now, it seems, the only spell you\'ve cast is one of disillusionment.Based on prior reviews, I waited for it to be on sale. After playing it, I\'m not sure i\'d recommend it if it were free bonus content for an actual good game. In most other cases, I\'d say storage is cheap, but in this case, save the drive space.',''),(2450,'So, this is a difficult one. I\'m currently at arournd 11 hours of ingame time and haven\'t finished the game yet but I wanted to write a review anyway to share my thoughts and help people to decide whether or not to buy this game or avoid it. As you can see I do recommend the game, however there are different things that I put into consideration.But let\'s start with the negative points first. If you take into consideration that Square Enix who also created Life\'s Strange and a few other really good games, it\'s understandable if you\'re a bit disappointed. Which takes me to the next point. The game is priced at 80$ which is a ridiculous pricepoint for any game and I don\'t think I have ever seen a AAA Game at a pricetag this high without including any DLC\'s or Expansions. I have read other reviews of this game and people were complaining about how empty the Overworld is and boring the story. While playing I was sort of able to understand where the frustration came from, however I do not fully agree with that, more to that later. I believe that the difficulty setting only affects the enemies hp bar and not the difficulty of the fight itself. Which causes the fights to take longer and causing them to get tedious to some extend.But that\'s about it for the negative points. Let\'s get to the positive ones and the reason why I did end up recommending the game. The story itself is surprisingly good and the conversations between the main character and her \'companion\' are honestly hilarious and I personally love the sarcasm aspect. While the world is sort of unspectacular there are quite a lot of fights even if they\'re just 200 (overexaggerated) normal boring enemies or sometimes more challenging ones. So unless the people who were complaining simply ran from story point to story point without doing anything besides that I do not agree with their statement of the the overwolrd being extremely empty and boring. The graphic, although it looks like a game made for consoles, is actually beautiful, all you have to do is get used to the chosen graphical style. If playing the game you HAVE to play it on a controller as it\'s unplayable on MnK but when doing so the controls feel good and well thought out. The game has CATS! So that\'s a big plus and you can even pet them. The UI actually looks good, I really loke the color scheme they went for and the ability effects are also pretty neat.That\'s it for the positive aspects that\'re worth mentioning about this game and I\'m ending this review with my final thoughts.If I had bought the game at it\'s normal price tag then there is no way I would\'ve been able to recommend it, however I bought it during the autumn sale for around 30$ and that\'s the reason of my current recommendation status. The other part that is sort of bothering me is, that  it feels like this game was meant to be a more story focussed one (such as Life\'s Strange or Tomb Raider) and is sort of trying too hard to be open world to match the current trend AAA games are headed towards (even though it doesn\'t even need to be that) hence why the world is not as special compared to the world of The Witcher 3 or Assassin\'s Creed Odyssey. But it\'s still a good game and I do enjoy the time I\'ve spend playing it and I will continue to play the game and finish it\'s story. One last thing, the game could really be more optimised than it currently is, as I sometimes have frame drops below 60fps on a 4090 at only 2k resolution.I hope this review was able to help you choose whether to buy or avoid this game and if it did I\'m glad I was able to help with that!',''),(2451,'This game is absolute trash. How is it that a game that has been ported to pc gets zero support from square enix. I can\'t even play the game because the camera is just spinning non stop. I got the game refunded. it is really sad because the graphics look pretty cool no mater how woke the story is.',''),(2452,'Important note: I bought this at 60% discount.So, I think why this game flopped as hard as it did was the frankly absurd base price compared to the quality it offers. But if you pay 30 euros for it, suddenly it\'s actually quite good and I\'m much more likely to be forgiving.I can indeed confirm what other reviewers are saying, that the combat is really good and the rest is bad. Well... I wouldn\'t say \"bad\", more like... awkward. It\'s awkwardly paced, awkwardly written, awkward camera angles and cinematics etc etc. Stuff that you would forgive in an indie game, but not in a game that asks for 70 euros.It\'s a shame, because a sequel with a lot of polish and a bit tighter focus would have probably been amazing, but I heard that the studio has been axed, so... that\'s corporate greed for you, I guess.',''),(2453,'So much potential but terrible in execution:Protagonist is so whiny and annoying. You just can\'t gel with her or her decisions.Combat works but could have been so much betterBut... the performance and bugs! FPS drops are constant and sound is just broken (voice drops for certain chars, echoey sounds, distortion).Even moving to cut scenes is terrible... so jarring it breaks immersion.Story is ok and will keep you entertained for about 20 hours.Game does support ultra wide screen and HDR so that\'s nice.Summary - if they can fix the bugs and performance it\'s worth 15-20 quid in the steam sales.',''),(2454,'Not the best game ever, but way better than most people make it seem. I enjoyed it, though i did need a really powerfull PC to actually enjoy the incredible visuals and while the World does seem somewhat empty, i actually liked the atmosphere and the story.',''),(2455,'great visuals and animation BUT hollow world and unlike able characters',''),(2456,'Enjoyable game; reminiscent of Horizon: Zero Dawn, though H:ZD is a superior game.  I was hesitant - I\'m not usually a huge fan of games where parkour is a huge component.  But I\'m glad I stuck with it.  The story is decently compelling, and had at least one twist I didn\'t see coming.  The gameplay, once you master the parkour, is fast - I beat the game in 37 hours, though I did a fairly straight run with few side quests.  Note that it\'s not clear, when you\'re progressing, that some side quests (called detours in the game) will become unavailable if you don\'t finish them by a certain point.  There are warnings when you\'re moving to the next chapter, but they doesn\'t communicate clearly the consequences of that - and the guides I referenced on line generally spoke of quests being available \"after completing ______,\" but not of availability ending.  Combat is fast paced and reasonably fun.  It took me a while to get the hang of switching between magic systems, but once I did, that made the combet lively and interesting.  Complaints:  I feel like the first two (of twelve) chapters are essentially tutorials, and they drag a bit.  The video sequences aren\'t as engaging as they might be, and there are a LOT in chapter one.  I almost gave up because I felt like I was watching an interactive movie!  But it\'s worth it to wait through all that.  The last two chapters are similar, especially chapter 11.  Those video sequences could REALLY stand to be tightened up!  They got interminable after a while.  Talky-talky-talky ... that information didn\'t need to take ungodly long to impart.  But overall, the game was worth both the purchase price and the time.  Recommended, if you like games of this sort.',''),(2457,'So, I do overall recommend this game(When it\'s on sale absolutely not for $70), it\'s actually fun when the game just let\'s you play and leaves you alone, however, Frey is the worst game protagonist of all time. She never gets better, she is selfish and awful the entire game. I recommend reducing in game chatter to low or off, and just kind of dealing with Frey. The journey is rather predictable but pretty satisfying to see the closure. It can be completed in about 18 hours. One of the ending cutscenes isn\'t in engine, it\'s like sort of pre-rended and looks like a youtube video with bad compression and I just found that funny. FSR3 is cool tech and the game looks nice and utilizes it well.Tl;drGame funFrey badDon\'t pay full price.',''),(2458,'i will say the main issue with the game is Frey\'s voice acting and her character as a whole. She is unbearable and annoying. The gameplay itself if fun but gets bogged down by constant comments by Frey and she is mega cringe with her Marvelesque quips. I give it a thumbs up just for the gameplay and combat system. The movement and freedom are also a plus. Overall not as bad as when it came out. definitely get it when it\'s on sale i wouldn\'t pay more than $40 for this',''),(2459,'I got the game on sale, but bookmarked it on release. Hesitant as the reviews were so negative, instead I am enjoying myself. Full price would have been dicey, but this is a massive game with plenty to do and things to blast.Somehow Fable springs to mind, positive energy story, and plenty of monsters  to slay at not too hard a difficulty.  So great for a few spare hours of relaxed exploring.',''),(2460,'All this game and the controversy surrounding it proves to me is that mob mentality is a strong force. The overall story and presentation kind of reminds me of a fantasy made-for-tv movie but for this it works in it\'s favour. The only issue I had coming from the demo was that the quips and banter between the characters in the open world would become grating, but after a few hours it was fine. It kind of reminded me of the repetitiveness of Ordis from Warframe. Also to be honest the dialogue in general being described as over the top cringy is a little ironic looking back on it. The way the lines were delivered had almost exactly the same energy as the majority of the current era marvel films and I don\'t see anybody complaining about them. The music was great, and fit the story pretty well. I would say Frey\'s theme was by far my favourite and hearing the motif show up through most of the in-game music definitely made me feel a little emotional at times. There were a few negative points though. For some reason the sky textures looked horrendous no matter what I put the settings on and took me out of the game a couple times. Everything else was textured fine but then there would be this eyesore every time I looked up. About the only story point I would change is maybe the length of time they try to keep Frey\'s selfishness story beat going.Performance wise I can\'t say too much as I\'m currently using a 4070ti. It gets me about 75-80 FPS average on 3440x1440 with ultra settings, DLSS Quality and the extra Raytracing settings and about 80 without. Honestly though the Fidelity FX and raytracing options aren\'t worth the performance hitStory length to side content ratio is a little wonky. I would have liked to have either the story a little longer (which probably would hurt it to be honest as it feels like it would end up with quite a bit filler content), or for there to be either less, but more meaningful side content to balance everything out.Open world wise I enjoy going out and seeing all the landmarks and getting equipment but the Mana collection system is definitely not something I enjoy. Getting mana just through levels or having a wide range vacuum for them that didn\'t have a cooldown would\'ve been a real help and would\'ve fixed some of the monotony. Also, too many spells. I think perhaps they should have followed the 5 or so abilities for each damage type like FFXVI. It would have made the combat a little more focused.*UPDATEAfter getting all the achievements I can say the side content is incredibly out of proportion. expect up to 20 hours of storyline with some occasional sidetracking but 30-40 extra for open world/ side content. I wouldn\'t suggest doing anything beyond the story/DLC unless you\'re a dedicated completionist.*Long story short, the majority of people who are dog-piling on the game at this point usually have an inability to think for themselves and fail to see things objectively. Ultimately you can decide whether you like the game or not, but don\'t let others make your decision for you. It\'s definitely not $114.95 AUD good, but if you can get it on sale for under $60, it\'s worth a try.',''),(2461,'It\'s a really good game. Not sure what others are talking about. The worst part is the UI, but that can probably be attributed rushed timelines so I\'ll knock half a point off for that.Everything else is more or less excellent. The world it is set in is huge and fantastically beautiful. AAA quality graphics and gameplay that is essentially 4D Sonic.',''),(2462,'Not the best, but way better than people make it seem. Enjoyed it, though it gets better once you get more skills to play with.',''),(2463,'Refunded because the camera kept spinning and looking up. It looked great but was unfortunately unplayable as I need to be able to look where im going without spinning.',''),(2464,'The banter between cuff and the main character can get tire some but over all i quite enjoy playing this game.',''),(2465,'Ill recommend this on sale, the story is mediocre with lots of plot holes and uneventful things... You dont need to fight any of the enimies on the way.. there is no reason to. Most of the extra objectives are worthless as well. Basically there is no reason to do anything except main objective and the store is just not there for a great game. The side stuff is 100% boring.... there is only one or two times they send you out for anything slightly story related. Dont buy it unless its like 20$. Just not worth it really :/ suck.',''),(2466,'graphics dont even load properly ♥♥♥♥ ass game',''),(2467,'pretty fun gameplay main character annoying af writing also not the best',''),(2468,'And now, developers from Teyon, we are waiting from you a great FPS in the Blade Runner universe! :D',''),(2469,'I think robocop movie is good, I think robocop game is good. in fact, both are very good',''),(2470,'A good game for people that want some 80\'s and 90\'s Robocop nostalgia and for fans of Robocop in general.Its a straightforward FPS game set in the universe of Robocop. You play as Robocop and they have the sound effects and movement down to a tea. They also have the original voice of Robocop which is a nice touch. I would compare this game to the Terminator:Resistance game. Both fantastic for the nostalgia elements and fan base of either Robocop or Terminator. But the game itself isn\'t that well optimised and I personally don\'t think it is worth the £45 asking price. But you do get a solid 15+ hour story and campaign and a lot of fun. Just don\'t expect this game to be like a solid AAA FPS game. It isn\'t. I think most of the positive reviews are based on the nostalgic elements to the game, as opposed to the actual gameplay itself, but I had a good time in any case. For achievement hunters it is a very easy and straightforward 100% with nothing missable and the options to replay missions from certain points after completion.',''),(2471,'I like the game, but this comes with a huge caveat Aside from some minor performance issues I\'m happy with the opening of this title. It sets the scene well, it is very 80\'s retro-futuristic. Acting seems suitably camp, decent humour and the gameplay, while nothing groundbreaking, is perfectly fine.But this comes with a big negative.The game has no manual saving. That is fine in itself if autosaves were regular, such as time based, or picking up items, or starting/completing quests etc.But they are not. It appears to be on new area only. That means you could easily be forced to play for several hours between saves. Terminator included a half decent time based autosave as well as terminals here and there where a manual save can be dropped.Why not here? It is 2023, why have such a stupid autosave system?Heaven forbid real life gets in the way of playing a video game.Manual saving, if only in free roam and not in instanced missions, would simultaneously be a basic quality of life inclusion and an incredible addition.Quite honestly I am close to refunding, even if I do think the game is decent. I do not want to be at the whims of a video game dictating when I can and cannot shut it off without losing potentially hours of progress.Lack of manual saving is fine if autosaving is well implemented, and in this title it really isn\'t.Thumbs up for the game, but considering a refund because honestly that is such a poor mechanics choice.Edit: Putting in for a refund.I\'ve slept on it and yeah, putting in for a refund.Why? As enjoyable as I can tell the game is, even within the first 90 minutes, I really don\'t want to be held hostage (so to speak) in regards when I can and cannot switch the game off.It is such a simple and ridiculous oversight to not have better Autosaving Checkpoints if the game is void of a Manual Save function.Whether the zones are large or small I want to explore. I want to bumble around and look at the level design, all the little nods and jokes. I want to stumble across subquests, I want to take in the atmosphere. You cannot do that if you are constantly checking to see if the game is saved. As small as the world may be it is highly detailed and I just cannot freely explore it if you are pushed from checkpoint to checkpoint because you are afraid \"Real Life\" could get in the way any moment. Losing anywhere between 20 to 60 minutes worth of progress because I took my time to sight-see isn\'t an attractive prospect.The game itself is great, if you personally can work to the checkpoints you\'ll enjoy it. I can\'t guarantee my play sessions will suit the game, so yeah, requesting refund.Will pick this up again if they add in a basic quality of life improvement that has been built into  games since before Super Mario World on the SNES; the ability to save at will, or the reassurance of regular autosaving.',''),(2472,'Story:- Sticks with the original concepts of man vs. machine dilemma, juggling what\'s right vs. what\'s political convenient, and humanizes main characters and side characters. A- Full of choices, many of which have substantial impacts on story outcome. A+- Great time strolling down memory lane from RC1 and RC2.Gameplay:- Auto-9 comes with unlimited ammo and is as powerful as it looks in the movies. A+- Hearing the Auto-9 shoot is like hearing the singing of the angels. A+- Customizing the Auto-9 into something even more powerful is BA. A++- Hidden side objectives are easy to miss and revealed after the level when players cannot go back to get. C- Shooting baddies is just satisfying every time. A+- No NewGame+ mode to continue on with all your perks, boards, and chips, but you have almost all the perk points you\'ll need anyway to make the end boss a breeze if played right. B- Over-the-top gore (but in a comic book style) stays true to Verhoeven\'s original masterpiece. A+- The voice acting will make players want to turn the Auto-9 onto themselves, so C-, but... Peter Weller reprises his role as the voice of Robocop, so adjusted to A-.Fan Service:- Everything everyone loved about the first two movies is in here.  So many callbacks, throwbacks, easter eggs, and good memories.  It\'s like playing through a sequel to the first two movies, but it\'s rated R and doesn\'t suck. A+OVERALL GRADE: A - 9/10; would again buy that for a dollar.',''),(2473,'Jesus had days like this.',''),(2474,'As a 90s kids, Robocop getting his own proper, full-blown game in 2023 is a beautiful thing to see. This game is actually very fun and quite well done overall. I was pulled in from the first mission and have about 8 hours into this game so far across three play sessions. The gameplay is a bit simple, it\'s mostly a first person shooter but with some RPG elements for leveling up. You have your primary story missions which take 30-60 minutes on average to complete one. There is also quite a bit of side content that is also very well done and detailed, it doesn\'t feel tacked-on at all. I have enjoyed every one of the side-missions that I have played so far.The story takes place after the first Robocop film, and he is still dealing with various glitches in his programming as a subsequent result of being still somewhat human, despite being treated as if he is nothing more than a machine by OCP (the amoral corporation that owns the police, somehow, in this dystopian retro-future version of Detroit in the 1980s (or possibly 1990s, not sure which). Ultimately, the writing seems to be serviceable so far. Don\'t expect AAA-level writing and character development, but they do a good job building upon what was already in place from the first Robocop movie.I like to also touch on the technical aspects of a game when I review them, this one is pretty sound in the regard. Just be sure to understand that this game is using Unreal Engine 5, making use of Lumen (software-based ray tracing) for Global Illumination and Reflections (although Screen Space Reflections are used also), Nanite and Virtual Shadow Maps. My point is that the game is somewhat heavy, like all UE5 titles but visual fidelity is quite striking. Performance is pretty good on my desktop PC (System Specs on my Profile if you care). I have even completed a few levels on my Steam Deck, although I would not recommend buying this game if that is your only way to play it. You have to set everything to low, set FSR/TSR/XeSS upscaling to Balanced mode and you still aren\'t always at 30FPS. There are also some graphical glitches like characters appearing to be missing teeth and something weird with the normal maps on character models\' faces, it looks like something is wrong with their skin. This only happens on my Steam Deck, not my Windows PC. I don’t think that this is really a reflection of Teyon’s work, it’s just that the Steam Deck isn’t really fit for purpose when it comes to running the newest games striving for photorealism, they comes with a relatively demanding cost in terms of the necessary hardware to get a good experience. WARNING- Cloud Saves appear to be not working, I hope Teyon/Nacon fix this, because it is really annoying for people with multiple ways to play their Steam games. I\'m still gonna recommend this game but that could change later on if they don\'t patch it to support cloud saves later.',''),(2475,'It\'s impressive how much Teyon has improved since their attempt at a Rambo video game, which had to be among the worst video games of that decade. They showed a lot of improvement with their Terminator adaptation and have become even better now with this version of RoboCop, which pays a lot of homage to fans of the franchise and, surprisingly, actually stays accurate to the source material. And I bought this video game solely because it seemed to stay true to the roots of RoboCop. Yes, RoboCop is actually unapologetically white male as he should be. There\'s none of those blatant woke tropes that we often see in modern productions these days where people have to virtue signal every time you walk around a corner or load into a new cutscene. As they like to say, it feels good to be represented for once.The game is just pure fun and carnage as video games should be. Minor destructible environments such as being able to chip away at pillars, lots of gore which is reminiscent to the bloody mess that was the F.E.A.R franchise, and even a morality system where prominent NPCs will actually remember actions that you make or dialogue that you choose in response. There\'s a lot of content which surprised me, as I thought this was going to be a very short video game and that it might be too overpriced at $50 USD. It is still kind of short, though, so for a lot of people, $50 USD full price might seem too steep of a price tag for a singleplayer video game. But somewhere around 50 quests, split somewhat evenly between main missions and side missions? A fun RPG system that allows you to invest points into a character build as well as being able to upgrade your pistol efficiency? And a semi-open world where you have a lot of opportunity for exploration and easter egg hunting? That\'s pretty good for a AA video game title.You don\'t need to spend the extra $12 USD or so on the current DLC as these are just cosmetic packs, but I\'d recommend doing so just to support these developers in their journey to AAA status, as Robocop is a step in the right direction and I am holding onto hope that they can only continue to go up ever since their Rambo video game. On a sale? It\'s worth the buy even more so, especially for shooter game fans and Robocop fans in general. Maybe a Judge Dredd video game can be next.Things to dislike:-While I love the gunplay and the gore, the ragdolls need massive improvement. It is not at all realistic to the degree that you\'d find from games like Red Dead Redemption and Grand Theft Auto. Corpses are constantly contorted in an unrealistic way. I love ragdoll physics but the physics here are immersion breaking.-The psychology path in the skill tree needs reworking. It is fundamentally useless and a waste of points currently. Unless it was just bugged for me. I almost always focus on maximizing the skills that allows me access to more dialogue choices such as with Fallout, but with this game, you don\'t actually need to do anything but put two points into it to access ALL special dialogue choices, which are very minimal. I think I did every quest and talked to as many NPCs as I could find and I only remember seeing around three or so special \"psychology\" dialogue choices. It sounds important when you are researching the skills tab, but it truly isn\'t. As of now, I don\'t think there\'s any way to reset skills points, either. Which also needs to be added as it\'s become the norm in modern gaming for players to be given the freedom to explore different builds without needing to restart from the very beginning.-There needs to be a \"new game+\" mode so that people can re-experience the video game with the skills that they\'ve unlocked. Otherwise, XP needs to be given in greater values so that you level up more before the conclusion of the video game. There simply isn\'t enough to do in this game to maximize all of your character\'s skills. Crime evidence is littered throughout the maps, for example, and gives you a point value for collecting it but for many areas of the game, these points are redundant unless you have the quest for collecting a certain amount of crime evidence items, and this side quest doesn\'t exist in every map. I\'d suggest converting the arbitrary points value of these items into XP points instead. It\'d encourage players to find more of the secrets as well, because those stashes are otherwise pointless to look for since you are not actually being rewarded for it. -The music isn\'t all that great, especially during some of the more action packed sequences of the game. You\'d expect something way better than what they used. Something to get you pumped as a robotic cop dispensing deathly justice to all of the criminals and thugs. The music here seemed more like something you\'d hear from a Spider-Man game as you are swinging around the city or something. It\'s more peaceful, relaxing music rather than something that you\'d expect to play during a major boss battle.-The game needs a manual save feature or better auto-saving. I had to quit playing at some point and when I came back to it, I was like 10+ minutes behind from where I signed out. I can only imagine how far back you can go if you actually die. -Difficulty is a bit too easy, but that\'s just a personal gripe. Even on expert mode, I only died twice. And both instances were not even to the bosses, but because I was distracted by something else going on around me and looked away from my HP bar momentarily. Other than that, I really did enjoy the 14 or so hours I put into the game. I got all of the achievements in that time frame, and playing it on an easier difficulty probably means that you can beat it even faster so take that as you will for its price tag.',''),(2476,'A must-have for any 90\'s kid. Now do Dredd.',''),(2477,'Honestly not sure why it has such good reviews. Flat voice acting. Boring dialogue. Extremely tedious combat, insofar as I got to experience it - because it crashed nearly constantly. It took a huge amount of wrangling just to get to the point where a mission broke because... I have no idea why. An action just wouldn\'t complete. Got tired of it at that point. Hopefully can still refund - most of the \"two hours\" was repeatedly crashing, I\'ve barely touched it.',''),(2478,'Looking for a decent movie between Robocop 2 and Robocop 3? Look no further than RoboCop: Rogue City. The game got the whole spirit and feel of the original movie and put a good gameplay on this.  There are some rough edges, but all in all, a very good shooter with some RPG elements. For RoboCop fans a very clear and definitive buy.',''),(2479,'Great game.. Finally a basic shooter, not  some Fortnite, 12 year old addicted to aderall nonsense. Just a straight shooter basically putting you into the movie as RoboCop.',''),(2480,'I\'d buy this game even if it\'s not for a dollar. 8/10',''),(2481,'AA games deserve to exist alongside AAA games and indie developed projects, and Robocop Rogue City is the best example of a fun AA game done right, and for a popular IP, done tastefully for the fans and newcomers alike.I recommend this game, and I hope to see DLC in the future!',''),(2482,'Played about 12 hours so far. If you like the original RoboCop, which I do, this game is very faithful to the source material. I will say that it is much easier to play with keyboard/mouse than with a controller, and I do wish you could manual save, but the game is a lot of fun and I hope this company continues to make faithful adaptations of other sources.',''),(2483,'Fantastic game which captures Robocop perfectly.As following Terminator: Resistance which was a great Terminator Game, these devs know how to make these 80\'s film classics come to life, giving the sense of being there with all the old cast and more.Being Robo in the neighborhood, chilling and doing some different missions is nice and the cozy mood music sets the tone. Peter Weller is Great.Would save cat 10/10 again.Recommended',''),(2484,'TLDR - Game\'s good. Buy it.They say, that the reason that I\'m not entranced with video games the same way I used to is that I\'ve gotten older. I just have more things to spend my spare time on. They say, games are simply not as interesting to mature adults with responsibilities. Mature adults with responsibilities live in the \"now\", not in some fantasy fairy tale.Well, this game proves them wrong. The contrast between Robocop and recent(ish) \"big\" games from \"AAA studios\" made me really question what modern gamedev has become. All these garbage games get presented in a pretty wrapper - and when you don\'t enjoy it - it\'s YOUR fault. You\'re the one that changed.It\'s not the endless grind for some random amount of whatever; it\'s not the superficial plotline or the boring fetch quests; it\'s not the collecting of a million somethings all around the map to get an achievement, that no one cares about; it\'s certainly not our f*cking in-game store, where you can buy a pretty picture for something that was intentionaly made plain. And it gets repeated so often, that you actually start to believe it. After Baldur\'s Gate 3 released they all whined \"oh, but we can\'t compete with that, look at how much time they spent on it...\". Well, maybe that\'s how it supposed to be? ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥, they should at least try! And it looks to me like this relatively small gamedev actually did try.Yeah, it crashed on me acouple of times. Yes, the lines are cheesy af. And yes, I\'ve rolled my eyes quite a bit at the plot, especially towards the end. The first time I started to robo-walk somewhere I couldn\'t believe they dared to release a game in 2023, where you are forced to walk THAT. F*CKING. SLOW.But release it they did. And you know what? I had fun.You walk into a mob of enemies and pull the trigger. Heads explode spectacularly. Blood all over the place. Polish it with a cheesy robo-line. Continue. Rinse. Repeat. But for some reason you don\'t tire of it. There are many variations of ugprades for Robocop\'s pistol. It can be made into a proverbial Super-Deagle or a full-auto SMG. It has infinite ammo. It kicks ass. There are different uprades for the Robocop - perks to give abilities or boost specs. They\'re cool. There are different weapons you can pick up from the enemies. Midgame and later you don\'t need them - your pistol is the sh*t.The small side-quests you get to do, the secondary characters you get to shape, locations that don\'t seem like it\'s all the one same place (even when it is, lol), the ridiculous sh*t npcs sometimes say - it all somehow adds up into a very engaging experience...And now, that you\'ve read to down here - if you\'re still with me - I\'ve never seen a single Robocop movie :D ... But I absolutely adored this game.Yeah, maybe it isn\'t the polished triple-A experience, that we are so used to nowadays. But, perhaps, it shouldn\'t be? It\'s simply good the way it is, flaws and all.I guess that\'s what really brought on my existential mid-life venting - Robocop ignores quite a bit of mordern gamedev concepts. But, right off you can tell, that these guys had put their hearts into the game - and, suprisingly, it turns out, that that\'s enough.A rare gem in a sea of soulless trash.',''),(2485,'I\'m not even invested in the Robocop franchise, I still had a really good time in this game. While there are some negatives, over all the game is really good.GraphicsGraphics are a bit mixed but good most of the time. They really did nail the look and moves of Robocop. Happened twice that the framerate almost grinded to a halt while playing. Had to restart the game to fix it. Facial animations look a bit stiff but it looks ok. The reflections on the ground look weird on the wet asphalt. If you move your mouse in a circle while the asphalt is visible you will see what I mean. The reflections will get this weird white noise but will start calming down once you stop moving your mouse, it\'s like the ground is anxious or something.MissionsMostly they were good and entertaining. What bothered me the most is that they put you in a smaller sandbox with a main objective and expect you to stomp around all over town to find all other hidden side objectives, they expect you to do this multiple times in the same sandbox as well. Imagine going back to the police station and getting \"You didn\'t save the hostages\". What hostages? No one called the cops? At least give me an area to investigate so I don\'t miss stuff like this by mistake. Later in the game the citizens have no problem calling the cops and asking for help. Why couldn\'t they ask for help earlier in the game?DifficultyPlayed this game on hard and most of the time the game was kind of easy. There was a very distinguished difficulty spike with a boss (first time you meet ed 209), except for that It mostly felt like I was OP. If you are used to playing on hard I would recommend playing on harder difficulty.WeaponsThe gun you get is really good, you get to mod it etc. While the modding wasn\'t very intuitive to begin with you get used to it quickly. My biggest issue is the way you combine circuits and just get random stuff. Can be really annoying when you want a part that is shaped in a certain way and the RNG just never gives it to you.Some of the effects are a bit confusing too. I picked an upgrade that was supposed to give me \"MASSIVE DAMAGE\" but it also resulted me in getting a penalty of 20%. So was this a good or bad thing?The stats look worse and the \"MASSIVE DAMAGE\" doesn\'t really show up anywhere. Well, I got \"MASSIVE DAMAGE\" so it was worth it but it wasn\'t clear.What about other weapons? Didn\'t really feel like it was worth using other weapons. I used some early on but it didn\'t feel like it was worth picking any up since your starter gun gets really good with upgrades. You also need to constantly pick up ammo and you can only have about 2 mags on you for the other weapon.Think I will just use my gun with infinite ammo and press down left mouse instead.Might sound negative but again, I had a really good time with this game. It\'s so nice being able to play single player games like it\'s the early 2000 again. Really surprised haven\'t heard more about this game.Another thing I have to give this game is the destructibility of the environment. Feels really nice seeing an area transform into a war zone.EDIT:This is after viewing all Robocop movies. This is like an alternative timeline in the Robocop franchise with the exclusion from the 2014 movie (reboot) and most inspiration coming from Robocop 1 and 2 (the best ones).They made something new but it still feels like it stays true to the source material without stepping on fans feet which can be a very hard thing to do now. I know people have complained about the gun sound but it didn\'t really bother me that much. They have of course made some changes, for example they didn\'t replicate the terrible uncanny valley face animations from the evil robot in robocop 2 (which is a good thing).I can appreciate the game much more now after watching robocop 1 and 2. This is a great re-imagination of an old franchise in form of a game.',''),(2486,'Incredible experience and immersion in the RoboCop world. I had a ton of fun and laughs with the side and main quests, there was never a dull moment. Hoping we eventually get a new game plus with more fun side quests, maybe RoboCop will get to adopt a cat. I was really rooting for RoboCop to get a kiss at the end. Anyhow fantastic job by the devs!',''),(2487,'There are a few shortcomings, in an entire playthrough I had 3 crashes, there\'s no dedicated button to spin your pistol, that\'s about it. The gameplay is fun, blowing bad guys to pieces, on the hard difficulty it was a bit challenging. Extremely faithful to the original series and story, it\'s very refreshing to see a game not desecrate a beloved retro franchise and instead give it an absolute best effort, faithful modern new entry. It really felt like it\'s own Robocop movie in addition to being a game. Solid 8/10',''),(2488,'\"I\'m a shape shifterAt Poe\'s masqueradeHiding both face and mindAll free for you to draw\"It only took me an hour to fall in love with it',''),(2489,'Take a shot every time someone says \"For real?\"Take two if Ryuji says itYou will die',''),(2490,'Before I played This Game... I had a small wee wee, no friends, no girlfriend, depression and absolutely no will to live. None of these things have changed, but the game is pretty good.',''),(2491,'Just finished the game with roughly 110 hours of playtime. 8.5/10. The story (especially in English) isn\'t as mature/dark as I expected it to be, but it does a pretty good job delivering some scenes for the main story. However side content could feel a little flat/uninteresting even though it was cool interacting with the characters. Despite it feeling like a Saturday morning cartoon at times, I\'d give the story a 7~/10.That being said, this game just, really f*cking cool. It makes generally uninteresting things like commuting, texting in a group chat, and even opening an umbrella feel buttery-f*cking-smooth. The UI, the music, just playing this game feels really good. Vibes get a 10/10.Combat feels really good, and even though I find turn-based combat generally kinda boring, the music, visuals and strategy needed for some bosses easily make up for it. Combat\'s an easy 9/10.',''),(2492,'Just finished the tutorial',''),(2493,'Persona 5 Royal - One Hell Of An Experience Persona 5 Royal is definitely one of my favorite games of all time, I fell in love with it\'s amazing visuals, addicting gameplay, memorable characters and the gold mine which is the soundtrack itself. The story is pretty enjoyable although it has its ups and downs but when it hits hard, it hits hard. The whole game is like a rollercoaster, you just hop on it and enjoy the ride. Overview You play as Ren Amamiya (or the MC which you can name him however you want), who got falsely convicted of a crime, ends up with a one-year probation sentence and had to move to Tokyo to attend at Shujin Academy. However, you awaken your powers which is called \"Persona\", you and your friends use your new powers to try changing society for the better. The Story Is it life-changing? No.Is it long? Yes, it is kinda dragged on a bit but the game does a great job at sucking you into it\'s world and characters, you won\'t feel that the game is long because you are having fun and enjoying the game.Is it entertaining? Yup. The Gameplay The gameplay consists of you going to school to live a normal student life and dungeon-crawling.I love that the game\'s version of going outside and touching grass is pretty freaking entertaining which makes you want to forget about the real world. Like say, your friends invite you to go out for a drink and you say that you’re busy, but you’re actually playing P5R and you want to hang out with your pal Ryuji instead.The dungeons are well made, except for THAT one dungeon of course.The combat is turn-based and some of you may don’t like it, but honestly it is pretty damn fun. It’s like pokemon where you deal more damage by hitting the enemy’s weaknesses, but you knock the enemies all down by doing that and perform a stylish beatdown afterwards. I want to say more about the combat but it is best that you experience it for yourself.The soundtrack is incredible and it is a work of art. Some of my favorite tracks are Life Will Change, Beneath The Mask, Rivers in the Desert and I Believe. What The Royal Version Offers - Quality of life changes (pretty good)- A new dungeon which consists an extra 20 hours of playtime- 2 brand new characters with new story too- One new location- New activities Conclusion The game is amazing, and you should give it a try if you have the chance. In fact, it is on sale for 50% off right now which is a good price not gonna lie.So yeah, that’s all I have to say.',''),(2494,'Can\'t date Akechi Pancakes Goro 1/10',''),(2495,'The most incredibly profound and awe inspiring work of art I have ever had the pleasure of experiencing in my entire life. This ♥♥♥♥ is what makes life worth living, and makes it suck ♥♥♥♥ once it\'s over.',''),(2496,'If you want to enjoy this game, you might want to avoid this in your first playthrough:- The Wikia- The Persona fandom- Letting people know that you are playing this game- Searching anything related to Persona on Youtube- The BritishFailure to avoid any of the aforementioned will result in SPOILERS, and this is a pretty long game. Sob sob.',''),(2497,'Persona 4 Is Better',''),(2498,'As satisfying as P4',''),(2499,'Absolutely reccomended. The story, charachters, gameplay, music and performances are phenomenal! This game has both style and substance and worth all the hours that are put into finishing and completing it. Played the original versio years ago when it fist came out and I thought was really nice but after playing this one I actually fell in love.',''),(2500,'delicious pancakes',''),(2501,'good game but met too many kamoshida method actors in the fandom',''),(2502,'the guy from smash bros',''),(2503,'One of the best gaming experiences that I have had and I didn\'t even do the dating stuff',''),(2504,'神中神',''),(2505,'It\'s like a dating sim mashed with Pokemon but you\'re collecting JoJo\'s stands instead of animals. And the soundtrack absolutely slaps.',''),(2506,'One of the best JRPG ever made! Great soundtrack, art-style, and game-play. Perfect 10/10My only complaint was player choice feels restricted, with the different confidants having a correct answer to maximize points. Then I had an epiphany; I would rather play an JRPG, that has a linear experience than slog though a Western open-world game.',''),(2507,'I like gymnastics now',''),(2508,'MAKE US WHOLE AGAIN. BRING DEAD SPACE 2 REMAKE, MOTIVE. THANKS',''),(2509,'Can’t start it without internet connection, wtf?!',''),(2510,'Make us whole again, Issac.This is a remake of the 2008 original game of the same name. This review will assume you\'ve either played the original or are unbothered by minor mechanical and story spoilers. These are the main differences between the the original and the remake:- Improved visuals - Issac now has a voice, the character did not speak at all in the first game. Dead Space 2 was when he got a voice.- The limb system is improved, flesh will tear off the bone before more force is required to maim a necromorph.- Upgrades are slightly different, arguably improved- Some of the puzzles are different, for instance that horrible sequence where the ADS cannons are offline in the original is dramatically improved.Tech and PerformanceOn the following specs I was able to run the game at the high preset at 1440p around 50-90FPS. However, I ended up enabling V-sync to lock it at 60 because the fluctuation became too much.Ryzen 5 5600XRTX307032GB DDR4 @ 3600Mhzhttps://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=3121661740In addition to the visuals, the game does a much better job at conveying what is actually going on while still being vaguely mysterious. Of course this is difficult to achieve having played the other two games numerous times.https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=3121665732The one improvement I wished was in the remake is the ability to alter what the locator is looking for. Such that you\'re able to find benches, stores or save stations easier.There are other differences as well such as needing security clearance to open certain lockers or storage units. You won\'t miss them, it\'s part of the story. Previously, you would have needed to use a power node to open [optional] doors. A resource used otherwise to upgrade weapons or your suit. Kind of like using a shiv in the Last of Us to open doors.The GistThis is a great remake, if it doesn\'t inspire Dead Space 2 and 3 to also get remade I hope at the very least in reignites interest in the franchise and Dead Space 4 gets made.If you\'ve found this review helpful, consider following my curation — Station ArgusSemi-Unrelated: Using genre tags and nomenclature of labelsThere are many people that describe this series as “Survival Horror”. And they also say that Dead Space 3 specifically strays from this path becoming an “action” game. Well, I\'ve got news for those people, Dead Space was always an action game — just set with a horror aesthetic and theme. What I believe people intend on conveying when they say “survival horror” is that there is resource scarcity that requires management that makes combat more difficult. Which is not untrue of Dead Space, but on the medium difficulty there\'s nearly no place where you won\'t have health packs or ammo. In my understanding, the term “survival” — at least in regards to genre tags — implies there is something akin to tending to needs like hunger, thirst, sleep, etc. But for whatever reason, the survival part of “survival horror” seems to only be used in the more traditional sense. The sense where you are trying to not die. Which can be applied to a considerably large number of games. In any case, I consider the Dead Space series, or games like Resident Evil 4 and older to be action games set in a horror theme. The original 3 Resident Evil games, not the remakes, are what I truly think of when the term Survival Horror is used — \'tank\' controls, inability to aim precisely and fixed cameras. But that\'s just my two cents.',''),(2511,'A masterclass at atmosphere, pacing, immersion and tension building in horror media.',''),(2512,'How can Space be Dead??? 🤔🤔🤔🤔🤔🤔🤔',''),(2513,'CLEAN UP AISLE: MY PANTS!!!!!',''),(2514,'Never had the chance to play the original fully, but this was an awesome game and truly a scary experience',''),(2515,'Amazing experience held down by constant stutters.Before you say computer bad, I have R9 7950x and 7900xtx',''),(2516,'Here I will leave the cat, friends who pass by can pet it and give it a thumbs up and awards　　　 　　／＞　　フ　　　 　　| 　　 l　 　　 　／` ミ＿xノ　　 　 /　　　 　 |　　　 /　 ヽ　　 ﾉ　 　 │　　|　|　|　／￣|　　 |　|　|　| (￣ヽ＿ヽ)__)　＼二つ',''),(2517,'That\'s the EA I remember! Yeah can\'t play it. Crashes either somewhere in main menu or after 5-10 minutes of gameplay. Tried just about every \"fix\" I could find online. Didn\'t this come out months ago? It\'s this broken still?3700 and a 13700k',''),(2518,'Man... waited a year to get it during a sale and hopefully, getting an ironed out version.Barely 3 minutes in game and it stutters like crazy. Seems to be a well known issue without any fix planned from the devs.',''),(2519,'Dear Steam Support,I hope this message finds you well. I am reaching out once more regarding my request for a refund concerning the purchase of Dead Space. Despite multiple attempts, I have encountered challenges in seeking a resolution for an issue that has greatly affected my gaming experience.My disappointment stems from the current refund process, which appears to be governed by an automated system rather than a thorough consideration of individual cases. Upon examining my game time and achievements, it becomes evident that the title in question is, regrettably, plagued with technical issues, rendering it nearly unplayable. This is further echoed in the reviews provided by a significant portion of players who have encountered similar crashes and bugs.While I understand and respect the time constraints outlined for refunds, I am slightly beyond the stipulated three-hour limit due to persistent attempts to navigate through these technical impediments. I am earnestly seeking your understanding and support in this matter by facilitating a refund. My intention is not merely to retract the purchase but to reinvest the credit in a more polished gaming experience—one that aligns more closely with my expectations.Despite patiently awaiting an update or patch from EA, it is disheartening to note the absence of any significant remedial action over the past few months. The lack of resolution has led me to explore alternative avenues for addressing this issue, as it significantly impacts my enjoyment and satisfaction as a customer.I kindly implore you to reconsider my request for a refund, allowing me the opportunity to choose a game that offers a more fulfilling and functional experience. Your assistance in resolving this matter amicably would be greatly appreciated. However, if a satisfactory resolution cannot be reached, I may regrettably need to explore other means of seeking recourse, such as involving my financial institution.Thank you for your time and attention to this matter. I eagerly await your response and hope for a positive resolution.',''),(2520,'There\'s been some talk about whether any single remake is ever as good or better than the original in any meaningful way outside of a few graphical upgrades. I never played the original Dead Space so I can\'t judge it in terms of that, but I can say this remake is pretty awesome.In fact, the only Dead Space game that I\'ve played before this was Dead Space 3 which is a less than terrifying co-op shooter. That experience did not prepare me at all for this. There\'s only one way to kill the monsters in this game. We\'re talking Total Dismemberment. Hands, arms, legs and, of course, heads will roll. It\'s something else. You\'ll \"kill\" critters only to see them get back up. Issac has to stomp the crap out of their bodies to make sure. It\'s gory and often terrifying. No, Dead Space 3 did not help prepare me at all.Dead Space is one of those Alien or Event Horizon ordeals where a Spaceship doubles as a haunted house. In this case it\'s the USG Ishimura, a gigantic mining vessel which just happens to have huge medical research facilities, a gargantuan hydroponics farm, a space basketball court, etc. Ishimura is the star of the show (well, other than the monkey stomp corpse button). It is huge and full of places for monsters to drop out of the ceiling. Your constantly running across the ship taking care of various objectives like \"do a spacewalk to fix our anti asteroid batteries while monsters try to cut your head off,\" or \"stop a nuclear bomb from detonating and destroying the ship while monsters try to cut your head off,\" or \"save us from poison gas by flushing a big monster into the great toilet that is outer space while other monsters try to cut your head off.\" It all flows together very well and the pacing is first rate.I liked it a lot and it makes me wish I\'d played the original. Better late than never.',''),(2521,'Stutter simulator on Steam Deck',''),(2522,'More a warning than a review First Playthrough worked like a charm. Stuttering began in the middle of New Game+, then it finally crashed my PC in chapter 10 of 12. All saves were gone. Internet research showed me that it\'s a known problem since release and I\'m not the only one. It still hasn\'t been fixed and probably never will. I\'m trying different ways now to restore at least my recent savegame, but I fear the damage is done.The game is an okay remake. Graphics are definitely an improvement and the game has some decent quality of life gameplay improvements, like Isaac\'s smoother controls and the \"open-worldish\" interconnections between the levels. In my opinion the Zero-Gravity gameplay was done a tad better in the older Dead Space 2 and 3. If it wasn\'t for the technical problems on my second Playthrough, I would ABSOLUTELY recommend the game. But if you are not ready to randomly lose all your progress, I recommend the original Dead Space. Played it a year ago and It still holds up very well.',''),(2523,'While the game is fantastic, it still has servere performance issues with traversal stutter',''),(2524,'This remake of the original Dead Space is one of the best remakes yet in horror genre along with some Resident Evil games and does justice to the original. The game takes us on a journey of a man\'s descent into darkness straight from the start. From loosing comrades and then eventually family then when finally facing the ultimate horror there is no fear, just anger and the lines \"This is all I got left\" felt genuinely sad to hear. Overall the game is a roller coaster of emotions with a particular emphasis on how low humanity will sink given the opportunity. The jump scares were random so it was effective as well especially the ones that had no enemy tied to them be it the showers turning on when entering a bathroom for scavenging or trams suddenly stopping with horrific scratching rides on the outside which made me take off my headphone when in transit via the trams.  Although I did\'nt get a chance to play the original (just watch), this experience felt more than enough to make up for my loss and is an absolute must play for horror enthusiasts.',''),(2525,'This is one of the best remakes ever made, I recommend playing it, preferably with headphones!✅Excellent visuals, up to par with modern standards in all fields. Dead Space never looked better, and feels just as eerie as the original for the most part.✅Expanded content, with a side-quests system and more optional areas. Clearing everything will require much longer than in the original.✅Overhauled / reworked gameplay mechanics with better alternate fire-modes, quality-of-life improvements and mechanics from other chapters, like free flight in Zero-G.✅ The technical issues of the original, related to running it on modern systems, are no longer present.✅A carefully-done remake that respects the original vision, atmosphere and gameplay loop, without deforming it too much with modern implementations.➖The game spawns ammo only for the weapons you have equipped, and this causes balance problems in the long run➖occasional errors in loading textures and elements.',''),(2526,'10/10 Remake',''),(2527,'10 / 10 with one caveatAbsolutely outstanding work from people at Motive and a rare win for EA. I dislike them as much as the next guy, but they really pulled through on this one.A worthy remake of an absolute classic, giving it a fresh and gorgeous new coat of paint, fixing dated game mechanics, removing all annoying crap from the original game and even adding new content / story. This is a better game in pretty much every sense, and it\'s clear that it was made with passion by people who love and play video games. If these people remake Dead Space 2, I am easily buying it.If you love the original Dead Space, you owe it to yourself to play this game!The caveat: If your game happens to crash, there is a possibility that it will corrupt your save files, essentially deleting all of your progress. If this happens, you also lose the ability to save the game in the future: your game is essentially bricked, you can no longer load or save. This happened to me just near the end of my Impossible playthrough, and if it wasn\'t already my third playthrough of the game, this would\'ve probably been a negative review.',''),(2528,'I wasn\'t going to write this at first because I was so 50/50 on recommending it or not but after Bethesda started replying to negative reviews about why the reviews they\'ve written are wrong I feel compelled to write something.I would not recommend this game for $70. I would recommend waiting until the game is fully released with all of its DLCs *on* *sale* to buy it. To me there was just not enough there to justify the price. It feels like a game that\'s only had a few years of development rather than seven and it\'s just kind of under cooked.The game itself is just boring and uninspired. It\'s sterile and safe, built to appeal to the widest possible audience and not offend anybody. The characters sometimes have their shining moments but for the most part are bland and your companions are the worst of these offenders because they all have the same opinion on everything, they\'re all the same. The characters also don\'t look great, they have this dead eyed uncanny valley effect to them made worse by the skyrim style zoom in whenever they talk. The quests themselves with the exception of a few, are so uninspired and boring and offer no moral dilemmas or require any serious thought. Compare the Ryujin quest line to the thieves guild quest line in Oblivion. With the thieves guild quest like there is a gradual progression which teaches the player not only how to be a thief but what to expect as far as how challenging a given assignment will be. Ryujin gives you three childishly easy quests that are so easy that they neither teach you how to be a thief nor give you an idea of what\'s to come then the difficulty meter suddenly jumps with the next quest to really quite difficult. Thankfully I happened to have enough levels saved up to dump some points into stealth otherwise I would have had to fail or just leave the quest, level up, and come back. This quest comparison also highlights another issue because Ryujin takes place in one of the saddest areas in the game, Neon.Locations. What is Bethesdas engine really good at? It makes it relatively easy to hand craft huge worlds. So what does Starfield do? They hand crafted a few locations and left the rest up to procedural generation of course!... Oh, well... the few hand crafted locations are great right? No? Oh okay then. New Atlantis is kinda cool but it\'s so small, it\'s close to having some literal and figurative depth to it with the well but that\'s barely explored. New Akila looks cool but again is far too small. The Key is not a city. And Neon... Oh Jesus Christ Neon...Neon is \"we have Nightcity from CP2077 at home.\" It\'s suppose to be this cyberpunk, blade runner-esque city rampant with crime and drug use. You basically get the DisneyLand (not even DisneyWorld) version of that. There is no crime to witness. There are no daily schedules like Oblivion npcs had. Just the same blank faces staring at you like your ♥♥♥♥ is out but you don\'t know it like all the other cities. They hype up a drug that can only be bought in a particular very talked up club in Neon and the club is one of the saddest things i\'ve ever seen in a game. It\'s one relatively tiny room with flashing neon lights and out of shape spandex wearing conehead cosplayers gyrating uncomfortably. Keep in mind this is one of the few hand crafted locations, pretty much everything else is procedurally generated. You also can\'t even smuggle the drug out for any profit, it\'s worth the same no matter what planet you bring it to which doesn\'t make any sense. So locations are not great which brings me to exploration...Exploration in Starfield is not great. In a Fallout or an Elder Scrolls game you can stumble upon countless interesting hand crafted locations and encounters in the game to the point that getting lost is a good thing. In Starfield you won\'t stumble upon anything because you fast travel from planet to planet, system to system. So to explore that has to be your express goal. Okay, fine. Except everything is procedurally generated so after you\'ve done it once you\'re just going to see it copy and pasted on different looking planets. You\'re not going to find anything new in that cave because it\'s the same cave. You\'re not going to find anything interesting on that planet because it\'s going to have the same stuff as the last one, just with different plants around it and the grounds a different color. Just go system to system looking for content until you get bored with that. They made some decent random encounters that you can have while out in space but not enough of them, I\'ve run into Grandma half a dozen times by now.And as far as things to do... the ending: Spoilers ahead obviously. It\'s another multiverse story. I understand 7 years ago when the game began development this concept wasn\'t quite as tired and cliche as it has become but good God am I sick of multiverses. The whole point of the game is to just replay it again, that\'s how it ends. I wish I was joking. It\'s message is basically it\'s not about the destination, it\'s about the journey, which is fine but the journey is not good... Unfortunately the game has, to me, no replayability until new content in the form of DLC drops. Which I may not even buy until it goes on sale because I just don\'t care. The story is that uninteresting. This is not to say that everything about Starfield is bad. The gun play is actually pretty great though not worth it alone to buy the game. The ship building is actually really fun despite it being janky, probably some of the most fun i\'ve had in the game. Some of the quests are fun like the UC quest line and other shorter, one off quests. They all have the same problems though: if they do offer any interesting ideas they do not fully explore them, they acknowledge them and that\'s about it. Things like the Well, tensions between the UC and Rangers, and the UC being a fascist state are all explored in only the most superficial terms. Bethesda has always had the problem of being wide as a lake but deep as a puddle and Starfield is unfortunately a prime example of how this problem has only gotten worse with every subsequent Bethesda release since Morrowind. I did enjoy parts of this game but I cannot recommend it for $70. It is so frustrating to see Bethesda finally get a crack at creating a unique IP that isn\'t another Elder Scrolls or Fallout game and they make this boring, uninspired whimper of a game. This game is all of Bethesdas bad habits, everything they\'re bad at and nothing they\'re good at, finely distilled. One of the most frustrating things to me is that this game is mediocre, it\'s not bad like No Mans Sky and it didn\'t ruin Bethesdas reputation like CP2077 did on release so it\'s not going to get the attention it needs to be made into great game like those studios did. Chances are post launch will be handled very much like FO4 where we\'ll get a couple of bug fixes but not nearly enough and a couple of nickle and dime DLCS then one or two really solid ones. They have ES6 to get to work on after all. This means the game will probably not have a miracle come back like those games did and will probably always be mediocre, which I think is a shame because it does have good bones there\'s just no meat on them.',''),(2529,'Starfield is a game that has an excess of nothingness.An open world RPG that is so overstuffed with meaningless content that the seams are starting to split and the empty calories are spilling out.Starfield is big, both physically requiring 125 GB to install, but also in activities.Planets, cities, missions, NPCs, combat, research, space travel, space combat, space research, ship building, base building, relationship building, main story, side stories, factions, jobs, and cooking.And all of it beautiful, grand, silent, serine, action packed, and ultimately unfulfilling.A tremendous lack of focus makes each individual part of the game hollow. In the modern Glittering Era of entertainment; Starfield is another spec of shine, so concerned with bland mass appeal that it makes any individual gameplay mechanic as empty as the space we’re flying through.',''),(2530,'the story is as generic as it gets and the gameplay gets boring. i wish there was a reason to even bother exploring planets and building outposts. everything is fun until you do it once, then it\'s all a repeating, soulless chore.',''),(2531,'After dedicating countless hours to creating mods for Skyrim and Fallout 4, amassing over 5 million downloads, it pains me to announce to my modding community: I won\'t be modding for Starfield. I\'m at a loss to comprehend Bethesda\'s direction. In an era graced by masterpieces like Cyberpunk 2077, Red Dead Redemption II, Elden Ring, and Baldur\'s Gate, Bethesda has somehow managed to release a game that feels archaic, lackluster, and painfully underwhelming. The game\'s script is lackadaisical, the gameplay lethargic, and the overall experience is profoundly uninspiring. It\'s a far cry from the innovative standards set in 2023/24.This weekend, as I pen this review, the player counts speak volumes:Starfield: 20,027 playersFallout 4: 20,089 playersSkyrim SE: 23,723 playersThese figures paint a grim picture for Bethesda. It took them eight years to produce a game that not only fails to surpass but barely matches the engagement of their older titles. A \"Fallout 4 - Space Edition\" or a substantial DLC would have likely been a more successful venture.I played Starfield for a mere 8 hours, enough to confirm the myriad issues highlighted in other reviews. I refuse to waste more time on a game that has left me, a long-time Bethesda admirer, deeply disappointed, frustrated, and saddened. There\'s no incentive for me to invest my creativity in playing or modding Starfield.Bethesda, this is a farewell from a disheartened fan. Peace.',''),(2532,'i was coping.i paid 100 dollars to play this slop before anyone else due to my consoomer mental illness and even told myself and others i was enjoying it, up until the point where i played another game again, then i realized exactly how unfun, unpolished, and unacceptable starfield is. we do not have to settle for games like this any longer. (there are good things in this game spread thin and far between that kept me going but i\'m telling you right now as a whole package it is so disappointing.)leather jacket moment.edit: what i enjoyed about the game was dogfights and most things surrounding the ships. the problem is i am sad the only place you ever get to fly is in orbit and everything you do with them, including getting in and out, is a loading screen. it\'s much like being stuck on a roller coaster ride and it\'s very restrictive. but hey the backdrop always looks cool and bethesda only asks that you BELIEVE in order to make this all work. so if you\'re ok with loading screens being the way in which you navigate this world, which most of the content does not make up for, then it might Just Work. i also really liked the photo mode in this game and taking pictures of my ship and sarah\'s big butt (it looks great when she leans over on the counter).loading screen moment',''),(2533,'It\'s alright, kinda mid, don\'t pay full price.',''),(2534,'Many reviews have already pointed out that the new content Starfield offers isn\'t very good.I want to offer another perspective by pointing out the many ways in which Bethesda seems to have intentionally made Starfield *worse* than their previous titles. So many gameplay elements/mechanics have been removed:Can\'t craft armor/weapons/ammo. You can\'t modify melee weapons. Weapon mods are no longer items that can be transferred from one weapon to another.Combat is the bare minimum. There are no \"special\" weapons. They had a golden opportunity to create new weapons designed for fighting aboard spaceships (which you really don\'t want to damage while you\'re inside one...) and in zero-g, and they squandered it.NPCs no longer have their equipped armor/clothing in their inventory, and it can\'t be removed from them.There are no traps (tripwires, tension triggers, pressure plates, noisemakers, etc.)NPCs are less interactive than what GTA 4 accomplished more than a decade ago. In Skyrim, when you used your special powers, npcs would be amazed or frightened, and guards would scold you for disturbing the peace. In Starfield, no one even seems to notice unless you hurt someone with it.Companions can no longer be given orders to move to specific places, or interact with things, or loot containers, or attack specific enemies. You can tell them to wait and carry items, that\'s it.No gore/dismemberment.No limb crippling.No reverse pickpocketing.This is all stuff that players should be able to take for granted from a Bethesda game like this, because they\'ve already done it before!',''),(2535,'I have 270 hours and 3 new game pluses under my belt. This game has UI, starship and outpost building, and character growth issues (tied to story). It\'s like playing a vanilla skyrim or Fallout 4, but without the epic storytelling those two had. Unfortunately at the end of the day, this story telling just falls flat. There are not enough branching options and nuances that make it worth it. These are things the community has polished and are tired of polishing. That is why the game is a let down. We\'re playing a game and once again having to fix things \'we\' always have to fix. Where is the maturity? where is the polish from a mature game studio? Why are we needing quality of life and literal math calculation fixes from broken elements of the game in the first month while the studio is silent , scrambling to correct graphics options that should have been present day one? (really, no functional HDR or DLSS support when you could probably train a chimp to read steam hardware survey results and know nvidia cards are king in the marketspace)It\'s a disappointment not because the game is bad, its a disappointment -because it\'s a Bethesda game like we\'ve always come to expect- and honestly, its 2023, the world has seen some poop in the last few years, and it\'s nobody wants to accept a vanilla skyrim or fallout 4 experience. It\'s borderline disrespectful to the community to not bake-in the refinements of elements from these games of the past to learn from those. You can tell no one on this dev team played fallout 4 or skyrim with 100+ mods, and if they did, they were just too afraid, too soft, or not skilled or trained enough to be in a culture where they can provide negative feedback and have that be a healthy interaction with their peers and their managers to speak up and say \'this isn\'t right\'.Overall, i rate the game 6.5 / 10 and say It probably needs another year and some of the story retconned, and the world livened up. I would like to see faster paced ship combat and slower paced ship combat based on ship size (ship of the line vs. dogfighting), UI and inventory management polish, better character progression, better and more ship customization features , more control over ladders and connecting spaces between ship parts, better Outpost object clearing (sometimes rocks just turn invisible instead of being properly removed when i place an outpost item over them so suddenly i have invisible walls), Reduced and smarter random spawns of ground locations (random spaceports and other points of interest on planetary maps) It\'s incredibly disappointing to land on a planet that looks desolate and, without fail, always see some human-made building within sight because the algorhyhm says there needs to be one. Spoiler: this even happens on the planet during Sara\'s companion mission if you walk about 1k meters ish outside the hand crafted landscape. Seriously immersion breaking and ruins that bit of story.In the end, I think people will be playing starfield in 11 years but not because they played all 11 years, but because they waited another 2-3 years , an apology and a free DLC that lured them back in. I doubt they can pull a CDPR cyberpunk though. It\'s kind of sad, because the dev\'s failure on this is also a sign of disrespect to themselves after they complained about TES and FO series and wanted something new. Here is their new IP, their new story and opportunity for world building and it\'s just a let down...Yeah I played 270 hours, but I really only needed 40. Some questlines are vastly more enjoyable than others despite being optional ( and thats cool ) but geez. I\'ll never pick the game up again for probably a year or two, and i\'ll -never- purchase DLC or expansions for the game unless I get the equivalent of content and updates of one DLC / expansion\'s worth of free updates that show they have the passion to at least fight for their respect again.',''),(2536,'Midfield',''),(2537,'Decent game but I think I expected a bit more from it. There is not enough depth to the game and the planets are a little lifeless. I can see this game being massively better in the future after many updates and possible DLC\'s, along with the modding community. But it feels a little empty right now and lacks a bit of replay-ability.I think it would have been better to add half a dozen incredibly detailed planets which you could become fully immersed in, as opposed to hundreds of lifeless planets. Crafting and base building is on the whole, a little pointless unless you are focused on XP grinding and weapon upgrades, but the upgrades you can add to weapons make hardly any difference. The 100% is easy but can be a grind depending on how you play this game. The only missable achievement as far as I know is getting a companion to full likeability/marrying them. This will take most of an entire campaign playthrough and you should really just keep one of the companions at all times.On the whole, I enjoyed the game but I expected more from Bethesda considering how long this game was supposedly in development.',''),(2538,'If you\'re looking for a \"play once\" game, then Starfield will meet your needs.  It\'s okay for a one time playthrough.  Once I had done all the quests, played through all the NGs, struggled through the janky outpost building, crafted quite a few ships (as well as stealing lots of them), and explored all of the star systems, I was done.  I even tried my hand at roleplaying by pretending the first hour and a half of the game never happened and plopping my character in a certain locale, then ridding myself of all possessions and pretending I didn\'t have a ship.  But the game dialogue and the choices the player is forced to make really made it difficult.  I was also really disappointed with the companions available.  Sarah was like a scolding mother.  Barrett was just ludicrous.  Sam had a child--seriously?--and a child does not belong on my ship.  She and Sam would strike up conversations in the middle of battle and make it really hard to concentrate.  Andreja was the best, and I lost her when the Hunter attacked.  That was a real downer, and I don\'t play games to be sad.So, if you want a real RPG--go back to Skyrim.  If you want to build, go back to Fallout 4.  That\'s where I\'ll spend most of my time now.  Starfield is not bad, but it\'s not what I was expecting.  I was really happy with it at first--but then I was just bored and sad.  I really hope BGS spends some time improving it.  I know that\'s expecting a lot, but if they want it to be playable for the next ten years, that\'s what needs to happen.',''),(2539,'Loading screens simulator, I played this after BG3, liked had a gourmet dish for lunch then went Mcdonald for dinner.-Everything fell bland, out of date, nothing stand out from story, character, combat...etc. -Loading screen even enter 1x1 room? Come on Todd, this is 2023 game not 2011If your next step is to bring paid mods like what you just did with skyrim SE, I guaranteed this game will hit rock bottom',''),(2540,'Wasted potential is the best way of describing this game, Ship combat terrible . ships are glorified backpacks, planets are mostly empty which would be fine if we could fly the ships in atmosphere but sadly no. Ships can pretty much fast travel everywhere , no real risk of getting lost or feeling vulnerable during flight. To put it bluntly , this game could have been so much more .',''),(2541,'I have toyed between liking and not liking this game for a very long time. I saw it was met with a mountain of hate, and I\'d been able to embrace some flawed games in the past. Deus Ex Mankind Divided, Mirror\'s Edge Catalyst, Mass Effect Andromeda. I had to get my own opinion on this. Running endlessly on planets is horrific, but I could fix it with the Jetpack Overhaul mod and the gunplay was satisfying. The quests in the game just weren\'t gripping me, but maybe I could invest past the lack of voice acting and body language and into the words and meanings, and hey you can build really cool, livable, usable starships! Then something broke in me. When I finally reached a certain point in the story quest, all the effort I put into levelling my character and starships all suddenly felt pointless. It was in that moment it truly clicked with me that I was playing a soulless game.Like the pot boiling the frog you can\'t quite notice it at first. One distraction after another when you land on another barren planet, a dopamine-producing alien killing gunspree later, and ooh maybe that 1 promising outpost in the distance could have cool enemies, a horrifying back story, or great items? Ah it was just enemies in a maze-like interior. And oh there\'s another over there, I wonder if it\'s any different! Eventually, you learn to never touch them again, short of if you want to specifically grind for experience points or better weapon tiers, and even then you\'re better off running around killing wild aliens for XP, which by the way level you 10x faster than any other method.That\'s what 100 hours in this game was for me. Creating that awesome starship I always wanted to, calculating the best weapons and mass distribution I can put on it. Chasing down resources to create experimental weapon mods on every new weapon I picked up. That kind of felt... *fun*?And then || after a... I think, *exciting*? Main story mission where Walter and I negotiated with an ex-employee for an artifact in Neon, I met the Starborn. What followed was what I can only describe was as if a Redditor was given the task of writing about a new, illusive, dominating alien race making first contact, and that Redditor clearly being a fan of Mass Effect. After some of the most clunky dialogue exchange between you, the Starborn, and your companions, you\'re able to fight this \"ship design you\'ve never seen before\" who is prepared to \"send you into oblivion\", who I immediately trounced and who had only escaped with a smidge of health because I attempted to disable its engines, to which I discovered you can\'t dock it anyway. ||I think that\'s what\'s shallowly buried beneath the lines here. It\'s that constant theme in Starfield where something promising shows itself, where it be a mechanic, a new world, the NASA punk art style and sounds, or embers of a space epic story, and then you\'re very quickly met with a hollow, just slightly stimulating experience so as to keep your head numb and stop you from realizing what\'s really going on. Playing this game feels like undergoing the processes of indoctrination, but in real life.That dialogue sequence though. That one dialogue sequence. It triggered memories it should not have. As soon as I remembered the intense feelings I felt during the Mass Effect trilogy, and just how harrowing it was to meet a Reaper for the first time, I snapped out of my stupor and realized how dry my throat has been for soulful story experiences that have real emotion, voice acting, and charisma.This game lacks all of it, it has no charm. And when you realize it, every effort you put into your action RPG pseudo-roleplay that they\'ve engineered you into comes tumbling down like the weak house of cards it is. The only winning move is never to play. I used to think it was the most mixed gameplay experience I have ever had. Now I can only see it as... a husk of a video game.There is one thing that this game gave me that I\'m truly grateful for. It has helped me realize what I truly value in a game - and what that actually looks like. I\'m off to escape my indoctrination before it\'s too late. I\'ll be starting the Outer Wilds and Baldur\'s Gate 3 now.',''),(2542,'I really, really wanted to like Starfield.  I own every Bethesda title, and considered myself a fanboy. But damn, has this game ruined that for me.On the surface, this game looks like your traditional Bethesda title. But once you get in the game, you quickly realize that the soul the other games have is missing here.  The carefully hand crafted points of interest found in the likes of Elder Scrolls and the Fallout franchise are few and far between in Starfield, in their place are you will find cut and paste points of interest with little to no environmental story telling. This story telling is what made the points of interest, interesting, without them it\'s simply boring.  Before this game, I used to let myself wander and explore Bethesda titles to see what I would find just over that next ridge, or around the next corner.   In Starfield, you either find nothing, or worse yet, a cardboard cutout of what could have been.The main quest line... where to begin.  The biggest questions posed by the events of the main quest line are NEVER answered and the new game plus aspect of the game loop makes me have Groundhog Day flashbacks. The Main Companions... There are only two companions in this game that I even remotely like.  Vasco, and Sam. The others have either nagging, loud, or otherwise obnoxious personalities.  And all of them are \"Good Guys\" so if you want to play a bad guy, you can forget about having them with you.The Powers... The superpowers you get in this game feel like re-skinned dragon shouts from Skyrim.  Hell, when I hit the first temple in the game, and got my first power, I wasn\'t excited, I felt let down because it -FELT- like learning a dragon shout in skyrim.   Same system, Same mechanic, Same effects, Different skin.The Ships...  When we were told we could navigate the galaxy, and could land on planets.. I was expecting something like Elite Dangerous, where you actually PILOTED the ship all the way down to until on the ground.  Instead we get loading cut scenes.  If you want a true space sim, get Elite or something similar.  This will game will leave you wanting.   Although, I got to had it to them, the space combat is fun, so is the ability to hijack ships...   Would be nice if we had to repel enemy boarding parties every now and then tho. Ship Building... The modular design of ships is cleaver but the builder is not fully fleshed out.  The U.I. is clunky, you can\'t rotate all modules, and you have zero control over the placement of doors and ladders. Travel... In Space, it\'s 90% menu and fast travel.  On Ground, it\'s 90% walking simulator with occasional bouts of fast travel.  There\'s a reason this game has gotten the nick-name Snorefield. The Factions...  The factions don\'t care weather you work with the other factions.  You can work with the police equivalent, and the pirates won\'t even bat an eye.  You can work with the rebels, and the organized government just shrugs.  Your alliances do not matter in this game.  In prior Bethesda titles, at least when you allied yourself with a faction, their enemies no longer trusted you.  In this title, they don\'t give a damn.Base Building ... If you\'ve played Fallout 4, or Fallout 76, you pretty much know what you\'re in for.  It can be fun, but the building system is janky at times.  Oh, and if you do wind up buying this game, watch tutorial videos, or you\'ll never get the supply lines stuff working properly. Over All ..  My advice to prospective buyers, wait for patches, and dlc before buying, wait for the creation kit to be released so modders have the proper tools to fix some of the issues with the game.   Because right now, this game is not worth 50 US Dollars.  It has too many bugs, and not enough soul.',''),(2543,'Boring, souless game. Took the one thing fun in Bethesda games, exploration, and replaced it by copy pasted, repetitive mini dungeons. Do not buy',''),(2544,'Just buy cyberpunk',''),(2545,'Sadly, I just uninstalled Starfield. I\'ll likely never play it again.I really liked Fallout 4, and still spin it up for another modded playthrough from time to time. Skyrim was one of my favorite games of all time. I also have fond memories of Morrowind, a game that got me hooked on the open world RPG genre. I also generally like space games, such as Mass Effect. I thus expected to fall in love with Starfield. In fact, I was so hyped for this game, I timed the purchase of a $10,000 PC and a 48 inch OLED display so as to have Starfield as my first gaming experience on the new rig and to enjoy everything the game had to offer under the best possible circumstances.Even after a few hours of pondering, I am still finding it hard to describe just how much I dislike Starfield and the depth of my disappointment, but I\'ll try.The list of small gripes is a mile long. Far too long for a comprehensive list in a short review, and rehashing the obvious likely adds little to the conversation. To mention just a few, these include a clunky UI, ridiculously low inventory space, absurdly low vendor cash even at major space ports, and the notorious plethora of loading screens. Normally, I hold off on modding a Bethesda game until I\'ve had at least one full playthrough and sink a few hundred hours into a vanilla experience. In this case, the mechanics grew so painful after only a few hours, I rushed over to Nexus to see if I could salvage any enjoyment from a game that I very much wanted to like. Several hours into the modded experience, with many quality of life issues mitigated, it dawned on me that no mods would likely ever fix the game\'s real flaws.I found myself desperately waiting for any sort of hook that would get me even remotely interested in this world. The game intro was by far the most banal of all Bethesda games that I\'ve ever played. I started off bored, and that boredom only grew with each passing hour. By the time I was only 15 hours in, I simply couldn\'t take it any more. Wandering through such an uninspired view of humanity\'s future left me feeling almost disembodied. I felt like neither I, nor my avatar, was actually part of the world. What\'s more, each part of the universe, and even every game mechanic felt oddly disjointed. Nothing jelled and very little made sense.I\'ve designed fantasy worlds from the time I was in middle school, creating custom campaigns for my friends to explore. As I learned to program, I then tried my hand at text adventure games and on and on it went. World building is hard. Certainly, not all of my attempts were successful masterpieces, but I\'d like to think that my skills have grown over the decades. The world of Starfield serves as a near perfect example of a disjointed, illogical, boring, uninspired, and nonsensical universe. I am very literally considering using it as an example of poor world building in my computer science course. Top that off with (mostly) bland dialog, illusionary player choices, dull worlds filled with endless procedural voids with slow traversal, AI that doesn\'t even match Bethesda\'s previous titles, and one is left with a meaningless shell of a game.',''),(2546,'I am a huge BGS and Sci-Fi fan, easily 2k hours in their games since I first played Oblvion on the Xbox360. This game should be a free win in my book and here are my spoiler free thoughts on why that is not the case. Playing this game felt like returning home, but some one stole all the furniture and replaced each piece with the same ugly, boring chair. Bethesda has not evolved at all and in fact has regressed by having these barren planets with copy paste dungeons, which unironically they couldn\'t even move the furniture around, it is literally copy paste. Those unique encounters and moments of world building hardly exist in this vacuum of space. The game mostly feels like an empty sandbox, which pales in comparison to No Man’s Sky and not a living breathing world like Fallout or The Elderscrolls. They claim that is by design, but it is not backed up immersively or mechanically. For the player it just means navigating menus since ship travel might as well not exist, then holding W key for 5 minutes until you find the same copy pasted dungeon on a slightly different colored rock from the last one. Shallow survival mechanics, no alternate methods of travel, boring points of interest,  and the only reason to explore a planet is for a few credits. They do not even have an encyclopedia to document your discoveries. They spent so much effort going for realism even the planets just look earthy with some oversized copy paste fauna strewn about them. When I play Bethesda games It is like going to a different world I can live in, Starfield just feels like a bunch of disconnected rocks I need to fast travel to. The planet exploration is about as bad as the original Mass Effects, which is fine if that is secondary to the game being a great RPG. The thing is Starfield is a fine looter shooter from the last console generation. I wouldn’t call it unfair or unfortantue since Bethsda did this to themselves, but I played this game inbetween Baldur\'s Gate 3 and Cyberpunk 2077: Phantom Liberty. Those two games in every way blow Starfield out of the water. Starfields conversations always feel disjointed and ignore the players choices, background, and experiences in the world. Which is immersion breaking in its own write but then It is coupled with creepy, dead NPCs and dated presentation. I remember feeling actually offended when I got to Neon; I tell the guard I am a neon street rat and the very next line of dialogue they forget that fact and start talking to me like it is my first visit to the planet. The game just feels very on rails and the players story comes second to the one Bethesda is trying to tell, which Is pretty boring in its own right. Most conversations just feel like a huge let down compared to other RPGs. Then we have the persuasion system which does not even come up very often, but when it does it feels so goofy and disjointed. It is literally the Oblvion persuasion system, canned responses from the NPCs and all. Roleplaying is weak in the conversation department how does it stack up gameplay wise? Well the skill tree feels like a watered down version of Fallout 4s and does not have a real impact on gameplay outside of a few key abilities that should not even be locked behind a skill tree. At its core the gameplay can actually be fun. The shooting is better than it ever has been and actually feels tight, responsive and punchy. There is a good variety of guns too even though energy weapons exist for no reason beyond a one minute section in a single mission.  I enjoyed jetpacking around blasting people. The problem is the people themselves. You will mostly be blasting one of three factions of dudes in space suits in different copy paste dungeons. Unfortunately these dudes have negative AI and present zero challenge for the player. After a while it feels like your are just blasting empty space suits devoid of sentient life, especially since there is no Fallout gore or gibbing in this game. I need those critical gibs Todd. I am no stranger to exploiting Bethesda’s lack luster AI, but this feels the worse out of all their games. Companions….well the 4 real companions are milktoast whiteknights with no moral complexity. Honestly they are just kinda boring nerds. The rest are just there to afk at an inferior outpost system to Fallout 4s settlements. One thing I did really enjoy besides going full Frank Reynolds is the ship building. It is really cool building your ship and dogfighting in space. It actually gives a reason to grind currency that has been missing since Morrowind. Unfortunately even being my favorite part of the game it is mired with issues. Chiefly among them is the restrictions, you must build in a small box, your exterior paint options are limited, no decals, you can not view or even change the interiors outside of selecting between 3 different modules as Deimos and Stroud are almost identical, and you are even restricted on the number of parts you are allowed to use and the types you use. Even better is if you place objects in the ship or on weapon racks and mannequins, soon as your change one thing on the exterior it all just goes to the cargo hold or if you are unlucky like me it bugs out and your items are lost. This leads to your ship interior looking the exact same as every other ship but with a different layout. You can fill your ship with all the sandwiches you want but then you can not upgrade it at all. The actual ship builder itself is clunky and unintuitive and lacks any real information regarding your ship or the parts themselves. Then you have the perfect class 4 beast and you get to have 1-2 minute dogfights in a tiny skybox and that is all the use you will get out of the ship as we are playing fast travel menu simulator.There are many other issues but in summary, this is not a good Bethesda game, not a good RPG, not a good space exploration game, sadly it is just an average to slightly above average looter shooter depending on what you are comparing it to. After playing this all excitement for the Elderscrolls 6 has been drained from me and even though it will probably not happen I hope Bethesda can learn from this mistake and not only deliver a more focused experience, but try some innovation for once. You can no longer ride on the back of Morrowind and hope the modders sort the game out for you.',''),(2547,'This is easily GOTY in 2003',''),(2548,'This is very satisfying action rogue like,  It feels like a great mix of Dead cells and hallow knight.  The game is very fun and challenging at the same time.  I think it will satisfy the folks who are craving a challenge as well as the more casual gamers out there.  As of writing this I have 141 hours on record.   I have yet to finish all the content.  Granted I don\'t claim to be good at the game. =)',''),(2549,'Fun game. Reminds me of Hollow Knight mixed with the vibe on Cartoon Network.Great on deck.',''),(2550,'Outstanding art style',''),(2551,'Its time to show them who\'s boss.',''),(2552,'At first, the game was a thumbs down for me because it\'s irritatingly difficult and feels imbalanced. But once you get accustomed to the enemies, weapons, and skills, the game becomes very worth it. 9.5/10.',''),(2553,'Good',''),(2554,'The game feels smooth to play, is quite fairly balanced (bleed is great, though), and has a charming style to it. Overall, a good game to pick up and play, being rather easy to understand.',''),(2555,'Good action roguelike with great visuals.',''),(2556,'have a nice game',''),(2557,'8/10not as good as hades but still a very good game',''),(2558,'Love it! The game is a dungeon runner like Enter the Gungeon or Dark Souls where you have one chance to rush your way through and once you\'re dead, its back to the start with you. No block button, you simply have to dodge and evade the increasingly more complex array of enemies. You have 3 weapon slots. One for your scythe, and the other two slots can hold a spell or another weapon that you find along the way.Very challenging but if you like that kind of thing then I\'d give Have A Nice Death a try for sure. For me it was the art style that really sold it. There\'s a lot of care and detail put into the animations in the story-book-style world you walk around in and it looks kick ass',''),(2559,'Very difficult and unforgiving to start the game, but if you are into that type of thing this is awesome. The music and aesthetics are done very well and give the game some enjoyable elements beyond speedrunning and fighting everything you see. Like I said very unforgiving, in comparison to other \"roguelikes\" Have a Nice Death does not have as many supporting systems for new game+ which means further progress mostly comes from experience instead of new upgrades. They do still have these systems and did them in a unique enough way to stand out. Overall made me pretty angry but in the good way 8/10',''),(2560,'Alright.Here\'s the deal:This game is fairly fun.It has charm, personality, an incredible soundtrack, beautiful environments, and a neat concept.But it lacks in a lot of areas.-A lot of dialogue feels half-finished and is filled with errors or nonsensical \"jokes\" (not to mention that a lot of the lines are accidentally assigned to the wrong person in certain conversations).-There are plenty of bugs.-A lot of the lore is kinda just word soup that doesn\'t make much sense even within the context of the game.-Narrative quests can very easily break and be unfinishable.-Half the weapons are not viable.And the most critical, most important thing?The game struggles to maintain a balance between difficulty and fun.There\'s an entire area of the game that feels extremely out-of-place with how unfun and unFAIR it is.I\'m talking about the natural disasters department.In every other area of the game, every attack feels dodgeable. Every hit you take feels entirely like your own fault.But in the natural disasters department?Every enemy is unpredictable, every enemy is hard to avoid, every enemy is a nightmare.The thanager and the boss are the monarchs of \"how in the hell was i MEANT to avoid that?\"Half the attacks punish you FOR dodging by placing a new attack right at your landing zone.Extremely different attacks have very similar telegraphs.Half the hits you take feel like the game put you in an unavoidable situation, or is punishing you for being 1 frame off.This is in STARK contrast to the actual final area of the game, the Time department.This area, while hard, is FAIR.Every attack is well telegraphed, the bosses are dodgeable, and every hit you take FEELS LIKE YOUR FAULT.Another thing this game struggles with is replayability, which is weird to say given it\'s rogue-like nature.Runs don\'t feel different enough to eachother.Most of the difference lies in what weapons you get.The enemies get boring after a while.The pre-built-but-randomly-arranged rooms get samey after your 50th run.And even the weapons start to lose their flair once you realize only about half of them are worth using in any capacity.What makes it worse is that this game is, at it\'s core, a series of boss fights.The actual departments themselves serve more to waste the player\'s time.The enemies are usually not too threatening. With the exception of the unbalanced bozos in the natural disasters department, every enemy is relatively easy to deal with.Even a mediocre build can sweep through most areas with ease.Sure, If you get a mix of tougher enemies, you can take a few hits, but overall it\'s not difficult at all.And then you get to the thanagers and sorrows.And then the game proceeds to completely change it\'s approach and slaughters you.You can take 9+ hits from a normal enemy, only for a boss/miniboss to kill you in 3.And remember, the bosses take a while to kill, so you\'re likely to make a mistake somewhere.The game is a series of boss fights with semi-pointless filler between them.You spend your time between bosses going through floors, easily clearing them, and getting upgrades.The bosses are real challenges that can kill you VERY VERY VERY easily, while everything else is trivial, barely hurts, and is just plain boring.The gameplay would essentially amount to the same thing if it was LITERALLY just a series of boss fights that just let you pick a few random upgrades before each one. That\'s what the game already feels like it is....This game is an \"art first, gameplay second\" type of game.The visuals, the audio, the lore, it\'s all stunning.It\'s not without flaws, that\'s for sure, but almost all of those flaws are easily understandable and excusable.The team behind this game came together to create a work of art.I love the story being told. I love the environments.I love the music.I love the characters.It\'s a damn shame that all the beauty is bound together with mediocre, tedious, and sometimes unfair gameplay.',''),(2561,'a',''),(2562,'A great game. Works well on the Steam Deck, and the developers are constantly updating it with new features and challenges!',''),(2563,'For everyone reading reviews in December 2023: it still runs like absolute crap.Do not pay more than $20 for this.It\'s a complete improvement over the first game in every way except for the performance.',''),(2564,'Great single player experience. Great story, great characters, exactly the game fans want from the Star Wars universe. This sequel takes everything the first one did good, improves it, then adds to it. Unfortunately the ridiculous performance issues made me give it a thumbs down. It is absolutely a spit in the face to the consumer in this day and age when technology is literally at our fingertips for a game company as huge as EA to release any game with these kinds of performance issues. Most of the time for me it ran fine and I managed to complete it. But from time to time there were and still are a string of crashes that just happen randomly and there\'s nothing you can do, also some frame drops here and there. I disabled ray tracing because it\'s almost non existent in this game, even though there is the option in the Settings and the game looks better without it and runs a bit better. I\'m running it on an RTX 4080 / AMD Ryzen 7 7800x3d machine and it still gave me trouble. Granted, nothing to completely stop me from playing but not the smoothest experience. I love this series, too bad it\'s in the wrong hands.If you want to play it, it highly recommend it. But make sure you have a decent machine and for the love of baby Jesus don\'t get it full price. I got it at a discount and still felt robbed. Wait for a massive discount.',''),(2565,'Trust all those negative reviews guys, the port is of a disgusting quality even this many months following release.  Constant stutters during cutscenes, random crashes to desktop and the game has to \"optimise files\" every single time it loads which takes half a minute plus.I have a RTX 4070 ti, i7 - 13700F and 16GB RAM and have no trouble running graphic intense games.  Its just a lazy awful port.',''),(2566,'Running on a 1070ti GPU with 8GB DDR5, i5 9400F 2.9 ghz CPU, and 16GB ram. So, I\'m just barely above minimum specs. Runs fine for me, 40-65 fps at 1080 on high settings. Only compiles files for about 60-90 seconds on startup. So, performance wise (which is probably why you\'re looking at reviews anyways), it is fine now. Update: Finished the game and started New Game+. Over 25 hours played at this point. Performance for me was just fine all the way through, rarely dipping below 50 FPS (most of these dips occur on Koboh, in the Cantina, and looking at the Holomap on the Mantis). Absolutely loved the story and gameplay. It improves upon Fallen Order in every way. So strong with the force, I can\'t wait for my next 25 hours.',''),(2567,'A long time ago in a galaxy far, far away....This has game of the year potential. Really great story telling and combat mechanics! If only it wasn’t for it\'s massive performance issues. And finally, after several months, there were no more performance issues.Jedi Survivor really makes you feel like a Jedi who has survived. One thing I love about these Star Wars games is the atmosphere, I love the buildings and the settings. This was a good game. The levels can get a little exhausting, but overall a good experience. I can\'t wait for the next one. This sequel better than original \'\'Fallen Order\".Don\'t watch last three movie Star Wars from Disney, better you play this game and the original.One more thing, Rick the Door Technician is the my favorit boss XD',''),(2568,'There\'s a great game here....somewhere....hidden beneath a thick coat of embarrassingly bad and persistent performance and tech issues that will seemingly never be resolved.',''),(2569,'Ah Jedi: Survivor, are you a good game, yes. Gameplay\'s engaging, the story is interesting, with a return to the old crew with some nice additions and the one called Turgle. The powers are well balanced and progression is decent with the ability to go exploring to collect rumours to follow up later. It is definatly one the the strongest star wars games in a long while.So why a negative vote?Because the game is  a car wreak on PC. On release it was barly playable and performace was just playable. But you might point out thier were patches to fix things. Well one patch caused the game to crash unless you had ray-tracing on, the next made it crash if you did have ray-tracing on. Side quests could fail to progress and more bugsd were added than removed.Currently the game has a memory hole in it such that a system with 32gb of memory and a 3090 with 24gb of video memory can somehow run out of memory in a few hours.  Don\'t buy the pc version, if you want to play this game, and it is worth playing in time, play it on console, on PC its garbage at the moment with no sign of acutaly updates worth a damn coming.',''),(2570,'DO NOT BUY THIS BROKEN GAME.Google \"KOBOH CRASH\".I spent about 3 hours playing the intro area of the game. I actually had a great time, once I told windows to prioritize the game with my CPU (which cleared up all the glitchiness). But then I got to the second world, Koboh. The game crashed as soon as the ship door opened. I restarted. It crashed before the first ledge jump. I restarted. It crashed before the first wall run. I restarted. I think you get what i\'m saying here.The game became UNPLAYABLE, and because I played for over 2 hours, STEAM would NOT refund me my money. So now i\'m stuck with an unplayable broken game.You can google how EA supposedly patched this trash heap in October. None of this seems to matter for me though.I might as well have just set my money on fire. Do yourself a favor and skip this one.',''),(2571,'You made it run well the first time, so wtf happened. How do giant studios keep releasing unoptimized ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥.Just optimize the gameJust optimize it before releaseJust do itand if you can\'tget a job outside of game development, because you aren\'t good at it.',''),(2572,'I haven\'t played that long but I\'ve already had about 8 game crashes. Happens randomly but always makes me lose any progress I\'ve made since the last meditation point. Sometimes that can be 20 minutes lost. Fix your game!The visuals, combat, and story are great so far. I just wish it worked.',''),(2573,'i can\'t get this to run smoothly on my rtx 3080 system im sorry i cant work with this',''),(2574,'Excellent game - if it were not for the multiple, serious PC port issues.That some of the very basic ones have not been fixed in all these months is beyond ridiculous!Trust the negative reviews as per the technical issues, and trust the positive ones as to what an awesome game this could be without the issues.I will update this review when the most serious issues are fixed (and I\'m still playing).Just the most ridiculous: (1)CPU usage is extremely high. FPS is CPU limited. I have to turn off ray-tracing to get to a manageable CPU load (still way too high). This is the only game with which I\'ve experienced this in the past few years.(2)I have to disconnect mouse and keyboard to be able to play with controller.If the game receives too many kbd/mouse input events (including unvoidable events from miniscule mouse movements) then the game switches to kbd/mouse mode, turning of the controller input and with no ability to switch back to controller input. Only solution is quit to desktop, restart and unplug kbd/mouse.This game is strongly (and correctly) recommended to played with a controller - kbd/mouse puts you at a disadvantage.(3)Optimizing game files (compiling shaders) at EVERY start of the game. Caching appears broken. The workarounds that can be found all have their own drawbacks (you need to write-protect an entire config file).(4)Does not work with non-standard aspect ratios. I have a 16:10 display (which is not that uncommon, actually).You either have significant parts on the sides cut off, or you get a stretched image. The game does not letterbox if you configure a 16:9 resolution.In other words, the game does not display properly with 16:10 - no matter what workarounds you try, some parts with be distorted or cut off.Not recommended even at a steep discount as long as these basics remain broken.',''),(2575,'The core of this game (gameplay, combat, exploration) is absolutely brilliant but the PC performance is a complete disaster, even months after release. Even on a 4090 and 5900X, the constant stuttering was too insufferable to keep playing.',''),(2576,'Performance isn\'t that good but the game has really amazing story, combat and graphics, definitely worth getting it on a sale.',''),(2577,'This game still plays terribly on PC.  Don\'t believe the hype train on youtube about how respawn \"fixed\" the PC performance.  It\'s terrible.',''),(2578,'Not having a EA launcher on my PC.',''),(2579,'Was about to put about 20 hours into the game with no issues, then all of a sudden I get an error upon start up and the game crashes. It\'s ridiculous that the game has been out for so many months and there are still these sorts of problems.',''),(2580,'This game does not support 16:10 monitors currently. Unfortunately, in turn I do not support games that do not support 16:10 monitors, especially if I paid lots of money for those games. (Google this, btw, you\'ll find this brought up on the official forums, with the \"accepted solution\" saying simply that 16:10 is NOT supported (as of 2023 November.) That\'s quite a nice solution, isn\'t it.)I will update my review when EA and Respawn update their support of 16:10 monitors. ;)',''),(2581,'Tldr. poor PC port that still haven\'t been fixedAfter leaving the initial starting area and going to the first planet, the game just keeps crashing over and over. I\'ve meddled with settings. Turned off things like RayTracing and Frame Generation. Lowered settings. But the crashes keep on happening. I can also see that I am not alone in experiencing constant crashes. Seems that despite all this time since launch, the game is still essensially unplayable for many people.',''),(2582,'The stutter is making head hurt. Game is good but the stuttering is crazy!',''),(2583,'Starforce collection when?',''),(2584,'Write a review for Mega Man Battle Network Legacy Collection Vol. 1',''),(2585,'Some of the best Video Games I\'ve ever played. It\'s hard to describe how awesome the combat system is, but the bottom line is it accommodates any player. If you have bad reflexes, you can play this as a strategy game. If you have good reflexes, you can play this as a real time action game. You can also play anywhere in between. Even outside of combat, all of the games are very story rich which a vibrant world with timely overall messages about the growth of the internet and how we communicate.As for the collection, it lets you trade and battle with Steam friends on top of letting you insert any E-reader content every released for these games if you so desire. It fixes bugs, some translations, and restores content that couldn\'t fit in international cartridges due to storage space. This is no doubt the best official way to play these games. This particular collection contains 4-6. This is a good starting point, because 1-3 don\'t have all of the QOL improvements that these ones do, so in my opinion start here and if you like it buy the other collection.',''),(2586,'Very Unique game nothing quite like it',''),(2587,'Ishin has a phenomenal atmosphere, a gripping story, and is really fantastic as a period piece in the Yakuza/Like a Dragon universe. However, this was all present in the original release of the game on Playstation, and this remaster is not a good port. Cutscenes are locked to 30 FPS, the combat and physics on Unreal Engine don\'t feel true to the series, and there were some highly questionable practices with the game\'s DLC (who puts consumable, repurchaseable item packs in a singleplayer game?) But by far, the Ishin remake has the worst grind of any game in the series for anybody seeking 100% completion. I have the platinum trophy for every game released on Steam so far, and I have never had an experience as painfully boring and anti-fun as with Ishin. Not only has the price of equipment at the forge been inflated to absolutely ridiculous prices, there is a dizzyingly long list of equipment seals you will never get your hands on without abusing the RNG that determines when they appear. If save scumming is the ONLY viable strategy for completing your game in any reasonable amount of time, something has gone terribly wrong.I love the Yakuza series, and it seems like it will be returning to glory with Gaiden and Infinite Wealth. If you really want to immerse yourself in the world of Ishin, then by all means do so. But I can\'t recommend it after so much of my time with it was spent completely ignoring that world in favor of endless menu navigation for that final, painful platinum.',''),(2588,'i never want to hear any of you complain about the yakuza 3 completion list ever again',''),(2589,'majima is even hotter now',''),(2590,'mmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmmm!',''),(2591,'Not as good as a bento made by someone\'s loving wife.',''),(2592,'AMAZING!',''),(2593,'Its Yakuza set in the past, need i say more?',''),(2594,'10/10 Game. The engine felt a little off at first but eventually clicked with me. Please also give us Kenzan!',''),(2595,'I have no idea how in the world a playstation 2 remastered game can be beating out some of the titles coming out this year. but it has. I c