 game, especially if you like Phasmo. Just don\'t expect it to be a clone.Things don\'t work the same wayBetter graphics.Less crashing and better performance than Phasmo (for me at least) (13900ks+RTX 4090)More jumpscares than phasmo.Cooler interactions with the voice.',''),(2776,'would be good if it didn\'t stutter, freeze and crash consistently.',''),(2777,'Game was ok when I first tried it for 30 minutes or so. Then the new patch came out and the optimization is shoddy at best. Crashes when trying to navigate the menu, load into lobbies, load into a game, making a lobby, even opening the settings will cause a crash. Massive fps drops and stutter too. Can\'t recommend until this is fixed, have requested a refund.',''),(2778,'This game is all style,  no substance. I was originally attracted to it because its a phas clone but with much better visuals. And to be fair it does have very nice looking maps. There is a lot of detail and creepy atmosphere in its maps. The safehouses are pretty cool too, and you can spend money unlocking permanent cosmetics such as different safehouses and furniture for them. Which is a cool idea, but the problem it doesn\'t go far enough, leaving the safehouses still looking bare and bland. Character customisation is a nice touch too with minimal customisation. But basically, those are the good things. Everything else is bad. The game is essentially a Phasmophobia clone, with less maps, less equipment, no hiding places and virtually no chance to survive the hunts until you learn how and where you can loop the ghost. There is no mechanic to carry more gear such as in Forewarned, you\'re stuck carrying 3 gear only, and that means 2 if you want a flashlight. All optional objectives are locked until you decide which ghost it is. While putting Exorcism in the game is pretty cool at first, it ends up being too easy or too confusing wtf you\'re supposed to do. Levelling up in the game unlocks some maps and items, but after a certain point does nothing at all and is completely pointless. In addition, the game still plays like an early access game, filled with bugs and crashes and instability issues. Often the EMF reading occurs in the wrong room, bleeding through into the floor above or below, and sometimes even sounds can be heard a fair distance away from the \'ghost room.\' Sure banging doors or moving furniture could be heard in different rooms but for example, in the hospital, you shouldn\'t be able to hear rustling sheets or squeaking trolleys in a distant corridor on a whole different level. Another criticism is the \"Susie storyline.\" One of the secrets of the game is a badly written, badly told story about a mad person called Susie, and you have to go back and forth between the most expensive safehouse and the asylum map reading exhaustive notes. Only the host player can read the notes so in multiplayer its frustrating not being able to do anything and standing around whilst player 1 reads the notes out because no one else can even see them. The climax comes with a choice, but again only the host player can make it or even see the book. There is an achievement for completing the story, but you guessed right, you don\'t get it unless you\'re the host player. An utterly disappointing and frustrating waste of time. The devs don\'t listen to the community and released out of early access without warning. It should be noted their previous 2 games were abandoned and although they say this game will be updated, I wouldn\'t get your hopes up. Even looking at the game\'s trello board reveals nothing at all, there is no evidence on what the devs are working on and no promises for future content. Ultimately, Demonologist is complete waste of time and money worth spent elsewhere.',''),(2779,'Not optimized',''),(2780,'This game takes Phasmophobia to another level. For some reason I never got into Phasmo at all, but enjoyed watching it. This one feels like a more immersive experience and gives you more to do in game while regularly putting out new updates and customization for your safe house and characters!',''),(2781,'Fr how does this game still have \"playable\" status on Deck? It consistently crashes 100% of the time and requires a hard restart',''),(2782,'Me and my friend buy the game to’ played together, and haven’t been possible to played because to one of them the game crash just starting. When they arrange this issue I could give a proper review but at the moment isn’t playable.',''),(2783,'The full version is currently not playable on Steam Deck after the patch/update.Just to be clear: The demo works, but the full version crashes every time, when loading the level from the safehouse/lobby.',''),(2784,'We couldn\'t even get it to launch a game. Super upsetting, considering we enjoyed the demon. Don\'t expect the devs to actually fix it,',''),(2785,'It needs work but it\'s good. It brought back the feeling of playing Phasmophobia for the first time. The levels are quite detailed and the interactions and special events in each level are more intense and captivating. There\'s more of a narrative wrapped around what you\'re doing compared to other ghost hunting games, which is fun to unpick when you\'re playing with friends in multiplayer.The initial level proved a bit of a learning curve and you have to replay it a fair few times before progressing. There are some rough edges too. The player models look generic and the ingame customisation store is split into two by gender; at first I thought it wasn\'t letting me select the hoodie I bought for my character, but turns out I bought the female hoodie, with no obvious way to sell it (and for some reason female was set to default purchase even though the default character is male, which is a massive troll.) Other issues include stuttering before events happen (which can ruin immersion) and my game crashes whenever the lobby closes. There\'s potential to fix these things and the foundations of what this game is are pretty solid. For those of us looking for a fun multiplayer horror experience, this ticks most boxes. For fans of Phas, it lets you relive that same panic you felt when you first played it, but it offers something more.',''),(2786,'Neglected by the devs and latest updates have created more issues. Used to be pretty decent game, but compared to the competition i cant keep pretending this game is good. Maybe if they put more love into the game i\'ll change my review.',''),(2787,'This is a game where I just have to open with it and say, why did this game have to be published by Electronic Arts. This game had so much potential, it is fun, and inventive with great designs for practically everything. Combat is fluid and fun and every moment playing this game feels great, until it doesn\'t because its riddled with performance issues. It hurts that I can\'t recommend this game because it is really fun and has so much potential it will never reach because Electronic Arts simply doesn\'t care about it like most of their games, and I will be honest this game is never getting another update. I can tell KOEI TECMO who have experience in the monster hunting genre with other solid games like Toukiden knew what they were doing here and really wanted to make something good, I wish they would have been given the chance. The game is solid but its launch was riddled with performance issues and like any EA game that was enough to give it the axe instead of just giving it that little bit of time, and resources it needed to be a great experience and maybe even a true Monster Hunter franchise competitor. Its a shame to see games like this that could really do well be ruined on the whims of corporate suits but sadly that is the reality of a lot of game development, don\'t buy this game now unless its really cheap and go in expecting mediocre quality, this game is such a lost opportunity and that\'s a shame, its also a shame I have to lament the money I spent on it, but i\'m sure EA is happy about that.',''),(2788,'I played for about 40 or so hours on Game Pass to \"try it out\" and, well, I put about 40 hours into it there and got it on sale here. I wasn\'t expecting my save file to transfer over and that was a very nice bonus surprise. I like the game and hope the surge of Game Pass players and sales from people like me who liked it enough to go buy it encourage them to come back and keep adding more content. Or make a sequel.I\'ve had a few performance issues here and there, but nothing more noticeable than a slight dip in framerate in certain spots or when grouping up with other players and a ton of effects go off at once, but it\'s not even a consistent enough problem to impact my suggestion to check it out-if only on sale or on Game Pass. It has crossplay, so don\'t let the Steam numbers fool you into thinking no one\'s playing it. It also launches thru EA\'s stupid launcher, so I\'m assuming that\'s not only how my file crossed over, but how the matchmaking is supported. It\'s very unfortunate EA is the publisher of this game because it is a fantastic foundation to be a true competitor in the Monster Hunter game genre.For starters, the movement and combat system is better than in either of the Monster Hunter games I\'ve played so far. Those games felt pretty wonky/janky/clunky in terms of how you fight and move around to chase down the monsters. In Wild Hearts, however, the movement system is a lot faster and the combat feels more fluid and fun to play with more of the weapons. I\'ve mainly used the bladed wagasa (umbrella), but I enjoyed the katana they start you off with and the bow and hand cannon, as well as the claw/blade, and the shapeshifting staff weapon that turns into a giant shuriken, twin tonfas, or a bladed polearm with different attack sets for each transformation. I haven\'t tried the giant hammer or sword yet because I\'ve been having so much fun with the umbrella\'s combat.Outside the weapons, you also have access to an increasing number of what the game calls karakuri. Contraptions used to move around the maps or fight the monsters in the game. As you keep playing, you might get what the game refers to as bursts of inspiration while fighting specific monsters and unlock fusion karakuri. Basically, you can quickly place a combination of basic contraptions and they\'ll fuse together into a new one that does something to help you out during the fight. It could be providing you and your allies a healing mist in an area, a giant bomb to damage and stun the monster, a fireworks explosion to bring down a flying one, a big barricade to stop a charging attack, and so on. There\'s a wide range of things you can try to quickly make or place during a fight to help. The basic karakuri can be things like springboards to launch yourself at or out of the the way of monsters, a flame to coat your weapons in for a bit to potentially set the monster on fire, blocks to climb up high and do a drop/jump attack on it, or even a celestial thread to connect yourself to a point on the ground and quickly move yourself around. All those and more can potentially be combined to make new things on the fly that will help take down the monsters faster and it all makes hunting them more fun and engaging.Then there\'s the weapon crafting and upgrade system. As you\'re running around the maps, there are plenty of small monsters to kill and materials to collect to help make weapons/armor in addition to the parts you get from hunting the big monsters. Each weapon type has a big upgrade tree you can look at and enhance/alter it\'s damage type and appearance as you work down it. If you choose to revert to a previous version to try a different route, you usually get the items back used to upgrade it. I think it\'s done to encourage experimentation and changing your weapons for specific monster weaknesses. I like that it also lets you change the inherited traits from previous versions you upgraded it from. Like if you\'re working down a path that adds a specific trait you want, you can keep it for future upgrades and sort of further customize your weapons as you upgrade them. In addition, the armor sets often have what\'s known as a Human or Kemono path you can use to modify and upgrade them. Depending on the path you choose, you not only get a different cosmetic look to the armor, but you can potentially unlock different abilities for it if you\'re far enough down the path. For example, I went full Kemono and have a trait that will let me ignore death once when I take fatal damage. It\'s great for giving me an extra chance to try and heal and finish killing the monster.In all, I think I fought about a dozen different big monsters not including different versions of the same one but I also haven\'t finished hunting the main monster from Chapter 3. I don\'t want to spoil anything, but I think not long after I got to Chapter 3, it felt like going from Low to High Rank in Monster Hunter World if that makes sense to anyone. Like the world shifted and a bunch of more powerful versions of monsters appeared and some new ones showed up and I\'m able to go to the next tier of weapons and armor. I tried to fight the big monster for the chapter ASAP and it wrecked me. I now am trying to upgrade my gear before trying to tackle it a second time with the realization that for the most part, I\'ve been having more fun playing this than I did during most of my time with Monster Hunter games. I wanted to like them, but I think I like this more.After each hunt of a big monster, you get something called kemono orbs (you can also get them from breaking and chopping off parts of kemono/monsters) and you can use those to upgrade and unlock new karakuri. The basic and fusion karakuri used for combat aren\'t the only kind in the game. There are also a kind called dragon karakuri and they are permanent structures you place in your maps/world. They can be simple decorations or a means of collecting materials or further processing those materials for use during hunts. Such as a device to collect fish from water sources and then a drying rack to dry out those fish. Fish are one of the kinds of food you can eat raw or refine to provide better stats in exchange for using up more than you get out of it. Like 9 veggies to produce 3 dried veggies with better stats. Eating the food is this games way of temporarily boosting your stats like HP or defense, only they seem to last for a certain amount of real time rather than a specific hunt because I\'ve had it last even after I lost a hunt and tried a different one. Beyond the food, you just have a simple healing item you can increase the amount of which can be carried by finding and collecting things called tsukumo scattered around the maps and upgrading yours at a campfire. A campfire is one of the dragon karakuri you can build around the map. There are also things like ziplines and aerial lifts and a scouting tower to help locate monsters for hunting-and all karakuri which can be upgraded from the kemono orbs you get for hunting monsters.With all that combined and the lack of needing to stop and sharpen your weapon to keep fighting without your attacks bouncing off the monsters, it\'s a lot more fun and engaging to fight the monsters in this like I said earlier in the review. If you think your machine can handle it, I definitely recommend checking it out. There\'s not only a good amount of content to this game for their first attempt at a Monster Hunter style game, but all the things they did different to put their own spin on the formula make it work better overall-at least in my opinion. It\'s one where I think whether you really enjoyed the Monster Hunter games or tried to get into them and just couldn\'t, you should check this out. (Probably on sale and/or on Game Pass. I like the devs Koei Tecmo, but I really dislike EA and their decision to try and charge $70 for games now.)',''),(2789,'Really fun and enjoyable game. Played a lot more outside of steam.But for next time... let\'s not go with EA',''),(2790,'My review is long overdue, mainly because I was saddened by how this game lost its support. This game had a lot of potential in the monster-hunting category, maybe not enough to make the Monster Hunter series \"sweat\" as new competition but enough to make the players see that the genre can evolve more than what Monster Hunter currently provides.If this game is on a big sale (at least 50% or more, maybe 75% if you can\'t spare too much), this game is worth picking up just to experience the fresh ideas the devs had. Please note that my pointers below are in comparison to Monster Hunter as it\'s arguably the biggest name for the genre Wild Hearts is in.Pros: - The karakuri system as an idea as well as how it was executed is the biggest pro. It is a new inventive way to interact with your environment in order to plan your hunts and mobility to augment your quality of life during gameplay. This was something that I strongly feel was not expected by anyone coming into the monster-hunting genre much less this game. It expanded how you approached each quest rather than simply augmenting some factors of it.Karakuri introduced new ways of base-building such as being able to customize your own camps and move them around, resource farming, ziplines you could place for mobility and so much more. To me, this was something that Monster Hunter should have adopted a long time ago. The freedom to make a map comfy for you in whatever shape or form is amazing.Combat karakuri added a fun and freeing way to approach how you can augment your fight kind of like how wirebugs work in Monster Hunter Rise, but combat karakuri are more tangible in use as they can directly influence combat rather than passively influence your skills. You can build a wall to shield yourself, build a gadget to hover in midair for eagle-eye vision and positioning, or simply create weapons like ballistas for extra damage.- Diverse weapon fighting styles is something that Monster Hunter already has, but Wild Hearts expands on this with its unique weapons that encourage you to dominate not only on the ground, but in aerial combat as well. Because of the karakuri system, weapons have ways to incorporate aerial combos not only for mobility, but to get better angles on hits.The claw blade lets you perform guerilla attacks to a monster, the cannon lets you use an arguably nuclear laser, and the wagasa introduces a new way to enhance people who like parries or counters.Cons: - Linear gear progression (specifically armor). There\'s not many skills to customize and most of your changes are tied to your weapon crafting tree. The armor skills are still neat, but because it pits you into choosing one or two forms of passive skills, there\'s not a lot you can customize. I suppose this is somewhat fair as the available weapons and combat in general are already customizable.- Performance can tank at times. This is an ongoing issue, and even though I rarely ran into this myself, I do admit that because Wild Hearts requires you to be able to watch things happen smoothly, any frame drops may kill you both in-game and your motivation to play. A part of me thinks they definitely could have toned down on the outer ends of the environments and made it easier within the sandbox instead.I haven\'t played in a long while due to responsibilities IRL, but this game is definitely one I look fondly back on. Wholeheartedly recommend this game to those who can afford it, and/or those who wish to see a new way monster-hunting can still evolve as a genre. The pros outweigh the cons, and with enough budget and time, this game could have easily solidified a spot as a monster-hunting game in the genre.',''),(2791,'Unfortunately a waste of money fix the bugs and make smoother and will definitely come back.',''),(2792,'good game but the performance issues make it basically unplayable',''),(2793,'Works well through EA app when I played through my sub (100+ hours and 40/48 achievements). I liked the game enough to buy it through Steam and that\'s where I went wrong. Through Steam: it crashes, slow loads, and Steam forces to verify files. I\'ve yet to experience anything like this until now. With tinkering, the game loaded but dropped to snail pace on game loads, zone loads, menu loads and ultimately crashed on a mundane activity. Overall, horrible experience for an overall good game that simply cannot function through Steam.',''),(2794,'Great game play, honestly it ticks off many boxes monster hunter never looked at. The story line is even richer.',''),(2795,'Sadly the game is no longer supported. There was some special monster hunting here and some great mechanics. The perf issues weren’t fixed fast enough afaik so the game flopped, but it’s worth playing.',''),(2796,'This game is SO GOOD but it comes as no surprise that EA destroys everything it touches. They need to sell the rights to this game to someone else that will give it the LOVE it DESERVES, because without the performance issues this is BETTER than Monster Hunter and Im not joking.',''),(2797,'Mid due to being rushed :(',''),(2798,'I got an AMD Raedon 6600 (Hopefully that\'s spelled well) and I run the game good so hopefully people with \"stronger\" GPU\'s can run the game.  I\'ve played an older MHFU game as well as MH World just like I\'ve played Toukiden 2 and Wild Hearts.  MH is overrated for my own taste compared to the competitor.  I tried forcing myself to play MHFU multiple times while later the same year I completed Toukiden 2 and even started a 2nd play through because it was that fun (Played them on my Vita).  With Prior hunter experience being set, I tried Wild Hearts and MH World.MH World (from my experience) is for people who want a chill and easy game to play.  There\'s nothing wrong with that.  Wild Hearts is like going from pop to POW with the gameplay personally.  It\'s faster, innovative, and has combos to find with the basic karakuri.  There\'s no discussion for which game is more fleshed out more.  1 game has years of refinement for what it is while the other had less than 1 year with literally \"EA\".  MH World will have more content and such like it should after having years of refinement.  Wild Hearts just simply has better gameplay.  Given they had a publisher that wouldn\'t ♥♥♥♥ with the process,  MH World would be the casuals hunter game and Wild Hearts would be those who want that extra Dopamine (the intense gamers).  This is all my opinion of course.  I do recommend the game when it\'s on sale for anyone that\'s looking for something different with some OOMPH (I\'m tired af and I hope yall have a good day!)',''),(2799,'Great game to grind!',''),(2800,'Ok Let me preface this by saying I KNOW some people are doubtless having LEGITIMATE performance issues because there ARE some light-medium stuttering in places. BUT now the game is on sale (if you dont have gamepass) it is THOUROUGHLY worth a go! Personally, despite the ire i will draw, I found it to be much more fun experience than both monster hunter world AND rise, of which i loved both dearly, and despite being labelled a \"clone with fortnite aspects\" before launch, it is different enough to be its own thing and Capcom could learn a thing or two here. Any \"mon-hun only\" person denying this game at least sets some new standards for monster hunter series is lying to themselves AND you!Now that the preface is over: for MOST people, the negative reviews can literally be chalked up too \"PC player doesn\'t want to take ACTUAL time with his/her settings, Has google chrome running with a few tabs open, and cant stand being at 59 frames instead of 60 and thus blames game\" Or simply \"REEE it\'s not monster hunter whats the popular negative review i can give\"I played this game in 2 states! First on launch with a 1070, Mixed settings, some high others low - mid (the usual suspects) In 4k resolution because i use a TV as my monitor (and 1080 On said TV looked blurry for most games so i defaulted to 4k) WHILST streaming! and yes i had the odd stutter but being a console player my whole life prior to making a pc 2 years after the 1070 launched. it didn\'t much phase me, i was still getting pretty good frames considering my 1070 being almost minimum requirements but i WOULD have to close chrome to do this! Another streamer friend i recently re-picked the game up with ALSO had stuttering issues and was ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ like crazy live...till he closed chrome, so take that as you will.I recently picked it back up with upgraded... and now its all max setting all the time and 4k and it\'s so good that now i can only complain about some in game mechanics!-The Karakuri system is GREAT but also in a team can become so spammable and oppressive to the poor monsters! So much so that i feel that celestial thread (the currency to build) should be harder to gain so that you have to REALLY plan what to use and when or be out of luck when you need it!-I wish there were more weapon options! 7 weapons types they do have are great and all feel different and unique (i exclude the 8th weapon type the cannon because i dont like its playstyle lol though im sure others will love it) and the way you can min max your weapon via the growth tree is PHENOMENAL, However, more types would be great! theres a distinct lack of a more \"tank\" weapon to utilise provoking perks (minus the umbrella which has a small parry window) so something with an outright shield would be good.-The lack of endgame is a bit of a letdown, even after the later on updates that trickled out (and i feel this is maybe becase of the tensions leading to ea supposedly dropping support) but there is still some content there but dont expect mon-hun DLC levels of extra story, just a few new monsters and even harder versions of ones you already faced!Despite all that I feel the MAJOR flaw of this game was the price! It was £70 and i FEEL that with the pre-release backlash, and the fact it was a new IP (and early more legitimate performance complaints) a £50 pricetag would have sufficed. I know EA said they stay out of the \"EA Originals\" titles more, but they CERTAINLY don\'t stay out of the pricing.I Honestly hope that If you CANNOT afford this game even on sale, that you will try it via gamepass, and if EA drop support some other, more monetarily/time forgiving company, will help them along because the devs really did a good job making this (despite any legit performance issues people have) and deserve a second chance even if you did suffer some issues... I\'m just saying, i\'ll bet many of the people complaining about \"performance\" gave games like cyberpunk or NMS their chance at launch despite issues and kept going and even more have gone back now so the REEEE-fest is a little hypocritical to me.',''),(2801,'Fix the performance please! The game is actually not that bad, it just irritating due to the fact it freezes in 5 seconds every minute.',''),(2802,'Game play is not to bad, though there are some performance issues. Leaving a review as I heard that EA has apparently decided to drop support to this game, so there will be no further updates. Kinda sad considering it\'s been out for less than a year.',''),(2803,'Runs like crap.It pains me to write this, because I really really wanted to play this. The gameplay idea is brilliant, the weapon types interesting and different, the world looks beautiful and alive, the monsters have nice design...but it runs like crap.I waited patiently and believed the devs would eventually fix the performance issues, but it seems they really stopped updating the game in every single way. Which means I have to play this at 30fps, if that even works, and I won´t be able to see for myself if the gameplay is as good as I thought it would be.Now, I have RTX2060, so maybe it works with better specs. If you still want to try, the game is on gamepass, try it there to see if it works for you.',''),(2804,'Lack of players and support, game runs terrible can\'t get past 60fps. Just another cash grab EA they\'re copying the blueprint of Anthem game. Not even a year after the game launched and it\'s been abandoned.',''),(2805,'I\'ve been a Monster Hunter fan since my days with Freedom Unite on the PSP. In my recent playthrough, I encountered no performance issues, mainly slightly extended loading times, which I attribute to using an HDD drive. It\'s worth mentioning that I played this game on my robust 3D work/editing PC, which likely contributed to the smooth performance. Nevertheless, I\'m thoroughly impressed by this iteration.This MH- like  feels refreshing, providing a simpler and faster Monster Hunter experience enriched with fantastic features and numerous quality-of-life improvements. In the past, I often relied on external sources like the wiki to find specific items or understand their rarity across areas or monster ranks. However, this game conveniently offers nearly everything one needs to know directly within the in-game menus. It\'s an incredibly convenient addition.The standout feature for me undoubtedly lies in the weapons. Within the initial 20 minutes of gameplay, I was captivated by the aerial combos and the unique playstyles associated with each weapon. However, personally, I found the cord/string-knife less effective compared to, say, the hammer. Its damage output, particularly dealing a mere 7 damage in a 10-hit combo, pales in comparison to the hammer\'s potential 1,000 damage output. The choice between weapons becomes evident, especially during prolonged grinding sessions.Beyond the exceptional gameplay, the story proved captivating and engaging. At times, the pacing choices invoked a chuckle, like when the drunk character assures the village\'s safety, only for another character to immediately interject with catastrophic news. This slapstick-style humor injected a delightful element of entertainment into the narrative. The story itself showcases a blend of Japanese and Western cultural influences, with philosophy subtly woven throughout. While there aren\'t branching paths or significant choices impacting the plot, the variety in dialogue options adds depth to character interactions, encouraging further engagement.However, there\'s one glaring flaw: a sound design decision that truly grated on me. One particular armor emitted a high-pitched, metallic sound reminiscent of jewelry, which was incredibly bothersome. I opted to discard this armor, preferring a less effective one despite the higher risk in combat.so. game good. grab a partner play it in coop and have the greatest Monster hunter-like Experience i know till this day. I use the term \'Monster Hunter-like\' similarly to how \'Souls-like\' is used in the Souls community. It describes a game that draws inspiration from Monster Hunter while putting its own spin on the formula, striving to emulate its essence while incorporating unique elements and mechanics',''),(2806,'Honestly, a couple cool concepts, but I just keep going back to MHW...and then never really returning. An interesting 30 hours, and haven\'t touched it again since.',''),(2807,'Season 1 launches 20 GB update10 minutes of verifyingLaunch gameUpdate requires restartLaunch game Shaders optimizingTakes another 5 minutesAll my classes were resetCreate Warzone loadoutLaunch WarzoneGame crashesCan\'t verify game filesVerifying game files 127 GBUninstall CODWrite this reviewBye.',''),(2808,'You\'re profile was signed out...You\'re profile was signed out...You\'re profile was signed out...',''),(2809,'I wanted to check out the free play weekend, so I downloaded 140 GB for the game to not launch. I click play and it just doesn\'t launch. I\'m not even surprised. actual hot garbage.',''),(2810,'My friend I play with said that if I post a review about the game and it gets 200 likes and 50 rewards, he\'ll buy me a bag of chips and a RTX 4090. So I\'ll leave this here.',''),(2811,'This game is trash. *Keeps playing*',''),(2812,'𝐈𝐧𝐢𝐭𝐢𝐚𝐥 𝐓𝐡𝐨𝐮𝐠𝐡𝐭𝐬At the launch of Call of Duty: Modern Warfare 3, I had little to zero intentions of buying the title for a price tag as oblivious as $70.00 (USD). Especially as someone who typically purchases Call of Duty titles for a specific game mode. In this case, I would have only bought it at first glance for the zombies mode. I decided to purchase the title once the game had gone on sale for $48.00.𝐂𝐚𝐦𝐩𝐚𝐢𝐠𝐧Some may have enjoyed the campaign (although it is an unpopular opinion), but in my case, I did not enjoy this title\'s campaign. Compared to all of the Call of Duty campaigns throughout the years, this truly is the worst that has come for the franchise. The storytelling of the game did not retain my attention to continue on, as the missions had little to no originality and did not provide a compelling reason for why you are partaking in the adventure that the protagonists of the campaign are partaking in (if the description is vague, I do apologize as I do not want to include any hints of spoilers for those whom still would like to play for their first time without any knowledge of the story).𝐌𝐮𝐥𝐭𝐢𝐩𝐥𝐚𝐲𝐞𝐫Bits and pieces of nostalgia arose when I played the multiplayer modes of the title. The mechanics are spectacular, as you feel a sensation of: \'freedom,\' being able to maneuver without the restrictions that were present in the previous title (Call of Duty: Modern Warfare II). I do not concur with the reviews for down voting the game due to the presence of: \'Skilled Based Matchmaking\' (SBMM). A lot of complaints I hear about video games having SBMM: \"I just want to relax and casually win games against people that aren\'t sweats,\" \"it\'s harder for me to get clips\" (whether it is a content creator (small time/big time) or someone that just wants to show off). Games like Call of Duty are supposed to be competitive in my opinion, especially being an First Person Shooter (FPS) title. In my point of view, if you are being placed against people that are just as good as you or even better, that should be a motivating factor for you to improve - be better? It simply seems as if everyone nowadays just want handouts for subpar performance/quality.𝐙𝐨𝐦𝐛𝐢𝐞𝐬My first impressions were thrilling. Everything was new, different levels of zones was in a way, intimidating. For a solid 10 - 15 matches, it was great to catch on to little things I did not know about the game mode until I learned bits and pieces of information from someone else or through exploring. I would definitely recommend this game mode to hardcore zombies fans of the franchise, as yes, I understand that it does not follow the traditional style of the franchises\' zombies, but it is something new, and a good new, a refreshing experience for those who are looking for something different in zombies or burnt out on the previous franchises\' zombies. 𝐂𝐨𝐧𝐜𝐥𝐮𝐬𝐢𝐨𝐧On top of the fact that the title was retail priced at $70.00, consumers may opt to purchase the \'Vault Edition\' that came with the game for a total of $100.00+. I am truly failing to see how anyone producing this title believed that this would be satisfactory to any and all consumers of the franchise. It is clear that Activision no longer wishes to hide from the criticisms of many consumers for being a poorly managed company, built upon greed (added bonus: also being a company that has a history with tolerating sexual harassment, sexual assault, and inappropriate behavior in a workplace environment). I would not recommend this game simply because of the retail price of $70.00 because it does not meet the quality that deserves the preset amount. The campaign is subpar, everything within\' the game looks to be easily copied and pasted over, and the greed displayed through heavy focus of micro-transactions instead of focusing on the quality and originality of the game. For a retail price of >$30.00, this would have been a reasonable purchase.',''),(2813,'hELLO IT DONT WORK!!!!