hat intelligent AI in combat compared to other games. The gameplay hasn\'t changed much from the previous one(Tom Clancy’s The Division™). I\'d say Tom Clancy’s The Division® 2 itself is good. However, it\'s a typical \"Pay-to-Win\" game with 100% bullet sponge enemies. Because of the high dependence on items, it means that in theory you cannot kill an npc with a low-quality gun even if you hit its head 100 times, and you\'re actually going to experience it. Playing this kind of less-reality game was a really bad experience for me. Moreover, forced real-time Ubisoft online connection is so annoying and frustrated. The problem is that the quality of Ubisoft online connection is very low, and considering Ubisoft\'s notoriety for \"Play while you can\" server operation, it\'s the worst part. Furthermore, its story wasn\'t interesting at all because the story took most from the first one(Tom Clancy’s The Division™) and made it feel like a rehash. Now, I’ll briefly list the pros and cons of this game.Pros- Very Detailed and sophisticated map design- Continuous support and new content development until now- Somewhat superior and intelligent AI in combat compared to other games- Very detailed character and weapon customization- Great SoundtrackCons- Pay-to-Win game. Hard to enjoy the game without buying in-game items because of lack of items and supplies even though I bought the Ultimate edition,- 100% Bullet Sponge enemies guaranteed! The overall balance between enemies and my weapons was terrible! Enemies don’t die even if they gets hit by a head shot.- 24/7 Forced Ubisoft Online Server Connection.(Ubisoft is notorious for its \"Play while you can\" online operation. Not sure what will happen after the server shuts down.)- Poor story and characters & too short and easy(meaningless) campaign/singleplayer missions- Feel like somewhat downgraded version of the previous game(Tom Clancy’s The Division™) in terms of its map design(Open-world elements), story and campaign.ConclusionThe game itself is fine, but I personally don\'t like Pay-to-win games with bullet sponge enemies, lack of reality & storyline, forced online connection etc as a single-player user. And compared to the previous game, the quality is relatively low in terms of its map design and story. I recommend buying it at over 70% off, and I don\'t recommend it to anyone who wants to play single-player and campaign. It’s the game where real-time online connection is required, and most of its content focuses on multi-player and PvP.',''),(3137,'Difficult to get in to now, especially without friends. But it looks and plays great, the gameplay and skills are fun, and the story is good and rewards exploration and investigation (just be prepared to listen to a lot of audio logs).  Matchmaking is sparse for all but the high-level/endgame content at this point so you will probably end up playing solo a lot, but it is easily playable solo until endgame. I feel like it is objectively better in every way compared to D1, and yet I just can\'t quite get invested like I did with the first game. Perhaps this is just due to the fact that it\'s not a fresh IP at this point and it\'s harder to impress and delight the second time around.Get on sale and enjoy 30-40 hours of a great game.',''),(3138,'If you liked Wildlsands youll probably like this tooMain difference is the enemies have drones and robots,  Pretty much zero human enemies will survive an Anti Tank Rifle to the brain,  but prepare for some big ass robots to be \"boss fight\" bullet spongesAlso there is apparently a feature where if One player owns the game, they can \"host\" a guest to play with them for free, even if the guest doesnt own the game',''),(3139,'Do yourself a favour and turnIMMERSIVE MODE ON and  GEAR SCORE OFF!I bought the complete version on Steam again to give this game another chance.I already got an endgame character after playing it excessively when it was released. I really enjoyed the coop and most of the mis