ont show continue',''),(3227,'Impossible to progress - game-breaking bug makes it impossible to continue past any results screen without force-closing the application.',''),(3228,'The Ubisoft title STEEP has always been one of my favorites.  This is all that STEEP was plus a whole lot more.  A great deal for the $10 I spent. Its interesting even without buying into the extra DLC.',''),(3229,'Took ages to get working because of the absolute mess that\'s called Ubisoft Connect. It\'s by far the worst launcher that I\'ve ever used. When it finally worked after restarting multiple times, I found out that skateboarding isn\'t included in the base game, but costs an additional 39,99 euro\'s. I bought the game a while back on sale, because I heard about the upcoming addition of skateboarding, but didn\'t expect it would become a paid dlc, let alone one that costs as much as the base game. Should have know better. I would refund the game if I could.',''),(3230,'Great game just that The game won\'t load on geforce Now anymore it just keeps crashing as soon as i load my session',''),(3231,'Buy the standard edition. The skate controls are trash and not worth it. Nevertheless, pretty good game. Just get it on sale',''),(3232,'bike',''),(3233,'GameplayThe game hosts various challenges you can tackle in about a dozen designated event types, snowboarding and skiing, mountain biking, flying with rocket wing and wingsuit, the DLC skateboarder and BMX as well as the toys. A lot of fun and varied ways to traverse this beautifully made map. If you haven\'t guessed yet; freeroam is easily my favorite aspect of this game.You can also participate in races called events against CPUs, winning these will get you exp for the relevant career. Leveling your career up will reward you either with better gear or bucks you can spend on outfits. These outfits are on weekly rotation. While tastes are subjective I think there\'s plenty of good outfits you can earn for free. You can also earn gear and outfits from completing sponsor challenges.Beyond this there\'s a lot more activities you can participate in like online Mass Races and Trick Battles. There\'s also Daily Sponsor Challenges, Weekly Challenges and Weekly Shop Rotations making you almost never run out of reasons to play even after finishing the main game.DownsidesThe game opens up with a tutorial and cutscenes, you\'ll quickly notice this game is a little cringeworthy, but that only makes up a tiny percentage of your playtime. The dialogue in general is a little cringeworthy, but again it only makes up a small percentage of your total playtime. The music isn\'t really good in my opinion, different strokes for different folks I guess. You can disable the ingame music, still use the other sound effects while playing your own music in the background.Events are in my opinion the weakest part of this game, because it\'s an open world game it has to confine you to the intended area and route somehow. Basically keeping you from taking shortcuts during races or earning trick points in unintended locations. Their less than elegant solution is to put checkpoints every 30 feet. If you miss a checkpoint during a race you can kiss your victory goodbye. While an alternative solution is hard to come by, at least make the checkpoints less frustrating to deal with, I\'ve lost tons of races just because I missed and arbitrarily sized checkpoint.There\'s also little incentive to try if you can\'t make it into the top 3 as 4th till 12th (last) get the same rewards. I know it\'s supposed to reflect medals in real life, but from a gameplay perspective it makes little sense not to just make it more incremental. However once you have your gear you can mostly avoid events in the bulk of your playtime.MonetizationThis is basically an MMO so it should be considered a live service game and should be treated as such. Premium outfits shouldn\'t be considered any more or less taboo in this than other live service games like ESO or Warframe. Doing so is kind of a double standard. This is a game that gets regular updates and DLC. The developers need to be paid to get us that content.I preface this because the game seems to catch a lot of flack for selling outfits for real money exclusively, However compared to other monetization schemes Riders is arguably one of the healthiest ones. I\'d argue it\'s a really good example of how monetization should be done.They\'re confident enough you\'ll enjoy the DLC items, they let you playtest them for free so you can make an educated decision whether you want to buy them or not. There are no lootboxes or fomo items as about half the seasonal Premium outfits can be bought outside their featured week and there\'s no pay-to-win at all. Even the bought currency isn\'t purposefully inconvenient as the incremental amounts you can buy are usually exactly what you need for a set number of outfits.',''),(3234,'If you just want to have fun then this game is for you.I agree with other people the game does require lots of other DLC if you want skateboards and BMX\'s and stuff, but if you just want to ride bikes and stuff then this game is for you.I personally like this game a lot because it\'s ton of fun.',''),(3235,'Best game ever',''),(3236,'Bikes snow and skating',''),(3237,'Wäre ja nicht mal schlecht aber meiner meinung ist es eine anmassung die hälfte der Sportarten in dlcs (die echt teuer sind) zu packen ausserdem ergeben die pysics oft gar keinen sinn bin sehr entäuscht',''),(3238,'I have never talked to a woman irl',''),(3239,'This is at once a surrealist masterwork, a sexist male power fantasy, a geniune deliberation of romance and a well of existential dread.This was recommended by a friend, they said I might like it, though I believe for the wrong reasons.I laughed out loud so often, sometimes because the jokes are nice, sometimes because of the sheer absurdity of it and sometimes out of joy, because the actors are so sincere.The acting is way better than this game deserves. But why is it absurd and surrealist? Gu Yi has got to be the most limp-wristed, incompetent and inconsiderate man on the planet (well except for his supposed talent for art).',''),(3240,'A Genuinely Delightful VNPros1. Dirt cheap.2. At least ten hours of gameplay with lots of variations on what you can do.3. Very likable characters with tons of personality including some of the side characters.4. At least from what I can tell, the team that made this seems genuinely passionate about making a good game.5. Actually a good game.6. Pretty SFW.Cons1. Like most romance VNs, the male MC is kinda bland.2. While having so much variation in scenarios is definitely great, it\'s also hilarious when you treat a girl like crap for ten scenes in a row but she still wants to get together with you.3. Occasional audio quality issues mostly relating to the filming.4. Occasional drop in quality in some videos and pictures.ConclusionExtremely good value, great plot and characters, well designed game made with love and passion. I found the Behind the Scenes section surprisingly funny and touching. Really looking forward to the next game the devs will make.',''),(3241,'TLDR; I don\'t need to talk to real women anymore.Love Is All Around is not just a game; it\'s an emotional odyssey that captivates players with its charm, warmth, and delightful storytelling. From the moment I embarked on this love-filled adventure, I found myself immersed in a world that seamlessly blends whimsy with profound emotions.The visuals are a feast for the eyes, featuring a vibrant and beautifully crafted environment that mirrors the game\'s uplifting narrative. The story building, reminiscent of a living storybook, creates an enchanting atmosphere that pulls you into its embrace.What truly sets Love Is All Around apart is its ability to evoke genuine emotions. The characters are well-developed, each with their unique quirks and personalities, making it easy to connect with them on a personal level. The dialogue is witty and heartfelt, contributing to a narrative that effortlessly tugs at the heartstrings.The gameplay is both engaging and accessible, striking a perfect balance between challenge and enjoyment. Puzzles and tasks are seamlessly integrated into the storyline, ensuring that each moment spent playing contributes to the overall narrative arc. The game encourages exploration, allowing players to uncover hidden gems and intricacies that add depth to the overall experience.The soundtrack is a standout feature, perfectly complementing the emotional highs and lows of the journey. From uplifting melodies during moments of joy to gentle tunes that accompany reflective scenes, the music enhances the emotional impact of the narrative.Love Is All Around is more than just a game; it\'s a celebration of love, friendship, and the intricacies of human connections. It\'s a rare gem that manages to strike a balance between gameplay mechanics and heartfelt storytelling, leaving players with a warm glow that lingers long after the credits roll. If you\'re in search of a game that goes beyond entertainment and leaves a lasting impression, Love Is All Around is a must-play experience that reminds us all that, indeed, love is everywhere.',''),(3242,'Translations are pretty bad, game uses some weird server DRM which makes it unresponsive at times and often freezes on black screens',''),(3243,'This was a great tool to help me practice my Chinese skills!!!',''),(3244,'Sometimes you just gotta choose the obviously dumb & bad decisions just for the hell of it.',''),(3245,'im very happy and sad mostly lonely',''),(3246,'I can fix her',''),(3247,'Found this thanks to Disguised Toast.A totally valid purchase for someone who seeks to relearn their mother tongue. I am absolutely  only buying it for that reason..............Edit: Managed to get my first ending as a Close Male Friend. Extremely realistic.....Edit 2:  I\'d choose Xiao Lu with Zhong Zhen coming a close second. Sad you can\'t get Yunsi to a happy ending or else she\'ve been my second choice.',''),(3248,'Constant Blackscreens, Forum talks about needing a chinese vpn to play properly, a lot of lag in choice feedback if you do. Not worth it. There might be a good game underneath but these decisions just killed any interest I had in it.',''),(3249,'I have love, but it\'s not around, it\'s on this game. don\'t mind mejust do your thinghave a nice dayhope it gets sequel1❤️/10',''),(3250,'This game has one really major flaw.  It seems that there\'s really only one correct path to finish the game.  The way the game is set up, is that it is done in chapters.  You have to increase the affection of the girls in each chapter to reach a certain goal.  If you don\'t meet that goal, you don\'t advance.  The problem here is that there seems to be one set way to reach that goal.For example:  I\'ve played this game up to chapter 5 and then got stuck.  A friend wanted to watch me play so I decided to start over.  Got through chapter 1 fine.  Chapter 2 however, I could not get any further even though I made all the same choices I made the first time I played.  I went back, chose different girls and all of their options and still could not get past chapter 2.  The only thing I could think of is that I made a different choice in chapter 1 that changed the starting conditions of chapter 2 preventing me to get the required points to move on.  This really is a crappy game mechanic.On the plus side, the girls are cute.',''),(3251,'After this game me n my homie decided to move to Asia',''),(3252,'There\'s a surprisingly high level of production value for this game; it really feels like we are watching a chinese netflix tv series and theres surprisingly a lot of options for a FMV game. The usual limitations of the FMV genres are there but there are also some frustrating conclusions to certain dialogue options that merit no sense. Overall a solid game and I can see why people nominated it for a story-rich award, even if I disagree.Rating: [6/10]',''),(3253,'bro, wake up this is not realty .',''),(3254,'Overall 9/10 - I enjoyed and love this game so much. I need more games like this.Everything is great. But there is one comment I would like to give so that if you make more games like this, you can make it better. To me, Shen Huixin, Lin Yueqin, and Zhong Zhen, who appear late, need more screen time to compete with the other three characters that appear in the early chapters. Also, add more mini-games like you did (Boxing, RockPaperScissors, Card). That\'s all, good job and keep up your good work, intiny team!',''),(3255,'There isn\'t enough of these types of more wholesome and well produced dating games on Steam, this is a must try for sure!',''),(3256,'I\'m learning rizz',''),(3257,'I should have majored in art instead of computers',''),(3258,'It\'s Vampire Survivors + Diablo 2 + Hades.',''),(3259,'Con:  Being a newly released EA game, it only has one, 20 minute zone.Pro:  I have gotten more meaningful play time, entertainment and FUN out of Death Must Die than I have through the entirety of Diablo 4.Pay $99+ for Diablo 4 and be bored, or pay $7 for Death Must Die and have fun.  The choice is yours.',''),(3260,'\"B movie\" early access Hades. Missing some of the later polish but there\'s a solid idea here.',''),(3261,'When I saw this described as Vampire Survivor + Hades + Diablo, I thought \"Eh, sounds kinda derivative\". But man, does it deliver on the fun aspects of all of them, and in a way that doesn\'t feel rehashed or stolen. Definitely my favorite VS-style game since VS itself!',''),(3262,'Prostagma.Actually a funny & fun game. Skeleton Archer is funnies with his remarks. Enemies tend to throw remarks and jabs at you, and so does the game at times, breaking 4th wall.The game has a wonderful comedic flavour of Herc\'s Adventures for PS1 mixed with a ton of hilarious references. Edit:After sinking more time in, I think I really enjoy it. It has a very good sense of what makes one game fun to play. Now, the important thing for the Dev team will be to keep on bringing new content, maps, enemies, items. The gameplay itself shouldn\'t change much. It\'s just content at this point. And maybe having an option to get a specific God more often than others. Not a fan of RNG on Gods themselves. I end up having 12+ alterations as a starting point. There should be an item that allows you to pick \"main\" god, and then who the extras will be.',''),(3263,'Absolutely stellar game. I hate leaving reviews but this game more than earns it. Stellar mechanics, graphics, and hilarious ambient dialogue. Game handles beautifully, extremely so for something that falls under the \'Indie Pixel Art\' style. Smooth animations, great game. Best $7 I\'ve ever spent on one. Would highly recommend.',''),(3264,'I am already a HUGE fan of survivors like games but this one blows the rest out of the water when it mixed in my love of Hades. You not only get to fight giant waves of baddies, receive buffs from the divine BUT ALSO you get to collect powerful items and customize your build before you even press go?? 100/10 concept, Death Must Die is a MUST for your Survivors collection.',''),(3265,'One of the best games in bullet-heaven genre. It\'s so addictive and charismatic that I can\'t stop thinking about it. The game doesn\'t have any voice overs/actors, but the characters are written so well that I can hear their voices by reading their dialogue texts. The chemistry between them is great and I really enjoyed the humor.I hope that the developers add more maps and enemy types with the final release because although I love the gameplay, there isn\'t enough content to justify it. The endless mode is desperately needed and the waves need to be randomized.It\'s also worth mentioning that all the characters except the knight need a buff. The assassin needs a health buff, the mage needs a speed buff and etc.The game also needs to give the player the option to pick two more starting skills besides the usual dash. I really liked Kangaroo (3 dashes) for example, but I only picked it up once because it\'s very rare to encounter it. The player must be able to keep these skills as a reward if they are to return victorious from the final battle.Some gods are actually unbalanced. For example; Lady Justice is overpowered which is good and I don\'t mean that I would like to see her nerfed. However, I would want other gods to be buffed to be as powerful as her. It would be really cool to get some healing abilities from other gods as well.Good luck developers and thank you for this great experience!',''),(3266,'As others have mentioned, this is a really good start for the game, and i hope to see it finished some day.hope we get to see more attacks added, right now it\'s not much, and the upgrades are a bit underwhelming. And for a game that relies on constant movement, it is a bad idea to have a movement penalty every time you attack, it really feels like you are walking through mud and it makes it very unsatisfying to play.',''),(3267,'if you like hades you will like this one',''),(3268,'Truly an enjoyable game! I found myself engrossed for a continuous 3 hours, The experience was fantastic. Anticipation builds for future updates as the game holds immense potential.The game\'s aesthetic and itemization are standout features, reminiscent of beloved ARPGs, It effortlessly caters to enthusiasts of the genre, offering a blend of familiarity and invigorating novelty.Even in its current iteration, the game delivers substantial value, justifying the investment. The fact that it remains in early access signals promising prospects for further enhancements and brilliance.',''),(3269,'In my opinion, DMD has potential to be a very cool entry into the genre but in it\'s current state doesn\'t offer fun enough gameplay, build variety and content to keep me entertained beyond the first few couple hours I\'ve played. Pros: -diablo-esque gearing-unrestricted shop to buy and sell items-presentation-voice acting-art styleCons:-not enough variety in classes /archetypes, aside from the sorceress, the 4 melee classes felt basically the same to play, especially because they all use the same boons-not enough variety / depth as far as boons go. I never felt like I could craft interesting synergistic builds with what I was offered. It all just felt like: \"make number go up, very slightly\"-Hades style boon system does not really make sense if player doesn\'t have a choice in what will be offered-movement penalties while attacking are unfun and I\'m gonna die on that hill-some enemies will straight up run you down before you find epic boots + movement speed upgrades and there\'s nothing you can do about it whenever your dash is on cd-only 1 level right now-not a fan of bind on equip items, this just seems like a restriction to increase the grind / playtime, but not in a fun way-no real innovation on the formula and therefore no uspUndecided:-no run of the mill meta progression where you upgrade dmg / as / area / range etc. incrementally. Let\'s be honest that\'s boring as hell at this point-\"meta progression\" instead tied to equipment, which is restricted by class specific gear and \"bind on equip\"-quite a lot of utlity is tied to gear now, like pickup radius, boon rerolls / banishes, luck etc.I think the most important aspects of this genre are fun rewarding gameplay and replayability enabled by depth and build variety. Death Must Die, in my opinion, is lacking in those aspects as of right now. I will keep an eye out for updates and the full release and I\'m more than happy to give it another shot and change my review based on further development.',''),(3270,'A fantastic game to spend the evening playing on the Steam Deck.The different gods and the blessings that they grant is fun to play with. Mixes things up each time as the order of the gods and blessings can be different from before, forcing you to try different builds. The different heros are nice. I\'m a sucker for loot drops.I hope they continue with the solid effort they\'ve made.',''),(3271,'Amazing game, how can I spend more money to support development?',''),(3272,'This has the potential to become my favorite survivor game! The part that makes this a fun game and differs it from many of the others is the dodge mechanic. You have to actually dodge attacks and not just focus on your build!This game has multiple classes to play with and also equipment to gear them up giving variety in what kind of builds you can try out.If you enjoyed Halls of Torment definitely give this one a try!',''),(3273,'Others have perfectly summarized this game asgameplay - vampire survivorinventory - diablo or similarcharacters - hadesoverall a good mix of games',''),(3274,'A great addition to the \"Vampire Survivors\" like games out there. This is not a copy and paste style game either, it has difficult boss fights and a bit of a Diablo(ish) loot and inventory system.There are plenty of classes to try out so far. If you like Hades, there is a big splash of Hades style of \"random Gods giving you perks\" each time you level or drop a mini boss. The addition of multiple dashes is also a great touch to these survivor games.If you like these types of games, this one is pretty awesome. I have put in a few rounds on the steam deck too... highly recommended!',''),(3275,'I rarely post reviews, but I think this one deserves it.* The writing style of how some of the characters speak doesn\'t change the quality of actual gameplay, and does not diminish the potential of the game. If you can look past their usage of emojis, the personalities are unique to each other.* I personally think that the NPCs/gods offering blessings are a highlight that featuure well-crafted and poetic dailogue. ( and I always love a game where around 80% of the lines are fully voiced ).* Although some criticise the skills being underwhelming, I find the current variety just right. Every run feels different which keeps the gameplay dynamic and exciting ( especially when you like achievement hunting). Considering it\'s still in early access, very optimistic about the potential for even more diverse /enhanced skills.TLDR; if you can look past the unconventional weriting style of your chartacters and appreciate the developed personalities/varied skills, the early access offers a promising experience :)))',''),(3276,'Vampire Survivors with a heavy dose of D2 and Hades. If you can beat the first 20 minutes of the game, you know your money was well spent. It\'s a 10/10 from me.',''),(3277,'Probably my favorite survivor-like right now. Just something about the control that you have of your character compared to the rest really sells me. Your own skills do tend to matter a little more in this game vs most of the rest. Dodging is actually useful, directing your attacks and deciding when to, etc. I\'m also a huge fan of the RPG style meta upgrades where you\'ll find armor and other useful trinkets with permanent stats that\'ll impact how effective your character will play.My only real gripe right now is that with there only really being one level it\'ll get fairly grindy. It\'s early access of course but still, it\'s worth noting. It\'d also be nice to get some extra variety between individual characters besides just their main attack. Something that separates them a little more from one another.',''),(3278,'My recommendation for Diablo 4 may be controversial because I am in the group of players that content creators like to bash on when discussing how Blizzard killed this franchise. I’m a grown man, that works 50+ hours a week and grinds this game on Friday nights and weekends.The “dumbing down” of the game actually appeals to me. It’s easier to follow the progression but still retains a ton of the build crafting that allows me to sink my teeth into it as I’m approaching end game content. I’m having fun with the game and it’s opened me up to others suchs as Last Epoch, Wolcen and PoE 2. Is it worth the price- eh, for me, yes, but you’ll have to make up your mind that yourself.',''),(3279,'I have heard/seen a lot of bad reviews on this Diablo. And I’ve been postponing buying this game or not. But I finally gave in and bought it after playing the free trial weekend. As someone who has played the past Diablo (3) , I’m not saying this is the best one. But I’m not saying it’s not enjoyable and just an overall good game. I have enjoyed this game just as much as the other, and I admit that I am addicted to it which I wouldn\'t have thought I would say. I love the gore within the game, I love the in-game content, the details within the variety of outfits,characters, environments, weapons etc etc (to be honest I\'m probably biased in this opinion as I’m a lover of gore so anything with blood is an instant yes from me).From what I gathered most of the reviews here that are negative, were from when the game was just released on steam and there were crashes, couldn’t log into the servers etc etc. so people as soon as they could “pounced” onto the negative reviews. Which they have obviously now fixed and the game is just overall fun to play with the recent reviews now being positive, it speaks for itself. For the price you buy it at, i’m not saying it should be as expensive as it should but it shouldn’t be cheap either, for how much it offers, they bring out monthly patches, they push for updates. they bring in new world events, which are enjoyable to jump into. So I recommend waiting when it’s on discount if you don\'t want to pay the original price. Even though I haven’t got over 100 hours (yet) on the game. I just know I will be playing this for many hours to come. with different classes and skills that it gives you to choose from (I just don’t know what to choose) making the overall experience that much better with each play through being different to your liking. If you feel like the game looks enjoyable and you would enjoy it! Just buy it! don’t fall into the rabbit hole of the negative reviews. That\'s what happened to me and I finally ignored them and tried the game for myself and I’m having fun playing it. It\'s a game I want to play everytime i start up steam. it\'s also a game i would write a long positive review for which is something i have never done before (and no blizzard did not pay me for this review).',''),(3280,'Season 2 has enough QOL fixes and new overworld end game stuff to do that I feel like it’s a lot easier to recommend this now. Upcoming changes have also been positive. Unfortunate that every AAA game comes in hot nowadays.',''),(3281,'This game feels like more like a MMO than an ARPG. Combat lacks the feel of impact and weight. The unending fetch and collect side quests... it all just feels tired. The game is beautiful, but it feels hollow, and I regret my purchase.',''),(3282,'There is no reason this game has to require an internet connection to actively play, and I returned it.  I wanted to just enjoy the story and play by myself without getting into all the online aspects.  The DRM crackdown on this is ridiculous.  Just let me install it with steam and play offline -- not too much to ask.Do that and I\'ll happily repurchase the game.',''),(3283,'This is my first diablo game. The gameplay loop is pretty fun, I can see why the series is popular. It\'s grindy in a fun mindless way, and it\'s a good movie/podcast game. But the focus on multiplayer and monetization hampers it. I just wanted to play this single player, and you can\'t as it\'s always online. It shouldn\'t be deck verified for that reason alone. It\'s not really a handlheld game to take on a flight, you have to have wifi. Even if you play solo. You can\'t pause the game for this reason either, so if you have to get up frequently or put games to sleep, this one isn\'t it for you. The game seems like it was once a good game, and then they in modern fashion stripped away all rewards and incentive for playing and charge for it. I got this for 40 dollars and beat the main story, with one character. I didn\'t do any of the post game and only did maybe a third of the side quest. You are bombarded with ads frequently, every time you unlock some tier, or to go to the map, there is an ad asking you to buy an overpriced cosmetic. The armor and stuff you unlock in game all looks the same, incentive\'s you to buy the predatory monetization cosmetics. I paid 41 for this game on sale. I truthfully think it\'s worth maybe 30 in it\'s current state , maybe less. I played at a leisurely pace and beat the main game and a 3rd of the side quest in 37 hours, solo.. If you\'re playing with friends, you might get more value out of it and beat it faster or replay it, but I play single player because as a 32 year old with a weird schedule, it\'s hard to find time to party up with friends, and most of my friends don\'t play this type of game, and I\'m too much of an introvert to add strangers and play. After work I just want to chill, and this game almost has that chill vibe to it, but it\'s got to constantly shoe horn in ads and purchases, and that ruins it for me personally. I have no desire to play it again due to it\'s short comings. If i could give a neutral review, I would. But due to the negatives outweighing the positives, I am giving it a negative review. I\'ve heard D1,2, and 3 are better. If they ever come to steam I\'d give them a chance, but I don\'t think I\'d give Diablo 5 a chance until it hits maybe 20 to 30 bucks if it\'s like this one. I don\'t like games as a service games, and this game is really trying to be that, disguising itself as an RPG, and that\'s just not for me personally.',''),(3284,'I have always played the Diablo games and I have always purchased them on release. Diablo IV was the first one I held off on and said I will buy it on special as a just in case. Reading reviews it was hard to find a positive one but I went down the review rabbit hole and focused on the positive reviews and decided it was worth my coin and I am enjoying it.I enjoy jumping in and just slaying demons.',''),(3285,'I\'m ngl, I recommend it. It is much better than Diablo 3, in terms of gameplay and story. It\'s less simplified than Diablo 3 (although the voice acting is simpler), has the appeal of Diablo 2 (not cartoony, dark story), and similar atmosphere and world-building to Grim Dawn. The story is actually engaging though it\'s slow. The map is open-world and scales with your level, and even though the terrain can get repetitive at times, many unique biomes are introduced to make up for that.The music, I dunno if everybody forgot what Diablo bgm sounded like but it sounds like this game.In terms of loot, you get legendaries pretty quickly so the game also introduces crafting early, and that makes builds much more accessible. If you don\'t get the gear you want, you can basically buy it (although it picks a randomr tier) through murmuring oobols- you get these by doing quests and events. It is also easy to refund skills. Just spend some gold (which you also get an abundance of).I don\'t care much for the online stuff in Diablo 4. Apparently, Blizzard made this game online-only to prevent cheaters in PvP. I don\'t play PvP, and I\'m not sure about everyone else but I\'m not playing these types of games for the PvP. And because it is online-only, you will get network issues and ping spikes even with \'faster than average\' internet. The game also forces you off the servers when you afk for like 10 minutes.That being said I recommend Diablo 4 if you played every other ARPG out there. If you haven\'t, I\'d instead recommend a forgotten recent release, Wolcen: Lords of Mayhem. The boss mechanics are much more enjoyable, it has an offline mode, and it\'s only $8 rn. That game\'s a lot shorter though.',''),(3286,'Game as such is not bad, story is alright buuuut:- poor inventory management- no possibility of saving/loading saved builds (would not mind for a cost but there is no way and you need to spend half an hour every time you dig through all your items, set up the skill tree and paragon board, very poor QOL.-  the micro-transactions prices are hilarious (milking every bit they can, no skin or skin set is worth that much money)- combat mechanics kinda slow, when you press your buttons if a certain, repetitive order of actions is pressed in rapid succession to clear any event or dungeon it often skips attacks and I died due to this several times- inability to zoom out the camera farther (you dont really see all mobs around you you plan to kite for instance, someone said you just see \"the character\'s forehead\", lol, I can agree)- boss mechanics are really bad, animations are skipped, are choppy and they feel clunky regardless of the bossI have not reached endgame yet and I\'m not really motivated to reach it.Today I heard rumors of the first DLC being put at a price range of $100 (one hundred dollars for a ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ DLC). which turns me off even more trying to \"beat the game\".Did I mentioned the inability to save or load builds? I\'m switching fairly often since I do not have all items I am looking for and like to explore different aspects of a character class and I\'d value this feature a LOT.There is more minor things I will not add here.1/5 stars',''),(3287,'I wrote up several paragraphs but Steam ate it: game seems more like WoW than D3 and thus is a step back. I\'ll finish the main quest and fart around a bit, but then i will probably uninstall.',''),(3288,'Forcing players to pay for season cosmetics that we\'re free in D3 just bothers me.  Maybe in a decade after there done with this live-service milk fest when all the DLC\'s are available during a sale for a few dollars... maybe.',''),(3289,'The game play is only slightly less inspired than a slot machine, but adds the inconvenience of having to click the thing that\'s got the bigger number into the gear slots every 47 seconds.Zero Stars.',''),(3290,'- The sheer amount of bullsh*t side-quests with meaningless rewards that end up being clutter in your inventory to be sold or broken into BS materials you\'ll likely never use to upgrade your gear cuz it barely makes any difference -- makes for a boring experience.- Mobs respawn, no sense of \"cleansing\" an area like in Diablo 1.- Too much random gear, weapons, armor, skins, and characteristics. None of it feels like it has lore or significant impact. The excitement for new gear drops real quick. Shops sell overpriced garbage too. I literally never bought a single item from the shop in 50+ hours of playing because there was nothing worth buying. I had 3 million coins that were never spent on anything. One of the best things about Diablo 1 was the fun of saving money to buy good stuff from Griswold.- Mobs feel like pests, while you feel like a braindead exterminator who has nothing better to do in life than repeat the same AOE skills the whole time.- Lilith looks like she has an OnlyFans.- Mobs don\'t sound spooky. The environments do not feel disturbing. Everything is too bright, you can see enemies from afar and you never get caught off guard / jumped by a tougher mob.- The graphics are less cartoonish than Diablo 3 but still cartoonish.- Blizzard has cut corners by not having your character narrate your dialogue selection. At least he\'s not mute altogether.- What\'s the deal with the Butcher teleporting to you \"from Hell\" in dungeons and being extremely overpowered? Who thought that was a better idea than having him await you in his bloody room full of chopped limbs?- The lack of horse mount/dismount animation is just laughable considering the game\'s price.- The game crashes often on a high-end rig (no crashes in other games).- Lag in a Diablo game, how about that.Like many other brands and products in various industries, the birth of \"Diablo 4\" relied on not much more than the reputation gained from its past successes, namely the first 2 installments. And since they keep going in the wrong direction, it\'s time for this franchise to go to Hell.',''),(3291,'Season pass and micro transactions on a $110 dollar game is expected from Blizzard but still not cool.',''),(3292,'I\'ve been playing the Diablo series since Diablo 1. I\'ve eagerly awaited each new version from announcement to release. Diablo is a series that has never disappointed or let me down...until now.Diablo 4 is a satisfying action RPG and I strongly recommend it for someone who likes those types of games. I find myself disappointed in it as a Diablo game, though.To keep this short, I just find it to be lacking in all of the areas that normally make a Diablo game great. The trailer featuring Lilith was incredibly interesting. The Lilith in the game...not so much. Every time she\'s in a cut scene it\'s cool but not the \"this is cool!\" levels of cool you\'d normally expect. As you track down Lilith, you encounter numerous mini bosses but none of them are memorable whatsoever and there\'s little buildup to each of them before you fight them. There\'s lore but it\'s lacking and no where near enough. There are lots of monsters along the way but again they all feel so generic. You don\'t feel like you\'re battling a demon outbreak and trying to keep hell from breaking out on earth. You just feel like you\'re hacking and slashing your way through a bunch of generic monsters. In fact, it seems as though many of the monsters you\'re used to fighting from older Diablo games are missing or have been overhauled so much they aren\'t the same experiences.As I played this game, I frequently found myself bored, not sure what my objectives were, and not sure why I was going on the missions I was tasked with carrying out. You\'re given missions but rarely are there more than just a few lines of dialogue explaining WHY you\'re going on the mission. I felt little attachment to the characters and almost no sense of purpose most of the time. This game very much feels like a MMORPG with too much focus on generic filler content and not enough focus on the main storyline. It\'s okay as a generic hack and slash rpg loot game but definitely does not deserve to carry the Diablo name. Therefore, I can\'t recommend it.',''),(3293,'Go play Diablo 2 or 3. Better games for a better price. It\'s ridiculous how bad the connection to the game\'s server is. Official support says its the players fault, but after following every guide imaginable to make this game playable I have given up. I have never had such a bad experience with a game. Constant latency issues, rubber-banding, and lagging for 10 seconds or more makes this nearly unplayable.',''),(3294,'beautiful game, but very booooring',''),(3295,'Use this comment as \"BLIZZARD, WE WANT DIABLO 2 ON STEAM! NOW!\" button.',''),(3296,'Prologue: You are a developer at Blizzard, back in the 2010s. You\'re working on Starcraft 2: Wings of Liberty. The pressure is high, Starcraft Brood War quickly became the most popular esport and has continued to enjoy massive success since then. You didn\'t work on it, but some of your bosses did, so you trust their design chops. You work late hours, you see the progress being made. The map editor is extremely impressive. Both simple in use and filled with features. It feels like just a few steps below an entire game engine. \"If they open up GalaxyScripting to the public...\" you think. Warcraft 3\'s editor invented entire new game genres, and you can easily see someone creating an entire video game with this new editor. Crunch. Crunch. More crunch. There\'re issues with matchmaking that you can see won\'t be fixed before launch, but you know this project won\'t be abandoned, and you can see it\'s shining future. This might just be the new gold standard in the RTS genre.Months pass...You\'re working on Heart of The Swarm now, the first expansion for Starcraft 2. You hear some noise from your friends on the WoW team, they\'re adding a purchasable cosmetic mount, 25 dollars. It gets announced, and the WoW fanbase revolts. \"This is ridiculous! You can\'t do this! This is going to ruin the integrity of the game!\" they say, and you agree. It\'ll potentially lessen the in game achievements of players. You don\'t think it\'s a good idea, but you think it\'ll probably flop, and they higher ups will likely abandon it in the long term. They\'ll probably just raise the subscription price, that seems like the best choice. People who play aren\'t going to stop playing because of a $5 or $10 increase per month. It\'ll make it harder for new players to justify joining, but that seems like a problem that can be solved.The sparkle pony is released. Things are quiet in work for a few days, not much noise. But then, you\'re talking to your boss, and he seems... flustered. Upset? Angry? Depressed? Worried? You\'re not sure, but you can tell something\'s wrong. The Sparkle Pony, that ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ pony. It made more money in a day/a few days than *all of the revenue combined* from Starcraft 2 WoL. That doesn\'t seem possible, but it\'s true. That ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ pony made more money from those stupid ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ losers playing WoW than Starcraft 2 WoL did. All your work seems pointless. You know the guy who made the pony, he made it in a day. None of those ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ idiots playing WoW could resist buying that ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ pony. Some of them lie and say they didn\'t when the really did. An absurd amount of money. Disgusting. The average gamer is disgusting. It\'s not just whales. That\'s a lie the average gamer tells themselves to justify their spending. \"I\'m not a whale, so it\'s fine\". ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥. ♥♥♥♥ these people. You can already see it. Gaming is ♥♥♥♥♥♥. Pandora\'s box is open. Publicly traded corporations have a legal responsibility to their investors. Not including some form of this ♥♥♥♥ in games might literally be *illegal*. Everything\'s ♥♥♥♥♥♥.Today:Diablo 4 is a Microsoft Activision Blizzard King game. What a name for a company. It\'s quite a good game, actually my favourite ARPG. It strikes an extremely good balance between simplicity and complexity. People will obviously compare it to Path of Exile. Path of Exile is essentially inapproachable unless you are willing to read a build guide. In which case, you are just opting to not engage with the puzzle/tactics side of the game where you learn about your abilities, the stat systems and damage calculations, and other systems and how they interweave and how you can exploit them to create powerful builds. I\'m positive if I put the effort towards it I could dismantle the build system of PoE and create some cool builds, but that would take a lot of work, that I much better put towards understanding more compelling games with consequences other than \"numbers go brrrr\". I vastly prefer to approach video games without a guide (a practice which seems to unfortunately be very uncommon nowadays). This is what I think Diablo 4 does really well with. I have not read any build guides or any external material. I have spent time experimenting and figuring out how to build builds for each of the classes. Say we could define a unit of measurement to describe cognitive effort, let\'s call it CEP (cognitive effort points), as well as a unit of measurement to describe joy, hedonics, or valence, which we\'ll call VP (valence points).  In Diablo 4, for every 1 CEP I receive 1 VP. Whereas in PoE, for every 1 CEP I receive .01 VP. I\'ve noticed this in other games as well. For example, I feel as though Slay the Spire does and extremely good job with this. If I play the game somewhat mindlessly, I have some fun. But my enjoyment and skill at the game rises greatly the more thought I put into it. At some point, there\'s a drop off, where the increase of enjoyment doesn\'t rise with CEP as much. Some people have put effort towards mathematically solving Slay the Spire, which is fascinating, but I am not as smart as those people, and I think that it would be more difficult than enjoyable for me to work on that problem. They research is fascinating to read, however.Diablo 4, without guides, has a decent CEP/VA curve *for me*. There\'s too much grinding to pay attention fully the whole time, which is why I typically play while listening to a video/podcast/book, but that\'s expected for the genre. I suspect a lot of players who dislike the game have not tried playing the game without following a build guide, and instead trying to figure it out on their own instead the whole way through. The art style is great, so much better than Diablo 3. The story and sidequests are great, also much better than Diablo 3. There are so many little details in the world that add to the world-building, and foreshadow future events in the story. This is the best thing the game does that I wasn\'t expecting. I was really surprised at how satisfying it was to explore the world and the towns and the people and their stories.The music is ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ amazing. Even if you don\'t buy this game, go ahead and listen to the sound track. It\'s excellent. I\'m a professional violinist, and I would absolutely love to someday play some of the quartet/chamber music from this game. It\'s excellent. Now to the elephant in the room. You know what? I can\'t blame Blizzard for adding in cosmetics. I\'m tired of people just blaming the corporations for this ♥♥♥♥ being games. Yeah, Bobby Kotick is a greedy ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ who [[censored so I don\'t get in trouble]]. But also, it wouldn\'t be added if people didn\'t buy it. And it\'s not just a few people, it\'s a bunch of you ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥. Take your sparkle pony. You earned it.Diablo 4 is worth it. It\'s the best ARPG out currently. I haven\'t even touched Lost Ark, or how one of the most outspoken people against Diablo 4\'s monetization (Asmonbald) has spent more money in Lost Ark than some of his audience makes in a year. \"Oh but it\'s for\" shut up. Literally nothing justifies spending tens of thousands of dollars on a pay-to-win videogame, and any justifications are just deflection or a defense mechanism.',''),(3297,'There is no reason a single player experience should have lag.',''),(3298,'10/10 don\'t have to play mahjong to get all achievements',''),(3299,'I\'ve... given up my past, my life, and even my nameAs I am awaiting the release of Like a Dragon: Infinite Wealth, to my surprise Ryu Ga Gotoku Studio released Like a Dragon Gaiden: The Man Who Erased His Name. This takes place after the events of Yakuza 6 and during the events of the 7th game. This title uses the action beat-em-up gameplay that the previous games have done, rather than the turn-based RPG mechanics that were used in Y7.Pros and ConsProsFantastic story with many twistsVery fun gameplay with a lot of abilitiesFun upgrades and interesting gadgetsTons of side content to doExcellent soundtrackBeautiful graphics that look amazingConsThe story is a bit on the shorter sideAgent style is a little underwhelmingStoryKazuma Kiryu is now putting his Yakuza life behind him, assuming the name of Joryu and effectively becoming a dead man to everyone he loves and the world. However, one night during a mission he was assigned to someone seems to know what actually happened to him and wants to bring him out of hiding. Joryu must find out what is actually going on and take down whoever is trying to expose him but it also seems a lot more is going on than it seems.https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=3111729471 The only issue I had with the story in this game, is that it’s really short. I completed it in like 6-7 hours at best. The story for this game is honestly fantastic, it fills in some gaps that Y7 had and the characters are overall amazing. It will also showcase some events from Y7 as well as some of the characters making a cameo appearance. To top it all off, the ending to this game actually made me shed some tears which is one of the first and only games to do so.GameplayThe gameplay is very fun, and I enjoyed playing through the beat-em-based combat as always. This is also the first game where I played on professional difficulty, which was manageable for me. You have access to two fighting styles, Agent and Yakuza, each having its own set of skills and abilities for Joryu to utilize. Agent style allows him to use the Daidoji Factions’s specialized martial arts. It’s a fighting style that is very fast-paced, with fast punches and kicks. Joryu can also use special gadgets in combat, including a grappling hook called the Spider, AI drones to home in on enemies called Hornets, Jet engines on his shoes called Serpents, and Firefly - a bomb disguised as a cigarette.https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=3111727742Then there is the Yakuza fighting style, which is more mixed with the Brawler and Dragon style used in the previous games. It now has triple finishers and a new red aura so your enemies can know you are a threat. All of his heat actions are back, from all the way back to the first Yakuza game, with two new ones added to spice things up. Overall, the Yakuza style is a slower fighting style and the one I used the most during combat, as it was my preferred choice.There are also times in the game when enemies do a special attack that will do massive damage. Joryu can counter these moves with a counterattack and deal some damage to the enemy while doing so. The Heat Action Meter has also changed - if you take damage the Heat Action Meter will no longer deplete, the only attacks that can make it deplete are ones that use electricity.While in Extreme Heat Mode any damage done to Joryu will be done to the meter instead and will keep doing this until it’s depleted or shut off. There is also gear you can equip that will help you out in combat by providing state buffs.To get upgrades in the game, you can do side content to get money and Akame Points. The latter are given to you after you are done with a side quest. You can get stuff like new moves, health, attack damage, etc. There is a ton of side content to do and I did a bunch of it throughout my playthrough to make sure I got enough Akame Points to get some upgrades. I never had an issue with getting enough Akame Points, though I did have an issue getting money as that is also used to get upgrades. However, there are ways to get money - it’s just that I ran out most of the time getting upgrades and buying healing items.As mentioned before, The Akame Network has a few side quests for you to complete that will earn you money and Akame Points. There are also Stroll and Patrol missions for you to complete that will give you the same rewards. This can raise your Akame Rank and the higher it is, your rank will go up in the Castle, which is a secret area you can visit that has a colosseum for you to fight other people.However, I do have one issue with the gameplay and that is with the Agent style; it’s underwhelming. The issue comes with the fact that the Yakuza style is better for taking out enemies as a whole. While the Spider Gadget is useful for crowd control and there are upgrades to grab more enemies with it, that also has an issue. To use any of the gadgets you have to hold down the button. So, for example, if I want to use the Spide Gadget, I will have to hold the B button on my controller and this applies to the other ones as well. To get them out is a bit slow and you are kind of a sitting duck while doing so.Except for the Serpent gadget, that one makes you move and it seems to be quick to activate. I wish I could have used Firefly more but besides the delay of holding X and the time it takes for the smoke to explode, it\'s not worth it as sometimes it will be out of range of enemies and can hurt you and your allies.Graphics and PerformanceThe graphics for the game are honestly beautiful with some of the scenes being simply breathtaking, all backed up with a fantastic soundtrack.https://steamcommunity.com/sharedfiles/filedetails/?id=3111728377I tested the game on an NVIDIA GeForce GTX 1060 3GB, AMD Ryzen 5 1500X Quad-Core Processor 3.50, and 16 GB of RAM. I experienced no issues while I was playing, and the game ran fine for me. Although there were some drops in my frames a few times that may be due to the fact I need new PC parts, only time will tell if I can run the next game.Final VerdictI had a ton of fun with Like a Dragon Gaiden: The Man Who Erased His Name, but I need to mention that if you are someone who is starting out with the series, I\'d avoid this game for now, as you won’t understand the story of this game all that well. Also, the game is only 6-7 hours long. There is a lot of side content but that only brings it up to about 20-40 hours in length. I’d wait for a sale before buying this game as 64.99 CDN is a lot of money if you only want to focus on the game\'s story.Listen, I been around the block a time or two, and I\'ll tell ya something, Life Needs a Little Sin  has some great quality reviews',''),(3300,'The best dragon engine game by far, even better than Lost JudgmentThe story is extremely good but a little on the shorter side because this game is a \'\'side game\'\'For a \'\'side game\'\' this game has too much contentThis game has: the best colisseum with multiple playable characters, pocket circuit (again), a lot of substories and judgment esque side cases and on top of that the combat is by far the best in the series.The combat feels nice but I found myself to have even more fun by using the Like A Dragon Gaiden Deluxe mod made by Tacoman805 on NexusMods, but even without mods the games combat is just too much fun.I cannot stress this enough. For a side game, I have played for over 30 hours and will probably play for even more, which is kinda crazy ngl.Wishing for RGG to make a yakuza style fighting game ong ong.Now I will go onto play Yakuza: Like a Dragon and then onto Infinite Wealth10/10 would recommend',''),(3301,'joryu',''),(3302,'Like a Dragon Gaiden: The Man Who Erased His Name.-----------------------------------------------------------------a MUST play for fans of the franchise.Love letter to the fans, and perfectly fixes some lose ends from Yakuza 7/Like a Dragon.The story is phenominal, characters are great, music hits perfect.Its a absolute blast to play. story is a little shorter, but the amount of content is not.Seeing Kiryu at the ending,(no spoiler) but it left a tear in my eye.A beautiful end to his story, i can not wait to see how ichiban will carry this further.Infinite Wealth is not far away. Let the hype begin.Yakuza/Like a Dragon is a ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ PHENOMINAL franchise.Enjoy the game !!!',''),(3303,'It\'s really a bit of a filler game for the series, but it ties up a few loose ends from Yakuza LAD. Definitely do not play this unless you\'ve also played at least LAD as it has a few spoilers. The plot is good with plenty of twists to keep you on edge, the Japanese voice acting is top notch as usual. It has all the usual silly side quests and minigames to keep you entertained. The Agent fighting style is fun, but the rocket shoes are a bit OP.',''),(3304,'Deliciously tightly packaged Yakuza!I\'m gonna be honest and say that at first I didn\'t expect much from this game. It seemed like recycled content with some Kiryu story that could have been part of the other games. But as more info got out and I learned more my interest got picked. Now I regard this among my favorites.I think right now my ranking goes something like this: Y0, Y7, YK2, Gaiden, YK1, Y5, Y6, Y3, Y4.In the end I feel that although shorter, this is a complete Yakuza package. Everything we\'ve come to love and expect is here. Twisting heavy drama story, whacky side quests, great minigames, memorable characters, awkward content to explain to your loved ones, Japanese weirdness and so on. The difference is that the game does all this without any bloat.I really liked how they portrayed Kiryu in this one and made him a bit more human. I also really enjoyed some of the new characters and how they got developed throughout the game. And I loved Akame! More Akame in the next games or we riot!I think RGG packaged the story they had with just the right amount of side stuff and fluff to leave you wanting just a bit more in the end. Which sucks! I was intending to wait a little to get Infinite Wealth cheaper but who am I kidding?',''),(3305,'9.5/10An absolutely beautiful love letter to Kiryu and the \"Yakuza\" saga of Like a Dragon. While it seems Infinite Wealth will be our farewell to Kiryu, Gaiden feels like a heartfelt farewell to the games that introduced us to him.The gameplay was a lot of fun. I\'ll admit, I definitely favored one style over the other, but even primarily using one style throughout most of the game, I still had a blast playing. As per usual, this game is chock full of minigames and side stories to invest your time in to, and they are absolutely worth it! Also in usual RGG fashion, the soundtrack was phenomenal. While being a game focused on Kiryu, it featured a cast of primarily new characters, and I loved them. Akame was an instant favorite for me. Shishido and Hanawa were strong favorites as well. But the story is where this game absolutely shines. It maintained continuity from the stories that came before, while also building up immense anticipation for the next game to come. The ending in particular was phenomenal.This game was absolutely meant for the Yakuza fans who have been along for Kiryu\'s entire journey. If you\'re new to the series, this absolutely should not be your starting point. But it is a fantastic destination to look forward to.',''),(3306,'My only male fantasy is to see Kiryu happy.',''),(3307,'A painful sort of parting. Let me state up front that, despite what Sega\'s marketing claims, this is the absolute worst place to start the Yakuza franchise. Not because of its quality, but because this feels like the closing epilogue to a saga that spans close to two decades in releases. I\'ve played Yakuza for going on twelve years at this point, ever since importing the Japanese release of Yakuza 5, then emulating the originals, and slowly working forward from there. It\'s given me great joy to see the new waves of popularity RGG have rightfully gotten in the wake of Yakuza 0\'s debut in the West, and it gives me even greater joy to see that rather than sit on their laurels, they\'ve consistently pushed themselves to make each new release as great as it can be. Gaiden is a side game, and that nature is plenty evident in everything from its skeleton to its skin. It simply lacks the wide variety of content that the mainline franchise is well known for. It tries, and my hour count- I hope- serves as sufficient evidence to show you\'ll get plenty of bang for your buck, but I would strongly encourage you to temper your expectations somewhat before diving in, and I think you\'ll be pleasantly surprised as a result. I don\'t want to speak overlong on the story, because I consider it Gaiden\'s greatest strength. If you\'ve been following Kiryu through the course of his life, from 0 to 6, then this absolutely *is not* something you want to sit out. Speaking personally, it\'s the sweetest kind of pain seeing what he goes through in Gaiden. It\'s the sappy, Valjean-esque sort of drama you\'ve come to expect from Yakuza, but it hits home all the more simply because it\'s Kiryu. To see an immovable force of nature show the scars and strain behind his stoicism wasn\'t only deeply moving, it was heart-wrenching. Because of Gaiden, because of the momentum RGG have been picking up with Yakuza 7 and Lost Judgment, I am wholeheartedly certain that Yakuza 8 will be their crowning masterpiece, and a game that\'ll leave me utterly broken with tears. I cannot wait.',''),(3308,'JORYU!',''),(3309,'Gaiden is the new peak of YakuzaAs a reminder: Do not play this before completing Yakuza 0-7This game is a conclusion of all the Yakuza games released to this day. Playing this first would be the same as watching the final Season of Attack on Titan or any other good series before Season 1-4. You would ruin your experience.Now for the review:Kazuma Kiryu is back, for better or worse, depending on how you see it, but on a technical level, this game takes everything that made Yakuza 6 and Kiwami 2 amazing and improves it quite a bit: Combat Kiryu keeps his Dragon of Dojima style, which is now called the Yakuza style, but it’s slightly nerved in comparison to Y6 and K2. They made it slightly slower and took away two of the side-steps, you can only do one now (and you get a roll upgrade later) otherwise the moveset is mostly unchanged.The star of the show is the new Agent style. It’s mixture of Yagamis Crane and Kiryus old rush style with some new gadgets, which are really fun to use.Gameplay wise Agent style is superior, especially on harder difficulties, due the nerving of Yakuza style and it generally being faster.One of the biggest changes in terms of combat is the number of enemies you can fight at once. Some battles (mostly in the Colliseum) makes you fight up to 20 enemies at once. After this game, One Man Army Kiryu definitely deserves his title. Minigames The main story might be shorter but in terms of minigames and side content, Gaiden has almost as much content as a normal Yakuza game: Improved Pocket Circuit Racing Improved Colliseum with it’s own Subplot including Team Battles and the opportunity to control and fight with different characters other than Kiryu. A mixture of Judgment side cases and and the classic Substories. It’s presented in a similar way as in Judgment but play out like the classic funny substories we know from Yakuza.New and old Karaoke songs, including BakamitaiBilliard for the first time in the Dragon EngineHostess Club (They made it worse and more creepy by using real actresses, but it’s there for the people who like it).Additionally, something, that doesn’t really fit into any of the Subcategories: You change the appearance of Kiryu now.Some outfits from older games return or you can just dress him up as a clown, and it will affect almost every cutscene!Now for the most important part of the game: The PlotIn terms of story writing, it\'s kind of amazing to think that the entire situation of Kiryu, where everything started to go downhill for him, begun in Yakuza 5 or more specifically it\'s ending.Before that, all Yakuza games had it\'s of own concluded stories without any big impact for it\'s successors, but with Yakuza 5 and successor Yakuza 6, everything changed:Kiryu ends up in prison due the aftermaths of Yakuza 5 (2012)Haruka leaves Morning Glory Orphanage due unwanted attention by media (sometime between 2012-2014)Haruka meets Yuta (2014)Haruka gets hospitalized due her involvement with Yuta (2016)Kiryu fakes his death to protects his family (2016)Which leads to Gaiden (2019-2020)Which then leads to Infinite Wealth, due the affairs in Gaiden and Yakuza 7. (2023)The entirety of Yakuza 6 and Gaiden could have been prevented, if Kiryu would have been there to protect Haruka. The decision Kiryu made at the end of Yakuza 5 to go into prison were the trigger for everything that took place afterwards. You could even go further back and say that Kiryus decision to let Haruka pursue her dream of becoming an Idol let to all of this, which is impressive to think about.You could say, that this is all an one big arc and it\'s still ongoing for 11/12 years now.If the writers of Yakuza, or Like a Dragon, how it’s called now, planned this from the start, it’s actually really good story writing. Now we will have to see how it continues in Like a Dragon Infinite WealthThe sum it up, without spoiling the game, this game has definitely the most emotional scene in the entire franchise with one of the best voice acting pieces I’ve ever heard, which would even make the toughest Yakuza cry. Please RGG give this man a happy ending, he has suffered enough.',''),(3310,'Bizarre to say a game in this franchise should be a bit longer, but I appreciate this bite-size \"Kiryu\'s Greatest Hits\" for what it is. It\'s Yakuza 6.5, Yakuza: Like A Dragon 7.5, Like a Dragon: Before the Wealth - It\'s my unexpected GOTY 2023.',''),(3311,'Very Good.',''),(3312,'Game\'s so good that I bought it on Steam after gamepassing it as an excuse to get all the achievements. While it does start off as an immediate follow up to Yakuza 6, it does spoil the crap out of Yakuza: Like a Dragon/7 as it assumes you played that first. I skipped all the cutscenes on my Steam run if you\'re curious about my playtime at time of writing for getting every achievement.Words of advice for anyone aiming for 100%: 1)The Dragon engine still has physics issues above 30 FPS so cap it at 30 when doing BIlliards2)Play as the chicken man for any Colosseum match\'s you\'re struggling with, most people struggle hard with the third King when playing as Kiryu. The chicken man\'s heat move kills everything once you max his stats out but he has no health so you\'re meant to run around while the heat meter fills up.',''),(3313,'ABSOLUTE CINEMA, WONDERFUL FAN SERVICE, STILL HAVEN\'T BEATEN IN IT BUT THIS IS ONE OF THE MOST PERFECT DRAGON ENGINE RGG GAMES RIGHT AFTER LOST JUDGMENT, well DONE!!!!i\'m not too thrilled to cry from the final scenes tho but that\'s gonna be so peak!',''),(3314,'i cried',''),(3315,'This review is probably tainted by the fact that this is the first Yakuza game that I have paid full price for, but I still feel like this game was severely lacking in the ways that other Yakuza game shine. I can say without a doubt that the story in this game was the worst in the series. The ending was emotional and amazing as always, but the meat of the story felt shaped by whatever schlock they could fit in to make an already short and simple story longer. Glad this game was made though and I\'m hoping Infinite Wealth is better in every aspect.',''),(3316,'This game is a single bite out of the double triple bossy deluxe Yakuza: Like a Dragon and Lost Judgment proved a RGG game can be. I beat it wishing there was more. It has a good, action-packed story, a few fun minigames, and the best (only) tournament mode from any RGG game since Yakuza Kiwami 2, though I personally found training clan members a bit too grindy to be engaging. Which is a shame, since about a third of the game\'s content revolves around said tournament mode, which requires you to have high-level clan members to progress through the side-story.I would only buy this game at full price for the story or if you\'re a big RGG fan. Otherwise, wait for it to go on sale, and save your money for LAD: Infinite Wealth.',''),(3317,'I started off \"Like a Dragon Gaiden\" with a strong feeling of déjà-vu, concerning the sceneries, map and gameplay - a feeling that progressively vanished as I went on playing the game.So, true; the bases of the gameplay are relatively the same as before, even if each Yakuza game has the talent to show some notable differences for this matter. The map consists in only the city of Sotenbori, and later on the castle, and at start I wished Kiryu could have evolved through a different area, city, as he was supposed to be \"incognito\".Well . . . fact is, now that I\'ve finished the game, I feel just blown away by those few dozens of hours I\'ve played, and its\' captivating story; it\'s a Yakuza title that is very worthy to appear in the series, even essential - with an ending that is certainly long, but \"Grand Finale\" style. And I think that what strongly participated to my feeling of satisfaction in the end was, as for other Yakuza games I\'ve played (including the Judgment ones), I just took my time, with the mini-games, with the Coliseum, and the Akame requests - and all just fit together perfectly, the game was a real blast and don\'t regret one bit playing this to the end. I also felt that the combat difficulty was a bit higher, which I appreciated.It isn\'t perfect though, some lengthy grinding may be necessary for the Coliseum for instance; or once again, the map is actually the most limited in the series - but whatever, Like a Dragon Gaiden is a total banger, mostly if you care to not rush it and explore well all of its\' map and everything it has to offer.So if you already played and liked some games of the franchise, you can buy this with no hesitation ; and if you\'re a newcomer, my personal advice would be to play the games in the most chronological order possible, starting with Yakuza 0, the first game in the series, and a most well reputed one, for all its\' great qualities and fun. But overall I can only recommend such a great game, that made me feel that RGG took all possible care in respecting their audience and followers, and executed that close to perfectly.','');
